<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GangViolence     04-13 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gang Violence,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LA Police Arrest Gang Member in Good Friday Shooting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old gang member has been arrested
in connection with a Good Friday shooting that left one dead and 11
injured and triggered the Police Department's all-out war on
drug-dealing gangs.
   In another development, five members of the crime fighting group
Guardian Angels, including group founder, Curtis Sliwa, were
arrested as they allegedly attempted to force their way into the
offices of a studio producing a movie they say glorifies gangs.
   Police said Tuesday the teen-ager was arrested Monday and will
be charged with murder. The youth was not identified because he is
a juvenile, but police said he is a known gang member.
   ``He was very belligerent and portrayed himself, as I've said,
as a real bad guy, until he was informed that he was being arrested
and booked for murder, whereupon he broke down and cried like the
big coward that he really is,'' police Chief Daryl Gates said of
the youth.
   Police were seeking two other people in the April 1 shooting,
which killed a 19-year-old man and wounded 11 others, including a
child.
   The City Council Tuesday voted $4.5 million in police overtime
to help the department continue its onslaught on gangs through
June. The police effort includes steps such as the 1,000-officer
task force that hit the streets last weekend and arrested 1,453
people, 794 of them gang members.
   District Attorney Ira Reiner said the police sweeps, done at an
estimated nightly cost of $150,000, have helped disrupt gang
activity and heighten public awareness.
   The district attorney's office has filed charges on 59 out of
118 cases submitted from the sweeps arrests, a ratio Reiner said is
about average for felony cases. The others were rejected for
insufficient evidence, said Deputy District Attorney Stephen Kay.
   Earlier Tuesday, six of eight reputed gang members arrested in
the weekend sweep pleaded innocent to narcotics charges.
   Despite the crackdown, four people were killed in drive-by
shootings over the weekend and nine others were injured,
authorities said.
   Meanwhile, Sliwa and four other Guardian Angels were arrested as
they allegedly attempted to force their way into the offices of
Orion Pictures in Century City.
   The Guardian Angels have been protesting Friday's scheduled
release of the movie ``Colors.'' The five were booked for battery
after allegedly pushing and tackling security guards, and were
being held on $500 bail each, said police Sgt. B.P. Kelepecz.
   Despite protests by the Angels and other groups, Reiner said he
believes the film may galvanize public support for the war on gangs.
   ``This is not West Side Story revisited,'' Reiner said of the
movie. ``These are not darlings who are going to dance their way
into your heart. These are sociopathic killers.''
</TEXT>
