<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     04-13 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT WASHINGTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The meteorologist atop Mount
Washington breezily observed the anniversary of the world's record
wind speed by phoning his counterpart who clocked the 231-mph wind
54 years ago.
   ``I wished him a happy wind day,'' said Greg Gordon, who phoned
Alex McKenzie on Tuesday. McKenzie was in the observatory at 1:21
p.m., April 12, 1934, when the southeast blast was recorded _ the
fastest measured on the surface of the planet.
   At 1:21 p.m. Tuesday, the wind was a mere 2 mph, ``which is
highly unusual,'' Gordon said.
   The 6,288-foot mountain has some of the world's harshest
weather. Its hurricane-force winds (above 74 mph) are registered an
average 100 days a year. The average annual snowfall is 178 inches.
   The coldest it has ever been on the mountain is minus 47
degrees, the warmest 71 degrees. Snow falls on the mountain in
every month and the peak is socked in by clouds 30 days a year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a sight to behold, even by New York
standards: 19 elephants parading through midtown Manhattan toward
Central Park to nosh on celery, carrots, cabbages _ and bagels.
   Tuesday's was the first midday circus elephant parade through
Manhattan in more than a decade, and was staged to exercise the
pachyderms and publicize the Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey
Circus.
   The clown-flanked elephants, led by Ringmaster Jim Ragona and
carrying brightly clad showgirls, entered the park's Great Lawn to
the cheers of schoolchildren for the picnic.
   ``What I like about these elephants is that they're New York
elephants,'' said Mayor Edward I. Koch as he poked food into the
maw of a huge beast named Jewel. ``They like bagels.''
   After the picnic, the elephants, walking tail in trunk and
followed by a pair of street sweepers, paraded back down Ninth
Avenue to prepare for an evening performance.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country music classic ``Walking the
Floor over You,'' has nothing on a singer who's so desperate to
perform for the Grand Ole Opry that he's walking 1,500 miles to
plead for a chance at the spotlight.
   David Stewart, 37, of Gillette, Wyo., plans to leave home on
April 30 and arrive in Nashville, the home of the Opry, on July 22.
   ``I'll show them I'm serious,'' Stewart said by telephone
Tuesday from his home. ``I respect country music and the people in
it. I think they will appreciate what I'm doing.''
   Stewart, a guitarist who's been singing part time for 20 years,
plans to walk eight to 10 hours daily covering 20 to 30 miles.
   Jerry Strobel, manager of the Grand Ole Opry House, said Opry
performers are usually established entertainers, and the Opry
usually refers aspiring singers to The Nashville Network's ``You
Can Be A Star'' show on cable TV.
   ``If I don't get on, the worst thing is that I will have lost a
little weight,'' Stewart said. ``Of course I'll be disappointed.
But I will have accomplished at least part of what I set out to do.
If a person has a dream and doesn't go after it, you're just idle.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
