<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     04-13 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Gets Consolation Tie As Third-Place Season Winds Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS got a consolation prize _ a tie with NBC _
in the second-to-last week of the season that will mark CBS' first
time as a third-place finisher in the prime-time A.C. Nielsens Co.
ratings race.
   Last week's tie was the closest CBS has come all season to
winning a week. NBC has won 24 weeks of the 29 weeks of the season.
ABC won the others with special sporting events like the World
Series and the Winter Olympics.
   For the week that ended Sunday, NBC and CBS had average,
prime-time ratings of 14.0. ABC had an 11.2. With one week left,
NBC is set to win its third consecutive season. It has an average
16.1 rating for the 29 weeks; ABC's is 13.7, and CBS 13.5.
   CBS got a boost Monday night from the NCAA championship
basketball game, which got an 18.8 rating and 30 share and was
seventh in the rankings.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million
households with televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in
use.
   CBS also was helped on Sunday night when its lineup of ``60
Minutes,'' ``Murder, She Wrote'' and the movie ``Red River'' all
made it into the top 10.
   The second half of NBC's low-rated, two-part miniseries ``The
Fortunate Pilgrim'' went up against the basketball game last Monday
and finished 34th.
   But NBC had the week's highest-rated movie, Raquel Welch's
``Scandal in a Small Town,'' which ranked fifth.
   With the onset of daylight-saving time, the evening newscasts
began what seems to be a typical summer slide in the ratings.
   ABC's ``World News Tonight'' won the week that ended Friday with
a rating of 9.7 and a 20 share. The ``CBS Evening News'' had a 9.3
and 20 share; ``NBC Nightly News'' 8.5 and 18. All three newscasts
dropped in ratings, indicating fewer viewers in front of their sets
in the early evening.
   In prime time, much of the week's lineup was made up of reruns
as the networks saved original episodes for the May sweeps.
   The top-rated shows of the week were: ``The Cosby Show'' NBC,
``Murder, She Wrote'' CBS, ``My Two Dads'' NBC, ``Cheers'' NBC,
``Scandal in a Small Town'' NBC, ``Golden Girls'' NBC, the NCAA
basketball championship on CBS, ``60 Minutes'' CBS, ``Red River''
CBS, and ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC.
   ABC's new ``The Wonder Years,'' was 11th. NBC's new ``In the
Heat of the Night'' ranked 15th.
   The lowest-rated shows of the week were: ``Family Man,'' ``High
Mountain Rangers,'' ``Buck James,'' ``Our House,'' ``West 57th,''
``Highwayman,'' ``Probe,'' ``Hotel,'' ``Supercarrier'' and
``Ohara.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
