<DOCNO> AP880413-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Greeks     04-13 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Greeks,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethnic Pull Helps Dukakis In Upstate New York, Elsewhere</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto AB1</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE ESPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREEN ISLAND, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek-Americans in upstate New York
state are doing just as their counterparts elsewhere in the United
States and rallying behind the presidential campaign of one of
their own: Michael Dukakis.
   ``If a man is good in his work, native Greeks, they'll always
stick with him,'' said Peter Apostol, a 72-year-old Greek-American
who works for his son in a restaurant supply business in Green
Island.
   ``I think it's strong,'' said the son, Michael, 42, of the
grass-roots sentiment for Dukakis. ``I think a lot of Greeks are
donating money. A lot are excited that one of our own is running.
The Greeks would like to see a Greek-American and an ethnic, a
hyphenated-American, in control of the presidency. It's no
different than why blacks support Jesse Jackson.''
   Dukakis, the son of immigrants, will get a big boost from
Greek-Americans who are also registered Democrats in New York's
primary on Tuesday. And should he be the party's nominee in the
general election in November, some Republicans and independents say
they will cross over to vote for him just because he's Greek.
   Among those ready to bolt the GOP for Dukakis is Jimmy Londis,
64, who came to the United States from Greece 30 years ago and runs
the popular Jimmy's Lunch in Troy, known for its French toast.
   ``I feel very warm about him,'' said Londis. ``He's the right
kind of person. He's a good governor. If it's going to be (Jesse)
Jackson and (George) Bush, I've got to vote Republican.''
   The Rev. Emmanuel Mantzouris, pastor of St. Basil Greek Orthodox
Church in Troy whose congregation numbers about 250, said many
Greeks are politically oriented. ``Just knowing he's Greek draws
their attention, somebody being Greek in the limelight.''
   As much as 25 percent of the $15 million that Dukakis has raised
in campaign funds has come from Greek-Americans, estimated to
number one million.
   ``A lot about the Dukakis candidacy stimulates
Greek-Americans,'' says Elias Vlanton, information director of the
American Hellenic Educational Progressive Association. ``He invokes
his Greek heritage and the values that Greeks hold dear _ love of
family, the need and importance of public service.''
   Paul Brountas, a Greek-American who is Dukakis' national
campaign chairman, acknowledges there may be some voters who will
support him just because of his heritage. But just the same, he
says, Dukakis has to prove himself on the issues first.
   ``There's no automatic vote or contribution to Dukakis just
because he's Greek,'' says Brountas. ``I believe the majority of
Greek supporters hear his message. The gap between what you know
about a candidate and don't know is often bridged either by
familiarity or a tie so he starts with the heritage connection.''
   One ardent supporter, John Oureilidis, a 40-year-old bowling
equipment supplier from Troy, believes what Dukakis says.
   ``Plus he's Greek,'' says Oureilidis. ``He talks sense. Nobody
talks about poor people like he does. I believe he can do it. He's
our boy so we have to vote for him.''
   But still there are some dissenters among Greek-Americans like
Michael Wilson, 31, who is in the printing business, and his
brother, George, 29, a continuity director for a radio station in
Schenectady. Both are diehard Republicans. And for good reason. In
1984, before moving to Schenectady, Michael Wilson was chairman of
the Fulton County Reagan-Bush Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0017 </DOCNO>
