<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalMedia     04-13 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Media,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Rely On Ads In New York Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson is mounting his first major
television drive of the presidential campaign season for next
week's New York primary, and he'll kick it off with an anti-drug ad
produced by filmmaker Spike Lee.
   Jackson spokesman Eric Easter said Tuesday that the campaign
expects to purchase TV time worth about $500,000 _ 10 times more
than what Jackson spent on media for the April 5 Wisconsin primary
in which he placed second.
   ``We plan to run a number of commercials,'' Easter said. ``We
haven't decided which ones to use and when to run them. We've just
decided a ballpark figure on how much we're willing to spend.''
   Despite the huge jump in Jackson's media spending, the civil
rights activist probably won't match the TV effort planned by
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. Gore spokesman Mark Armour said the
campaign had made a third media buy Tuesday and ``we're still
intending to run a million-plus campaign in New York.''
   Steve Akey, a spokesman for Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis,
declined to say how much the campaign is spending other than that
``we can be and we will be competitive with everybody in New York.''
   Asked if Dukakis would match or outspend his rivals, Akey
replied: ``It's not always necessary. We didn't spend the most
money in Wisconsin. You have to be very careful about targeting
your dollar.''
   Jackson has relied mainly on energetic campaigning and heavy
news coverage in past contests. But he took in more than $2 million
in March after strong showings in several states, assuring him the
means to project a stronger media presence in the expensive and
high-stakes New York contest.
   The new Jackson ad, shot Monday, shows Jackson and Lee walking
down a New York street. Lee comments on the sad state of the
neighborhood and the devastating impact of drugs on the streets,
and Jackson responds with a discussion of his anti-drug positions.
   According to Easter, in Lee's movie, ``She's Gotta Have It,''
Lee's character mentions having met Jackson and told him to run for
president. Lee has been a Jackson supporter for some time.
   Easter said other new ads would be made from filming done last
week while Jackson was campaigning in Brooklyn. He said the
campaign may also use endorsement spots that have proven effective
in the past _ one by entertainer Bill Cosby and another by a farmer
who says Jackson helped him save his farm.
   Gore had been running a biographical ad, another stressing his
experience as a Vietnam veteran and a third proposing that the
military be mobilized to fight drugs. Armour said the biography was
pulled Tuesday and a new ad on trade was scheduled to start upstate
and downstate on Tuesday night.
   Dukakis, on a roll after trouncing Jackson in Wisconsin, was
running three ads throughout New York, one of them a biography, one
emphasizing his experience as a chief executive and the third
emphasizing the war against drugs.
   The second, a variation on a spot he has used in several states,
says he is the only candidate to have balanced a budget, created
new jobs, built affordable housing and provided job training and
child care.
   The third, which began airing on Tuesday, included excerpts from
a speech in which Dukakis attacked the Reagan administration's
support until recently of Panamanian military strongman Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   ``How can we tell our children to say `no' to drugs when we have
an administration that paid $200,000 a year to a drug-peddling
dictator from Panama?'' Dukakis says.
</TEXT>
