<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--LostParts     04-13 0136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Lost Parts,0138</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Submarine Parts Recovered From Ocean Floor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trident submarine parts that fell into the Irish
Sea from a cargo ship two months ago have been recovered, the Press
Association reported. The five parts, worth $1.2 million, were lost
Feb. 5 and 6 off Wolney Island near Barrow-in-Furness in northeast
England.
   The parts, salvaged by an unidentified insurance company, appear
to be undamaged and have been returned to the Motherwell Bridge
steel manufacturers in Glasgow, Scotland, where they were made, the
Press Association said Tuesday.
   The forward dome section for a Trident missile-carrying,
Vanguard-class submarine was lost during a storm on Feb. 5. The
next day, four submarine deck sections fell overboard from the same
cargo ship for unknown reasons.
   The parts were being sent to a shipbuilding company in Barrow.
</TEXT>
