<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Afghanistan     04-13 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Afghanistan,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Urges UN Relief Program for Afghan Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of Afghan refugees heading home when
Soviet troops withdraw will need United Nations-run relief services
because of continued upheaval in Afghanistan, U.S. officials say.
   Further mediation efforts also will be needed to arrange an
interim government to replace the Soviet-backed regime, according
to the officials. ``A constructive effort is taking place to work
out an interim government and to help the refugees return in safety
and honor,'' State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said
Tuesday.
   ``The process has to be done in such a way that it's done
securely, that these people are taken care of,'' he said.
   ``There is obviously going to be some social disorganization
inside Afghanistan as this proceeds,'' he said. ``We need to try to
do this in a coordinated way.''
   He said the United Nations is the ``logical'' organization to
coordinate the work.
   Refugee resettlement and political maneuvering to set the shape
of future rule in Afghanistan have emerged as the next major issues
in the region, as the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops prepare to
withdraw.
   Under accords to be signed in Geneva on Thursday, the troops
will be out of the country by early next year, ending an eight-year
Soviet military domination of the Afghan government.
   The accords, to be signed at a ceremony attended by Secretary of
State George P. Shultz, also envision a non-aligned Afghanistan,
the return of the refugees and a peaceful Afghan-Pakistani border.
   Diego Cordovez, the United Nations mediator who led the
settlement discussions, is expected to continue _ in a private
capacity _ to work for a further understanding between the
U.S.-backed Afghan guerrillas and the Soviet-sponsored government
in Kabul.
   Complicating the problem is a superpower agreement to continue
aiding their clients in the country after the Soviet troops
withdraw.
   The United States had hoped to reach agreement with the Soviets
to cut all aid to the belligerents, but when Moscow insisted on its
right to assist the Kabul government, the United States said it
would continue helping the resistance forces.
   President Reagan sought on Tuesday to assure a group of U.S.
supporters of the Afghan resistance that the American commitment
would continue after the Soviets withdraw.
   ``The president told us repeatedly and in very definitive terms
that he is going to stand by the Afghan freedom fighters no matter
what,'' said Paul Weyrich, president of the Free Congress
Foundation. Leaders of the Afghan insurgents have vowed to continue
the war and with the spring thaw opening mountain supply routes,
Western diplomats in Pakistan have reported an increase in military
activity in Afghanistan.
   Renewed fighting has been reported near the large cities of
Kandahar and Khost and Soviet army forces continue to operate in
strength, the diplomats said.
   State Department officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said continued fighting would affect the return of the refugees,
but one expert said the removal of Soviet forces from the fray
would spark a massive return.
   ``The likelihood of continued violence does not frighten the
Afghan people,'' this official said.
   ``What made them flee in the first place was not the violence,
it was the magnitude of the violence, namely attacks from the
Soviet air force, napalm attacks, helicopter raids on villages.
   ``When that ends they will want to return,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
