<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LiberaceAuction     04-13 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberace Auction,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Liberace's Estate Auction Raises More than $2 million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estate auction of pianist Liberace's
often-gaudy possessions netted more than $2 million, a spokeswoman
for the group conducting the sale said Tuesday.
   On the final day of the auction, the flamboyant entertainer's
fleet of cars was sold, with five of them purchased by the Imperial
Palace hotel and casino in Las Vegas, Nev.
   Among the vehicles purchased for the Palace was a 1966
Rolls-Royce Silver Shadow with sable and gold coach lining for
$46,000.
   Proceeds of the auction will go to the non-profit Liberace
Foundation for the Performing and Creative Arts, which provides
scholarships at 28 schools and colleges nationwide.
   Robert Nye, a piano dealer from Redding, Penn., paid $22,100 for
one of Liberace's pianos on the first day of the auction. On
Tuesday, he paid $11,000 for a fox coat once worn by the pianist.
   He also bought a van owned by the entertainer that was decorated
on the side with a painting of the pianist's trademark piano and
candelabra arrangement, said Alexandra Destler, spokeswoman for
Butterfield & Butterfield, which conducted the sale.
   The four-day auction, which began Saturday, took in $2.08
million, Ms. Destler said.
   Liberace's driver's license, forecast to garner no more than
$200, went for $4,150 Sunday.
   Many bidders at the Los Angeles Convention Center auction
purchased items as investments, but many were fans who came to pay
respects to Wladziu (Walter) Valentino Liberace, who died Feb. 4,
1987, of complications of AIDS. He was 67.
</TEXT>
