<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StudentProtest     04-13 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Student Protest,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Students Banished from Campus in Racial Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRANVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Denison University
banished two white students from campus for the rest of the
academic year for making racial slurs to a black student, a
university spokesman said Tuesday.
   University President Andrew De Rocco ordered the two students to
leave the campus by 5 p.m. Wednesday, said spokesman Stewart Dyke.
   The students had been found guilty by the university's judicial
board of harassing Aaron Laramore, a black senior, by pounding on
the wall of his dormitory room and yelling racial epithets. The two
students live adjacent to Laramore.
   The board had ordered the white students suspended for the
coming fall semester, but black students claimed that punishment
was too lenient and called for a boycott of classes and organized
protest rallies. The suspension remains in effect, Dyke said.
   Jay Freeborne, a student from Upper Marlboro, Md., said the
incident has consumed the campus of 2,100 students about 25 miles
northeast of Columbus. He said instructors have given over class
time to discussions of racism.
</TEXT>
