<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0405EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TV-Turner'sCrusade     04-13 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV-Turner's Crusade,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turner Crusading to Save `Endangered Species' _ Humans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cable mogul Ted Turner has more on his mind
these days than making money. He's hoping to save mankind from
nuclear destruction.
   Turner's Better World Society, founded in 1985, is sponsoring a
series of television programs on such subjects as overpopulation
and nuclear proliferation, and the most recent is ``The Terror
Trade: Buying the Bomb,'' airing tonight and again Saturday on
SuperStation TBS.
   The content of the one-hour documentary is impressive, not to
mention scary.
   The centerpiece is an interview with ``Eric,'' a man who claims
to be a former arms dealer who traded in black-market plutonium,
sought by many Third World nations as well as terrorist
organizations wanting to build their own nuclear weapons.
   George Case, the British investigative reporter who reported and
co-produced the documentary, says Eric's credibility was verified
by the U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency, for whom he once worked as an
informant.
   At one point, Eric describes a ``flea market'' at a hotel in
Khartoum, Sudan, where 12 kilos of stolen weapons-grade plutonium
were up for sale _ stored at the airport, not in the hotel. Buyers,
Eric said, came from South Africa, Libya, Israel, Iraq, Iran,
Pakistan, Argentina and the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Eric said he was negotiating on behalf of South Africa and
unsuccessfully offered $5 million a kilo for the stuff. He said he
heard later that the plutonium was sold to Iraq. A few months after
the sale, in June 1981, Israeli jets destroyed an Iraqi nuclear
research plant.
   Richard Perle, former assistant secretary of defense in the
Reagan administration, is interviewed and says that while other
countries publicly deplored the Israeli attack, many nations
privately applauded it.
   Other officials interviewed include former President Jimmy
Carter and former CIA Director Stansfield Turner.
   The documentary suggests that U.S.-Soviet cooperation is the
best way to stop proliferation.
   Turner said he thinks it's a simple case of U.S. and Soviet
leadership.
   ``That threat's always there: `We can nuke you and you can't
nuke us back,' and it really makes the little countries angry,''
said Turner. ``That's the ultimate status symbol in the world
today. It's just awful. We set a terrible example, us and the
Soviets, but the Soviets want to get rid of nuclear weapons, and so
does the Better World Society, at least the chairman does.''
   Turner he created the society to finance controversial
television projects about world population problems and the nuclear
threat that couldn't draw advertisers.
   ``I've got five children,'' he said. ``Humanity is the most
endangered species on the planet, and it bothers the devil out of
me. I've just got a lot of pride. I like to see things better. I go
around pickin' up trash on my places on the weekend. It kills me to
see the trash on the side of the highway.
   ``And to see all the wonderful people in this world _ I've been
over to the Soviet Union and met the people over there, and they're
just as nice as the people here in the United States, and that's
true of the people in Iran and Israel and everywhere. It's all
misunderstanding. That's all it is.''
   Turner's simplistic approach to world peace isn't always
successful. The seven-part series ``Inside the Soviet Union'' was
largely dismissed by critics as too naive, showing lots of happy
Soviets and ignoring serious issues such as religious suppression
and persecution of those who seek to emigrate.
   Turner insisted that was the aim of the program, to counteract a
negative Soviet image in the United States.
   Turner feels so strongly about world peace, he has directed that
his Cable News Network in news reports use the term
``international'' instead of than ``foreign.''
   ``It's not really foreign, it's news from other parts of the
Earth,'' he said. ``We really should save the word foreign for
meteorites and things that come from outer space, because nothing
is foreign on this planet. We've already done it at CNN _
`international' instead of `foreign.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Education Bjt   04-13 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Education, Bjt,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Educators, Students Speak Out About Education System</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twice in the past week small groups of academics
have staged protests on Tiananmen Square in central Beijing,
daringly placing their careers on the line.
   Their message to the government: Give more money to education.
   One group came with shoeshine kits to parody government
suggestions that students and faculty work to supplement the
schools' meager budgets.
   Another group came with signs in English and Chinese, saying:
``We want more money for education.''
   At Beijing University, China's most prestigious, posters have
appeared saying that current financial strictures have made it
``useless to study,'' just as political oppression did during the
Cultural Revolution of 1965-75.
   The academics timed their protests to coincide with the National
People's Congress, China's legislature, which today concluded an
annual 20-day session.
   Although the shoeshiners were quickly escorted by police off the
square, officers allowed the sit-in by 19 students and teachers.
More important, delegates to the congress acknowledged the
protesters' grievances are real.
   Xu Jialu, a delegate and vice president of Beijing Normal
University, questioned the congress about the policy whereby
associate professors earn $33 a month: ``Is he or she worth so
little?''
   Shanghai delegates spoke of the ``devaluation'' of
intellectuals, and former congress Vice Chairman Zhou Gucheng said
some academics can't even afford to buy dictionaries. ``All this
should not continue if the country wishes to develop,'' he said.
   The response to the protests has been markedly different from
the conservative backlash that followed much larger pro-democracy
student demonstrations in December 1986 and January 1987.
   At that time, students were arrested and Hu Yaobang, the
Communist Party head, was purged from his post.
   Since then political activism has died out on campuses, with
students cowed by increased surveillance and threats of poor job
assignments upon graduation.
   The recent protests have avoided trouble because they have
stayed away from politically sensitive areas. They also came at a
time when some powerful officials are pushing for more money for
education.
   The current government of senior leader Deng Xiaoping and
Communist Party head Zhao Ziyang has recognized that intellectuals
are crucial to the nation's economic development and has tried to
raise their social status.
   Last year, millions of teachers and scientists were given 10
percent pay raises, their first in years.
   But Xu Pei, a young teacher demonstrating on Tiananmen Square on
Sunday, told Canadian Television that living conditions for
teachers remain ``terribly poor, you can't imagine. For instance, a
whole family with three or four or five members living in a small
room about 10 square meters (110 square feet).''
   Xu, who said he earns $24 a month, considerably less than a
manual laborer at a profitable factory, said he didn't want special
treatment for teachers.
   ``We only want teachers to get equal pay with other walks of
society. We think we are low, we are mistreated.''
   Educators say inadequate state funding for China's 640,000
undergraduate and 45,000 graduate students is seriously undermining
academic achievment.
   The state allocates around $485 a year for an undergraduate and
$1,080 to $1,620 for research students.
   Funding for education is to be boosted by 12 percent this year,
but much of that is for the daunting task of improving
elementary-level education in rural areas where 200 million people,
20 percent of all Chinese, remain illiterate.
   Party chief Zhao has told institutes of higher education that
they will have to fend for themselves, saying it is ``necessary and
possible'' for them to earn money by setting up factories and
providing other services to society.
   The State Education Commission also has proposed the financial
crunch be eased by having students, who now receive basically free
educations, pay their own tuition and be responsible for finding
their own jobs when they graduate.
   By 1993, according to one plan, 70 percent of undergraduates
will be paying tuition or will be sponsored by companies that will
hire them after their studies are completed.
   The reform, also designed to motivate students to study more, is
generally accepted as necessary. But qualms remain.
   ``Students,'' said demonstrator Xu, ``now can't see any future
for them because upon graduation they can't hope to make as much
money as a worker.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AviationModernization Bjt   04-13 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aviation Modernization, Bjt,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: FAA Underestimates Cost of Upgrading Air Traffic System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration's
ambitious modernization of its air traffic control system will cost
billions of dollars more than the agency estimates because of
unforeseen technical problems and delays, a congressional report
says.
   Largely because of unexpected problems in developing and
installing the new communications, radar, weather observation and
computer systems, the upgrading will cost at least $24 billion, the
General Accounting Office told Congress Tuesday.
   The FAA, which operates the air traffic control system and is
obtaining the new equipment, acknowledges that the program has
fallen behind schedule but has put the expected cost at $15.3
billion.
   ``Many of these technologies had to be invented, and the FAA
underestimated how long it would take to invent some of these
things,'' Kenneth M. Mead, an associate director of GAO, told the
House transportation appropriations subcommittee.
   The report by GAO, Congress' investigative arm, also said
hundreds of pieces of equipment that are being delivered to FAA
facilities across the country are simply sitting in sheds because
the agency lacks enough workers to install them.
   ``It's like ordering a piano and not having a living room to put
it in,'' said Rep. William Lehman, D-Fla., chairman of the
subcommittee.
   FAA Administrator Allan McArtor said in an interview after the
hearing that the GAO figures were ``misleading,'' but acknowledged
that the plan, introduced in 1981, is running behind its original
timetable.
   The GAO report focused on the National Airspace System plan, the
second largest civilian technology project ever undertaken in the
United States, behind only the Apollo manned spacecraft program.
   Federal officials believe the new equipment is necessary to keep
up with the continuing growth of aviation, the fastest growing
segment of American transportation.
   The FAA originally hoped the new equipment would be in place by
1996. But officials now concede that because of delays, the project
will not be completed until at least the year 2000.
   The study by GAO said that of the 12 major systems that comprise
the modernization project, only one _ a computer _ is nearing
completion. Major components have been delayed from between one
year and five years, the report said.
   Reagan administration officials have blamed many of the delays
on the slowness of federal purchasing procedures, and on a refusal
by Congress to provide enough money to buy the equipment.
   Meanwhile, a broad coalition of aviation groups, aircraft
manufacturers and airlines called on not only the industry but air
travelers to put pressure on the government to expand airspace and
airport capacity.
   The coalition, forming a group called Partnership for Improved
Air Travel, announced a two-year campaign to enlist grassroots
support for spending more money on airports and improvements in the
air traffic control system.
   The air traffic modernization plan must be put ``on a fast
track'' and new airports must be built or air travelers will face
declining service, mounting delays and travel problems in the
coming years, the coalition warned at a news conference.
   ``Unless we modernize the (air traffic system) quickly, we'll
choke off growth to the detriment of all,'' declared Robert
Crandall, chairman of American Airlines.
   Crandall was among five airline chief executives, and leaders of
groups representing aircraft manufacturers, business flyers,
private and commercial pilots and airport officials who attended a
news conference announcing the campaign.
   The group envisions spending up to $15 million over the next two
years to publicize the need for more airports and an improved air
traffic control system.
   ``The nation has not yet made a commitment to create an
(aviation) system that can efficiently meet today's demand and
anticipate tomorrow's,'' said Herbert Kelleher, the chairman of
Southwest Airlines, who also is chairman of the new coalition.
   Among the complaints voiced by the coalition were: too few air
traffic controllers are being hired and trained, federal efforts to
modernize the air traffic control technology is way behind
schedule, there are too few airports and the Federal Aviation
Administration needs to be restructured because it is hamstrung by
bureaucratic restrictions.
</TEXT>
