<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-MarineKilled 3rdLd-Writethru a0403 04-13 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Marine Killed, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0403,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Marine Killed in Panama</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CORRECT spelling of victim's hometown, SUB 12th graf, `The
dead ... LeJeune, N.C.' Picks up 13th graf, `Villahermosa ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Marine sentry was killed at an
American military facility, and U.S. officials said he apparently
was caught in crossfire between fellow guards on a night search for
intruders.
   A Pentagon spokesman in Washington said the identity of the
intruders was not known, but members of the Panamanian Defense
Forces are thought to have slipped into the facility before.
   A spokesman for the U.S. Southern Command in Panama said there
was ``no reason at all at this time to suspect'' that the
Panamanian military was involved in Monday's shooting. He said it
appeared to be an accident.
   The disaster was the second to befall U.S. troops in Panama on
Monday. Earlier, two helicopters collided on a runway at another
base about 50 miles away, injuring eight soldiers.
   The Pentagon spokesman, Dan Howard, said there have been a
series of intrusions at Howard Air Force Base in the past several
weeks by ``individuals who were uniformed and camouflaged.''
   ``When one has intruders into the base perimeter, who are in
uniform and are camouflaged, the assumption that one comes to is
that of course they are'' members of the Panamanian Defense Forces,
Howard said.
   However, Martin Alberto Paz, a spokesman for the Panamanian
military, said the Defense Forces had ``absolutely nothing to do
this'' shooting, and another official accused the United States of
trying to create an incident.
   ``This insinuation tries to implicate the Panama Defense Forces
in an incident in which only United States soldiers participated,''
Maj. Daniel Delgado Diamante told a news conference Tuesday evening.
   And Lt. Cmdr. Doug Schamp, a U.S. Navy spokesman attached to the
Southern Command, said ``we have absolutely no indication'' the
Defense Forces were involved in the shooting.
   The Defense Forces are under the control of Panamanian strongman
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, who has been indicted by a U.S.
federal court on drug trafficking charges. The Reagan
administration has used diplomatic and economic pressure to try to
drive Noriega from power.
   Pentagon and U.S. Southern Command officials said the Marine
apparently was shot by fellow guards while investigating a break-in
at Howard Air Force Base, on the other side of the Panama Canal
from Panama City.
   The dead man was identified as Cpl. Ricardo M. Villahermosa, 25,
of Santurce, Puerto Rico, a member of I Company, 3rd Battalion, 4th
Marine Regiment of Camp LeJeune, N.C.
   Villahermosa was one of nearly 2,000 Marines and Army personnel
dispatched to Panama in the past few weeks to increase security for
the canal, other U.S. installations and American citizens.
   U.S. Air Force Col. Ron Sconyers of the Southern Command said
Villahermosa was part of a 12-man Marine patrol at the Arriajan
Tank Farm, a fuel storage area near the air base.
   He said the Marine suffered massive internal bleeding from a
single bullet.
   The Southern Command and the Pentagon issued identical
statements saying the shooting ``occurred after an apparent
intrusion by six or eight individuals'' into the tank farm area.
   ``U.S. security forces patrolling the area had split up and were
in the process of rejoining when a trip flare was set off, sounding
like gunfire,'' the statement said.
   ``In response, the two elements of the patrol fired. Seven
rounds were discharged before the on-the-scene commander ordered a
cease-fire. Initial indications are that the fatal gunshot wound
was not the result of hostile gunfire, but rather the result of a
crossfire from the U.S. shots fired.''
   In the helicopter accident, eight soldiers were injured slightly
when two UH-60 helicopters collided at Fort Sherman, about 50 miles
north of the capital. They were not immediately identified.
   The Southern Command said they were permanently assigned to Fort
Kobbe near Panama City, one of 10 U.S. military installations along
the canal.
</TEXT>
