<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GangViolence     04-13 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Violence,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen Arrested in Gang-Related Shootings; Guardian Angels Also
Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-age gang member has been arrested in
connection with a drive-by street shooting that left one dead and
11 injured and prompted an intensive police crackdown on
drug-dealing gangs.
   ``He was very belligerent and portrayed himself ... as a real
bad guy, until he was informed that he was being arrested and
booked for murder, whereupon he broke down and cried like the big
coward that he really is,'' police Chief Daryl Gates said.
   Also Tuesday, five members of the crime-fighting Guardian
Angels, including the group's founder, Curtis Sliwa, were arrested
while protesting Friday's scheduled release of the gang movie
``Colors.''
   The teen-ager arrested in the drive-by shooting was a known gang
member, police said. He was not identified because of he is a minor.
   A 19-year-old man was killed and 11 others, including a child,
were wounded in the April 1 shooting in south-central Los Angeles.
Police are seeking two others in the case.
   City Council has approved spending $4.5 million for police
overtime by a 1,000-officer anti-gang task force that has so far
made made 1,453 arrests, including 794 gang members.
   District Attorney Ira Reiner said the crackdown has disrupted
gang activity and heightened public awareness. The district
attorney's office has filed charges in 59 of 118 cases resulting
from the street arrests.
   Those cases rejected were dismissed for insufficient evidence,
said Deputy District Attorney Stephen Kay, as were half of 41 cases
sent to the city attorney's office.
   Despite the citywide gang crackdown, four people were killed in
drive-by shootings last weekend, and nine were wounded in a similar
attack in suburban Willowbrook, authorities said.
   Police said the five Guardian Angels arrested Tuesday were
trying to force their way into the offices of Orion Pictures, which
produced ``Colors,'' a movie that anti-gang groups contend
glorifies gang violence.
   Sliwa and the four others were booked for battery after
scuffling with security guards and were held on $500 bail each,
said police Sgt. B.P. Kelepecz.
   Reiner, however, came out in support of ``Colors,'' saying it
may spur public support for the war on gangs. ``This is not `West
Side Story' revisited,'' Reiner said. ``These are not darlings who
are going to dance their way into your heart. These are sociopathic
killers.
   ``It's not the old days of switchblades and tire irons,'' he
said. ``You're dealing with Uzi machine guns and MAC 10s and mean
streets, very mean streets.''
   Police say there were 387 gang-related murders in Los Angeles
County last year and more than 85 such homicides have been reported
so far this year.
</TEXT>
