<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     04-13 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Democrats Would Bring Back Carter Malaise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush says he hopes
indicted former White House aides John Poindexter and Oliver North
are found innocent in the Iran-Contra affair but will keep his own
counsel on the subject of a pardon if they're not.
   Bush also conceded ``I've taken a lot of shots'' from Democrats
for refusing to reveal private advice he had given President Reagan
on the subject of arms sales to Iran.
   ``But it doesn't bother me, because I'm doing what's right,'' he
said Tuesday.
   The vice president was asked whether he would pardon Poindexter
and North if elected.
   ``I hope, my own personal hope is, they're found innocent of any
wrongdoing,'' Bush said.
   All but assured of the Republican presidential nomination, Bush
campaigned in New York saying he doesn't see much difference among
the three Democratic contenders.
   Bush called the Democratic contest, heating up here in advance
of the crucial New York primary next Tuesday, a ``bloodletting.''
He accused all three Democrats of seeking to ``set the clock back
to the malaise days'' that he said marked former President Jimmy
Carter's term.
   Bush planned to visit a public school in East Harlem today
before campaign stops in Buffalo and Rochester.
   At the school stop, Bush was expected to stress a favorite
campaign theme - a greater emphasis on education.
   He was also making a bid for minority votes. Asked on Tuesday if
Jesse Jackson's candidacy would make it difficult for Republicans
to attract black votes, Bush conceded it probably would, telling
reporters in Syracuse, ``There's sort of a race pride there that I
understand.''
   But, he added, ``I think my message of hope and opportunity,
more employment, a better shot through education, offers more hope
than some of those age-old Democratic answers that have failed.''
   Bush threw out the first ball at a Mets game at Shea Stadium on
Tuesday, then attended a $1,000-a-plate evening fund-raiser
sponsored by New York developer Donald Trump.
   Even though he has a lock on the GOP nomination, Bush has
indicated he plans to campaign throughout the remaining primary
season _ particularly in vote-rich states like New York.
   ``We've got to get into these states and command a presence,''
said Bush aide Peter Teeley.
   Bush, in a session with New York broadcast reporters, said any
discussion of pardoning Poindexter and North was ``too
hypothetical. A pardon imputes guilt. And the American system after
all is innocent-until-proven-guilty.''
   ``I'm not going to get into that,'' he added. ``If I had to face
that at some time, then I'll keep my own counsel and make my own
decision.''
   Bush also said he strongly opposes creation of a Palestinian
state _ a subject that has become a major issue on the Democratic
side.
   Jesse Jackson has said he favors a Palestinian homeland.
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. has also accused Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis of harboring similar sympathies, which Dukakis
denies.
   ``There shouldn't be a Palestinian state,'' Bush said. ``It's
not good foreign policy. Solving the Palestinian problem is.''
   On another subject, Bush told reporters that he did not think he
was too aristoratic to build wide support.
   ``If so, why would I have cleaned them (Republican rivals) up in
the primaries?'' he asked.
   ``For you to suggest that some aristocratic bias makes it
impossible for me to reach out - just you watch,'' Bush declared.
</TEXT>
