<HEAD>Off-Duty Correction Officer With Gun Whisked Out Of Jackson Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An off-duty city correction officer was whisked
out of a rally for Jesse Jackson in the Bronx on Tuesday night
after Secret Service agents noticed that he was carrying a gun,
police said.
   According to police, Capt. Henry Mack, assigned to the Manhattan
House of Detention, was attempting to take a photograph of the
candidate when the agents observed the gun in his waistband.
   ``As far as we know, he hasn't done anything wrong,'' Sgt.
Raymond O'Donnell, a police spokesman, said of Mack, who was not
charged with anything.
   Ruby Ryles, spokeswoman for the city's Correction Department,
said: ``He has peace officer status. That enables him to carry a
weapon legally.''
   O'Donnell said the incident happened at 9:50 p.m. at a rally for
the Democratic presidential candidate. Secret Service agents saw
the .32-caliber semi-automatic and took Mack out of the room, he
said.
   Barry Thumma, an Associated Press photographer who was covering
Jackson, said agents encircled Jackson and escorted him off the
stage in the opposite direction.
   Thumma said Jackson left the stage for a few minutes and then
returned and continued giving his speech, without explanation to
the audience.
   A dispatcher at the Secret Service office in New York, who
declined to give his name, said no one would be available to
comment until Wednesday morning.
