<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Sweden-School     04-13 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Sweden-School,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swedish School Appeals For Arab Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suburban school, apparently
disillusioned with the Swedish welfare system, has asked a wealthy
Arab sheikhdom to finance improvements, Sweden's national news
agency TT reported.
   The parents' organization of the Hjulsta comprehensive school
wrote a letter for publication in the Daily News in Abu Dhabi,
capital of the United Arab Emirates, that made the appeal and
detailed poor conditions at the school.
   It is located in an area with a high concentration of immigrants
and has pupils speaking 33 languages. Under Sweden's welfare
system, all schools are free but generally lack facilities to deal
with exceptional problems.
   ``It's a wonderful idea and I hope (Swedish) politicians are
really ashamed of themselves,'' said Harriet Martin who initiated
the appeal. ``I'm positive they (the Arabs) will help us,'' she
told Swedish Radio.
   TT, illustrating the problems, said on Tuesday that one
geography textbook used in the school was older than the United
Arab Emirates, created in 1971.
</TEXT>
