<HEAD>Victim Angry Over Attacker's Planned Legal Action Against Her</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman who was raped and mutilated
by Lawrence Singleton says his impending release and reports that
he is seeking court action against her have prompted her to renew
her court battle with him.
   Mary Vincent, left for dead after Singleton raped her and hacked
off her forearms, said Tuesday she has instructed her lawyer to
serve Singleton with a $2.4 million judgment she won against him
last year in Nevada.
   ``Before today's news ... I was almost ready to live and let
live, and go on with my life. That is no longer possible,'' Vincent
said Tuesday.
   Singleton was convicted of the rape-mutilation in 1978 and was
sentenced to a 14-year, four-month term. He is due for release from
San Quentin state prison on May 25.
   Vincent's statement, read by a spokesman for her lawyer, came
after a newspaper reported Monday that Singleton was seeking an
investigation into his claim that she kidnapped him at knifepoint
while hitchhiking.
   Singleton was paroled last year for good behavior and work
credits, but for the past 10 months has been living in a mobile
home on the San Quentin prison grounds after residents of several
Northern California communities fought plans to place him in their
towns.
   Singleton, who maintained that other hitchhikers were
responsible for the attack on Vincent, also told the Daily Ledger
of Antioch that he may spend his first days of freedom with a
church group in Oregon.
   Vincent, whose attorney says only that she resides in the
Pacific Northwest, was reported last year to be living in southern
Oregon.
   The pastor of a church in Azalea, Ore., said Tuesday that
Singleton would be welcome to live with church members after he
regains his freedom.
   ``We'd be liars if we denied him a home now,'' Tom Smith Jr.
told The News-Review of Roseburg, Ore. ``He would have to agree to
living our lifestyle, which is caring more for your brother than
yourself, and not everybody is willing to do that.''
   Smith said he hasn't been in touch with Singleton, though he had
tried to reach him through the parole division in California.
   When Singleton was due to be paroled, Smith offered him a job as
a handyman with the Bride of Christ Church, but Oregon officials
denied permission for Singleton to move to the state.
