<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0401,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiations With Hijackers Begin In Algeria</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NIC1, NIC2, NIC3, NIC4</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Algerian officials
negotiating with hijackers. Pickup 12th graf pvs, ``On Tuesday...''
TRIMS thereafter to tighten. ^By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Algerian authorities opened negotiations
early Wednesday with Shiite Moslem hijackers less than two hours
after their comandeered Kuwaiti jumbo jet with about 40 people
aboard landed on a flight from Cyprus, the official news agency
reported.
   Algerian Interior Minister Hedi Khediri was seen going in a
convoy of three cars to the plane, which was isolated on the tarmac
of Houari Boumedienne airport with spotlights trained on it. The
convoy returned 10 minutes later.
   There were reports Khediri was accompanied by Transport Minister
Rachid Benyelles and the head of state security, Abdelmadjid
Bouzbid.
   The APS news agency said negotiations started at 4:50 a.m.
(11:50 p.m. EDT Tuesday). Algerian government sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity, specified that negotiations were direct,
not by radio.
   Activity continued around the Kuwait Airways aircraft, but
nothing could be clearly distinguished from a distance. Reporters
were being kept in the terminal area 400 yards from the aircraft.
   The Boeing 747 left Larnaca, Cyprus, after the gunmen freed 12
more passengers in what they called a gesture of goodwill. The
hijackers have killed two passengers during the grim nine-day
odyssey.
   The plane landed in Algiers at 3:07 a.m. (10:07 p.m. EDT
Tuesday). Hours later, its red navigation lights continued to blink.
   The Algerian sources said rooms were readied at the Aurassi
Hotel, overlooking the city center, in the event they were needed
to take in hostages.
   Earlier in Cyprus, Akis Fantis, a government spokesman, told
reporters ``sources in Algiers'' gave assurances that the gunmen
would give up the hostages and the plane in Algeria, but one of the
hijackers denied it.
   The hijacker said by radio just before takeoff: ``We deny what
has been reported by radios and by the media that we are ready to
hand the plane to anyone. We refuse to do that, until martyrdom.''
He did not mention hostages.
   On Tuesday in Larnaca, the gunmen said they had donned death
shrouds and had renamed the jetliner ``the plane of martyrdom.''
   About 40 people, including the six to eight hijackers, remained
aboard the Kuwait Airways jet. It was commandeered April 5 on a
flight from Bangkok to Kuwait and spent three days at Mashhad,
Iran. It was subsequently allowed to land at Larnaca because it was
low on fuel.
   One of those freed in Cyprus said three members of Kuwait's
ruling family, Fadel Khaled al-Sabah and his sisters, Anware and
Ebtesam, still were on the plane, according to Dr. George Olympios
at Larnaca General Hospital, where the freed hostages were taken.
   ``No one is in a grave condition,'' Olympios said of the
released hostages. ``Most are in good health but are staying for
observation; nothing serious apart from fatigue.''
   Twelve passengers walked off the aircraft at 10:25 p.m. Tuesday
(3:25 p.m. EDT) in Cyprus and got into three ambulances as the
flashing lights from the plane and emergency vehicles illuminated
the runway.
   The hijackers have demanded that Kuwait free 17 pro-Iranian
terrorists, all but one of them Shiites, convicted and imprisoned
for a chain of bombings there in December 1983. Kuwait refuses.
   Inside the plane on Tuesday in Cyprus, the captive passengers
sweltered through the day under the Mediterranean sun. Some of the
passengers, who have reportedly been beaten, were nervous and
disoriented as the hijackers forced them to talk to the Larnaca
control tower.
   Fadel Khaled al-Sabah, a businessman and cousin of Kuwait's
emir, Shieik Jaber al-Ahmed al-Sabah, could barely speak when the
hijackers put him on the radio to plead for fuel.
   ``We depend on God for our fate,'' he said in a strained voice.
</TEXT>
