<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Trade     04-13 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Officials, Senators Open Bargaining on Veto-Proof Trade Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan administration officials are bargaining
with lawmakers over what kind of trade bill the president would be
willing to sign, but neither side appeared to be yielding ground.
   ``We had a good healthy discussion,'' U.S. Trade Representative
Clayton K. Yeutter said Tuesday after a 30-minute session with
three key senators that the participants acknowledged was
inconclusive.
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, merely
said the meeting ``confirmed some of the things that I had
thought,'' but indicated he had not gone into the session expecting
a quick deal.
   Also on hand for the session in Bentsen's office were Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III and Sens. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., and
John C. Danforth, R-Mo. The idea was to find out what items must be
dropped from the 1,000-page trade bill moving in Congress to
guarantee that President Reagan would sign rather than veto it.
   Confusion surrounds the bill because most of it has been
approved under a complex system set up by a conference committee to
resolve differences between House and Senate versions. Farm
lawmakers have been unable to finish their work and another panel
has yet to act on provisions requiring disclosure of foreign
holdings in this country.
   The Reagan administration opposes some of the provisions that
did get approval.
   One is a requirement that major employers give notice of plant
closings and large-scale layoffs. Another is trade sanctions
against Japan's Toshiba Corp. for the sale to the Soviet Union of
equipment that lets submarines run quietly.
   Lawmakers say they think Reagan would sign the central
provisions of the measure that streamline machinery for retaliation
against trade violations, including transfer of authority to order
such action from the president to the U.S. trade representative.
   But the possibility remains that lawmakers, who had tried to
have a final product before their spring break last week, will
decide to go back to the drawing board for one last effort to get
the measure into shape.
   Hours before the meeting, House Speaker Jim Wright warned
lawmakers against watering down the bill by dropping its most
stringent provisions in an effort to prevent a presidential veto.
   ``It is not really prudent for the White House to try to get the
last pound of flesh,'' Wright told reporters.
   Wright said the administration's ``persistent opposition to
several elements of the trade bill creates doubt as to whether it
really understands even yet the seriousness of America's
competitiveness problems.''
   ``What does the White House really want?'' Wright said. ``Surely
it shouldn't want to lobotomize the trade bill as the price for the
president's signature. Its spokesmen seem repelled by those
provisions which are bold enough, creative enough and potent enough
to deal with our persistent and growing superdeficit in trade, so
inappropriate for a superpower.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday there had
been ``notable progress on the trade bill'' but ``improvements must
be made.''
   ``The administration is prepared to continue working with the
congressional leaders and the full conference on an acceptable
bill,'' Fitzwater's statement said.
   ``But let there be no misunderstanding _ the president will not
hestitate to veto a trade bill that will hurt America's economic
prosperity,'' it added.
</TEXT>
