<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Curran-Catholic     04-13 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Curran-Catholic,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trustees Revoke Curran's Authority To Teach In Name Of Vatican</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Charles Curran says his battle with
Catholic University may be nearly resolved even though the
university's board of trustees stripped him of his authority to
teach theology in the name of the Vatican.
   Although they revoked the suspended theologian's ``canonical
mission,'' the trustees Tuesday allowed him to remain as a tenured
professor and conceded Curran can teach at the university in
programs other than those requiring Vatican sanction.
   ``This action does not remove Father Curran's tenure with the
university,'' the university said in a statement. ``It does bar him
from teaching in the university's Department of Theology.''
   Curran has dissented from church doctrine on a range of sexual
issues, expressing the view that contraception and sterilization
``are not intrinsically evil'' and that the church should allow
divorce ``in certain circumstances.'' He also said that for a
``genuine homosexual, homosexual acts in the context of a loving
relationship striving for permanency can in a certain sense be
objectively and morally acceptable.''
   The trustees directed top board members to talk with Curran
about ``an alternative teaching assignment within an area of his
professional competence.''
   That would leave him able to teach at Catholic, but outside of
the Department of Theology where the internationally known
theologian has taught for 22 years.
   The action sets up a possible end to a controversy that has
pitted the conservative church hierarchy against liberal Catholics
in the United States.
   It comes a week after a judge rejected the university's request
to dismiss a suit by Curran seeking his reinstatement.
   Curran has claimed in the lawsuit that he should be allowed to
teach classes that do not require the canonical mission, a form of
license to teach programs accredited by the Vatican.
   ``The board's action appears to acknowledge that such a
resolution may now be acceptable,'' Curran said in a statement
released Tuesday by his lawyers.
   ``If that proves to be correct, then we should be able to move
quickly to put this matter behind us and get on with our work,'' he
said.
   Curran's attorney, John Hunt, said Curran would only accept a
teaching assignment that is ``for real. His area of competence is
moral theology.''
   Curran has been suspended from teaching at Catholic since
January 1987, when Washington, D.C., Archbishop James A. Hickey,
chancellor of the school, acted on a Vatican ruling that Curran's
views on sexual issues left him ``neither suitable nor eligible to
teach Catholic theology.''
   Curran is now a visiting professor at Cornell University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
