<HEAD>Taxpayers Sink IRS Officials</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY ROSE DONAHUE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few local IRS officials were fully
``de-dunked-able'' this week for grinning taxpayers eagerly
spending their adjusted gross income for the chance to sink a tax
collector in a 4-foot-deep ducking booth.
   At $2 for three shots, it was an experience not to be
depreciated.
   The windup. ... The pitch. Whoosh. Whap! Splash!
   And IRS data processing manager Rick Denzio went into the drink.
(See paragraph 8.)
   ``It felt real good,'' exulted businessman Carlos Stewart, who
paid for the pitch that dunked Denzio at ``Tax Bash'' festivities
Tuesday, three days before the midnight filing deadline. ``I've
been audited a time or two and went through a lot of stress.''
   Stewart, a businessman from Temple, Texas, was in town for a
professional conference, which, of course, remains deductible under
the provisions of the Tax Reform Act of 1986.
   That act, you recall, was the sweeping tax simplification law
that somehow created 40 new tax forms to fill out and required
changes in 200 existing tax forms. (Now go to Paragraph 8:)
   Paragraph 8: IRS assistant division chief Debbie Moore wore a
``Miss 1040 EZ'' T-shirt Tuesday night. How she (a) screamed as she
(b) sat on the perch and (c) watched the baseballs whiz toward the
(d) target that would (e) collapse the seat (f) and dump her in the
(g) tank!
   She would not be exempted.
   ``I'll help you file your tax return if you don't do this,'' she
pleaded with one revenge-bent taxpayer. ``You really should be
saving your money.''
   And attaching Schedule B for dividend interest over $400. The
windup. ... The pitch. ...
   The ``Tax Bash'' at the downtown Union Station marketplace also
featured a 6-foot metal 1040 form painted on the side of a
refrigerator _ and a sledgehammer for eligible taxpayers to ``fill
in'' the boxes.
   Jeff Breeding, 19, of Indianapolis, paid $1 for three
sledgehammer blows on the 1040 form, avenging the $10 dent in his
wallet he got for a filing mistake last year. ``You got to get even
somehow,'' he said.
   The windup ... the swing ... Wham!
   There was also a character dressed as Uncle Sam available for $3
per photograph, to provide a permanent record.
   For the timorous taxpayer, the authorities provided a chance to
fill out tax returns and mail them in a special postal box.
   H&R Block representatives were on hand to offer free advice,
filing returns for a fee, with $5 per return donated, like the
sporting fees, to the Muscular Dystrophy Association _
contributions that were fully tax-deductible.
   John Hendrickson of Akron, Ohio, removed his suit jacket before
taking aim at Denzio, once again on the seat (f) above the (g)
tank. (See paragraph 8).
   The windup ... the pitch ... Whap! Splash!
   ``Put it this way,'' Hendrickson said as Denzio climbed out of
the (g) tank. ``This year was a tough year to do taxes with all the
rule changes. A lot of forms. This was a good way to balance my
frustrations by doing something constructive _ getting this guy
wet.''
   ``I'm freezing,'' Denzio complained. ``The water's cold.''
   Back on the seat (f), Denzio.
   Repeat steps (a) through (g). See paragraph 8.
