<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ByrdProfile     04-13 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Byrd Profile,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Byrd Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>He Learned His Craft from the Rule Book, the Bible, the Dictionary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Carlyle Byrd once described himself as
``a perfectionist who falls far short of perfection.''
   But this one-time meat-cutter, self-educated fiddler and student
of Shakespeare, used a lifetime of hard work, attention to detail
and an ability to change with the times to rise from the coalfields
of West Virginia to become a force in the United States Senate.
   He announced Tuesday he would give up the post of Senate
majority leader at year's end, after seeking re-election to a sixth
term as senator from West Virginia. Characteristically, he first
informed his fellow Democratic senators and his home state, by a
satellite hookup to Institute, W.Va., before going public.
   Byrd had two homes: West Virginia and the United States Senate.
   He used the Bible and the Senate rule book to make his mark in
both.
   Byrd led Senate Democrats for 10 years. He was elected majority
leader after the 1976 elections and served until 1980, when Ronald
Reagan became president and Republicans took control of the Senate.
   Six years later, when Democrats returned to power in the Senate,
Byrd regained the post after brushing aside a challenge by Sen.
Lawton Chiles of Florida.
   Until Tuesday, Byrd had kept constituents and fellow Democratic
senators in the dark about his future plans.
   When he made his announcement at a party luncheon Tuesday
afternoon, one senator who had left the room abruptly returned when
told by reporters what Byrd planned to say after dessert.
   Even Speaker of the House Jim Wright of Texas learned of Byrd's
decision from a reporter.
   Byrd's rise in the Senate _ he unseated Sen. Edward M. Kennedy
as party whip in 1971 for his first major leadership post _ was
almost as dramatic as his rise from childhood deprivation.
   Byrd was born Cornelius Calvin Sale Jr. in North Wilkesboro,
N.C. His mother died at age 10, his father abandoned him and he was
sent to the coalfields to live with an aunt and uncle, Vlurma and
Titus Byrd.
   Growing up in Crab Orchard, W.Va., Byrd worked as a gas station
attendant, butcher, store clerk and welder. He learned enough to
graduate first in his high school class and he learned to play the
fiddle.
   His fiddling earned him an honorary membership in the Country
Music Association. His reading and continuing drive for education
earned him a law degree in 1963, at age 45 and after he had been a
senator for four years.
   When he first ran for the U.S. House of Representatives in 1952,
a past, brief membership in the Ku Klux Klan was revealed and Byrd
was urged to drop out of the race.
   Instead, he went on radio and explained that, ``being only 24 at
the time, I joined the order because it offered excitement and
because it was strongly opposed to communism. After about a year, I
became disinterested, quit paying my dues and dropped my
membership.''
   That same year he gave up drinking; he remains a teetotaler.
   Byrd started out a conservative on social issues, voting against
the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and against the nomination of Thurgood
Marshall to the Supreme Court.
   But his move up the Senate ladder moderated his positions. When
he voted against a Supreme Court nominee last year, it was the
conservative Robert Bork. And when the Civil Rights Restoration Act
was enacted over a presidential veto this year, Byrd was a strong
supporter.
   For all that, he has remained an individual, priding himself in
his vast knowledge of Senate rules, his ability to recite poetry at
length on the Senate floor, his ongoing re-reading of the Bible, of
the works of Shakespeare and even the dictionary, page by page,
word by word.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
