<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Byrd'sChoice     04-13 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Byrd's Choice,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Virginia's Economic Problems Weighed on Byrd's Mind</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Byrd, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE M. ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INSTITUTE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Byrd's decision to step down from
the U.S. Senate's top post and become chairman of the powerful
Appropriations Committee was welcomed by political figures in his
economically struggling state.
   Byrd's job as majority leader gave him enormous power to direct
the flow of legislation in the Capitol. But at home, where he is
running for his sixth six-year term, his clout in Washington has
been overshadowed by criticism that he has done little for West
Virginia, a state mired in poverty and financial troubles.
   ``West Virginia is hurting,'' Byrd said Tuesday. ``The recession
that began in 1981 dealt a crippling blow to West Virginia. The
economic recovery that other regions have enjoyed has for the most
part bypassed our state.''
   The state in December reclaimed the national lead in
unemployment, when it surpassed Louisiana with an 11.4 percent
jobless rate. Joblessness swelled to 13.2 percent in February, the
latest federal statistics available. One recent study found that
slightly less than one-fourth of children in West Virginia living
in poverty.
   The state also has long ranked low on the list of recipients of
federal aid, once ``transfer payments'' to individuals such as food
stamps and Social Security are excluded. Byrd said he hopes to do
something about that as chairman of the appropriations panel.
   Byrd said he ``cannot work miracles'' but he will have ``a new
opportunity to have a more direct influence on the allocation of
our nation's scarce fiscal resources.''
   Several state political leaders had urged Byrd this week to
choose the appropriations chairmanship, saying he could do more for
the state there.
   ``As majority leader, you are being a choir director for a whole
bunch of people, which minimizes the time and dilutes the
opportunities you have for your own agenda, for your own state or
district,'' said Huntington Mayor Bobby Nelson, a former state
senator who once served as a Capitol Hill aide.
   ``I'd tell him to take the appropriations chairmanship. He can
keep up better with the state and still have a powerful impact over
his colleagues.''
   Republican Gov. Arch Moore, a longtime political foe, was one of
few West Virginia politicians to criticize Byrd's decision.
   ``I would be hard-pressed to suggest that West Virginians will
notice any difference as a result of the change,'' he said in a
statement.
   Byrd's seniority gives him first option on the chairmanship,
which is being vacated by retiring Sen. John Stennis, D-Miss.
Tradition would prevent Byrd from serving as party leader and
appropriations committee chairman.
   After serving in the state Legislature, Byrd was elected to the
House of Representatives three times beginning in 1952. In 1958, he
was elected to the Senate. He became majority whip in 1971 and
majority leader in 1977.
   He faces Bobbie Myers, a Huntington moving company executive, in
West Virginia's May 10 primary election. The winner will face state
Sen. Jay Wolfe or Buckhannon resident Bernie Lumbert, both
Republicans, in the general election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
