<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignNotebook     04-13 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Notebook,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Relives Baseball Days, Trades Bons Mots With Koch, Tries
Rhyme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, captain of his college baseball
team at Yale, jumped at the chance to pitch the first ball when the
New York Mets hosted the Montreal Expos at Shea Stadium.
   But first he warmed up, tossing an apple back and forth on Air
Force II with Rep. Guy Molinari, R-N.Y., who crouched down in a
catcher's position.
   When his time in came Tuesday, the former first baseman donned a
blue Mets jacked and hurled the ball to Mets catcher Gary Carter.
   ``I was worried about making the plate, but Gary Carter surged
forward and I stopped a little short of the rubber on that,'' Bush
recounted.
   New York Mayor Ed Koch was also present for the Mets' home
opener, and talked briefly with Bush at the start of the game.
   ``I knew George Bush in Congress,'' the Democratic mayor told
reporters, suggesting they were old friends.
   But did he plan to vote for Bush for president? Koch was asked.
``Don't be ridiculous,'' the mayor responded.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   George Bush says he's been getting lots of advice on a running
mate, but none of it is solicited.
   The Republican vice president says he hasn't even begun thinking
about the subject yet.
   Still, the vice president has told reporters that suggestions
keep coming to him ``over the transom, under the door in plain
manilla envelopes.''
   At least once, this stock answer came out ``plain vanilla
envelopes.'' And more recently, the suggestions have come to him in
``plain brown evelopes.''
   One unsolicited recommendation came from former President
Richard Nixon, who suggested on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' show last
Sunday that Bush should team up with his defeated rival, Kansas
Sen. Bob Dole.
   Bush said the proposal ``was interesting,'' and noted: ``It
wasn't over the transom or under the door. It was on Channel
Four.'' That was a reference to the NBC station that airs Meet the
Press in Washington.
   It may have been in mock response to Nixon's comments that
Democrat Michael Dukakis was a word processor and Jesse Jackson a
poet.
   During his current campaign swing through New York state, Bush
was asked by reporters in Syracuse whether there was ``a Dole in
your future,'' a reference that included both the Senate minority
leader and his wife, former Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole.
   ``Could be,'' responded the vice president. ``I have great
respect for Elizabeth. ... Bob tells me she really wants to help
too. All of that is positive.''
   However he went on to insist that he still hasn't given the
matter much thought.
</TEXT>
