<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ReaganHouse Bjt 1stLd-Writethru 04-13 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan House, Bjt, 1st Ld-Writethru,540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 7th graf bgng ``However, it ...'' to correct verb.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Businessmen Paid More than $150,000 Each to Buy Reagan's New House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two industrialists who have been members of
President Reagan's ``kitchen cabinet'' and other wealthy
businessmen paid at least $156,000 each to buy the California home
the Reagans will occupy when they leave the White House.
   A Washington law firm disclosed the information Tuesday by
releasing an exchange of letters with the Office of Government
Ethics in July 1986.
   Businessmen Holmes Tuttle and Earle Jorgensen are among the 20
or so people who helped buy the home, the newly released documents
show when paired with articles of incorporation on file with the
state in Sacramento, Calif.
   Tuttle, whose son Robert is director of the White House
personnel office, is a California automotive dealer and
industrialist. Jorgensen is chairman of a steel and aluminum
distribution company, and both men have been members of Reagan's
``kitchen cabinet'' of unofficial advisers.
   An informal opinion by the Ethics Office noted that the
president is subject to neither the criminal conflict-of-interest
laws nor standards of conduct for the executive branch of
government set out in a 1965 presidential order.
   If the group of businessmen decided to give the Bel Air estate
to the Reagans, the president would not violate the standards of
conduct regulations for the executive office of the president as
long as personal friendship was the motivating factor in the
transaction, said the ethics office.
   However, it said the president must take care not to give
preferential treatment to any of the approximately 20 investors.
   The new documents were released after reporters made inquiries
at the ethics office. One of the law firm's partners, Robert
Washington, has represented the real estate holding company set up
exclusively for the Reagan house purchase, Wall Management Services
Inc.
   The lawyers for Wall Management were seeking an opinion on the
ethical and legal implications of buying and renovating a home for
the Reagans that would be sold or leased to the president.
   ``Based upon the facts as you have presented them to us, it
appears that your proposal will not run afoul of the applicable
standards of conduct and conflict of interest statutes,'' the
opinion said.
   The request to the ethics office did say the president has
appointed some of the investors, their spouses or relatives to
various commissions or federal posts.
   Standards of conduct for the executive office of the president
prohibit the use of public office for private gain or the giving of
preferential treatment to anyone.
   ``Once this proposal gets under way, the president and the
individuals involved will have to be careful not to take any
actions that would reflect adversely on standards of conduct
matters,'' said the opinion by then-ethics office director David
Martin.
   The Reagans began paying rent on the home in the exclusive Bel
Air section of Los Angeles under a three-year lease which took
effect March 1. The Reagans have an option to buy, and the White
House says the first couple is paying fair market rent.
   In an interview, Wall Management's chief financial officer, Ira
Revich, said ``approximately 20'' friends of the Reagans had bought
stock in the company. He refused to identify them. The documents
written in 1986 mention ``a group of about 18 individuals.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
