<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PresidentLook-Alike     04-13 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-President Look-Alike,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hoover Library Picks Presidential Look-Alike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SPEER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BRANCH, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man impersonating Abraham Lincoln
could have fooled some of the people at least some of the time.
   Jim Sayre, a 52-year-old truck dispatcher from Lawrenceburg,
Ky., defeated six other presidential impersonators Tuesday night in
a contest sponsored by the Herbert Hoover Museum and Library.
   Sayre, who bears a striking resemblance to the 16th president,
started sounding presidential as soon as he donned his stovepipe
hat, and began making speeches in the parking lot before the
contest.
   ``Everyone takes freedom for granted,'' Sayre said. ``And we
don't need to do that. We need to know people died to gain this
freedom.''
   Sayre handed out cards saying ``Honest, It's Abe.''
   He said he had been impersonating Lincoln since a friend
encouraged him to enter a contest six years ago. ``I've always
enjoyed history but I never did any in-depth study on Lincoln until
I started this,'' Sayre said.
   ``He mostly does it because he loves it,'' said Sayre's wife,
Mary.
   As President Ulysses S. Grant, Tom Hildreth apologized for his
hard-drinking ways.
   ``Some people say I drink too much, smoke too much and cuss too
much,'' Hildreth's Grant said. ``Well, I am who I am. I hope I
don't offend anybody too much.''
   Sayre, who beat impersonators from Iowa and Illinois who
portrayed presidents Lincoln, Grant, Kennedy, Nixon, Carter and
Reagan, will help Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad open the museum's ``39
Men'' exhibit April 23.
   The exhibit features more than 200 presidential artifacts
including John F. Kennedy's rocking chair, Dwight Eisenhower's golf
clubs, Gerald Ford's football helmet, Lincoln's shawl, Harry
Truman's fedora and walking stick and an original copy of the
famous ``Dewey Defeats Truman'' headline from the Nov. 4, 1948,
issue of the Chicago Tribune.
   Also in the exhibit will be Calvin Coolidge's electric exercise
horse and Theodore Roosevelt's branding iron.
</TEXT>
