<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0449EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DemocratsDebate     04-13 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats Debate,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Intensifies Offensive In NY Primary</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos NY11</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Gore Jr. sharpened his criticism of
Michael Dukakis at a debate by the Democratic candidates, bluntly
challenging the front-runner on welfare, prison management and the
Middle East.
   Jesse Jackson stayed clear of the confrontation as Gore and
Dukakis wrangled, sometimes heatedly, at Tuesday's forum. Dukakis
at one point indirectly suggested that Gore's candidacy may not
last long.
   ``Don't lick your chops too soon, Governor Dukakis,'' Gore
responded. ``New York's going to have a bigger say about that than
you will.''
   The sharp comment was one of several fired off by Gore, who has
been waging an aggressive campaign in hopes of reviving his
flagging candidacy. Three more Democratic forums are planned before
the state's April 19 primary.
   Jackson played the conciliator, admonishing the audience for
booing Gore and clearly enjoying the limelight. After a lifetime as
an underdog, he said, ``Now I'm one of the top dogs, and I just
love it.''
   The booing came with Gore's first offensive, in which he
maintained that it was ``not a personal attack'' for him to
criticize Jackson's advocacy of a Palestinian state. Gore went on
to say Dukakis had expressed ``a lot more enthusiasm'' for such a
state than Gore had.
   ``I didn't express enthusiasm for a Palestinian state,'' Dukakis
shot back, tapping a table top with his fingers. ``I expressed
enthusiasm for presidential leadership'' for peace in the region.
   Much is riding on the New York primary for Gore, who has yet to
win a northern industrial state. He has campaigned pugnaciously
enough for some party leaders to call on him to tone down his
criticisms of his opponents.
   Dukakis took that tack early on in the debate, which was
sponsored by the Daily News. ``Ultimately this is a race against
(George) Bush,'' the likely Republican nominee, he said.
   But Gore said in closing remarks, ``It's not a personal attack
to note for the record that neither of my opponents has had a
single day's experience in foreign policy.''
   Gore also launched a direct blast on the issue of welfare
policy, charging that Dukakis' new proposed state budget includes
``very, very deep cuts'' in poverty programs.
   ``That's absolutely incorrect,'' Dukakis responded.
   ``The newspaper accounts are wrong then,'' said Gore.
   ``No,'' Dukakis shot back. ``You're wrong. You're wrong.''
   Dukakis' budget plan proposes a 5.5 percent boost in Aid to
Families with Dependent Children, just enough to offset inflation.
The budget proposes more than $50 million for other, new programs
for the poor and homeless, and AFDC benefits have risen by 47
percent the past five years.
   Gore also went after Dukakis on prison policy, saying the
governor had backed a state program providing two-week furloughs to
prisoners, including convicted murderers, in which 11 prisoners
fled and two killed again.
   Dukakis responded with some apparent rancor. ``Al, the
difference between you and me is that I have to run a criminal
justice system,'' he said. ``You never have.'' He cited low crime
statistics in his state and said prisoners must be prepared to
re-enter society.
   Dukakis said his state's program had been revised to exclude
prisoners serving life terms and it was widely approved by
correction professionals.
   Jackson rejected Gore's claim that New York favors underdogs.
   ``I do not think that New York has an underdog complex,'' he
said. ``I was an underdog for 45 years and 11 months. And now I'm
one of the top dogs and I just love it. New York loves a winner.
And I'm a winner.''
</TEXT>
