<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0450EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Robertson-Lawsuit     04-13 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson-Lawsuit,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson, Campaign Organization Sued for Back Rent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESAPEAKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rental company is suing Republican
presidential candidate Pat Robertson and his campaign organization
for $74,606 in unpaid rent, the company's lawyer says.
   The campaign was already about three months behind in rent
payments for a suite of offices at Greenbrier Tower I when it moved
out last December, breaking its lease, said Roger Schafer, an
attorney for Greenbrier Tower I Associates.
   ``The defendants have failed to make the required payment of the
rent and late charges due under the lease, and therefore are in
default,'' Schafer said Tuesday.
   A spokesman for Americans for Robertson, the candidate's
campaign organization, said the campaign has been negotiating
payment with its former landlords but was not aware that they
planned to sue.
   ``There have been negotiations between our offices on the terms
of that lease, and we have been working with them on a repayment
schedule,'' said Barbara Gattullo, a campaign spokesman.
   The campaign owes money to other vendors but is not being sued
for payment by any other company, Ms. Gattullo said.
   ``As far as I know, this is an isolated case,'' she said. ``I do
know we have made arrangements with many of our vendors to put them
on a payment schedule, but that is nothing unusual.''
   Robertson, a former religious broadcaster from Virginia Beach,
has lost a string of presidential primaries and acknowledges that
he is unlikely to win the 1988 Republican nomination.
   Americans for Robertson has scaled back operations dramatically,
cutting staff and expenses to avoid exceeding federal campaign
spending limits.
   Robertson initially had his national campaign headquarters at
the suite of offices at Greenbrier Tower I but has relocated to
more austere offices nearby.
   Robertson himself is being sued in the rent dispute because he
signed the lease, Schafer said.
   About $18,000 of the $74,606 is back rent Robertson's campaign
owed before it moved from the building, Schafer said. Robertson and
his campaign owe the remainder for breaking the terms of the lease
by moving, he said.
   The suit was filed in Chesapeake Circuit Court last week but
will not be processed until court clerks receive a filing fee that
Schafer's office mailed Tuesday, he said.
</TEXT>
