<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HijackReax     04-13 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack Reax,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kuwaitis Celebrate Release Of 12 Hostages But Fear For Others'
Safety</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State-run television interrupted its programming
to announce hijackers had freed 12 hostages from a Kuwaiti jet
before the plane left Cyprus for Algeria. But fear lingered for
about 35 captives still aboard the plane.
   The television network played patriotic songs after the
announcement Tuesday of the development in the hijacking that began
April 5 when terrorists commandeered the Boeing 747 on a flight
from Thailand to Kuwait.
   The gunmen first forced the pilots to land in Mashhad, Iran,
where 57 hostages were freed, and then to Cyprus. There two Kuwaiti
passengers were killed and their bodies thrown onto the runway and
one passenger was freed.
   Among the hostages aboard when the jet left for Algeria were
three members of the extensive Kuwaiti royal family _ a businessman
and his two sisters.
   In addition to the hostages, there are between six and eight
Arab hijackers armed with grenades and handguns.
   State television, in an urgent broadcast, reported the departure
of the Kuwait Airways jet for Algeria.
   The minister of state for foreign affairs, Saud Al-Mazidi, told
the official Kuwait News Agency that Algeria had agreed to receive
the plane after talks with Kuwaiti leaders on Tuesday.
   He said Kuwait's emir, Sheik Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, conferred
with Algerian President Chedli Benjedid, and Crown Prince Saad
Abdullah Al-Sabah contacted Algeria's prime minister, Abdul-Hamid
Ibrahimi.
   Al-Mazidi thanked Algeria, Cyprus and the Palestine Liberation
Organization for helping arrange the release of the 12 hostages and
the flight to Algeria.
   Word that the passengers had been freed came at 10:30 p.m., just
as many people in Kuwait were preparing to retire for the night.
   Television postponed a scheduled drama to broadcast bulletins
and patriotic songs with a background of landmarks and Kuwaiti
flags.
   As the jetliner prepared to take off, the television broadcast
live from the airport at Larnaca, Cyprus, for 15 minutes including
radio conversations between the tower and hijackers. The report
ended before the plane departed.
   There was little public reaction visible at midnight in this
desert city.
   Kuwait, in line with the Islamic prohibition of alcoholic
beverages, has no bars and many businesses open at 7 a.m. and close
early. Nights are quiet.
   Several Kuwaitis on a midnight excursion to the U.S.-style
Sultan Center supermarket expressed happiness for the freed
hostages.
   ``I feel very happy for the 12 people, but I want now to know
about the others,'' said Khalid Juma, a man wearing a traditional
Arab robe.
   ``They are our brothers, and we saw them on television when they
(the hijackers) killed two and dropped them from the plane,'' he
said as he stepped out of a Mercedes Benz sedan.
   Another Kuwaiti, Juba Al-Mohammed, said: ``They have to release
everyone, not just 12.''
</TEXT>
