<HEAD>Ohio Democratic Votes Unchanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Primary elections and caucuses in other
states have narrowed the Democratic presidential field, but have
produced no detectable bandwagon effects among Ohio ``super
delegates'' to the party's national convention.
   A survey showed Tuesday that of the 15 Ohio Democrats assured of
being convention delegates, six remained in support of choices
announced earlier and the others were still undecided. Three could
not be reached, including one delegate who has been out of touch
with the state party for many months.
   In the last AP poll of Ohio super delegates March 4, there were
two votes each for Jesse Jackson and Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis, while Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois and Sen. Albert Gore of
Tennessee had one each.
   Ohio will send between 180-190 delegates to the Democratic
convention in Atlanta on July 15-18, after an involved process that
includes the May 3 primary, in which 104 delegates will be elected
from Ohio's 21 congressional districts.
   Fifty-three will be elected statewide May 3, and an undetermined
number of Ohio's 13 Democratic members of Congress, probably most,
will also be added to the present 15 super delegates.
</TEXT>
