<DATELINE>MOUNT VERNON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 81-year-old lawyer is going to his
first Republican National Convention as a delegate, something he
hasn't done since he began attending GOP conventions in 1936.
   ``That sounds good to me,'' Frank H. Walker of Mount Vernon said
Tuesday after being certified by the Illinois Board of Elections as
winner of a spot to the convention.
   Walker was a sergeant-at-arms at the 1936 Republican national
convention in Cleveland when Republicans nominated Alf Landon for
president. Walker has been to every convention in between.
   ``I was going this year anyway,'' he said. ``But I'm glad to be
going as a delegate.''
   Walker ran for delegate in 1980 and 1984, losing both times.
   Walker asked after hearing the news of his certification
Tuesday, ``Can you count on that?''
