<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0522EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Hainan     04-13 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Hainan,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China's Newest Province Gets Special Treatment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China-Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hainan Island, China's newest province, will be
granted special economic privileges designed to transform it into
an export powerhouse that generates badly needed foreign currency.
   Foreign businessmen will be welcome to set up companies or joint
ventures, and foreign-funded, high-technology enterprises will be
allowed to sell part of their electronic products on the Chinese
market.
   Hainan will be the first province to issue visas to foreigners
upon arrival, for business and tourism. The visas will last for 15
days and be valid for Hainan only, according to the official
English-language China Daily.
   Hainan, off the southern coast, was made a province and a
special economic zone by the National People's Congress, which
ended an annual session today.
   The island of 6 million people became China's 30th
provincial-level government and will be allowed to keep all its
foreign exchange earnings.
   Already, thousands of young and unemployed are streaming into
the island, creating problems for local officials. Hainan
authorities have now received 150,000 letters from jobseekers, and
say 26,000 people have come to the island in search of work. Only a
tenth of them have received jobs, China Daily said.
   Zeng Peiyan, vice minister of the electronics industry, said his
office is already negotiating with the World Bank to finance
various projects.
   By making these changes, China hopes it can catch up with its
rivals in Asia, and give the four ``economic tigers'' of Singapore,
Hong Kong, Taiwan and South Korea a run for their money.
   Liang Xiang, head of the Hainan preparatory group, said he has a
formula to make the island a success _ the ``three freedoms'' of
inflow and outflow of capital, import and export of goods, and
entry and exit of foreigners.
   Despite the freedom, there will still be a lot of restrictions.
   ``Our market economy differs from the free economy in Hong Kong
or other capitalist forms of free economy,'' Liang said in a
statement carried by the official Xinhua News Agency.
   The state will still control railways, shipping,
telecommunications, banks and other ``economic lifelines.'' In this
way, Liang said ``We shall not deviate from the socialist economic
orbit.''
   There also are doubts over whether China can overcome the
problems standing in the way of making Hainan Island a center of
commerce.
   There is a serious lack of infrastructure. People still work the
land, buildings date from the early decades of the century. Housing
is in short supply, and some peasants live in huts of mud and straw
and go without electricity.
   Travel is difficult, and there are few flights to the region,
previously part of Guangdong province.
   The Chinese say new highways, deep-water ports, railways and
power stations will be built, and that all projects that would be
helpful to the island's economic development will be encouraged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
