<HEAD>Teacher of the Year Assumes Many Roles To Awaken Young Minds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School teacher Terry Weeks has donned the garb
of a terrorist to get his seventh-grade students in Murfreesboro,
Tenn., to grapple with viewpoints diametrically opposed to their
own.
   He also has posed as Andrew Jackson and Anwar Sadat to bring
history alive in his classroom.
   On Tuesday, Weeks assumed a new role that he will play for the
next 12 months: the 1988 National Teacher of the Year.
   The 37-year-old social studies instructor from Central Middle
School in Murfreesboro appeared on national television and held a
news conference to kick off a celebratory week that includes a stop
at the White House on Thursday to receive a crystal apple from
President Reagan.
   For Weeks, who makes $25,000 after 15 years in the classroom, it
was a taste of adulation he said he wished all teachers could share.
   ``I wish somehow I could bundle it all up and as I go across the
country this next year, just kind of spread it out to the
teachers,'' he said. ``They need to know that there are news
cameras waiting on the teacher of the year when he gets off of a
plane, people wanting to know how he teaches ... and what is it
that keeps him in the classroom.''
   He also told reporters, ``I can't do the moon walk. I can't slam
dunk a basketball. ... I'm a teacher.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jim Brady, Wife Describe Plight Of Head Injury Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential press secretary James Brady and
his wife Sarah are urging Congress to expand home health care and
other services vital to head injury victims, describing vividly
their own plight since Brady was shot.
   ``My name is Jim Brady. I am a 7-year survivor of a traumatic
brain injury,'' Brady said evenly as a hush fell over a packed
Senate hearing room Tuesday. ``I know only too well the tragedy
surrounding a head injury. I am pleased that you are taking a keen
look at our problems.''
   Brady was shot during the 1981 assassination attempt on
President Reagan and at one point was reported dead. He delivered
his brief statement to the Senate Labor and Human Resources
subcommittee on the handicapped from a wheelchair, with little
expression in his face or voice.
   Mrs. Brady said Brady had received first-rate care, even down to
a 24-hour Secret Service guard by his hospital room door.
   The rude shock came when Brady was released from the hospital
and there was no support network, his wife said. She said her
family's No. 1 need is for home care for her husband, who cannot be
left alone during a short shopping trip much less the many hours of
a full-time workday.
   Mrs. Brady said families and survivors also need support and
counseling programs to cope with the tragedy that has shattered so
many lives _ children, parents, spouses and the victims themselves.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>__</HEAD>
<HEAD>HUD Plans More Housing Vouchers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Samuel
R. Pierce says federal housing officials plan to significantly
increase the number of people getting vouchers to help pay their
rent.
   The voucher program, the Reagan administration's alternative to
building more public housing, now assists about 100,000 low-income
families, with another 34,000 to be added by the fall, Pierce told
a House Appropriations subcommittee.
   HUD plans to add another 100,000 families in 1989, he said
Tuesday.
   Rather than subsidizing housing units, the program gives poor
families a voucher which can be used to pay a portion of the rent
on living space they choose for themselves. The value of the
voucher is fixed according to each family's income, leaving the
amount of additional rent flexible. The program was made permanent
by Congress last year.
   ``Vouchers give families the dignity of choice, offering them
the opportunity to locate near family and friends, schools,
churches and jobs,'' rather than in public housing projects, said
Pierce. He appeared before the subcommittee on HUD-independent
agencies to discuss his $21.6 billion budget request for fiscal
1989. HUD's 1988 budget is $18.6 billion.
   Pierce said the number of households to be assisted by various
HUD programs would increase from 4.3 million in 1988 to 4.4 million
next year.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>BLM Considering Halting Large-Scale Giveaways of Wild Horses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bureau of Land Management says it is going
to decide whether recent allegations of cruelty to animals should
mean an end to its practice of giving away large numbers of wild
horses.
   ``We're putting the large-scale adoptions under an intensive
review,'' BLM spokesman Tim Locke said Tuesday. But he declined to
confirm a report that the no-fee, large-herd ``adoption'' program
had been suspended.
   Since the mid-1970s, the bureau has offered for ``adoption'' the
wild horses taken in its roundups from the Western range on payment
of $125.
   Use of the term ``adoption'' is really a marketing tool, since
after a year the bureau gives the ``foster parent'' title to the
horse.
   Since 1984 the bureau has waived the fee for people willing to
take 100 animals or more.
   Locke said the review was prompted by recent allegations of
abuse, including one at Sheyenne, N.D., where earlier this month
bureau officials reclaimed what was left of a herd of 400 horses on
a ranch there.
   The Grand Forks (N.D.) Herald last week quoted John Boyles, head
of the bureau's wild horse and burro division, as saying, ``We're
not approving any more than those already approved.''
   Both Boyles and Robert Burford, director of the bureau, were
traveling Tuesday and unavailable for comment. Locke would say
only, ``The instruction memo has not been issued. Large-scale
adoptions are still in our regs.''
</TEXT>
