<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Reach All-Time High, Dollar Dips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed at
an all-time high for the third consecutive trading day today, while
the dollar eased back in trading against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
5.97 points Tuesday, added another 54.71 points, or 0.2 percent,
and finished the day at 26,985.55.
   ``The market is keeping the upward trend, led by electricals and
large-capital issues such as steels,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama of
Nikko Securities.
   He said a Japanese news report that the Ministry of
International Trade and Industry plans to increase voltage of
electricity for home use from the current 100 volts to 200 volts by
1995 to meet an increasing demand for large-capacity home
appliances boosted the popularity of electrical issues.
   Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's major economic daily, reported
today that MITI will talk with electrical firms on increasing
electricity voltage.
   Increased voltage may lead to swifter sales of large washing
machines, refrigerators and other appliances, and investors saw the
news as reason to buy shares in electricals, traders said.
   Shimoyama added that a strong showing on Wall Street overnight
and the dollar's stability also boosted the Tokyo market.
   In New York, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed
Tuesday at 2,110.08. It was the first time since the market
collapsed last October that the index went above the 2,100-mark.
   Prominent among gainers were steels, shipbuildings and
electricals. Drugs and oils were also firm. Losers included weak
electricals and pulps.
   Volume of the first-section trade was a heavy 1 billion shares
against 750 million shares Tuesday.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at
126.45 yen, down 0.05 yen from its close of 126.50 yen Tuesday. It
had opened the day at 126.90 yen and ranged between 126.43-126.97
yen.
   There was no notable movement in the market and the dollar
remained stable ahead of the completion of the meeting of seven
major monetary nations in Washington and the release of U.S. trade
figures for February, according to Yuichi Sawa of the Bank of Tokyo.
</TEXT>
