<2ND_LINE>PM-Ship Explosion,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Crewmen Die in Tanker Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British-registered tanker was
delivering crude oil offshore when its boiler room exploded,
killing four crew members and injuring four others, authorities
said.
   The Coast Guard said the cause of Tuesday afternoon's explosion
aboard the 865-foot Argo Iduna was under investigation. At the
time, the vessel was about 75 miles southeast of Galveston.
   The four injured crewman were airlifted by two Coast Guard
helicopters for treatment at John Sealy Hospital in Galveston,
where they arrived Tuesday night, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   Anthony Rodrigues, 28, and J.R. Yadav, 29, suffered superficial
burns and were treated and released Tuesday night, said hospital
spokeswoman Leeann Teymour. Remesh Chend, 30, was in fair condition
with burns; Ratesh Kumar, 29, was in good condition with a rib
injury, she said.
   The tanker, with the four dead crewmen aboard, remained at sea
early today, tied up to another tanker providing it electrical
power while towing was arranged. The names of the dead were not
available, the Coast Guard said.
   The explosion occurred as the vessel transferred a load of crude
oil to smaller ships for transport to shore, said Coast Guard Lt.
Bob Carson in New Orleans.
   ``As far as we know, the vessel is still seaworthy, it is
floating,'' said Petty Officer 2nd Class Ron Mench. ``Of course, it
has no power, they expect it to be towed by civilian tugs.''
   The ship was of British registry and its home port was Hong
Kong, he said.
