<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0617EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FCC-Broadcasters     04-13 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FCC-Broadcasters,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Promises Station Owners Relief from `Sham' License Challenges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission
wants to protect radio and TV station owners from frivolous license
challenges that the agency's chief says make running a station ``a
kind of Russian roulette.''
   Some of the commission's license renewal policies result in
``nothing short of extortion'' that is costly for station owners,
FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick said Tuesday in a speech to the
National Association of Broadcasters convention.
   ``I'm know you'll agree that running your business as a kind of
Russian roulette cannot help but disserve the public interest,''
Patrick said on the closing day of the convention.
   At license renewal time, a station owner can face challenges by
groups that want to compete for the license to use that station's
frequency. Radio licenses must be renewed every seven years and TV
licenses every five years.
   Challengers can easily structure an application that looks
better than the record of the existing station because they do not
have to prove they have the necessary financial and technical
qualifications to run a station, Patrick said.
   Existing procedures give preference to certain applicants, such
as those who are female, minority and from the local community. The
FCC has been concerned that existing procedures make it easy for
``sham'' applications _ those filed by groups that have recruited
someone who fits the preference criteria so they will have an edge
in the competition for the station license.
   Renewal challenges often are settled by a station owner making a
financial payment to competing applicants, he said.
   ``Petitions to deny are a useful and statutory part of the
process where they identify bona fide problems,'' Patrick said.
``But where they are filed in a bad faith attempt to extract money
or concessions unrelated to any legitimate public interest
concerns, they are nothing short of extortion and it has to stop.''
   He mentioned specifically the case of WBBM-TV in Chicago, which
currently is facing challenges to its license renewal. ``The
proceeding may put some Washington lawyers' kids through college,
but I can think of other uses for the money that would be more
beneficial to audiences in Chicago,'' Patrick said.
   The chairman said the FCC can take some actions to change
policies governing the process without need for congressional
action.
   He said the commission will formulate policies that would give
``station owners who perform acceptably a reasonable expectation of
renewal,'' while ensuring that bona fide applicants can still mount
a challenge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
