<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     04-13 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wedtech Trial Witness Admits Lying Under Oath</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense lawyers at the racketeering trial of
Rep. Mario Biaggi may have thrown a prosecution witness's entire
testimony into doubt after getting her to admit she lied under oath.
   Near the end of her testimony Tuesday, the defense had former
Wedtech Corp. bookkeepper Celia Lewis admit on the witness stand
that she had previously lied about meeting with prosecutors.
   Mrs. Lewis denied speaking with government lawyers three times
before she was forced to own up after a prosecutor spoke with the
judge.
   ``You deliberately lied a few minutes ago, didn't you, when you
said you had not met with the prosecutors?'' defense attorney
Jeffrey Glekel asked.
   ``Yes, I did,'' she replied.
   The admission came after Assistant U.S. Attorney Mary Shannon
informed the judge, first in private, and then in open court, that
she had met with Mrs. Lewis for about 90 minutes on Monday evening
and for 45 minutes Tuesday morning.
   ``The government has a duty,'' U.S. District Judge Constance
Baker Motley told the jury ``to advise the court whenever a witness
has said something which is not true which the government knows is
not true.''
   Although both sides declined to comment on the disclosure,
citing a gag order banning discussion of the case with reporters,
defense lawyers were visibly jubilant as they left the courtroom
during a recess.
   There was no allegation of wrongdoing by prosecutors who are
allowed to speak with government witnesses before and after their
testimony unless they are being cross-examined by the defense.
   Cross examination of Mrs. Lewis was completed Monday afternoon,
followed by re-direct questioning by the prosecution.
   Biaggi, D-N.Y.; his former law partner, Bernard Ehrlich; Wedtech
founder John Mariotta and four others are accused of turning the
now-bankrupt defense contractor into a racketeering enterprise that
paid bribes in return for government contracts.
   Mrs. Lewis, who began her testimony last week, has directly
linked Mariotta to a $5 million slush fund she supervised for
Wedtech officials.
   Mrs. Lewis, testifying with full immunity from the government,
also previously has topld the court she kept track of $50,000 in
payoffs Wedtech officials allegedly gave former Bronx Borough
President Stanley Simon, another defendant.
   In later testimony, a lawyer who once worked in Biaggi's law
firm said its political connections were what got the firm hired by
Wedtech.
   ``They were paid for political connections,'' said Carlos
Cuevas, a former associate at the law firm of Biaggi & Ehrlich.
</TEXT>
