<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthKorea-Corruption     04-13 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Corruption,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chun Resigns Public Posts, Blames Scandal On Himself</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Chun Doo-hwan today
resigned all his public and political posts to accept
responsibility for his brother's role in a massive corruption
scandal.
   Chun, looking tired and strained, told a news conference he was
resigning as chairman of the Advisory Council of State Elders and
as honorary president of the governing Democratic Justice Party.
   The former president said he was giving up the offices because
he failed to prevent his brother's embezzling a fortune in cash,
land and stocks through government contacts. He said his brother
should be judged sternly.
   ``I cannot but keenly feel that it was due entirely to my own
incompetence and lack of discretion that I have failed to control
and supervise my younger brother,'' Chun said.
   Chun Doo-hwan's resignation leaves him without any official
positions and appears to signal his departure from politics. As
president of the advisory council, he served as a principal adviser
to the president.
   Chun's brother, Chun Kyung-hwan, is awaiting trial on charges of
embezzlement, influence peddling and extortion while he was head of
the semi-official Saemaul Undong, or New Community, development
movement.
   The younger Chun was named to the post in 1981, while his
brother was president, and resigned last year. The movement
oversees rural and urban development projects.
   Government prosecutors say they have evidence that millions of
dollars was stolen by the younger Chun and his associates to build
a private empire that operated under official protection.
   Some government officials are being investigated on suspicion
they covered up protection to protect the president's family. The
former president has not been implicated in the corruption probe.
   ``I cannot refrain from being sorry that my foolish younger
brother has committed scandalous acts and caused uneasiness of
heart among the people,'' the former president told reporters.
   Opposition parties demanded the elder Chun cooperate with the
probe into Saemaul and prove he was not involved in the scandal.
   The opposition Party for Peace and Democracy, which has charged
the former president was involved in corruption, demands he prove
he was not involved in spiriting funds overseas.
   The opposition hopes to make the Saemaul revelations a major
issue in the April 26 National Assembly elections to embarrass the
governing Democratic Justice Party.
   President Roh Tae-woo, who succeeded Chun Feb. 25, is thought to
have sanctioned the corruption probe to discredit his predecessor
and undermine Chun's attempts to retain power. The former president
reportedly wanted to use his advisory position to wield influence
behind the scenes.
   Roh, a former general, helped put fellow general Chun in power
with military backing in 1980. But Roh promised during last year's
presidential campaign to investigate allegations of widespread
corruption under the Chun administration.
</TEXT>
