<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Gorbachev-FakeQuotes     04-13 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gorbachev-Fake Quotes,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorby Spokesman `Amused and Annoyed' By Speakes' Revelation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan-Fake Quotes, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: WorldPaper in 8th graf cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's chief
spokesman said he's ``amused and annoyed'' about Larry Speakes'
admission that the former White House spokesman attributed
fabricated quotes to President Reagan.
   ``I don't think it is the proper way to do the job, to put words
into anybody's mouth, especially your boss' mouth,'' Gennady
Gerasimov said at a news conference Tuesday.
   ``I'm not going to this. I think if I do this I will be
discovered and fired.''
   He referred to the admission by Speakes in his memoirs that he
twice attributed to Reagan statements the president did not make.
   Gerasimov speculated that the quotes were made up, including one
during a 1985 summit meeting between Reagan and Gorbachev in
Geneva, because, ``President Reagan is not always talkative.''
   ``I'm not offended. I'm amused and annoyed,'' Gerasimov said.
   ``Many strange things happen in this country that are discovered
afterward,'' he said when asked how serious he thought Speakes'
actions were. ``It's just another thing that has happened that
makes your life so interesting.''
   Gerasimov was in Boston to participate in a two-day conference
on ``Global Information: The Invisible Reshaping of Our World,'' in
connection with the 10th anniversary of WorldPaper, a journal based
in Boston and circulated in 24 countries.
   Gerasimov also predicted there will be a civil war in
Afghanistan if both sides do not accept the reconciliation program
program proposed by the Soviet-backed government.
   ``It's up to them now. We did what we could,'' he said, adding
that Moscow ``will think twice, thrice again,'' before getting
involved in such a war. ``A situation like this is not going to
happen again,'' he said.
</TEXT>
