<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0716EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-GoldenTemple     04-13 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Golden Temple,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Militants Open Fire Inside Holy Shrine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants today fired into the air
with automatic rifles and other weapons inside Sikhism's holiest
shrine.
   There were no reports of injuries from the shooting, which
occurred at the Golden Temple during a religious holiday for the
minority faith.
   Police said the 15-minute burst of gunfire panicked devotees
trying to visit the temple for Baisakhi, the anniversary of Guru
Gobind Singh's introduction of the so-called baptism by sword for
Sikhs in 1699.
   The new evidence of militants keeping weapons inside the shrine
came as tensions were increasing over the Sikh radicals' demand for
an independent nation they call Khalistan, or ``land of the pure''
in the Punjabi language.
   Police also said for the first time that the militants were
building fortifications inside the temple complex and chipping
gun-holes into walls, apparently to prevent police or soldiers from
entering the shrine.
   In June 1984, the Indian army carried out a massive raid to
drive militants from the Golden Temple and more than 1,200 people
were killed, including Jarnail Singh Bhindranwale, a militant Sikh
preacher. Five months later Prime Minister Indira Gandhi was
assassinated by two Sikh bodguards in revenge for the raid, setting
off anti-Sikh rioting in which 2,000 people died.
   Police say Sikh separatists who have been fighting a guerrilla
war for five years for an independent homeland in Punjab often take
refuge in the temple.
   The United News of India reported at least 18 deaths in the last
24 hours in Punjab as Sikh radicals kept up attacks to press their
separatist demands. More than 700 people have been killed this year
in the northern state in attacks blamed on the radicals.
   Izhar Alam, Amritsar's police superintendent, said it was not
known why the militants fired inside the temple today, except to
mark the holiday.
   He said the militants also raised flags of Khalistan atop
several buildings in the complex, including the Akal Takht, the
so-called ``throne of immortals'' where the temple's chief priest
sits.
   Witnesses said 400 to 500 devotees visited the temple today,
compared with more than 20,000 who used to come for the holiday in
more peaceful times.
   Baisakhi marks the day when, at a meeting of the Sikh masses,
the 10th and final Sikh guru called for five men to come forward
and sacrifice their lives for the faith. One by one they entered a
tent and screams were heard.
   In the end, Guru Gobind Singh presented the five men to the
crowd, all alive, and called on Sikhs to become soldiers of their
faith. He decreed Sikhs would carry swords, introducing militancy
to the erstwhile pacifist faith.
   The low turnout at the temple today may have been due to fears
of trouble and the fact that a chief Sikh priest, Jasbir Singh
Rode, called a meeting of all Sikh organizations the same day at a
seminary in southern Punjab.
   Sikh radicals maintain a separate nation is needed to keep their
minority sect from being overwhelmed by Hindus, who are more than
80 percent of India's 780 million people. Sikhs make up 2 percent
of the country's population, but they are a majority in Punjab.
They allege discrimination by Hindus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0639EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i Dollar-Gold     04-13 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Dollar-Gold,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Higher, Gold Drops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose in thin European trading
today on market hopes that better American trade figures will be
released Thursday, foreign currency dealers said. Gold prices fell.
   The dollar was supported by speculation that the February U.S.
trade deficit has shrunk from January's gap of $12.4 billion,
dealers said.
   Some economists predicted a deficit of $11.2 billion and one
Frankfurt dealer said there were rumors it may even have fallen
below $10 billion.
   The trade speculation was overshadowing today's meeting in
Washington of finance ministers from the Group of Seven
industrialized countries, dealers said.
   Finance ministers from the United States, Britain, Canada,
Japan, France, West Germany and Italy are expected to discuss the
dollar and reaffirm last year's agreement on economic-policy
cooperation and the stabilization of exchange rates.
   ``The G-7 is under no great immediate pressure to come up with
new policy initiatives right now, so the usual comforting joint
statement is probable,'' said one dealer in Milan, Italy.
   A Munich dealer said ``only the trade figures are really
important.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar dipped 0.05 yen to a closing of 126.45 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 126.80 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.6922 West German marks, up from 1.6853
   _1.4007 Swiss francs, up from 1.3967
   _5.7390 French francs, up from 5.7165
   _1.8968 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8890
   _1,254.25 Italian lire, up from 1,249.75
   _1.2360 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2370
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8450, cheaper for buyers
than late Tuesday's $1.8515.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $449.30 a troy ounce,
down from late Tuesday's $451. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $448.50.
   One London dealer said gold was pushed below its recent support
level of $450 by some mild selling during Asian trading.
   But he said European trading was very light and he expected
little movement throughout the day as the bullion market watched
the G-7 meetings in Washington.
   In Zurich, gold's bid price was $448.50 an ounce, down from $451
late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.39 to close at a bid $450.82.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.37 a troy
ounce, down from Tuesday's $6.45.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
