<DOCNO> AP880413-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0717EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bono-Election     04-13 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bono-Election,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Entertainer-Restaurateur Easily Elected Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sonny Bono, who easily won the
mayor's office of this desert resort, says his fame as Cher's
ex-husband and former singing partner was both an asset and a
handicap during his campaign.
   ``I think the celebrity status got me a lot of name
identification,'' Bono, 53, said after Tuesday's victory, but said
it was hard to overcome his image as ``a straight man for Cher'' _
who won her first Academy Award the night before.
   ``At first, he was viewed as a joke. But then he got out and
started talking to folks and became a legitimate and very popular
candidate,'' said Rebecca Kurtz, managing editor of Palm Springs
Life magazine.
   Bono, a restaurateur and the state's newest celebrity mayor, won
by almost a 2-1 margin, with 4,842 votes to 2,498 for accountant
Lloyd Maryanov, his closest competitor in the field of seven, city
officials said.
   In coastal Carmel, where actor Clint Eastwood decided against a
second, two-year term as mayor, voters elected community activist
Jean Grace to succeed him. Grace, who received Eastwood's
endorsement, got 1,144 votes. Her chief challenger, Clayton
Anderson, got 868 votes.
   In the race for the state Assembly seat vacated by San Francisco
Mayor Art Agnos, former U.S. Rep. John Burton won with 20,550
votes, or 52.2 percent, to 14,341 votes, or 36.5 percent, for gay
activist lawyer Roberta Achtenberg, 37.
   Burton, 55, held the seat between 1965 and 1975, then
represented the city in Congress until 1982, when he left office to
treat a cocaine addiction. He and Achtenberg are on the June
primary ballot for the 1988-90 term of the seat.
   Bono, who moved to the desert resort city 110 miles east of Los
Angeles four years ago, got 44 percent of the vote and Maryanov got
23 percent, with a voter turnout estimated at 55 percent, said
Assistant City Clerk Patty Bode.
   Bono will serve a four-year term with an annual salary of
$15,000. During his campaign, he said he would draw tourists back
through carefully planned events including a film festival and
concerts.
   Bono rose to fame with Cher, singing such songs as ``I've Got
You Babe'' and ``The Beat Goes On.'' Cher went on to a Hollywood
career, and on Monday won the best actress Oscar for her role in
``Moonstruck.''
   Bono and his fourth wife, Mary, 26, are expecting their first
child this week.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
