<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0719EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Robinson-Newspage     04-13 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robinson-Newspage,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frank Robinson Named Manager of Orioles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hall of Famer Frank Robinson, major league
baseball's first black manager, took the helm of a team for the
third time when he was named to replace Cal Ripken of the Baltimore
Orioles.
   Ripken was fired as manager after the Orioles lost their first
six games of the season in their worst start in 33 years. Baltimore
finished the last season with 67 wins and 95 losses.
   Robinson on Tuesday became the major leagues' first black
manager since he was fired from the San Francisco Giants in 1984.
   ``I don't think I ever felt the pressure of being in the
position of being a black manager,'' he said at a news conference.
``I am aware of the pressure of the position, but I don't let it
bother me.''
   In 1974, he became the first black major league manager ever
when he took over the Cleveland Indians. He held that post until
1977, and was made the Giants' manager in 1981.
   Only two other blacks have managed in the major leagues: Larry
Doby with the Chicago White Sox in 1978 and Maury Wills at Seattle
in 1980-81.
   Robinson has spent 13 years with the Orioles' organization, as
player, coach or in the front office, and was a special assistant
to the president when named manager.
   An outfielder, he was elected to baseball's Hall of Fame in 1982.
   Ripken, who succeeded Earl Weaver as manager after the 1986
season, was the first man ever to manage two sons _ Cal Ripken Jr.
and Billy _ simultaneously in major league baseball.
   Ripken was offered a position as special assistant to General
Manager Roland Hemond. He said he had not made up his mind about
taking it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
