<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0731EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Pizza     04-13 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Pizza,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Line Up to Buy American-Style Pizza</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Until now, the pizza sold in Moscow only vaguely
resembled the American-style pie.
   It usually consisted of a thick, doughy crust smeared with
tomato paste. Toppings, when available, included canned, cold
tomatoes, sardines, chopped egg or lumps of salt pork.
   So it was no surprise when a crowd of Muscovites lined up in
Lenin Hills on Tuesday for pizza from a specially equipped van that
is part of a joint economic venture involving a New Jersey company.
   Nearly 1,200 slices, costing $2.10 each, were dispensed by the
mobile pizzeria a three-hour period by midafternoon. Workers
couldn't say exactly how many slices were sold because some were
given away.
   ``The reaction is extraordinary,'' said Louis Piancone,
president of Roma Food Enterprises in Piscataway, N.J., at the
van's first day of operation in Moscow. ``We'll be moving through
the city to determine what the market is for opening pizza
restaurants. Judging from today at just this location, there's a
market.''
   A new law allowing Soviet firms to enter into joint ventures
with foreign companies is one of the steps taken by Mikhail S.
Gorbachev to raise productivity and provide sorely needed consumer
goods and services.
   Many Western entrepreneurs have been wary, however, saying the
rules require the joint firm's director to be a Soviet, that
hirings and firings must conform to Soviet law, and that the
venture can compete with its Western parent abroad.
   Since the law went into effect, joint ventures have been signed
involving coal, paint and fertilizer production. Pepsico Inc. last
fall signed a contract to have two Pizza Hut restaurants in Moscow,
but they have not yet opened.
   ``We thought this was a great opportunity. We thought we'd get
the Yankee spirit and come here and open this,'' said Piancone's
U.S. partner, Shelley M. Zeiger, standing in front of lettering on
the van proclaiming the ``First American Pizza in Moscow.''
   Zeiger said they intend to open as many as 25 pizza restaurants
around Moscow if the Soviet government approves and demand is
sufficient.
   Only tomato and cheese slices were sold Tuesday, but Piancone
said 20 toppings, including meat, would be sold starting today.
   He said ingredients from the United States are being used now,
but company officials hope to use some Soviet ingredients
eventually.
   ``This is part of the spirit of the joint venture,'' Zeiger
said. ``We hope to work with the Soviet agricultural people so we
can get tomatoes with just the right acidity for our recipes. And
the cheese _ we want to buy Soviet cheese, but it has to have the
right fat content.''
   He said pizza will be sold for foreign currency in a few weeks,
but only when the van is parked near hotels and areas that
frequented by tourists. Depending on its location, the van will
sell pizza for either rubles or foreign currency, but not for both
in the same day.
   Zeiger, who operates a Trenton, N.J., real estate and import
firm, said 51 percent of the profits go to his Soviet partners and
the remainder to the New Jersey company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0807EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-AnnJillian     04-13 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Ann Jillian,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jillian Gives Talk on Cancer Struggle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Jillian made nearly 2,000 people laugh
and cry as she revealed how she fought and won her struggle with
breast cancer.
   The 38-year-old actress was in Decatur on Tuesday, the third
anniversary of her double mastectomy, to share her story and
emphasize the need for early detection through self-examination and
mammography. Her visit was sponsored by St. Mary's Hospital.
   She recounted the details of her own illness, explaining that
she took the second opinion of a doctor and did not have a biopsy
immediately after finding the first lump.
   ``His advice was exactly what I wanted to hear,'' Ms. Jillian
said. ``I was doing an awful lot of work and it never occurred to
me I might have breast cancer.'' She discovered a lump in the other
breast, but chose not to alarm her husband until she was sure if it
was cancer.
   ``May I tell,'' she said. ``Please involve that one significant
other. To have them come in as `Johnny come lately' is not good.''
   Ms. Jillian's husband, former Chicago policeman Andy Murcia, sat
on stage as she spoke.
   The actress returned to work 11 days after having both breasts
removed. She continued working despite chemotherapy that made her
gain weight and lose her hair.
</TEXT>
