<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BlackApplications     04-13 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black Applications,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College Applications by Blacks Up, Suggesting End of Enrollment
Decline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intrigued by a 35 percent increase in applications
from black students for 1988-89, Brandeis University has found a
similar trend at other colleges nationwide.
   Ten of 11 schools responding to Brandeis' request reported a
growth in applications from blacks compared to the last academic
year.
   The largest increase was 52 percent at William and Mary College
in Williamsburg, Va.; the lowest was 0.33 percent at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology in Cambridge.
   Oberlin College in Ohio reported no change and nine schools did
not provide information for Brandeis' informal survey.
   Some education experts were upbeat about the figures, saying
they appeared to point to an imminent reversal of a protracted
downturn in black enrollment.
   The most recent statistics supplied by the U.S. Census Bureau
show 28.6 percent of college-age blacks enrolled in colleges and
universities in 1986, compared to 33.4 percent in 1976. The low was
26.1 percent in 1985.
   ``If this survey is reflecting the national trend, this is great
news,'' said Bob Hochstein, spokesman for the Carnegie Foundation
for the Advancement of Teaching. ``When they're up that
dramatically, it suggests that will be translated into increased
enrollment.
   ``It suggests that progress is being made and ... it's a tribute
to colleges and universities that have actively been pursuing
enrollments,'' said Hochstein, whose nonprofit foundation acts as a
think-tank for American education.
   Others were more cautious.
   ``It may result in an increase in enrollment,'' said Trevor
Chandler, dean in residence at the Council of Graduate Schools in
Washington. ``But increased applications don't necessary translate
into increased admissions.''
   Six other colleges reported increases in black applications.
They are Clemson University, South Carolina, with 51.4 percent;
Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, 37.4 percent; Rice
University, Houston, 33 percent; Claremont Colleges, California,
19.6 percent; Reed College, Portland, Ore., 11 percent, and the
University of California at Los Angeles, 10.3 percent.
   The admissions office at Syracruse University, Syracuse, N.Y.,
said figures were up from last year but did not break them down
into a percentage increase, in the survey. Brandeis provided a copy
of results to The Associated Press.
   Applications in general also were up but in lagged far behind
those from blacks alone. Claremont and Clemson, both with 15
percent, showed the highest overall rate of increase in
applications.
   Brandeis spokesman Bob Mitchell said in a telephone interview
Tuesday that the colleges polled were picked at random, with the
intention of covering as large an area as possible.
   Admissions or minority recruitment officials at several colleges
concurred in separate interviews that more aggressive courting of
blacks in recent years likely played a role in the upswing.
   Rice spokesman Bill Noblitt said his college ``blanketed the
country'' last year with information that minority scholarships
were available to gifted blacks.
   Richard Vos, Claremont's dean of admissions and finances, said
``there was a lot of hand-wringing'' in the early 1980s, when black
admissions began declining, and ``in our shop, we spent more time
and money on minority recruiting than in past years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
