<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0824EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoliceSuicide     04-13 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Suicide,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspended Police Chief An Apparent Suicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CABOT, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Little Rock's suspended police chief
apparently killed himself with a bullet to the head, authorities
said, one day after he denounced a misdemeanor theft charge against
him as unjust.
   Jeff F. ``Doc'' Hale, 47, was found dead Tuesday at his home in
this town 30 miles northeast of Little Rock, said Lonoke County
Sheriff J.O. Isaac. Hale's wife, Jean, discovered his body in a
laundry room when she came home for lunch, Isaac said.
   Little Rock City Manager Tom Dalton said the single gunshot
wound appeared to be self-inflicted. However, Isaac declined to
speculate about the death until autopsy findings were released
today.
   No suicide note was found, Isaac said, but friends said Hale was
disturbed about the allegations against him.
   Hale was suspended with pay until a charge was settled that he
took less than $200 from a drugstore cash register in February and
March. Buice Drug Store, a popular hangout for politicians and
police, is owned by the son of state Rep. George Wimberly.
   Wimberly, the store's pharmacist, is a former Little Rock mayor
who has dabbled in police politics.
   Hale, who was arrested by state police outside the drugstore
March 10, said he had an unwritten arrangement with the elder
Wimberly to borrow money from the register. Other lawmen have said
they took similar loans.
   After a court appearance Monday on the charge, Hale labeled the
accusation ``a bunch of bull.'' He was to have been tried May 24,
and faced up to a year in jail and a $1,000 fine.
   Kenneth W. Collins, Hale's neighbor of 17 years, said that
``everything was normal'' when he and the chief did farm work
Monday afternoon, although Hale was concerned about the effect of
his legal problems on his elderly mother.
   Hale promised ``to fight all this,'' Collins said.
   ``We said, `Hey, Doc, what can we do to help?''' Collins said.
``When I talked to him, he said: `I don't drink. I don't smoke. I
don't do anything wrong. And I can't believe any of this stuff.'''
   Attorney General Steve Clark, for whom Hale directed Medicaid
fraud investigations for four years, said the theft charge
``challenged at the core of what he held to be the most dear, and
that was his integrity and character.''
   Clark added, ``The pressure of that challenge, and there had to
be lots of it, in some way influenced his thinking or his decision
that led to his death.''
   Flags were at half-staff and officers wore black tape across
badges at the Little Rock Police Department, where Hale was
appointed chief Oct. 20, 1986. He joined the department in 1962.
Hale's annual salary as chief was $64,071, and he also received a
pension of $18,762 a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0834EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-UniversalHealthCare     04-13 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Universal Health Care,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mass. Legislature Passes Health Care Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Massachusetts Legislature, meeting in a
marathon session, delivered a first-in-the-nation universal health
care bill to Gov. Michael S. Dukakis by a narrow margin early today.
   The state House accepted a House-Senate compromise by a vote of
77-75, and the Senate did the same by an 18-15 margin. Those close
votes came despite overwhelming Democratic majorities in both
chambers.
   Dukakis, who has frequently pointed to the health care plan as a
national model during his quest for the Democratic presidential
nomination, has indicated support for the compromise. Legislative
leaders said he could sign it as early as next week.
   Lawmakers adopted the plan to guarantee health insurance to all
Massachusetts residents by 1992 after nearly nine months of intense
legislative debate and negotiations with a host of special
interests,
   ``It's been very difficult,'' Senate Ways and Means Chairman
Patricia McGovern said. ``It's been the most difficult piece of
legislation I have ever been involved with personally.''
   But McGovern, who first proposed universal health care for the
state more than a year ago, added, ``I think it has the potential
to be the most rewarding piece of legislation. It really is
landmark. It is historic. It is breaking new ground.''
   Dukakis' presidential ambitions were also raised at every turn
in the drive to pass the bill. ``I hear television commercials are
being held up so the governor can run with this legislation in New
York,'' Assistant Minority Leader Kevin Poirier said Tuesday,
referring to the New York presidential primary April 19.
   But a Dukakis campaign spokesman denied the report. ``I know of
no such commercials in existence,'' he said. ``Commercials aren't
made in advance. You wait until things happen and then you put them
together.''
   McGovern and House Ways and Means Chairman Richard Voke, who
co-chaired the committee that reached the compromise and were floor
leaders on the bill, pointed to heavy lobbying from a multitude of
special interests as the main factor in the close legislative
voting.
   Businesses, hospitals, insurers, labor unions and consumers all
had concerns about the bill. As late as Tuesday, labor unions were
upset by a provision in the compromise bill that potentially could
reduce public employee health care benefits by removing the issue
from collective bargaining.
   The health care bill sets Jan. 1, 1992, as the deadline for
businesses to begin offering health insurance to their employees or
begin paying an surcharge to the state so it can provide coverage
to the state's estimated 600,000 uninsured residents.
   The bill includes tax breaks, exemptions for businesses of five
or fewer employees, state-sponsored pooled insurance and the
possibility of outright state subsidies.
   Republican opponents repeatedly warned that the bill would raise
business costs, putting some out of business and discouraging
expansion of others.
   The two-part bill also renews the state's hospital financing
law, containing about $1 billion in hospital fee increases over the
next four years. Another $95 million in new revenues was added for
42 hard-pressed hospitals.
   Despite the Legislature's lengthy consideration of the proposal,
some lawmakers were still asking late Tuesday how much the bill
will cost, what it will offer the uninsured and how many people
ultimately will take advantage of the program.
   Dukakis has budgeted $78 million in fiscal 1989 as the state's
share in the first full year of the four-year universal health care
phase-in. But cost estimates over the four-year period vary widely
_ from $550 million to $1.2 billion.
   Specific health plan coverage will be decided later by a new
state agency set up to oversee the program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
