<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Extortion     04-13 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Extortion,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Demanding $1.6 Million From Japanese Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group trying to extort $1.6 million mailed poison
and explosives to five branches of a Japanese bank, police said
today.
   Authorities in Osaka said the target of the extortion attempt is
the Sanwa Bank. They said parcels containing threatening letters
along with the poison and explosives were sent in the last two
weeks to Sanwa branches in Osaka and the western cities of Okayama
and Takamatsu.
   One police spokesman said the poison included cyanide and
arsenide and that there was enough to kill about 3,000 people. He
said the explosives included picric acid and saltpeter.
   According to the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
one of the letters read: ``We have obtained 14 weapons, including
poison and explosives such as cyanide, arsenide, arsenic acid,
dynamite and black explosives for a revolution. ... We don't want
to be forced to give them to the Red Army. You'll buy them for 200
million yen.''
   The figure is equivalent to $1.6 million. The Red Army is a
leftist Japanese terrorist group.
   The police spokesman was unable to say why the extortionists
chose Sanwa. Bank spokesman Soichi Hayakawa said, ``We can't even
guess why, judging from the contents of the letters.''
   Police said the first parcel was mailed April 4 to Sanwa's
Kawara-machi Branch in Osaka. A note demanded the branch give 200
million yen in two cardboard boxes to a deliveryman who would visit
the branch three days later.
   Sanwa informed police of the attempt, and police formed a
35-member special task force. No one came for the money on April 7.
   More parcels were sent to the other Sanwa branches, with the
last one delivered Tuesday to the Takamatsu branch on Shikoku
island, about 344 miles southwest of Tokyo. This time, there were
no instuctions on what the bank should do with the 200 million yen.
   Instead, police officials said, the letter in the parcel read in
part: ``We note that our proposal has been rejected. ... We may
become the killers.''
   Sanwa, ranked fifth among Japanese banks in fund volume, is
based in Osaka and has branches in Tokyo and other major Japanese
cities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
