<2ND_LINE>PM-Nixon-South Africa,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-President Says Sanctions Not Best Tactic Toward South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increased American investments in South Africa
may do more to erase apartheid than sanctions and disinvestment,
former President Richard M. Nixon said today.
   South Africa has failed a ``moral litmus test'' on its policies
toward blacks, Nixon said.
   ``South Africa presents a problem where everybody agrees we are
against apartheid,'' he said. ``The question is what can we do
about it?''
   He said sanctions and pulling out investments should be given a
chance to work, but if they don't ``we may have to go completely in
the other direction.
   ``I do know that American corporations are one of the most
progressive forces for change and I think it's really better to
have them into South Africa, adopting policies, providing equal
opportunities and going far beyond that than their getting out and
having South African racists running'' the country.
   Nixon made his remarks on NBC-TV's ``Today'' program in the last
of three interviews in connection with his seventh and latest book,
``1999.''
