<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Ball Machines,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ball Machines Get a Reprieve</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The issue of noisy tennis ball machines
in this upscale town is being put on hold.
   Town Council members acknowledged Tuesday that most of them had
never heard a tennis ball machine and decided to hold off on
approving the first reading of an ordinance that would limit their
use.
   ``I think we need to listen to them first,'' Mayor Yvelyne
``Deedy'' Marix said. ``Then we'll rediscuss the entire subject.''
   The issue was taken up by the town's Ordinances, Rules and
Standards Committee two weeks ago after a few residents complained
about the machines, which are in frequent use on backyard courts
here.
   The residents want the machines' use limited to the same hours
allotted for heavy construction. They want the machines banned
their use Sundays.
   ``I do want to take into consideration the people who want to
sit and enjoy their patios without the thump-thwack or whatever it
is,'' said Council President Nancy Douthit.
   But Councilman Bill Weinberg said he's getting pressure from
another interest group.
   ``I've also had complaints from tennis players who don't want
their rights violated,'' he said.
