<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pakistan-Blasts     04-13 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Blasts,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teams Scour Streets for Missiles after Pakistani Blasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCHEHEREZADE FARAMARZI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAWALPINDI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of weapons teams today
combed streets for unexploded missiles from a weekend blast that
showered rockets on residential areas and killed 96 people.
   The government said Tuesday that 170 teams of explosives experts
were working around the clock and had cleared 20,000 missiles,
grenades and other weapons from the streets of the twin cities of
Islamabad and Rawalpindi.
   The weapons rained down on residents after an explosion Sunday
at a army ammunition depot, injuring nearly 1,100 and causing
secondary explosions and fire. About 100 people remained missing
today.
   The government has said the blast may have been the work of
saboteurs seeking to undermine Pakistan's position in talks on
withdrawing Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   The Defense Ministry said today it would begin detonating
unexploded ammunition in an unpopulated area near Islamabad.
   A four-man U.S. team of explosives experts so far recovered
about 20 fallen projectiles at American facilities, including the
U.S. Embassy.
   Medical vans roamed the streets and medical workers vaccinated
people for cholera and typhoid. The neighborhoods remained without
water and electricity.
   Little pockets of fire still burned today at the Ojeri Army Camp
where the initial blast occurred. Many houses in surrounding
neighborhoods were damaged, and narrow alleys were littered with
bricks, twisted metal, broken furniture and glass.
   Government teams inspected damage and promised compensation to
victims within three days.
   No official cause of the initial blast was given. But Defense
Minister Rana Naeem Mahmoud said Tuesday that military
investigators ``are not ruling out the possibility of sabotage.''
   He said saboteurs might have been attempting to put pressure on
Pakistan before the signing of the Geneva agreements on
Afghanistan, scheduled for Thursday. Pakistan has been supplying
weapons to rebels fighting the Soviet-backed Afghan government.
   Eyewitnesses said they spotted burning trucks bearing Afghan
license plates Sunday near the ammunition depot.
   The disaster has prompted several small demonstrations accusing
authorities of negligence. Some opposition leaders have called for
President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq to resign.
</TEXT>
