<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest     04-13 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paper Says Ethnic Riot Started by Azerbaijani Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethnic rioting in a southern Soviet city that
killed at least 32 people was sparked by refugees who fled the
Armenian republic for Azerbaijan, a newspaper said today.
   The report in the weekly Moscow News confirmed previous reports
from unofficial sources that Azerbaijanis who fled Armenia during
large protests in the neighboring republic sparked three days of
rioting that began Feb. 28. Today's report was based on comments by
officials of Azerbaijan.
   ``We didn't pay enough attention to the Azerbaijani refugees
from the Armenian city of Kafan, and they became the match from
which everything erupted,'' Melek Bairamova, one official, told
Moscow News.
   The newspaper did not say why the Azerbaijanis fled Armenia, but
Armenians began mass protests in mid-February for annexation of the
Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan. Armenian activists said
hundreds of thousands of people took part in the demonstrations,
but that all were peaceful.
   Moscow News said Communist Party authorities in Azerbaijan still
listed 5,120 Azerbaijani refugees from Armenia.
   The official media has said 32 people _ 26 Armenians and six
Azerbaijanis _ died in the Sumgait rioting. Armenian activists
claim the death toll was much higher.
   Sumgait Prosecutor Ismet Gaibov has authorized more than 60
arrests so far, and a team of more than 100 investigators from
throughout the country is continuing its work, the newspaper said.
   Vagif Kakhramonov, assistant director of the city Health
Department, said 81 people were treated for injuries in the
rioting, and that 16 of them remained hospitalized in Baku.
   The city Communist Party chief, Muslim Zade, the mayor,
Tavakkula Mamedov, and the police chief, K. Dzhafarov, all were
fired after the rioting, Moscow News said.
   The newspaper said Sumgait streets are empty at night, even
though a curfew was lifted several weeks ago, and that the streets
of the Azerbaijani capital Baku also are usually quiet.
   ``The situation has created psychological pressure: on trolleys,
at the market, at the airport, they only talk about what happened,
about the relations between Azerbaijanis and Armenians,'' it said.
</TEXT>
