<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTLAuction     04-13 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL Auction,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PTL Auction Comes Up Short</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGA CAY, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There were no takers for the former home
of Jim and Tammy Bakker and the PTL auction fell far short of its
$4 million goal, but ministry officials say they'll keep trying to
sell off excess property.
   The auction Tuesday brought in only $596,500 toward the $5.3
million the PTL ministry, based in nearby Fort Mill, needs to raise
by a May 2 bankruptcy court deadline.
   Only five bids were accepted on nine properties offered. Bids on
two others were insufficient and a $425,000 bid on former PTL
President Richard Dortch's home is still being considered, PTL
Trustee David Clark said.
   There were no bids on the former residence of the Bakkers, the
ministry's deposed founders, Clark said, although several people
have expressed a serious interest in the home.
   ``It's the kind of house that you have to have a special buyer
for,'' said Clark. ``And I think that person is the kind of person
who might not come to an auction.''
   The auctioneer began the bidding at $900,000 on the former
Bakker residence, a 9,300-square-foot lakeside home with 4 bedrooms
and 5{ bathrooms in Tega Cay.
   But auctioneer Rodney L. Robinson stopped the auction when he
had dropped the price to $500,000 without any takers.
   ``We didn't get an offer that I thought was substantial enough
to open the bidding,'' Robinson said afterward.
   About 40 bidders participated in the 30-minute auction.
   One of the rejected bids was $900,000 for 33 acres of
undeveloped land. Clark said that property and all others remaining
would now be sold through real estate agents.
   ``We are not going to give away the assets of the church,'' he
said.
   PTL has an estimated $60 million debt as well as a $60 million
to $80 million claim of back taxes from the IRS, Clark said.
   PTL already has laid off almost 300 of the 1,153 employees on
hand at Bakker's departure last year amid a sex scandal. Clark said
Tuesday that officials are reviewing all operations and will make
further cutbacks if necessary.
