<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LouisianaExecution 2ndLd-Writethru a0561 04-13 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Louisiana Execution, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0561,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mass Killer Dies in Louisiana's Electric Chair
^Eds: INSERTS one graf after seventh pvs, ``It was the xxx, to note
that it's 97th since 1976</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENT PRINCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANGOLA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leslie Lowenfield was executed in the
electric chair early today denying to the end that he killed his
girlfriend and four of her relatives, including her 4-year-old
daughter, in a jealous rage.
   ``Don't give up on me, although my life will be over tonight,
because the one responsible is still out there,'' said the
34-year-old Lowenfield after he was led into the death chamber at
the Louisiana State Penitentiary.
   On Tuesday, his lawyer lost appeals to the Louisiana Supreme
Court, a federal district judge and a federal appeals court.
   His attorney had argued that he should be spared because he was
a paranoid schizophrenic who could not understand what it would
mean to be executed or why he was being executed.
   Shortly after midnight, the U.S. Supreme Court refused to issue
a fifth stay of execution for him.
   Lowenfield was pronounced dead at 12:25 a.m.
   It was the nation's fourth execution this year and Louisiana's
second. The state has put to death 17 murderers since it resumed
executions in 1983.
   It was also the 97th execution in the nation to be carried out
since the 1976 U.S. Supreme Court ruling legalizing the death
penalty.
   Lowenfield, a welder from Guyana who came to the United States
from Canada in 1975 on a work permit, spent most of his final hours
with Dale Brown, head basketball coach at Louisiana State
University, and two spiritual advisers.
   The murders occurred Aug. 30, 1982, in the New Orleans suburb of
Marrero. Prosecutors said Lowenfield barged into his girlfriend's
house and shot everybody there, including her 4-year-old daughter,
as most of them were eating boiled crabs at a kitchen table.
   The victims were the girlfriend, Sheila Thomas, 27, who was a
Jefferson Parish sheriff's deputy; her daughter, Shantel Osborne,
4; Ms. Thomas' stepfather Owen Griffin, 45; mother Myrtle Griffin,
44; and Shantel's father, Carl Osborne, 33.
   Before the 1984 trial, Lowenfield was found competent, and he
refused to allow his lawyers to use insanity as a defense,
insisting instead that he was in Jacksonville, Fla., at the time
the family was killed.
   Prosecutors said Lowenfield was jealous of Osborne. They said
Lowenfield and Ms. Thomas had lived together in a stormy
relationship until earlier in the summer of 1982 when he set the
house on fire and she moved out.
   He was convicted of three first-degree murders and two
manslaughters and received three death sentences.
   Two members of the victims' family _ Connie and Byron Encalade
of Harvey _ were in the front row of witnesses when Lowenfield
entered the execution chamber. He addressed them first, saying:
``Connie and Byron, I hope y'all feel satisfied.''
   He then spoke briefly to his original defense lawyer, the
sheriff's detective who investigated the case and also the chief
prosecutor.
   Then, after professing his innocence, Lowenfield said: ``Thanks
to y'all. Peace.''
   Brown, a Catholic priest and a Catholic nun arrived about 9 p.m.
Tuesday to spend Lowenfield's final hours with him, said Warden
Hilton Butler.
   Brown, widely recognized as a motivational speaker, had been
corresponding with Lowenfield since Brown took the LSU team on a
tour of Angola's death row in 1984, Butler said.
   ``It was a lifetime here tonight _ a lifetime with Leslie, a
lifetime with the warden. You don't see it in the movies,'' Brown
said after the execution. ``I asked him several things _ Can I ease
the pain? And he said, `No, thank you.'''
</TEXT>
