<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LockSnake     04-13 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lock Snake,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicken Snake Blamed for Boater's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKEECHOBEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An accident that overturned two boats
and swept a fisherman to his death under a Lake Okeechobee lock
gate was probably caused by a 5-foot chicken snake, an investigator
said.
   ``Sometimes the truth sounds very abstract,'' said Don Grey of
the Florida Marine Patrol. ``But I'm 95 percent positive. As
far-fetched as it sounds, I have to go with it.''
   The snake apparently crawled over an electrical switch while the
two boats were in the chamber between the water-controlling gates
of a lock March 3. The locks are equipped with gates to change
water levels to raise or lower boats so they can enter and leave
Lake Okeechobee.
   The reptile's weight _ probably about two pounds, a snake expert
said _ put enough pressure on the switch to send a signal one lock
gate was shut when it actually was raised two to three feet, Grey
said Tuesday.
   That triggered the raising of the other gate, causing water to
rush into the chamber prematurely, swamping the boats and pulling
Hubert Major, 68, under one of the gates.
   Major, a retired engineer who lived in Lakeport, drowned in the
turbulent water. The other boater, Donald Blickenstaff of
Sharpsburg, Md., was able to reach a ladder on the wall and climb
out.
   The South Florida Water Management District has installed a
second switch on the other side of the gate in an effort to prevent
future accidents.
   ``There will have to be a 15-foot-long snake, or two snakes
working in cahoots with each other, to trip both of those switches
now,'' said Francis Davino, contract locktender at Lakeport.
   Chicken snakes, also called yellow rat snakes, are a common,
non-poisonous family of reptiles that can grow to 7{ feet. They
climb the lock structures to find warmth, Davino said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
