<1ST_LINE>d a PM-Obit-Rubin     04-13 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Rubin,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Art Historian Who Studied Tatoos, Rose Parade Dead at 50</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Art scholar Arnold Rubin, whose diverse
interests took him from Africa to Pasadena as he studied everything
from human tattoos to the annual Tournament of Roses Parade, has
died at age 50.
   Rubin, an associate professor of art history at the University
of California, Los Angeles, died Saturday of stomach cancer, said
his daughter, Hannele Rubin.
   He had just finished editing and contributing to an anthology on
tattoos and other forms of body adornment titled ``Marks on
Civilization.''
   ``We put holes in our noses or we don't. We put plugs in our
ears or we don't. We put designs on our bodies or we don't,'' Rubin
had said last month in discussing his studies of how human beings
adorn their bodies.
   He saw such actions as challenging the definitions of what it
means to be civilized.
   His study of the annual New Year's Day Tournament of Roses
parade in Pasadena started while he was teaching a class on art
research methods at UCLA. He recalled that he and his students
decided to find a local art event that couldn't be judged by
traditional standards.
   He said the parade caught his interest because the floats were
joint efforts, unlike most art works, which are created by a single
artist, and because the floats do not last, as traditional art is
supposed to.
   ``The measure of art is not in its permanence,'' he said of the
parade. ``This is a whole body of art born for a brief lifespan.
But this is still art.''
   Rubin is survived by his daughter and a son, Gabriel.
</TEXT>
