<DOCNO> AP880413-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Premier     04-13 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Premier,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Li Denies Struggle With Zhao</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China-Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Premier Li Peng said today he believes in
fighting to the end to get what he wants but dismissed reports he
fights with Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang over policy.
   ``The major decisions are all products of collective
discussion,'' he told a news conference in the Great Hall of the
People. ``Zhao and I have no differences on political issues.''
   Li, 59, an engineer by training, generally sounds a more
cautious tone that Zhao in public statements, emphasizing the need
for economic stability over rapid change. He was approved as
premier during the 20-day session of the National People's Congress
that ended today.
   Zhao tends to emphasize the need for speedy action if China is
to transform its rice-paddy economy into one capable of competing
internationally in high technology.
   ``There is some comment in the foreign press that Zhao favors
reform and opening to the outside world ... and I'm in favor of
stabilizing the economy. They somehow pit these two views against
each other,'' Li said.
   ``This is a misunderstanding. The very purpose of reform ... is
to bring about economic growth and sustained and steady economic
growth in turn will facilitate the smooth pursuit of reform.''
   Asked to describe his philosophy of life, Li said he believed in
Marxism but added, ``I believe that if I set my mind to something I
can't waver but have to stick it out to the end.''
   The official translator used a more colorful phrase in English
than Li chose in Chinese, quoting Li as saying he believed in
``slugging it out.''
   Li's news conference was reminiscent of one given by Zhao last
November immediately after being appointed party general secretary.
   During that conference, the first of its kind by a high Chinese
leader, a high-spirited Zhao walked about the room, shaking hands
with reporters and clicking glasses with them as he fielded
questions.
   Li's news conference was more formal. He and his three vice
premiers _ Wu Xueqian, Yao Yilin and Tian Jiyun _ sat behind a
table facing rows of seated reporters.
   He appeared more relaxed than at past public appearances but
refused to answer several questions, including one about his
experiences during the far leftist Cultural Revolution. Hundreds of
thousands of Chinese suffered during that violent campaign from
1966-76, but Li was protected by his adopted father, then Premier
Chou En-lai.
   Asked if his own rapid rise in politics was due to his
relationship with Chou, China's most popular leader, Li said, ``I
think my promotion has nothing to do with him.''
   Li was orphaned at 3 when his father was killed by Nationalist
troops in China's civil war. Chou and his wife, Deng Yingchao, who
had no children of their own, adopted about 10 war orphans.
   Li attempted to portray his ties with Chou as somewhat distant,
saying that as a youth he lived with fellow students, not Chou and
Deng, and saw them only occasionally.
   ``But their ideals and moral influence had a profound impact on
my upbringing,'' he said.
   Li said university students who have put up posters in the past
week calling for more funds for education are ``welcome ... to
voice their opinion, much of which is correct.''
   He played down the significance of the posters and of a sit-in
Sunday in Tiananmen Square by 18 students and teachers. He said
Chinese have the right to express their views, but ``within the
scope allowed by law.''
   Li also said China would welcome talks with the exiled leader of
Tibetan Buddhism, the Dalai Lama.
   The Panchen Lama, Tibetan Buddhism's second-highest leader and a
supporter of Chinese rule, indicated last week that the Dalai Lama
would be allowed to live in Tibet if he returned to China from his
Indian exile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
