<HEAD>U.S. Pilot Killed in Small Plane Crash in Iceland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A light airplane plunged into the sea
on its approach to this city's airport and killed the U.S. pilot,
an aviation official said today.
   The two-motor, PA-44 Seminole plane crashed Tuesday about 1,800
feet short of a runway, said the official, speaking on condition of
anonymity. He said it was snowing and visibility was poor.
   The pilot's identity was not released.
   The plane left Narsarsuaq on Greenland's south coast 5{ hours
earlier. Its pilot planned an overnight stop at Reykjavik, the
official said.
   He said the plane initially left the United States for Europe,
but he gave no cities.
   Ice had apparently accumulated on the wings, he said.
   The plane disappeared from the airport's radar shortly after the
pilot radioed his approach to the airport. He did not report
problems, the official said.
   Rescue teams said they found the aircraft early today in 18 feet
of water, with the pilot's body inside.
