<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ViaAgape     04-13 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Via Agape,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palm Beach Dead End Becomes Via Agape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The town elders have apologized, a
resident's ruffled feathers have been smoothed and Palm Beach has
got itself a name for a dead-end street.
   The Town Council voted unanimously Tuesday that the street that
joins Nicholas D. Athans' home to South Ocean Boulevard should be
named Via Agape.
   Athans, who was born in Greece and is a self-proclaimed
descendant of Plato, Hippocrates and Alexander the Great, explained
why he had lobbied for the road to be christened ``agape,'' which
he said means spiritual love.
   ``If we all practice love for our fellow man, we will have fewer
problems in the Middle East, in Afghanistan, in the rest of the
world,'' he said.
   That kind of miracle worked in this posh resort _ on a much
smaller scale _ over the name itself, which the council was less
than enthusiastic about last month.
   Two of its members, Bill Weinberg and Paul Ilyinsky, cracked
jokes at the time that Athans took to be ethnic slurs. He called
the remarks ``very ugly.''
   Both councilmen apologized, and Weinberg said they ``have come
to a common agreement and we now have a little agape between us.''
   ``I'm very pleased,'' Athans said. ``I thank all of them and I
accepted their apology.''
</TEXT>
