<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PenaRecall 1stLd-Writethru a0577 04-13 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pena Recall, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0577,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pena Recall Group Racing Toward Deadline</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, ``Doty expressed xxx,' to add reason why
39,091 required; deadline 7 p.m. EDT, lead prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of a drive to recall Mayor Federico Pena
were racing to meet today's deadline for filing petitions with
enough signatures to force a new mayoral election.
   ``We're counting them every minute,'' said recall organizer
Marge Doty, who launched the recall effort of the Metropolitan
Action Committee in January. ``It's looking real good.''
   The recall drive was launched late last year by a group angered
over what they claimed was fiscal mismanagement by the Pena
administration. The campaign gained momentum after many residents
were left stranded for several days by a major holiday snow storm
while Pena was vacationing out-of-state.
   Doty expressed optimism there would be a recall, but stopped
short Tuesday of a promise to deliver the necessary 39,091
signatures of registered Denver voters to the Denver Election
Commission. That number is 25 percent of the total number of votes
cast in the last mayoral election.
   ``I hope so,'' Doty said, adding, ``That's not a yes or a no.''
   Doty said volunteers worked late Tuesday to check the signatures
for accuracy. Only an unusual run of invalid signatures could block
the drive, Doty said. ``I don't think we're going to find that. I'm
not seeing that now.''
   While there is some dispute about procedures, Denver's charter
calls for an entirely new election.
   Any candidate who collected 300 names on a nominating petition
could run, and if no candidate mustered a clear majority, a run-off
would be held next.
   Susan Duncan, head of a volunteer committee of recall opponents,
predicts there will be enough errors in the petitions to thwart the
recall.
   Some 300 Pena supporters planned to gather at state Democratic
headquarters early Thursday to begin checking and challenging the
signatures.
</TEXT>
