<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WaterShortage     04-13 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Water Shortage,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seattle Water Officials End Drought Control Measures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seattle water officials say drought controls
enacted last summer have been ended due to recent spring storms
that have restored the city's water supplies.
   The reservoirs are above normal and 90 percent full, and
mountain snowpack will bring them up to capacity by June, officials
predicted in announcing the end of the drought emergency on Tuesday.
   However, Seattle residents were asked to continue to limit lawn
watering to every third day and to practice other conservation
techniques.
   Last year, the water department was faced with the worst water
shortage in its history as a result of a prolonged dry spell.
Special pumps had to be installed in reservoirs, and most outdoor
uses of watering were restricted.
   Other parts of the state remain dry, and water shortages are
expected this summer in some areas east of the Cascade Mountains.
   Meanwhile, firefighters in south-central Oregon battled a
60-acre blaze as other crews began mopping up another fire that
charred 35 acres in the Siskiyou Mountains.
   A series of fires has prompted forestry officials to consider
imposition of logging restrictions due to dry conditions in
southern Oregon.
</TEXT>
