<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh     04-13 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>4 Killed, 100 Hurt in Bangladesh Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists with clubs, guns and bombs
fought police and political opponents in delayed local elections,
police said. Four people were reported killed and more than 100
wounded.
   About three-fourths of the country's 21,000 voting centers held
local council elections on Feb. 10, when at least 100 people were
killed. The violence forced officials to postpone other voting.
   Tuesday's new killings raised to six the number of election
deaths since voting resumed Saturday.
   Authorities shot two brothers Tuesday in an effort to break up a
riot at Kakta 50 miles north of Dhaka, said police who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   They said 20 people were hurt there when supporters of rival
candidates resorted to bombs, shotguns and clubs.
   Two other people were shot to death by rival groups in other
parts of the country, police said.
   Elections for local councils are not conducted along party
lines, but they arouse strong personal rivalries.
   In other unrest, students at Jahangirnagar University near Dhaka
rioted over the closing of their dining halls, and administrators
today shut down the school indefinitely.
   Students on Tuesday ransacked the vice chancellor's office,
damaged cars and buses, and cut telephone lines, according to a
statement released by the university.
   A strike has kept its two dining halls closed since April 5.
   Dhaka University, a center of political agitation, has been
closed indefinitely during opposition protests against President
Hussain Muhammad Ershad, a former army general who took power in a
1982 coup and later was elected president.
</TEXT>
