<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AmtrakWreck     04-13 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amtrak Wreck,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Won't Charge Tower Operator in Amtrak Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAN GEHORSAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEDIA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No state charges will be filed against a
control tower operator who caused an Amtrak crash that injured 25
people because authorities cannot prove drugs were involved, a
prosecutor said today.
   Traces of marijuana, cocaine and methamphetamine were found in
blood and urine samples taken from the control tower operator, Tom
Connor, more than 72 hours after the Jan. 29 wreck in which a
passenger train struck a work vehicle, District Attorney William
Ryan said.
   ``However, his usage of these controlled substances cannot be
related back to the time of the accident and there is no evidence
that Connor was impaired by or under the influence of drugs at the
time of the accident,'' Ryan said at a news conference.
   Connor could have been charged with counts of recklessly
endangering another person, Ryan said, but prosecutors concluded
they could not prove the drug-use relationship needed for a
conviction.
   Connor said he forgot to switch the Amtrak Night Owl from the
track occupied by the work vehicle, but he denied being under the
influence of drugs or alcohol at the time, according to
investigators. The train was bound from Washington to Boston.
   Connor, who fled his post at nearby Marcus Hook immediately
after the accident, told National Transportation Safety Board
officials that he blamed himself. According to investigators, he
said he panicked when he saw the wreckage, fearing the two men on
the work vehicle had been killed.
   Connor did not emerge from hiding until three days after the
accident. He then spoke with investigators and underwent drug tests.
   Ryan said he will ask state lawmakers to introduce legislation
that would make it a crime for railroad operators to leave the
scene of an accident. U.S. Rep. Curt Weldon, a Republican who
represents the area, introduced similar legislation in Congress,
Ryan said.
   Connor, 30, quit his job in February before an Amtrak hearing on
the accident.
</TEXT>
