<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mayor-Japanese     04-13 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mayor-Japanese,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Steps Down from Post, Didn't Want to Deal with Japanese</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAPAKONETA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mayor who says he doesn't want to have
anything to do with the Japanese has resigned his post to avoid
hindering his city's economic development.
   With his city in an area that has proven attractive to Japanese
investors and a trade mission from the city heading to Japan next
month, Mayor William V. Lietz announced that he was stepping down.
   ``I was on a destroyer (in the South Pacific) that was sunk .. .
and I was in the hospital,'' Lietz said. ``I don't care if it would
have been the Germans. I would have felt the same way. I'm an
American, and I love my country.''
   ``I am just going out because I figure it's best for the town,''
he said. ``I don't hate (the Japanese) at all, but I just don't
want to have anything to do with them personally.''
   City Council President Charles Brading said he would take over
as mayor, effective Friday, and would go on the 10-day trade
mission, set to depart May 6.
   Lietz, 64, who has been mayor for 13 years and was re-elected to
a four-year term in November, submitted his resignation to Brading
on Monday. His salary as mayor is $3,500 per year, and he also
works as a brick mason.
   At a council meeting last Thursday, Lietz issued a statement in
which he said his personal views should not affect the city's
economic development.
   ``I served our country in World War II. I do not apologize for
that,'' he said. ``But 40 years have gone by, and the world has
changed a great deal. The personal feelings of the mayor, any
mayor, must take a back seat to the greater needs of his
community.''
   ``I think it is unfortunate that this is the way to end his
service to Wapakoneta,'' Brading said. ``He has a right to his
opinion concerning the Japanese.''
   Wapakoneta, a city of about 8,000 people, is about 15 miles
north of Anna, where Honda has an engine plant, and about 50 miles
northwest of the Honda motorcycle and auto plants in Marysville.
</TEXT>
