<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-NearCollision 1stLd-Writethru a0590 04-13 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Near Collision, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0590,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jet Takes Emergency Action to Avoid Collision at Gatwick</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 16 grafs to ADD details, pilots saying runway
closure was dangerous. ADDS byline. Picks up 13th graf pvs, `The
Air ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British Airways jet with 119 people aboard had
to veer off a taxiway into mud to avoid being hit by another jet
that landed on the wrong runway at Gatwick Airport, authorities
said today.
   The incoming jet, a British Island Airways aircraft carrying 117
people, landed on the taxiway instead of the parallel runway it was
supposed to use, the Civil Aviation Authority said.
   The airport's main runway was closed for repaving and pilots
were directed to use alternative runways.
   The landing jet threw its engines into reverse and screeched to
a stop about 750 feet short of crashing into the other jet, said an
aviation authority spokesman.
   He said the incident occurred at 10:20 p.m. (5:20 p.m. EDT).
There were no injuries.
   Airport duty manager Ian MacCorquodale said the pilot of a
British Airways Boeing 737 was taxiing toward a runway for takeoff
when air traffic controllers ordered it to take evasive action to
avoid being hit by the British Island Airways BAC 111.
   He said the British Airways jet swung to one side and came to a
stop with its wheels stuck in the mud and grass beside the runway.
British Airways said its plane was traveling ``slowly'' when it
took the evasive action.
   MacCorquodale said the closure of the main runway shouldn't have
contributed to the near disaster, but the 1,300-strong Guild of Air
Pilots and Air Navigators disagreed.
   ``The worry lies in the fact that the British Airports Authority
are digging up the main runway at one of the busiest times of the
year,'' said the organization's clerk, Capt. Paul Wilson.
   Freddie Yetman, technical secretary of the British Airline
Pilots Association, said: ``Possibly the emergency runway was not
as well lit as the main runway would have been. But it's up to
pilots to be very, very careful when there is a change in landing
procedures.''
   Airport officials praised the controller who diverted the
British Airways jet. An airport spokesman said the controller
prevented ``an incident from becoming an accident.''
   He also commended the BA pilot for responding ``quickly and
positively.''
   Gatwick Airport, 25 miles south of London, was closed for 20
minutes while the British Airways jet was towed away. It was not
damaged.
   Next to London's Heathrow Airport, Gatwick is the world's second
busiest airport in terms of international passengers.
   The BAC-111 was arriving from Venice, Italy, and the British
Airways jet was destined for the Greek island of Rhodes.
   British Island Airways and the Civil Aviation Authority were
investigating the incident, and the airline said it took its flight
crew off duty while the investigation was going on.
   The Air Traffic Control Center in West London and the Civil
Aviation Authority said they are also investigating a near
collision Monday involving a military jet and a civilian helicopter.
   The helicopter, owned by Dollar Air Services, was doing pipeline
survey work for the British Gas corporation, flying at 500 feet,
when the observer spotted the supersonic Jaguar strike fighter
about 150 feet below it.
   The incident happened near Penrith in northwest England. The
Royal Air Force uses the remote area for low-level flying exercises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
