<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--MuddyPicasso     04-13 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Muddy Picasso,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Picasso Sculpture Recovered From Muddy Mississippi River Bottom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Picasso sculpture stolen from an art
dealer has been recovered by police divers from a muddy river
bottom.
   The sculpture, one of two $5,000 works taken in thefts from
Bryant Galleries, was discolored and slightly marred from its stay
on the bottom of the Amite River, gallery owner Bryant Allen said
Tuesday.
   The other sculpture had been sold to a pawn shop for $50, police
said. They found the Picasso after acting on a tip that it had been
tossed from a bridge near McComb in southern Mississippi after
thieves learned police were on their trail.
   ``We consider this nothing short of a miracle. We took this on
as a challenge,'' said Don Bartlett, chief of detectives with the
Jackson Police Department.
   The gold-plated Picasso called La Femme, about 12 inches tall,
was taken March 5. The smaller sculpture, Sunol Alvar's bronze La
Paloma, disappeared on March 21.
   Police said no arrests had been made and the investigation was
continuing.
</TEXT>
