<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CaseworkerIndictments     04-13 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Caseworker Indictments,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two State Caseworkers Indicted For Misconduct</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Contents of 15th graf, `An autopsy ...,' may offend some
readers</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two family service workers fired for failing to
do their jobs properly have been indicted on misconduct charges in
connection with the murders of two babies whose homes they were
assigned to investigate.
   A Cook County grand jury handed up the indictments Tuesday
against Hattie Roland, 37, and Diane Henton, 35, former employees
of the Department of Children and Family Services.
   The indictments, said State's Attorney Richard M. Daley, should
serve as a notice to other caseworkers that ``we're going to be
looking at those records in order to protect all the children of
this county.''
   The two women worked in an office in which as many as eight
caseworkers had to be disciplined, said Gordon Johnson, director of
the department.
   ``I think we should have done a better job of administering that
office,'' he said. ``I'm not sure it would have saved the children,
but I would have been satisfied that we had done everything
possible.
   ``We transferred, terminated and suspended seven or eight
people,'' he added.
   Ms. Roland and Ms. Henton were fired by the agency last year
after an internal investigation.
   Ms. Roland was indicted on 63 counts of misconduct on grounds of
allegedly failing to file adequate reports, falsifying reports and
failing to provide child protection services, said Lisa Howard, a
spokeswoman for Daley's office.
   She is accused of lying about her visits to check on Debra
Hardy, a Chicago-area mother who was convicted of strangling her
4-month-old son, Ms. Howard said.
   According to the indictment, Ms. Roland said she had been in the
Hardy home on nine separate dates between Feb. 21, 1983, and June
21, 1984, when, in fact, she had never set foot in the house.
   Ms. Hardy was convicted of murder and sentenced to 20 years in
prison.
   Ms. Henton, who also supervised other caseworkers, was charged
with failing to report the abuse of Jonathan Campbell, who was
killed Jan. 25, 1986, on his first birthday.
   Anthony Habener, a friend of the child's mother, was convicted
of murder and sentenced to 65 years in prison.
   Ms. Howard said Ms. Henton visited the home on Jan 16, eight
days before Jonathan was killed, and closed the case two days later.
   An autopsy report showed the child's ears were nearly torn off
and that he had 25 or more bruises on his body, many at least 10
days old.
   Ms. Howard said the women face up to five years on each count of
misconduct if convicted of the charges.
   Ms. Roland appealed her firing to civil service officials, who
overturned the department ruling, Johnson said, but has not
returned to work pending the outcome of the indictments.
</TEXT>
