<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--WellBlowout     04-13 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Well Blowout,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Families Evacuated After Oil Well Blows Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARLOW, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil well blew out today and spewed
natural gas into the air, forcing authorities to evacuate nearby
homes, officials said.
   No injuries were reported, but gas was hanging in the air and
the Oklahoma Highway Patrol said it might take 24 hours to cap the
well.
   ``We've got people on location and we have a plan to bring the
gas flow under control,'' said Jerry Jones, regional manager for
Apache Corp. of Tulsa, which operates the well.
   ``The gas flow to the surface needs some attention. There's not
been an ignition source to this point in time,'' he said.
   Central High School, a 12-grade school with about 350 students,
was in no danger from the blowout two miles away and was not being
evacuated, said Principal Larry Malcom.
   The oil well, known as Minnick 2-17, is five miles west of
Marlow.
   The highway patrol said it could not obtain an accurate count on
evacuations because most residents of homes near the well were at
work or in school.
</TEXT>
