<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Keating     04-13 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Keating,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Keating Has Support Of Home-State Civil Rights Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Francis A. Keating II, recommended by Attorney
General Edwin Meese III as associate attorney general, has the
support of civil rights leaders in his home state despite his
membership in an all-white country club.
   Keating, currently an assistant Treasury secretary, is a member
of the Southern Hills Country Club in Tulsa, Okla., club general
manager William Dorman said this week.
   Oklahoma leaders of the NAACP said Keating's membership in the
club does not affect their view that he's qualified for a high
position in the Justice Department.
   The Rev. Wade Watts, state executive director of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said the NAACP
has presented Keating with service awards in the past.
   ``Frank has always helped us,'' Watts said.
   Jim Wilson of Claremore, Okla., executive board member of the
state NAACP, said emphasis on Keating's Southern Hills membership
``kind of implies that he's a racist or a bigot and that's not
true.''
   ``I believe he's an honest and fair man,'' Wilson said. ``We in
the NAACP would love to see Frank Keating as the attorney general.''
   Keating is currently assistant Treasury secretary for
enforcement. Meese has recommended to the White House that he take
over the department's third-ranking position. He would succeed
Stephen Trott, who was confirmed as a federal appellate judge.
