<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--CharterCrash     04-13 0114</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Charter Crash,0117</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jockeys, Trainers Die in Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chartered airplane crashed
in an eastern state and killed all 23 people aboard, including some
of the country's best jockeys and horse trainers, officials said
Wednesday.
   The twin-engine Dakota went down Tuesday night about 200 miles
south of Johannesburg in the Orange Free State.
   The passengers included jockeys, trainers and racing officials
returning to Johannesburg after a race.
   A private aviator said he heard the charter pilot radio that
there was a fire on board just before the crash.
   Authorities withheld release of the list of those on board the
plane operated by United Air, a domestic carrier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
