<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   04-13 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0831</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: be emulating.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   April 8
   The Chattanooga (Tenn.) Times on air traffic controllers:
   The House vote to require the Reagan administration to rehire at
least 1,000 of the 11,400 air traffic controllers President Reagan
fired in 1981 presents the administration with a crucial decision:
Should the safety of the nation's air traffic control system have a
higher priority than the labor dispute that prompted the firings?
   Common sense says yes. ...
   The system is still operating with fewer controllers now than in
1981 _ roughly 15,500 compared with 16,375. Moreover, fewer of the
controllers now working are at the ``full performance level'' of
the most experienced and proficient controllers working in 1981.
   Meanwhile, there have been major increases in air traffic. The
Federal Aviation Administration argues that safety is not being
compromised and that it is adding more controllers into the system
gradually. ...
   The controllers were wrong to strike in violation of the law,
but that's no reason for the government to put the air traffic
system at risk by refusing to approve this bill.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 8
   The Columbus (Ga.) Ledger-Enquirer on Vietnam war bitterness:
   There's yet another sign that the bitterness left by the Vietnam
war is dissipating.
   Nguyen Dy Nien, a Vietnamese deputy foreign minister, made some
concilatory moves in a conversation ... with Sen. Larry Pressler,
R-S.D., a member of the Foreign Relations Committee who was in
Hanoi.
   Nien, in what was regarded as an overture to the Reagan
administration, urged that the United States and Vietnam each open
an ``interest section'' in the other's capital as a step toward
full diplomatic relations.
   He also suggested negotiations on the resettlement in this
country of several thousand political prisoners released recently
by the Hanoi regime.
   We hail both suggestions.

</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 8
   Las Cruces (N.M.) Sun-News on the arrest of Juan Ramon Matta
Ballesteros:
   We doubt if many people were disturbed by the report of how
American drug agents used subterfuge and foreign police to arrest
an alleged international cocaine czar and bring him back to the
United States for trial.
   As a matter of fact, there are probably a lot of folks
applauding the federal drug agents' ability to get their hands on a
major drug suspect in Honduras, Juan Ramon Matta Ballesteros.
   Defense lawyers and civil libertarians may throw up their arms
in dismay, but the U.S. courts agree with the opinion of most folks
_ how defendants got to the United States is not a legal concern if
no U.S. laws were broken.
   The practice of getting suspects from beyond our borders will
not prevent criminals from going about their business. But it sends
a message that the long arm of Uncle Sam can extend into foreign
countries.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 9
   The Orlando (Fla.) Sentinel on the plight of the homeless:
   Often the first step toward solving a problem is to achieve a
consensus on how serious it is. That's why it's encouraging to
learn from a new poll that 90 percent of Americans think the plight
of the homeless is ``a national disgrace.''
   The people interviewed also are concerned about the need to
rehabilitate low-income housing and provide down payment loans for
young families who can't buy homes without them.
   In fact, more than 60 percent of people questioned by the
National Housing Institute said they would be willing to pay $120 a
year in additional taxes if it would help solve our housing
problems.
   Enthusiasm for additional taxes tends to wane when hypothesis
turns to reality. But institute officials estimate an average tax
increase of that size would bring in between $12 billion and $17
billion a year.
   That would about double the shamefully little money the federal
government is putting into housing programs now.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 9
   The Milwaukee Journal on violence on the basketball court:
   Anyone who thinks basketball isn't a contact sport didn't watch
the national collegiate basketball tournament or spend much time
watching the pros in the National Basketball Association this year.
   Bodies crash to the hardwood almost as frequently as they fall
on the gridiron.
   Sometimes, the rough stuff goes too far. The just-concluded
collegiate tourney ... didn't get out of hand, but during the
regular season several college games were interrupted by fights
between players. One player even threw a chair at a fan.
   In a welcome attempt to restrain the mayhem, new rules have been
adopted by the National Collegiate Athletic Association. ...
   With the new NCAA rules, a uniform system of discipline has been
introduced into the game. ...
   Nevertheless, violence is as out of place in basketball as are
drugs and cheating. A round of applause to the NCAA for having
blown the whistle.
</TEXT>
