<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   04-13 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the whistle.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   April 11
   Vicksburg (Miss.) Evening Post on the need to curb use of
chemical weapons:
   The altogether convincing evidence of hideous mass deaths
indicts Iraq once again for using chemical weapons in its war
against Iran.
   Incredibily, Iraq also committed a monstrous crime against
hundreds of its own people, Kurdish Iraqi civilians, in order to
use poison gas against Iranian troops occupying an Iraqi front-line
village, Halabaja. ...
   International horror over chemical warfare during World War I
led to the 1925 Geneva protocol, which banned the use of what
(Winston) Churchill called a ``hellish poison.''
   The dangerous turn in the Iran-Iraq war confirms the need for a
new international agreement that restates the prohibition against
chemical weapons, destroys existing stockpiles and provides a
credible international punishment for those who violate it.
   Meanwhile, Washington and Moscow should join in making it clear
to the (Persian) gulf combatants that the use of chemical warfare
will result in joint economic and military sanctions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 6
   The Palm Springs (Calif.) Desert Sun on the impeachment of the
Arizona governor:
   The principal crime of Evan Mecham probably was that he
embarrassed the people of Arizona.
   Oh, the official charges in his impeachment were serious enough
_ obstruction of justice and misuse of state funds. They were
charges, though, of the sort that could be explained away _ and
probably are in hundreds of instances.
   True, a third charge of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan was
dismissed by the Arizona Senate because Mecham faces a criminal
trial on the charge.
   But the plain fact is that Mecham made America ridicule Arizona.
... Mecham offended blacks and Asians and gays. He put his foot in
his mouth too often and kept it there too long.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 11
   The Honolulu Advertiser on the Afghanistan accord:
   Mikhail Gorbachev can only gain now by a ``successful''
withdrawal from this adventure (in Afghanistan) that is both an
economic burden and at odds with Moscow's effort to change the
world's perception of its intentions.
   The ... plan, if it holds, comes in time to keep Afghanistan
from being a sticking point when Gorbachev and President Reagan
meet in Moscow May 29 to talk about reducing strategic nuclear arms.
   But the Soviet troop withdrawal to begin May 15 will likely be
followed by more bitter fighting and possibly efforts to partition
Afghanistan. The leader of the seven-party resistance has vowed to
make no peace with the Soviet-backed government in Kabul.
   By many assessments, that government will not last long. But the
Afghans are divided among themselves as to how to run their country.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 8
   The Sun, Westerly, R.I., on trucks with idling engines:
   Anyone who has paused at a truck stop along the highways knows
the sound of parked behemoths. There they stand, sometimes 20 or so
_ giants muttering softly as their diesel engines are left idling
while the truckers go in for a coffee or a meal.
   There are reasons for this practice; the idling engines keep the
truck cab cool and warm, according to the season, and may also be
used to keep fuel warm for a ready departure.
   But Argonne National Laboratory researchers have taken some of
the fun out of it. A study reportedly shows that an hour of idling
causes as much engine wear as two hours of driving. The bad effects
are cumulative.
   The director of Argonne's Center for Transportation Research
offers this formulation: the average truck is left idling some 800
hours a year, equivalent to 64,000 miles on the road _ and that
requires an engine overall about a year sooner than would otherwise
be necessary.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 9
   The Charleston (W.Va.) Gazette on debates by the presidential
nominees:
   Vice President George Bush, the GOP's de facto presidential
candidate, may be trying to weasel out of debating his Democratic
opponent this fall.
   A Commission on Presidential Debates was established last year
by the chairmen of the Republican and Democratic parties to
coordinate the dates and places for the 1988 faceoffs.
   At the time, Bush staffers said it would be inappropriate for
Bush to make debate commitments until he bcomes the GOP nominee.
   Now, with the GOP nomination locked up, Bush's staff still won't
agree to a debate schedule and Bush himself won't discuss it.
   The question arises: what is Bush afraid to talk about?
</TEXT>
