<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Singapore     04-13 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Singapore,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singapore Prime Minister Meets Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan met Wednesday with Singapore
Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew, reported by an aide to be anxious for
the United States to maintain a strong role in Asia.
   Reagan greeted Lee at the White House for a 90-minute meeting
and lunch, which both sides indicated would cover a wide range of
issues including East-West relations.
   Lee does not want U.S.-Soviet summitry and superpower accords on
arms control and a Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan to overshadow
the unsolved problem of Cambodia, said spoke only on condition of
anonymity.
   Moscow-backed Vietnamese troops have occupied much of Cambodia
since 1978, the year after the Red Army entered Afghanistan.
   Lee already has conveyed his concerns to U.S. officials during
two days of talks that included meetings with Reagan's national
security adviser, Colin L. Powell, and Secretary of State George P.
Shultz.
   Lee was quoted by the aide as telling Shultz that if the Soviet
Union can withdraw from Afghanistan, there is no reason the
Vietnamese cannot pull out of Cambodia.
   Shultz briefed Lee about the Afghanistan withdrawal accords
which the United States will endorse in Geneva on Thursday, and the
two men also discussed the just-begun negotiations about the lease
of U.S. bases in the Philippines.
   Singapore would like to see a favorable outcome from the
negotiations in order to ensure a continued U.S. commitment to the
region to counter a growing Soviet presence.
   Lee' visit, which is described as a private one, also has
included meetings with members of Congress who complained about
Singapore's restrictions on foreign press coverage and about the
detention of suspected communist activists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
