<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BostonPollution     04-13 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boston Pollution,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Pays U.S. $2.4 Million For Polluting Harbor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts will pay the federal government $2.4
million for polluting Boston Harbor in a settlement reached after
years of negotiations, a top state official said today.
   The agreement marks a departure because $2 million of the total
will go to a special Boston Harbor cleanup fund, according to
William Geary, who heads the Metropolitan District Commission.
   Of the total amount, $425,000 will be paid as a fine to the U.S.
Treasury, Geary said.
   The settlement stems from a lawsuit that began in the mid-1980s
when environmentalists and lawyers representing the city of Quincy
sued the district commission for polluting the harbor. The
commission has wide authority over public services in the
metropolitan area.
   As part of the case, the state created the Massachusetts Water
Resources Authority which took control of the harbor cleanup effort
and was granted power to bill sewer and water service customers.
   But negotiations between the state and the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency continued over damages for pollution of Boston
Harbor, which state and federal officials say is the dirtiest in
the nation.
   ``Fortunately the commonwealth and the EPA have come to terms
with establishing a vision for the future in which we clean up the
harbor rather than dwelling on the past of how it got polluted,''
Geary said. ``The agreement closes that sad chapter.''
   Geary said $2 million of the money would go into a special
Harbor Trust to benefit harbor-related projects such as beach
restoration and protection of wildlife.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
