<DOCNO> AP880413-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RamseyVerdict     04-13 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ramsey Verdict,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts Man in Newspaper Office Confrontation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has acquitted a man who shot up
the offices of the Anchorage Times of attempted murder, finding he
didn't intend to kill anyone, but convicted him of attempted
kidnapping and other charges.
   The defendant, Donald Ramsey, was upset with publisher Bob
Atwood because the Times refused to print a political advertisement
attacking Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, in October 1986, the
prosecution said.
   Ramsey stormed the newspaper office, threw a smoke grenade and
confronted Atwood and his daughter, Elaine. The Atwoods subdued
Ramsey and no one was injured seriously, although numerous shots
were fired.
   Atwood and several other people from the Times listened
impassively from the back of the courtroom as the verdicts were
announced Tuesday afternoon. Atwood, 81, said later he just wanted
to make sure Ramsey stayed in jail for awhile.
   ``My only concern has been if they found him not guilty and
turned him loose,'' he said. ``What position does that leave me in
... what are my options with him running around loose?''
   In addition to attempted kidnapping, the jury convicted Ramsey
of third-degree assault and reckless endangerment.
   In statements to investigators, Ramsey expressed great animosity
to Atwood. He said he believed the publisher and other political
figures were conspiring against him and were responsible for a fire
that destroyed his apartment.
   Defense attorney Craig Howard described Ramsey as a naive
political activist who ``just snapped'' when he found he couldn't
right wrongs by simply pointing them out to public officials.
   The attempted kidnapping conviction carries a recommended
seven-year prison term, but Assistant District Attorney Valerie Van
Brocklin said she might argue that Ramsey should get more because
of the unusually serious nature of his actions.
   Howard said he expected Superior Court Judge Mark Rowland would
give Ramsey a substantial sentence with lots of probation time
tacked on.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
