<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--CityDebt     04-13 0125</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--City Debt,120</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Eight Cities Owe One-Fifth of Municipal Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just eight large communities account for more
than one-fifth of all the debt owed by U.S. cities, the Census
Bureau reported Wednesday.
   The nation's cities had total indebtedness of $164.8 billion at
the conclusion of fiscal 1986, the bureau said.
   Of that, just over $37 billion was accumulated by eight cities,
led by New York with $15.72 billion, the report said.
   Los Angeles was a distant second with $4.36 billion in debt,
followed by Philadelphia, which owed $3.12 billion.
   The remainder of the large-debt cities were Jacksonville, Fla.,
$3.08 billion; Chicago, $2.90 billion; San Antonio, Texas, $2.70
billion; Washington, $2.66 billion; and Houston, $2.59 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0597 04-13 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0597,700</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT new 5th graf with Dukakis spokesman comment bgng ``But
Dukakis...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Michael
Dukakis said the United States must ``be prepared to use nuclear
force'' in the event of a Soviet invasion of Europe that could not
be halted with conventional forces, according to a newspaper report
published today.
   Dukakis said he could conceive of a scenario using nuclear
weapons against the Soviets in Europe.
   ``I don't think it's going to happen,'' he said in a meeting
with New York Daily News reporters and editors. But he added,
``We've got to be prepared to use nuclear force. Obviously with
great restraint, only when there seems to be no other alternative.''
   Dukakis' statement drew criticism from rival Albert Gore Jr.
that it was ``unwise and irresponsible.'' Gore said the comments
indicated the Massachusetts governor's lack of foreign policy
experience.
   But Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach disputed Gore, saying today
that ``Al Gore read the morning newspapers and started shooting.
And once again he got his facts wrong. Experienced leaders don't do
that. They check their facts before they act.''
   Dukakis also said he would order in the military if communist
forces crossed the West German border or the 38th parallel in Korea.
   Dukakis was back in Boston today attending to state business as
governor of Massachusetts, taking a break for part of the day from
the campaign for New York's important Democratic presidential
primary one week away.
   Vying with Gore for the support of Jews, who make up close to
one-fourth the Democratic voters in New York, Dukakis met privately
with Orthodox and Hasidic Jewish leaders in Brooklyn on Tuesday. He
emerged to address a large rally with people filling a city street
and received the strong endorsement of Rabbi Morris Shmidman and
the area's congressman, Rep. Stephen Solarz.
   Shmidman is executive director of th Council of Jewish
Organizations, a group representing 190 different Jewish
organizations.
   ``I know in my heart Michael Dukakis is the best choice, and I
will vote for him,'' the rabbi said. ``I urge you my friends to
follow me.''
   Dukakis praised the Jewish community warmly and drew analogies
with his own heritage as the son of Greek immigrants. But he did
not directly respond, if he heard them, to the repeated shouts from
some young people in the crowd pressing him for more detailed
answers on support for Israel and to draw distinctions with
Jackson, a candidate who has stirred strong opposition among some
Jewish leaders for past statements and associations.
   ``I have some disagreements with Rev. Jackson,'' Dukakis said.
``I have some disagreements with Sen. Gore. I'm going to run a
strong campaign that puts my best foot forward ... in the hope I
can win the support of the people of New York.''
   Dukakis met a day earlier with other Jewish leaders, following
by more than a week a similar appearance by Gore in which he struck
a strongly pro-Israel stance that has won him some support among
Jewish leaders. Meeting in a debate earlier in the day, Gore
suggested Dukakis had shown ``enthusiasm'' for creation of a
Palestinian state _ a move opposed by some Jewish leaders and which
Shmidman called ``a dagger at the heart and soul of Israel.''
   Responding to reporters surrounded by those at the rally,
Dukakis said that Israel must ``exercise maximum restraint'' in
dealing with Palestinian unrest in the West Bank and Gaza.
   Some in the crowd shouted to Dukakis, ``What about Jackson.''
Afterward, some in the crowd voiced only qualified support.
   ``He was very vague in regard to Israel,'' said Daniel Cohen, a
Hebrew teacher. ``I find him very hazy.''
   Yet several also voiced a concern often heard here _ that a vote
for Gore would in effect help Jackson in what is regarded as a
two-way race for the lead in New York with Dukakis.
   ``There is a fear of Jackson,'' Cohen said.
   Dukakis later campaigned at a rally with New York women,
repeating his commitment to providing basic health insurance for
all Americans. He was praised by a colleague, Vermont Gov.
Madeleine Kunin, who called him ``a candidate who not only gives
you rhetoric but gives you a record.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
