<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Glacier,0121</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>India, Pakistan to Resume Talks Over Disputed Glacier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has agreed with Pakistan
to reopen suspended talks on a disputed Himalayan glacier
overlooking military bases of three countries, the defense minister
said Wednesday.
   The two sides broke off negotiations over the 50-mile glacier in
the Kashmir border region almost two years ago.
   Indian troops repulsed a Pakistani assault there in September,
and other clashes followed in January.
   Both nations view the Siachen glacier as strategic because it
overlooks Chinese, Indian and Pakistani bases in nearby valleys.
   Indian Defense Secretary S.K. Bhatnagar will go to Pakistan
later this year for the new talks, according to Defense Minister
K.C. Pant.
</TEXT>
