<1ST_LINE>u p PM-UtahGovernor     04-13 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Utah Governor,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Huntsman Drops Out Of Governor's Race After One Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrialist Jon Huntsman abruptly
dropped his front-running quest for the Republican gubernatorial
nomination today, citing business reasons and a need for party
unity.
   Huntsman's decision came one day before he was to formally
announce his candidacy for governor and 30 days after he had said
he was seeking to wrest the party's nomination from Gov. Norm
Bangerter.
   ``The building of our economy is and will be far more important
to me than the actual title of governor,'' Huntsman said in a brief
statement at Huntsman Chemical Corp headquarters. He said a recent
business trip to Asia presented unexpected opportunities to expand
his $1 billion-per-year chemicals empire.
   Without specifically naming tax-cutting independent
gubernatorial candidate Merrill Cook, a Republican, Huntsman called
on independents to unite behind Bangerter.
   Huntsman had already shocked Republicans once with his
announcement last month that he would challenge Bangerter, who was
trailing Democratic challenger Ted Wilson in polls, for the GOP
nomination.
   A long-time player behind the scenes in the state Republican
Party, Huntsman quickly gathered major support for his candidacy
from major party figures and launched a $236,000 television and
radio campaign on Saturday.
   Without specifically naming tax-cutting independent
gubernatorial candidate Merrill Cook, a Republican, Huntsman called
on independents to unite behind Bangerter.
   Bangerter, who also attended the news conference, said there
were no conditions set by either man for the withdrawal. Bangerter
said he would draw heavily on Huntsman's expertise to bolster the
state's economic development.
   Huntsman supporters ``certainly have nothing to be ashamed of
and have nothing to fear from Norm Bangerter,'' the governor said.
   Huntsman's decision came three days after a poll in The Salt
Lake Tribune showed the challenger had widened his lead over the
first-term governor. The poll by Bardsley, Hardison & Neidhart
found Huntsman with a 48 percent to 40 percent lead, although the
telephone survey had an error margin of 7 percent.
   Wilson, the former mayor of Salt Lake City, said it was
difficult to assess the impact of Huntsman's decision.
   However, he said, ``We're encouraged. We think this does help
our chances. It allows us to go out and take full command of the
jobs issue.''
   Huntsman, 50, former presidential aide and founder of a
chemicals empire with annual sales of $1 billion, had personally
loaned his campaign $100,000 while awaiting arrival of some
$200,000 in pledges made the day after his March 15 announcement.
   The 30-day campaign was Huntsman's first quest for public
office, but he has been a force in the state GOP for more than a
decade. His fund-raising skills, personal wealth and Washingtn
connections left a number of Republicans in his debt.
   He is presently Utah finance chairman for Vice President George
Bush's presidential campaign.
   In 1980, the GOP nomination to challenge popular Democratic Gov.
Scott Matheson was virtually assured Huntsman, but he declined,
saying a campaign would not allow him enough time with his wife and
nine children.
   His transformation from supporter to opponent was a bitter blow
to Bangerter, who scored Huntsman for a lack of loyalty. Bangerter
was deserted by several people who withdrew endorsements and
switched to Huntsman.
   For 12 months during 1971 and 1972, Huntsman served as a special
assistant to President Richard Nixon.
   A graduate of the Wharton School of Finance at the University of
Pennsylvania, Huntsman founded Huntsman Container Corp. in 1970.
Huntsman Container focused on food packaging, and the firm's
accomplishments included the invention of a styrofoam container for
Big Mac hamburgers.
   In 1982 he formed Huntsman Chemical Corp. The company's major
product is bulk polystyrene and other plastics derived from
petroleum by-products.
</TEXT>
