<1ST_LINE>u a PM-US-Sweden     04-13 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Sweden,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swedish Royalty Call Delaware Trip `High Point' Of U.S. Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sweden's royal couple today re-enacted
the landing of the first Swedish settlers in America as they rode a
boat up the Christina River as part of the city's 350th anniversary
celebration.
   King Carl XVI Gustaf and Queen Silvia arrived shortly before 9
a.m. to a cheering crowd of about 1,500 and greetings from Gov.
Michael N. Castle, Mayor Daniel Frawley and Rep. Thomas R. Carper,
D-Del.
   ``Today, most Americans don't know that the Swedish were among
the first Europeans to colonize North America,'' the king said. ``I
hope that this year of New Sweden will help us focus America's
attention on our common history and significant contributions made
by Swedes to the progress and development of this great country.''
   He called the landing in Wilmington the high point of the royal
couple's 15-city U.S. tour that began Sunday in Washington.
   The king and queen also dedicated an exhibit of artifacts found
in the wreckage of the Swedish 17th century warship Kronan.
   Carl Gustaf said he was impressed by the exhibit. He has dived
to the wreckage over the past several summers and said artifacts
found so far represent just a part of the bounty.
   ``There is a statue of natural size in nearly perfect condition.
That means there is a lot more to be found, hopefully,'' the king
said.
   Prior to the royal couple's arrival, the Afro-American
Historical Society of Delaware dedicated a plaque commemorating the
arrival of the state's first black settler, who was a slave aboard
one of the ships bringing the Swedish settlers.
   Following the morning stop in Wilmington, the king and queen
traveled to Philadelphia to open an exhibit at the American-Swedish
Historical Museum. They are scheduled to return to Wilmington for a
reception and dinner tonight.
   Lone Bear, a descendant of the Lenni Lenape Indians from the
area, was among those greeting the king, giving him a buckskin
hunter's bag, a beaver pelt and tobacco. A thousand people had
lunch with the royal couple under a tent outside the museum.
   On Tuesday, the royal couple opened an exhibit at Washington's
National Gallery that serves as the centerpiece of a nationwide
celebration of ``The Year of New Sweden.''
</TEXT>
