<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RetailSales     04-13 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Retail Sales,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Easter Buying Helps Boost Retail Sales in March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales rose a healthy 0.8 percent in
March, the government reported Wednesday, propelled by Easter
buying at department and food stores.
   The Commerce Department said retail sales for the month
increased by a seasonally adjusted $1.1 billion to $130.7 billion.
   It was the fifth consecutive monthly increase and the largest
since December, when sales shot up 1.1 percent. Revised figures
showed sales rose 0.6 percent in February and 0.1 percent in
January.
   Ever since the October stock market crash, economists have
watched retail sales closely for signs that the consumer sector of
the economy would weaken. But more recently, some analysts have
raised fears that too much consumer demand could rekindle inflation.
   ``If consumer spending were sustained at the March pace for
several months to come, we would probably be heading (toward)
higher inflation and higher interest rates,'' said Bruce Steinberg,
senior economist with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets. However, he
said growth in retail spending will likely slacken in April and May.
   ``The consumer was feeling good about spending in March, but
that doesn't indicate that a new consumer boom is in the making,''
Steinberg said.
   Economists had predicted only a 0.2 percent to 0.3 percent gain
in March. They said Wednesday that because Easter fell on April 3,
earlier in the year than usual, more people may have shopped for
the holiday in March than normally.
   Sales at department and other general merchandise stores rose
1.6 percent, after suffering a steep 2.6 percent drop in February.
   Sales at food stores rose 1.1 percent, following a 0.6 percent
decline the month before.
   ``The increase at department stores is definitely
Easter-related,'' said James Newton, an economist with Economic
Perspectives Inc., a Delaware, Ohio, consulting firm. He said the
increase at food stores ``might also be a bit Easter-related.''
   March sales increased in all categories execept furniture and
restaurants, in contrast to the first two months of the year, when
overall sales growth was spurred by auto sales.
   ``The strength in retail sales had been largely in autos,'' said
Scott Hoyt, an economist with Data Resources Inc., a Lexington,
Mass., forecasting firm. ``Now we're seeing it across the board,
indicating somewhat broader strength.''
   Auto sales rose 0.9 percent in March. Excluding autos, sales
were up 0.8 percent, the same as the overall rise.
   In February and January, car sales were much stronger than other
sales. They rose 2 percent and 2.5 percent, respectively, while
other sales increased only 0.2 percent in February and declined 0.6
percent in January.
   Sales of all durable goods _ items expected to last three or
more years _ were up 0.5 percent in March, while non-durable goods
were up 1 percent.
   The department offered these details of March sales:
   _Hardware and garden supply stores, up 0.5 percent after soaring
3.0 percent in February.
   _Furniture and appliance stores, down 2 percent after a strong
2.9 percent increase a month earlier.
   _Gasoline, up 1.4 percent following a 1.2 percent decline.
   _Specialty clothing stores, up 0.3 percent; restaurants and
bars, down 0.6 percent; and drug stores, up 1.6 percent.
</TEXT>
