<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Cuomo,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Gives High Praise To Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo heaped praise on
Jesse Jackson today as ``a singularly important Democrat'' who
could win for the party in November. Jackson thanked Cuomo for not
endorsing any of the presidential candidates.
   ``He is making this race a manifestation of the American idea at
its very best,'' said Cuomo during a late morning news conference
with Jackson.
   While Cuomo held to his pledge not to endorse any of the three
Democratic candidates before the end of the primary season on June
7, Jackson said that was fine with him.
   ``Governor Cuomo, just keep a freeze on all endorsements and
keep extending your support,'' the candidate told the New York
governor as Jackson supporters cheered.
   Jackson met with Cuomo for about a half hour this morning
following a speech at a $100 per person breakfast fundraiser for
about 200 people in Albany.
   In his introduction of Jackson, Cuomo said the candidate was
suffering from the ``dumb blonde syndrome'' in which potential
voters think that if a candidate demonstrates charisma and passion
there is little else. ``Nothing could be further from the truth,''
Cuomo said of Jackson. Cuomo, an eloquent political speaker, has
said he suffers from the same put-down.
   Cuomo told Jackson that the fact ``you can get to be president,
or so close, that they put your face on the front page of national
magazines just to explain this phenomenon; that is extraordinary
progress.''
   For his part, Jackson said he felt it was ``a wise use of
power'' for Cuomo to hold off backing any candidate until after the
primaries. Jackson said the move would encourage more people to
vote.
