<1ST_LINE>u a PM-LottoSuit 1stLd-Writethru a0594 04-13 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lotto Suit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0594,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Wins Suit to Get Half Lotto Winnings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to CORRECT that man is unemployed, NOT
homeless; picks up 4th graf pvs, ``Pando is xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who says he prayed to a saint for help in
picking the winning numbers on a Lotto ticket has won a seven-year
legal battle for half of the $2.8 million prize.
   Christopher Pando, 24, said he and the ticket's holder, Daysi
Fernandez, had agreed to split any winnings, and a jury decided
Tuesday after a seven-day trial that he was telling the truth.
   ``I believed in justice and I finally got it,'' said Pando, who
is unemployed.
   Pando is entitled to $1.4 million plus ``a couple hundred
thousand dollars'' interest that has accumulated on the money since
it was placed in escrow, said his lawyer, Joseph Ettinger.
   Pando testified that he prayed to St. Elegua, who told him which
numbers to play on four Lotto tickets he bought for Ms. Fernandez
in June 1981.
   One of the tickets won. At the time, the $2.8 million prize,
paid in annual installments over 10 years, was the state-run game's
biggest payout.
   Initially, Justice Edward Greenfield dismissed the case, saying
it could not be proved that St. Elegua had given Pando the numbers.
But the judge was reversed on appeal, with the higher court saying
that this was not the issue; that it was whether Pando and Ms.
Fernandez had an oral agreement.
   Ms. Fernandez, 44, a mother of three who had been on welfare
about 10 years when she won, said they never had such a deal.
   In the five years after she won, Ms. Fernandez collected about
half of the prize at about $267,720 a year. In July 1986, Pando won
a court order stopping further payments until the case was
resolved. She will receive any money remaining from her half of the
prize.
   When the verdict was announced, Ms. Fernandez wept, Ettinger
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
