<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan-Democrats     04-13 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Democrats,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says Democrats Will Be Bad For Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan told young business
executives Wednesday they should work to keep the White House in
Republican hands this fall if they want to protect their interests.
   Reagan did not make a direct pitch for Vice President George
Bush, who is expected to be the GOP's presidential nominee, but did
say the election could determine whether there is a healthy
business climate.
   ``And I want to ask you to become active and involved this year,
because the stakes are too high and the choice too clear for it to
be left up to others,'' Reagan said.
   Speaking to members of the Young Presidents Organization in the
Old Executive Office Building, Reagan said that ``if the policies
under which your companies have flourished are reversed, how could
your company's bottom line not suffer?''
   ``We cannot afford to have American businessmen once again
treated like a bunch of hired hands laboring on the federal farm,''
he said, ``where the folks in Washington act as if what you produce
belongs to them.''
   Reagan said that under his leadership, the nation has entered
the 65th month of recovery from the 1981-82 recession, the longest
peacetime expansion, and said nearly 16 million jobs have been
created during this period.
   ``It's no coincidence that while we've held down the rate of
growth in government, the private economy has been booming,'' he
said. ``Real GNP (gross national product) grew by nearly 5 percent
in the fourth quarter last year, and inflation remains low.''
   Without singling out any of the Democratic candidates for
president, Reagan made clear he does not believe any of them would
create conditions favorable to businesses.
   ``America will face choices this fall that will determine what
lies ahead for American business and the economy,'' he said. ``If
we can continue the pro-growth policies of the last seven years, I
believe that the next decade will be known as the roarin' '90s.''
   ``The choice we face is a very simple one: Is the federal
government going to grow or is your business going to grow?''
   Reagan has remained neutral in the Republican Party presidential
sweepstakes, although it has been increasingly clear he favors
Bush. Presidential aides have said that Reagan likely will be
actively involved in the general election campaign.
</TEXT>
