<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoliceStandoff     04-13 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Standoff,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gun-Wielding Man Shot Dead After Standoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gun-wielding man barricaded himself for
about 12 hours in a store before being shot to death by state
police in a gun battle as he tried to get away, officials said
today.
   ``Officers tried to talk him out; it was a long, ongoing
thing,'' said state police Sgt. Gilbert Studinger in Manistique, on
Michigan's Upper Peninsula. ``Finally he did come out, but he was
armed and tried to make an escape.
   ``He came out and was firing at the officers, and they returned
fire, and in the process he was killed.''
   Studinger identified the man as John Gillespie, 39, who recently
moved into an apartment attached to The Corner Store, where the
standoff occurred. Gillespie was a store employee and was the only
person there when the standoff began about 8 p.m. Tuesday, police
said.
   Studinger said he did not know how many shots had been fired.
   Studinger said the man may have been distraught over a recent
fight with his girlfriend, who also worked at the store.
