<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1355EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSCounselor     04-13 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Counselor,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Says He Helped Friend With ARC Commit Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An AIDS counselor who claimed in a television
interview that he helped a patient commit suicide did not tell
sheriff's investigators about his role in the death, authorities
said.
   AIDS counselor Marty James told a national television audience
on March 31 that he helped Keith Lower take his own life.
   ``He had lived a very good life and he wanted a very good
death,'' James said on ABC-TV's ``Nightline.'' ``There were no
convulsions, no discomfort that I could see. It was quiet. It was
peaceful.''
   James said that he had mixed a lethal dose of barbiturates in a
glass of grape juice and gave it to Lower to drink.
   James said he was questioned by investigators from the Los
Angeles County Sheriff's Department and the Coroner's Office
following Lower's death on Nov. 18, the Los Angeles Times reported
today.
   But James did not tell investigators about his role in Lower's
death, sheriff's Capt. Bob Grimm said.
   ``He made no representation of those facts to us,'' Grimm said.
``If he helped the victim commit suicide we would be very
interested in talking to him.''
   A coroner's report, written by investigator Michael Joseph, said
authorities recovered a note and a ``glass containing a clear
liquid from the table'' next to Lower's body.
   James, who said he counseled AIDS patients through the Shanti
Foundation and AIDS Project Los Angeles, did not immediately return
taped telephone messages relayed through the agencies and his name
was not listed in telephone directories.
   During the television interview, James said he was ``completely
aware of the fact that in California it's a felony and that I could
serve up to five years in the state penitentiary.''
   Lower, 28, suffered from AIDS-related complex, a condition
similar to acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   ``My friend, Keith, who I assisted to take his own life, was in
such a debilitated condition, he was manifesting malignant tumors
in his lungs, he had suffered AIDS-related complex for seven to
eight years,'' James told ABC.
   The symptoms of ARC include swollen lymph glands, low-grade
fevers, drenching night sweats, weight loss, extreme fatigue and
chronic diarrhea. The symptoms of AIDS include these plus
life-threatening cancers and infections that take advantage of the
body's weakened immune system.
   James, who said he also suffers from AIDS-related complex, told
ABC that he supports legalized euthanasia and hopes that someone
will help him end his own life if and when the pain becomes
intolerable.
   A coroner's report and death certificate contained no suggestion
that James participated in Lower's death, and characterized it as
an ``apparent suicide.'' Lower died from ``acute barbiturate and
diphenhydramine intoxication,'' the report said. The latter is an
antihistamine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
