<DOCNO> AP880413-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy     04-13 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Mita, Not Expecting Miracles, Forms Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the dominant Christian Democrat Party
formed Italy's 48th postwar government on Wednesday from the same
five moderate parties that made up the previous coalition.
   Ciriaco De Mita said he will present his government to
Parliament next week for approval.
   Giovanni Goria, a fellow Christian Democrat, resigned as premier
March 11 after eight turbulent months in office. The alliance,
which has figured in nearly all the governments this decade, also
included the Socialists, Republicans, Social Democrats and Liberals.
   Also remaining the same are many of the faces in the Cabinet,
including Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti, a Christian Democrat,
and Defense Minister Valerio Zanone, a Liberal.
   Asked if the new government would last through the end of the
legislative term in 1992, De Mita's rival, former Socialist Premier
Bettino Craxi, said Tuesday: ``It would be a miracle.''
   De Mita, after announcing the government on Wednesday, was asked
about Craxi's comment. ``Men don't produce miracles,'' De Mita said.
   The new premier will have to grapple with some of the same
complex and sticky issues that bedeviled Goria. They include the
future of Italy's energy policy and how to reform a cumbersome
law-making process and bureaucracy.
   In negotiations leading to De Mita's announcement that he had
succeeded in forming a government, the parties put off a decision
on whether to complete a nuclear plant north of Rome.
   President Francesco Cossiga on March 16 asked De Mita to try to
put together a government. Factional fighting among Christian
Democrats, Goria's own party, had beleagured the Goria government,
hastening its demise.
   The final straw for Goria was strong Socialist objections to a
government decision to go ahead with construction on the power
plant, despite a voter referendum which effectively called for a
moratorium on nuclear development.
   Right after De Mita's announcement of the Cabinet, some Social
Democrats said they were unhappy with the two members of their
party chosen for the Cabinet.
   However, they said they would support the government.
   De Mita, 60, has been leader of the Christian Democrats since
1982. The party, regularly winning about one-third of the votes, is
Italy's largest ballot-getter, and its leadership is considered the
country's most powerful political seat.
   De Mita is the first Christian Democrat to hold both the
premiership and the party helm in 29 years. Christian Democrats
will decide if they like that novelty in the fall, when the party
convention is expected to be held.
   The new premier has said that also holding the party post gives
him the authority to govern effectively.
   The son of a tailor, De Mita was born in Nusco, a poor mountain
village east of Naples. His bald pate delights political satirists.
   He was first elected to Parliament in 1963 and has held Cabinet
posts, none of them key ones.
   For the first time there is more than one woman minister, with
cultural affairs joining special affairs as ministries headed by
women.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Sikhs     04-13 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikhs Fire Weapons, Raise Outlawed Flag to Mark Religious Holiday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALWANDI SABO, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militant Sikhs fired a barrage of
bullets around the Golden Temple on Wednesday and raised the
outlawed flag of their visionary Sikh nation to mark the holy
harvest festival of Baisakha.
   The shooting sent many pilgrims, who visit the shrine for a
ritual bath on holidays, running for cover. Shopkeepers outside the
temple, Sikhism's holiest shrine, closed their shutters in fear.
   Police said the firing at the pool surrounding the Golden Temple
was evidence that the militants were gathering weapons inside the
complex.
   The Golden Temple's chief priest, Jasbir Singh Rode, said that
``if police enter the Golden Temple, the foundation for a separate
state will be laid.''
   Baisakha commemorates both the harvest and the anniversary of
Guru Gobind Singh's introduction of the so-called baptism by sword
for Sikhs in 1699. The guru was the 10th and last in the faith.
   The militants at the Golden Temple fired automatic rifles and
other weapons for about 15 minutes and raised the outlawed saffron
flag of Khalistan, the name they give their would-be state, police
and witnesses said.
   There were no reports of injuries, but police said many of the
estimated 400 pilgrims at the temple panicked.
   Police also said for the first time that the militants were
building fortifications inside the temple complex and chipping
gun-holes into walls, apparently to protect against any entry of
police or soldiers into the shrine.
   In Talwandi Sabo, about 120 miles south of Amritsar, Rode told
about 40,000 Sikhs that ``if police enter the Golden Temple, the
foundation for a separate state will be laid.''
   Rode is the nephew of Jarnail Sing Bhindranwale, who is regarded
as the founder of the militant Sikh movement.
   Bhindranwale was killed during the Indian army's 1984 raid on
the Golden Temple complex, which was aimed at driving militants
from the shrine. Hundreds of Sikhs were killed, and Prime Minister
Indira Gandhi was assassinated later that year by Sikh bodyguards.
   Rode announced the merger of two factions of the the merger of
two factions of the All India Sikh Students Federation, which is at
the forefront of the militant movement.
   Sikh extremists have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for
more political autonomy or a separate homeland in Punjab state.
Sikhs are a religious minority in India and claim discrimination by
the majority Hindus, but they are a majority in Punjab.
   Sikhs have been blamed for killing more than 715 people this
year.
   In New Delhi, Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi told moderate Sikhs
who came to his home with holiday greetings that there was ``a
conspiracy'' to alienate the Sikhs from the rest of Indian society.
   The United News of India quoted Gandhi as repeating his
accusation that rival Pakistan was aiding Sikh militants who are
fighting for an independent Sikh homeland. The challenge, he said,
``has to be met collectively by the people of India.''
   Gandhi said the government was prepared to talk with anyone
``within the framework of the constitution,'' ruling out the
militants' demand that talks focus on formation of a separate Sikh
nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--SovietIntercept     04-13 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Soviet Intercept,0144</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Soviet Bombers Turned Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the third time in little more than
a week, Air Force jets scrambled to intercept Soviet bombers
approaching North America.
   Master Sgt. George Crawford said two F-15 Eagles met the Bear-H
bombers about 460 miles northeast of Point Barrow on Tuesday. At no
time did the Soviets penetrate U.S. or Canadian airspace, Crawford
said.
   Their closest approach to land was 137 miles north of Shingle
Point in Canada's Yukon Territory, Crawford said.
   Tracking of the bombers was coordinated between U.S. and
Canadian commands, he said. The F-15s flew with the Soviet bombers
for a little more than two hours, he said. They were scrambled from
Galena and refueled by KC-135s from Eielson Air Force Base near
Fairbanks, he said. An E-3 from Eielson provided radar assistance,
Crawford said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
