<DOCNO> AP880413-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Ethiopia     04-13 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Ethiopia,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Warns of ``Human Catastrophe'' in Ethiopia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ethiopian government's decision to shut
down an international relief effort has raised the specter of a
``human catastrophe'' with more than 2 million people facing
starvation, the State Department said Wednesday.
   Department spokesman Charles Redman accused Ethiopia of
sacrificing the interests of millions of its citizens in pursuit of
military objectives in two northern provinces where anti-government
rebellions have been under way for years.
   He said the United States does not accept Ethiopia's contention
that the decision was made for the security of persons in that
area, that the expulsions of relief workers is temporary and that
indigenous organizations can take up the slack.
   These claims ``ring hollow against the sheer magnitude of the
disaster,'' Redman said.
   He said that even before the recent fighting, the combined
international and local feeding effort was slowly losing ground to
the growing numbers of hungry people.
   ``To assert that greatly reduced operations can now succeed is
folly,'' the spokesman said. ``The world cannot stand idly by and
permit innocent people to die.''
   Redman called on Ethiopia to reconsider its decision and to
allow relief operations on an ``open roads, open risk basis.''
Without a quick resumption, he said, hundreds of thousands of lives
may be lost.
   A United Nations emissary is expected to arrive in Addis Ababa
on Thursday to encourage Ethiopian authorities to resume relief
activities.
   The Ethiopian decision was the result of a dramatic escalation
in the conflict in Eritrea and Tigray provinces, where many of the
towns that served as distribution points have been taken by forces
opposed to the Marxist government.
   The United States has pledged a contribution of 250,000 tons of
food to Ethiopia for this fiscal year, comparable to the amount
promised by the Soviet Union, Ethiopia's principal ally.
   Total confirmed pledges by all foreign donors combined add up to
about 890,000 tons.
   The U.S. contribution amounts to $90.7 million, excluding $6.6
million for transportation costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
