<DOCNO> AP880413-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1456EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Strike     04-13 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Strike,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shipyard Reopens, but South Korea's Labor Unrest Spreads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union leaders and managers agreed to
end a three-day lockout at the nation's second largest shipyard
Wednesday, but labor turmoil spread with police firing tear gas at
200 taxi drivers.
   Officials at Daewoo Shipbuilding and Heavy Machinery Ltd. said
that the firm's 11,000 workers, shut out of the shipyard since
Monday, were expected to approve the agreement Thursday.
   They said workers would get a 20 percent increase, about $91, in
monthly salaries and allowances.
   Daewoo managers closed the shipyard on southern Koje Island
after workers demanded a 55 percent pay increase that the company
said it could not afford.
   On the outskirts of Seoul, police fired tear gas and arrested
five people Wednesday when about 200 striking taxi drivers began
hurling stones at other cabbies opposed to the stoppage.
   Hyundai Heavy Industries Co., the nation's largest shipbuilder,
and 181 taxi unions in Seoul notified the government Wednesday of
labor disputes.
   The latest outbreak brings to 320 the number of disputes this
year, according to the Labor Ministry. Labor officials said 74 of
those still await settlement.
   Violent protests battered many companies last summer after
student-led demonstrations prompted the government to promise major
reforms, including December's presidential election. Roh Tae-woo
won the election over a divided opposition, and government
opponents have been escalating their campaign to topple him.
   However, labor leaders recently asked union members to shun
violence and political demands, and most of the latest labor
disputes have been peaceful.
   In the southeastern port of Ulsan, union leaders from 24
companies, including Hyundai Motor Co., South Korea's largest
carmaker, joined forces Wednesday, threatening to strike over
demands for pay increases.
   Meanwhile, Daewoo Motor Co. remained paralyzed Wednesday for a
second day with 9,100 workers picketing four assembly lines near
Seoul and in the southern city of Pusan.
   The strike at South Korea's second largest auto company, a joint
venture with the U.S. General Motors Corp., has slowed delivery of
100,000 compact cars, mostly to the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1452EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Reagan-Editors     04-13 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Editors,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Suggests Jackson's Positions Getting Too Little Scrutiny</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today he fears that
public criticism of Jesse Jackson's campaign positions has been
muted because of concern that it could be considered racist.
   Answering questions during an appearance the American Society of
Newspaper Editors convention, Reagan said it seems to him that
``more attention is being paid to the difference in color than is
being paid to what he (Jackson) is actually saying.''
   Reagan rarely has singled out any of the Democratic candidates
for criticism, usually assailing general party positions on issues.
   But when asked to assess the state of civil rights in this
country during a year in which a black is running for president,
Reagan said of Jackson:
   ``I have to believe that a great many of us would find ourselves
in great disagreement with the policies that he is proposing, and
would perhaps be more vocal about them, if it wasn't for concern
that that'd be misinterpreted into some kind of a racial attack.''
   Reagan, whose administration's civil rights record was
criticized by Supreme Court Associate Justice Thurgood Marshall
late last year, said ``the most frustrating thing that I've endured
since I've been here, and the image-making that goes on, is that
I've been portrayed so often as in some way a racist or prejudiced
with regard to racial matters.''
   ``It's hard for me to take,'' the president said, ``because I
grew up in a family in which that was considered the greatest sin _
prejudice and discrimination.''
   Reagan went on to say he had opposed discrimination ``all my
life.''
   ``Back when I was a sports announcer broadcasting major league
baseball, I was one of the little handful across the country that
continued to editorialize for the breaking of the ban and the
allowing of blacks into organized baseball,'' he said.
   But Reagan also said ``I just regret'' that race has ``become a
factor'' in the 1988 presidential campaign.
   ``The candidates (campaigns) should all be based on what are
their policies and what is it that they would propose to do,'' he
said.
   ``And I would be very frank with you, I find a great
disagreement with some of the things that are being proposed by
Jesse Jackson. But I also find a great deal of disagreement with
his fellow candidates in that party, which is why I've suggested
everybody support a Republican,'' Reagan added.
   He did not spell out which Jackson positions he did not like.
   Asked how he thought the presidential sweepstakes would turn
out, Reagan said that ``in the Republican Party, of course, it has
now narrowed down to one candidate (George Bush), but even so there
is a convention to be held.''
   ``And on the other side,'' he said, ``I don't know whether the
candidates now campaigning ... whether anyone of them is going to
wind up at the convention with the nomination or whether there will
be a brokered convention or whether the Democratic Party will go
afield seeking to draft someone who has not been campaigning in the
primaries.''
   ``I just refuse to try to make a guess on this,'' Reagan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0160 </DOCNO>
