<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Ethiopia     04-13 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relief Official Says Drought Aid Will Wait Until Rebels Crushed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopia's chief relief official
said Wednesday that full drought aid operations in the north will
resume only after the government defeats rebel troops.
   Western relief officials fear this will cause deaths from
starvation within weeks.
   ``Our worry is not only the problem of famine, but the integrity
of the country,'' Berhanu Jembere, head of the government Relief
and Rehabilitation Commission, told The Associated Press in an
interview.
   ``It is the obligation of any government to defend its
territory,'' he said of the civil wars in Eritrea and Tigre that
have crippled efforts to feed 3.2 million drought victims. ``As
soon as the area is cleansed of bandit activity, we will resume our
operation.''
   Berhanu could not give a date. ``I have to leave that to the
military personnel in charge of the situation.''
   Also Wednesday, the government warned cross-border operations to
get relief food to the north would ``be met with an appropriate
response.''
   The Tigre People's Liberation Front in March announced it had
stockpiled 9 tons of food in neighboring Sudan and would deliver it
to areas it controlled in Ethiopia this month.
   A strongly worded statement from Ethiopia's Ministry of Foreign
Affairs said it had no doubt that ``Sudan will not fall prey to the
machinations of sinister forces and collaborate in such a serious
breach of the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Ethiopia.''
   After years of official silence, Ethiopia two weeks ago admitted
to being at war after losing or abandoning much of the north to
secessionist rebels, who have been fighting 27 years in Eritrea and
14 years in Tigre.
   The government pullback and last week's expulsion of foreign aid
workers has left the entire relief operation to Berhanu's
commission and the Joint Relief Project, a Christian consortium
that includes the Ethiopian Orthodox Church and is closely involved
with indigenous aid agencies.
   Berhanu claimed his agency could feed 2.4 million people, but
said neither his commission nor the Christians could operate
outside small areas still under government control.
   Western relief officials say the commission and the relief
project together could feed only 1 million people at most.
   They said starvation deaths could begin within weeks and expect
mass migration of the hungry toward Mekele in Tigre, and the
Eritrean capital of Asmara, two towns still held by the government.
   Berhanu said the government already has set up feeding centers
there and was preparing other ``contingency plans,'' including
shelters for refugees who include civil servants and local
government officials fleeing the wars.
   The government and aid agencies for months have tried to avoid
shelters. During the 1984-85 famine, which killed about 1 million
Ethiopians, more people died from diseases contracted in
overcrowded unsanitary feeding camps than from starvation.
   Berhanu stood firm on Ethiopia's expulsion of about 60
expatriates from Eritrea and Tigre and rejected relief agencies'
requests for a skeleton staff to remain to monitor food
distribution.
   The Foreign Ministry statement warned continued
``misrepresentation'' of the evacuation order ``could compel the
Ethiopian government to suspend their services altogether.''
   It suggested some relief workers were spies, saying ``some have
started shedding crocodile tears, perhaps because a few of their
agents masquerading as relief workers are no longer in place to
continue to perpetrate their sinister roles.''
   Berhanu warned of ``grave consequences'' unless all foreign
workers of the International Committee of the Red Cross left the
north by Wednesday. Red Cross spokesman Vincent Bernard said five
Western employees were expected to return Wednesday night.
   The relief operation relied almost solely on huge food shipments
from Western donors and heavily on Western-financed trucks and
airplanes.
   Berhanu said C-130 cargo planes carrying grain to Mekele would
be allowed to continue operations, but all light aircraft must
leave Ethiopia. Most of the small planes ferried passengers, but
some carried food to inaccessible regions south of Tigre and
Eritrea.
</TEXT>
