<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HighwayHostages     04-13 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Highway Hostages,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SWAT Team Storms Ambulance, Frees Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two convicted murderers commandeered an
ambulance Wednesday and held a prison guard and three medical
workers hostage, but police stormed the vehicle after two of the
hostages bolted, and the other two escaped unharmed.
   The two inmates were recaptured unhurt and returned to the
Tennessee State Penitentiary, police said.
   Edward Corley, 35, and Jerry Lynn Driver, 22, face charges of
escape, aggravated kidnapping and aggravated assault, authorities
said.
   Police said the prisoners overpowered a guard, a nurse and two
emergency medical technicians who came to the prison after one of
the inmates apparently faked an illness.
   The hostages were identified as nurse Vivian Bone, prison guard
Robert Peebles, and medical technicians Morris Tidwell and James
Pollard, said Metro Nashville Police Homicide Detective David
Miller.
   The two men forced the hostages into the ambulance early
Wednesday and drove east on Interstate 40 about 10 miles. The
ambulance was stopped and surrounded near the Stewarts Ferry Pike
area east of the city, Maj. Frank Galbaugh said.
   Galbaugh said one of the paramedics may have been able to warn
police of the escape over the ambulance's radio.
   Negotiators, dealing with the suspects over the radio, obtained
the freedom of one of the hostages.
   ``The hostage negotiators did a real good job in getting one of
the EMTs released, and he was debriefed,'' Galbaugh said.
``Meanwhile, we set up our tactical operation, and when the
negotiators reached an impasse, they turned it over to the SWAT
team.''
   The special weapons and tactics team had surrounded the
ambulance, and when the second paramedic bolted from the vehicle,
they moved in, Galbaugh said.
   ``The suspects were getting hysterical, threatening to kill the
hostages,'' Galbaugh said. ``That EMT was a brave individual to get
out and give us a chance.''
   Galbaugh said no injuries were reported, but said the two
inmates might have been shaken up during their arrest.
   ``When we disarmed them both and took them out of the vehicle,
they might have been bounced around a little bit,'' he said.
``We're very happy that nobody got hurt seriously.''
   When the SWAT team entered the vehicle, Corley was lying on one
of the two benches in the rear of ambulance, holding Ms. Bone by
the neck, Galbaugh said. Driver was lying on the floor near the
driver's seat, and Peebles was sitting on the other bench, Galbaugh
said.
</TEXT>
