<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrugCountries     04-13 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Countries,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Deadlocked Over Penalizing Five Latin Nations</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Ffrench in 8th graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee was stymied Wednesday on
the issue of whether to slap aid sanctions on five hemispheric
neighbors for not doing their part in the war on drugs.
   The Foreign Affairs Western Hemisphere subcommittee deadlocked
in a 6-6 tie on whether to penalize Mexico, the Bahamas, Peru,
Paraguay and Bolivia, all countries on a State Department list of
major drug-producing and transit points.
   The impasse _ similar to one reached a day earlier in the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee _ sent the five separate resolutions to
the full Foreign Affairs Committee without recommendation. Full
committee action is likely next week.
   During debate over the issue, a standoff emerged between
lawmakers who feel domestic political pressure to strike a blow
against drug trafficking and those who believe imposing sanctions
on allies and neighbors would do more harm than good.
   ``These nations may feel themselves offended,'' said Rep. Ted
Weiss, D-N.Y., who supported the sanctions bills. ``But these are
real life-and-death threats that my constituents face daily.''
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., argued against the legislation, saying
it was more a political palliative than an effective weapon in the
war on drugs.
   ``We are not serious about stemming the drug traffic'' in the
United States, Hyde said. ``We'd rather point the finger at Bolivia
and Paraguay than Miami, Chicago and San Francisco.''
   Leonardo Ffrench, a spokesman for the Mexican Embassy in
Washington, said his country regards the drug problem as a threat
to its own well-being and is devoting all possible resources to the
battle regardless of pressure from the United States.
   ``We are not looking for cheers or for jeers from abroad,'' the
spokesman said. ``We ought to strengthen cooperation instead of
pointing fingers and blaming each other. That might only favor the
interests of the drug traffickers themselves.''
   Under the law, countries identified as drug production or
transit points must be certified by the president each year as
``fully cooperating'' with U.S. anti-drug efforts or risk losing
half their aid money, trade preferences such as sugar import
quotas, and U.S. support for loans from international development
banks.
   On March 1, President Reagan made such a certification for 17 of
the 24 countries on the drug production and transit list, including
Mexico, the Bahamas and Bolivia. The administration said Paraguay
wasn't cooperating sufficiently, but certified it anyway for
national security reasons, as the law allows.
   Because none of the countries receives large amounts of U.S.
economic and military aid, the sanctions would have little economic
effect. The country with the most at stake is Bolivia, which gets
about $22 million in economic aid.
   But their political impact is potentially great. U.S.-Mexico
relations always are delicate, and the Mexican government has
served notice privately that if Congress succeeds at
decertification, cooperation with anti-drug efforts will be sharply
curtailed and U.S. authorities may be kicked out of the country.
   The Senate is likely to take up as soon as Thursday similar
sanctions bills dealing with Mexico and the Bahamas, and a separate
measure adding Haiti to the list of countries that should come
under increased scrutiny because of drug trafficking.
</TEXT>
