<1ST_LINE>r w AM-OwenProtest     04-13 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Owen Protest,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Protest Photographer's Drug Conviction in Spain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 250 placard-waving demonstrators
marched in front of the Spanish Embassy on Wednesday to protest the
drug conviction and sentence of American photographer Conan Owen in
Barcelona last week.
   ``The bottom line is that a good kid is in jail and he's not
guilty,'' said Joseph Traver, a director of the National Press
Photographers Association.
   Owen, 23, of nearby Annandale, Va., was convicted on
drug-trafficking charge, sentenced to six years and one day in jail
and fined $18,000. Since his arrest a year ago, Owen has maintained
he was duped into carrying $200,000 worth of cocaine in a
false-bottom suitcase.
   The crowd of friends, collegues and supporters chantedd in
English and Spanish ``Conan es inocente. Conan is innocent. Conan
es inocente, inocente, incente,'' as Owen's cousin Teresa Corrales
delivered a letter to the Spanish ambassador.
   At the embassy door, Corrales and her grandmother, Elizabeth
Goulett, both of Alexandria, Va., were met by the embassy's
communications officer.
   ``She (the communications officer) told me she would deliver the
letter to the ambassador, but said the demonstration would have
neither a negative or positive effect on Conan's situation,''
Corrales said.
   Although the demonstrators had hoped for a more decisive
reaction to the protest, Corrales said this was just the first
effort and more was to come.
   Traver, who met Owen while the younger man was a college intern
at the Buffalo (N.Y.) News in the early 1980s, said the defense
fund hoped to raise enough money to cover Owen's fine, legal costs
and living expenses. He also expressed concern about raising funds
to honor Owen's financial commitment to the Army ROTC program. So
far they have collected $20,000, he said.
   At his trial, Owen testified he had been hired in the United
States by Jorge Barahona to take pictures in Spain and Chile for a
Mexico City travel gency. As part of that asssignment, Barahona
gave Owen the suitcase, the photographer thought was filled with
travel brochures bound for Santiago.
   Barahona, an Ecuadorian-born naturalized American, received a
two-year suspended sentence in federal court on a drug conspiracy
charge after a reaching a plea bargain with prosecutors.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Justin Williams testified at Owen's
one-day trial that Barahona said Owen did not know cocaine was in
the suitcase he carried into Barcelona airport on March 13, 1987.
</TEXT>
