<HEAD>Post: Celebs Owe Bucks To NY State</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of ophthalmologist in 3rd graf bgng ``In
addition''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Debbie Harry and songwriter Irving Berlin
are among dozens of celebrities who owe back taxes to New York
state, the New York Post reported Wednesday.
   The Post said it had obtained state records which indicated Miss
Harry owes $241,354 for record royalties while Berlin owes $5,500.
   In addition, the Post said transsexual tennis player and
ophthalmologist Renee Richards owes nearly $33,000 and drummer
Lionel Hampton's Lionel Hampton Enterprises owes $10,500 in
withholding taxes.
   The records indicated the state was seeking almost $289,000 from
the estate of jazz great Duke Ellington and more than $91,000 from
the estate of singer Brook Benton, who died Saturday.
   On Monday, movie reviewer Rex Reed pleaded guilty to evading
more than $20,000 in state income taxes.
   The Post said most of the tax assessments came from the state
tax department's Los Angeles bureau, which examines celebrity
sheets, gossip columns and booking charts for the New York income
of West Coast stars.
   The Post said a secretary for Berlin denied that the 99-year-old
songwriter owed taxes. Hampton's manager, Bill Titone, said the
withholding tax problem was cleared up in 1987. A secretary for
Richards said the issue was being handled by Richards' lawyer.
   Miss Harry's lawyer, Gary Kurfirst, said the singer was repaying
her debt in installments and would owe no money by the end of the
year.
