<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WrongCounty Bjt   04-13 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wrong County, Bjt,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Can Murder Defendant Be Tried Again After False Start in Wrong
Court?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stephen Craig Schiefelbein was already on trial
for murder when a prosecutor realized the case was in the wrong
county, setting off debate over whether a defense lawyer who knew
of the mixup was right to keep mum and whether Schiefelbein must go
free.
   ``It would be a miscarriage of justice if he were able to escape
because of a problem like that,'' said Steve Roberts, the chief
assistant district attorney in DeKalb County, where prosecutors
hope to renew the charges that had to be dismissed in neighboring
Fulton County.
   But Bob Joiner, Schiefelbein's public defender, isn't
apologizing.
   ``All this guy's got going for him is me,'' he said Wednesday.
``If I've got to help the prosecutor, my God, he'd be better off
without a lawyer.''
   Schiefelbein, 38, was accused of fatally stabbing a man who
befriended him and invited him to dinner on Christmas Eve 1986. The
stabbing occurred in a home in an Atlanta neighborhood which
crosses the Fulton-DeKalb county line.
   Law officers in both counties had assured prosecutors the house
was in Fulton County, said Assistant District Attorney Linda
Finley, and no one contradicted them until the first day of
Schiefelbein's trial had been completed April 5 in Fulton County
Superior Court.
   Then, Ms. Finley said, she telephoned the owner of the house,
who was to testify the next day, to go over his testimony, and ``he
informed me that his house was, in fact, about two houses over the
line in DeKalb County.''
   The next day, Superior Court Judge Philip Etheridge declared a
mistrial and lectured Joiner, who said he had known the case was in
the wrong court. The judge told Joiner he ``wasted a lot of time
and did your client absolutely no service whatever.''
   Joiner contends what he really did was earn an eventual
acquittal for his client. He said federal courts have held that
part of a criminal case is proving it is being brought in the right
court, so failure to prove that amounts to failure for the entire
prosecution. Another prosecution for the same crime would violate
the Constitution's ban on double jeopardy, Joiner argued.
   In an interview, Etheridge disagreed, saying his court never
really had jurisdiction over the case so ``anything we did would be
a nullity.''
   Therefore, the judge said, Joiner had no reason to withhold his
information ``except to delay things.''
   Geoffrey C. Hazard Jr., a Yale Law School professor of legal
ethics who was the main draftsman of the American Bar Association's
model code of ethics, said Joiner was under no obligation to tell
the judge what he knew.
   ``Clearly not. He had an obligation not to say anything,''
Hazard said.
   ``The defendant in a criminal case is permitted to require the
state to go to its proof on every possible issue, and it's the
state's responsibility to carry the burden in that respect,'' he
said. ``The defendant did nothing to mislead the prosecution, and I
think (Joiner) did the right thing.''
   If he wins his argument that Schiefelbein cannot be tried again,
Joiner said, it will not be a case of an obviously guilty man going
free. He said Schiefelbein, the victim, Michael G. Hadden, and
others in the house had been drinking. No one present at first
thought Hadden's wound was serious enough to summon help, Joiner
said, raising the possibility he might have died from a lack of
medical attention.
   Schiefelbein also contends Hadden was choking him, he said.
   Roberts said the DeKalb County district attorney's office will
not decide whether to prosecute Schiefelbein until his case file
and the judge's order are received from Fulton County.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
