<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Candidates-PACs     04-13 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidates-PACs,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Leads in PAC Money, Much of It From Bank Groups</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush has received more than
twice as much political action committee money as any other active
presidential candidate, says a report issued Wednesday.
   Nearly a quarter of the $570,045 in PAC contributions to the
vice president's campaign came from groups representing the banking
and finance industry. One is associated with a bank that is being
aided by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   First RepublicBank Corp. reported Tuesday that it suffered a
$1.5 billion loss in the first three months of 1988, one of the
largest first-quarter losses ever in the banking industry. In 1987,
the bank reported losses of $656 million, prompting the FDIC to
launch a bailout and inject $1 billion into the institution.
   The bank's PAC contributed $1,000 to the Bush campaign and $500
to Democratic candidate Albert Gore Jr., according to Wednesday's
report by Congress Watch, an arm of Public Citizen, a liberal
organization founded in 1971 by consumer advocate Ralph Nader.
   The group based its report on Federal Election Commission
documents on campaign contributions through Feb. 29.
   Joe Bowles, a spokesman for First RepublicBank, said the PAC
donations are ``voluntary individual contributions. ... They have
nothing to do with the company's finances.''
   ``By law, a corporation cannot contribute to a political
campaign,'' he said.
   Gore was first among the Democrats with $210,655 in PAC money,
including $25,300 from the banking and finance industry and $11,487
from law firms' political action committees.
   Jesse Jackson was second with $42,350, including $34,750 from
labor union PACs.
   He received $3,000 from a PAC associated with the Coca-Cola
Bottling Co., $5,000 from one associated with the United Auto
Workers and $5,000 from the Teamsters Drive Political Fund.
   The other active Democratic candidate, Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis, has said he does not accept PAC money.
   Among the other contributors to the Bush campaign were the
Oppenheimer PAC, $5,000; Auctions Market, which represents the
Chicago Board of Trade, $5,000, and PACs associated with Allied
Bank, $5,000, and Norstar Bank Corp., $5,000. In all, Bush received
$125,290 from the banking and finance industry, according to the
report.
   The Bush campaign also received money from PACs representing
major law firms, including $2,000 from Pillsbury, Madison & Sutro
and $1,000 from Mayor, Day & Caldwell.
   Among insurance companies, the Mutual of Omaha PAC contributed
$3,000 to the Bush campaign and Provident Life's political action
committee gave $1,000. The Gitney PAC in the food and agriculture
industry contributed $1,000 to the Bush campaign and the Flowers
PAC gave $5,000.
   Contributors to Gore's campaign included the Good Government
Fund of Third National Corp., $5,000, and PACs representing First
Alabama Bank Shares, $1,000, and First American Corp., $2,500.
   The Tennessee senator also received $1,000 from a political
action committee representing the Washington law firm of Arnold &
Porter and $2,250 from one associated with Kutak, Rock & Campbell.
   A PAC representing Aetna Life & Casualty, an insurance company,
contributed $1,000 to the Gore campaign, and the American Family
PAC gave $5,000. Gore also received PAC money from Occidental
Petroleum, $5,000; Warner Communications, $1,000, and Pacific
Telesis, $1,500.
   Election law limits each PAC to contributions of no more than
$5,000 to any one candidate, in contrast to the limit for
individual contributions of $1,000.
</TEXT>
