<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Congress     04-13 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Congress,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People's Congress Ends With Promises of Economic Development</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China-Democracy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chinese legislature ended its annual session
Wednesday with tributes to retiring leaders and promises from the
new ones to make economic development their top priority.
   The National People's Congress completed the business of its
20-day session by approving laws promising company managers and
foreign joint ventures freedom from government interference in
making business decisions.
   The delegates also voted to make Hainan Island in the South
China Sea a new province and a special economic zone intended to
attract foreign high-tech joint ventures.
   The congress, made up of 2,970 delegates who serve five-year
terms, was characterized by unprecedented criticism of China's vast
economic and social problems and by a strong commitment to the
economic and political reform program of senior leader Deng
Xiaoping.
   ``The present congress should make it its primary duty to ensure
and promote reform,'' newly elected congress Chairman Wan Li said
in a speech to the closing session in the Great Hall of the People.
   Wan's predecessor, Peng Zhen, was a harsh critic of the reforms
and growing Western cultural influences that have accompanied them,
including pressure for democratacy.
   Wan thanked a sour-looking Peng for having increased the
influence of the National People's Congress. Peng helped draft a
new constitution in 1982 that gave the congress the power to enact
laws.
   The new president, Yang Shangkun, a close ally of Deng, also
paid tribute to his predecessor, Li Xiannian, 78, who asked to
retire.
   The delegates voted by a show of hands to approve the laws and a
series of work reports delivered to the congress. One to three
delegates voted ``no'' on nearly every item, including the keynote
report delivered by acting Premier Li Peng on the congress' opening
day.
   Three delegates voted against the report and six abstained. The
official Xinhua News Agency said the approved version contained 100
amendments to the one Li originally delivered and included a new
emphasis on protecting the autonomy of China's minority groups.
   At a rare news conference later Wednesday in the Great Hall, Li
told reporters the report was drafted collectively by the top
leadership, he dismissed foreign news reports that he and Communist
Party chief Zhao Ziyang clashed over its content and tone.
   Zhao is an enthusiastic supporter of rapid modernization, while
Li has stressed the need to move cautiously.
   ``Zhao and I have no differences on political issues,'' Li said.
``There is some comment in the foreign press that Zhao favors
reform ... and I'm in favor of stabilizing the economy. They
somehow pit these two views agaist each other.''
   The 59-year-old Li also denied that his rapid rise in politics
was due to nepotism. Li, orphaned at age 3, was adopted and raised
by the late Premier Chou En-lai, one of China's most popular
leaders.
   ``I think my promotion has nothing to do with him,'' Li said.
   There was heavy coverage in the official media of congress
delegates demanding stronger government action to solve such
problems as inflation, stagnating grain production and a shortfall
of education funds.
   Li promised that the government and party would ``try to
formulate solutions.''
   He also said the leadership welcomed the comments of university
students who in the past week held a low-key sit-in in Tiananmen
Square calling for more money for education.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
