<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Ads,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Ads Stress Democrats' Views In War On Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, Jesse Jackson and Albert Gore
Jr., in a new round of television ads before New York's Democratic
presidential primary next Tuesday, are stressing their calls for
more action against drugs.
   In the TV spots, Dukakis, the governor of Massachusetts, urges
``a real war, not a phony war'' on drugs, while Gore, a senator
from Tennessee, says the military should be enlisted in this
battle. Meantime, Jackson, having preached against drugs for years,
reviews his ideas with filmmaker Spike Lee in an ad set to start
Thursday.
   This is the first time Jackson has had enough money for a media
campaign to rival those mounted by Gore and Dukakis and reflects
Jackson's fund-raising success since his strong showings in recent
primaries and caucuses.
   Jackson spokesman Eric Easter said the campaign expected to
purchase TV time worth about $500,000 _ 10 times more than what
Jackson spent on media for the April 5 Wisconsin primary. Dukakis
won in Wisconsin, Jackson ran second and Gore finished third.
   ``We plan to run a number of commercials,'' Easter said. ``We
haven't decided which ones to use and when to run them. We've just
decided a ballpark figure on how much we're willing to spend.''
   Gore spokesman Mark Armour said the campaign made a third media
buy Tuesday and ``we're still intending to run a million-plus
campaign in New York.''
   Steve Akey, a spokesman for Dukakis, declined to disclose how
much the campaign is spending other than saying ``we can be and we
will be competitive with everybody in New York.''
   Asked if Dukakis would match or outspend his rivals, Akey
replied: ``It's not always necessary. We didn't spend the most
money in Wisconsin. You have to be very careful about targeting
your dollar.''
   Dukakis introduced a new ad Tuesday night including excerpts
from a speech in which he attacked the Reagan administration's long
relationship with Panamanian military strongman Manuel Antonio
Noriega.
   ``I'm running for president because I want to see a real war,
not a phony war, against drugs and alcohol dependency in this
country,'' Dukakis says. ``How can we tell our children to say no
to drugs when we have an administration that paid $200,000 a year
to a drug-peddling dictator from Panama?''
   ``A chief executive can make a difference in the fight against
drugs,'' a narrator says, echoing another ad now running in which a
narrator points out that of all the candidates, only Dukakis has
been an executive with a state to run.
   The new Jackson ad shows Jackson and Lee walking down a New York
street. Lee comments on the sad state of the neighborhood and the
devastating impact of drugs on the streets, and Jackson responds by
discussing his anti-drug positions.
   Lee's character in his movie, ``She's Gotta Have It,'' mentions
having met Jackson and told him to run for president, according to
Easter. He said Lee has been a Jackson supporter for some time.
   Gore is using an ad stressing his experience as a Vietnam
veteran and another proposing that the military be mobilized to
fight drugs. He added a new spot Tuesday night on trade.
</TEXT>
