<HEAD>Huntsman Drops Out Of Governor's Race 30 Days After Getting In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionare industrialist Jon Huntsman left
the race for the Republican gubernatorial nomination Wednesday as
abruptly as he entered it, throwing his support behind Gov. Norm
Bangerter.
   Huntsman, red-eyed and looking tired, announced he was
withdrawing in order to help restore Republican unity and pursue
new opportunities to develop his $1-billion-per-year Huntsman
Chemicals Corp.
   Huntsman's surprise decision came one day before he was to
formally announce his candidacy for governor and 30 days after he
had stunned the party faithful by challenging Bangerter for the
nomination.
   Bangerter has been trailing Democratic challenger Ted Wilson in
polls.
   Without mentioning him by name, Huntsman blamed his withdrawal
in part on Merrill Cook, a former Republican who left the party to
launch an independent bid for governor. Cook's tax-cutting platform
has drawn support from the party's ultra-conservative right wing.
   ``When I entered the race, I never envisioned a lengthy,
fragmented party division and never anticipated Republicans bolting
the party to run as independents,'' Huntsman said.
   Just last week Huntsman's campaign had launched a $268,000
television and radio campaign to improve Huntsman's name
identification among voters before the April 25 state party
caucuses, where delegates to the Junne state convention are elected.
   Huntsman, 50, former aide in the Nixon White House, had
personally loaned his campaign $100,000 while awaiting arrival of
some $200,000 in pledges made the day after the March 15
announcement he was entering the race.
