<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Navy-Inventory     04-13 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy-Inventory,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Faulted on Handling Spare Parts Stockpiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy is doing a poor job of keeping
records about the millions of items in service inventories of spare
parts and needs to improve its bookkeeping procedures, a
congressional watchdog agency said Wednesday.
   The service is doing a better job than it used to, but it's
still not good enough, said the review by the General Accounting
Office.
   ``The Navy's accounting situation is like a bank forgetting how
much money it loaned out, then asking the borrowers how much they
owe,'' said Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, chairman of the Senate
Governmental Affairs Committee, which asked for the GAO review.
   The review centered on the Naval Supply Center at Norfolk, Va.,
and the Ships Parts Control Center in Mechanicsburg, Pa.
   The survey was the latest in a series of GAO studies of Defense
Department recordkeeping and inventory control done for the
committee. Over the past four years, the panel has focused on
trying to improve the Pentagon's management of its vast stockpile
of spare parts and other items.
   In fiscal 1986, the GAO found, the Norfolk center had a record
accuracy rate of 69 percent, meaning that records for almost
one-third of the items were erroneous.
   ``With a value of roughly $28 billion, the Navy's inventory of
supply items and repair parts is a significant investment in our
national defense,'' said Glenn.
   ``These supplies must be well-managed and ready for delivery on
short notice. We simply cannot tolerate accounting inefficiences
that could undermine the Navy's ability to perform its duty. We
need effective supply operations on shore if we are to have
effective ship operations at sea.''
   At Mechanicsburg, officials couldn't account for all the items
sent to contractors or to other facilities for work, meaning the
items could have been stolen or lost, the GAO said. The center did
not maintain adequate stock or financial records, it said.
   In a response that was part of the GAO review, the Pentagon
generally agreed with the GAO's recommendations, but disputed the
criticism.
   In the GAO's criticism of both Navy facilities, ``the report
exaggerates the significance of observed incidents and does not
recognize the existence of effective management programs,'' said
Robert Costello, assistant secretary of defense for production and
logistics.
   The GAO said the Pentagon should improve administrative
management of the two centers, including requirements that better
records be kept.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
