<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1934EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pensions-Crash     04-13 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pensions-Crash,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Private Pension Plans Lost $135 Billion in Market Crash, Study
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's private pension funds lost $135
billion or 10.4 percent of their assets in the Oct. 19 stock market
crash and its wake, a private research group said Wednesday.
   The fourth-quarter 1987 loss _ the largest in five years _
helped reduce the total assets of 800,000 pension plans covering 40
million active and retired workers from $1.3 trillion to $1.12
trillion, the Employee Benefit Research Institute said.
   Net capital losses of $152 billion resulting primarily from the
25 percent decline in stock prices were partially offset by
dividend payments and interest income of $18 billion, the institute
said.
   Despite the fourth-quarter losses, the nation's private pension
plans still finshed 1987 with $37.6 billion more in assets,
including $29.2 billion in total capital gains for the year, than
they had at the end of 1986.
   Altogether, the pension plans sold off a net $5 billion or about
1 percent of their stock holdings in response to the crash, the
institute said.
   Larger plans with total assets of at least $75 million joined
the selling spree in reaction to the crash more than smaller plans.
The large plans sold a net $6.8 billion or 4 percent of their
equity holdings in the fourth quarter.
   The smaller plans, apparently finding several bargains in the
depressed stock prices, showed net purchases of $1.8 billion for
the quarter.
   The institute's data indicates that some pension plan managers
had anticipated a downturn in the stock market, selling off a total
of $34 billion in stock during the first three quarters of 1987.
   The crash did have two significant impacts on pension plans,
according to the data.
   First, the declining stock prices reduced the equity share of
their portfolios from 40 percent to 36 percent. And the plans paid
out $45.5 billion more in benefits than they took in in
contributions during the quarter.
</TEXT>
