<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan Bjt   04-13 0776</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan, Bjt,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Jesse Jackson Critics Fear Any Attack Will Be Labeled
Racist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Wednesday that Jesse
Jackson has been spared criticism in the presidential campaign out
of fear that any comments would be misinterpreted as ``some kind of
racial attack.''
   ``It seems that more attention is being paid to the difference
in color than is being paid to what he is actually saying,'' Reagan
told the American Society of Newspaper Editors convention.
   ``I just regret that this has become a factor,'' he said.
   It was the first time Reagan had commented on the sensitive
question of how race has become an issue in the 1988 presidential
contest. Jackson, a black leader, is waging a neck-and-neck battle
with Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis for the Democratic
nomination.
   Emphasizing his own stand, Reagan said, ``I find a great
disagreement with some of the things'' proposed by Jackson, who has
advocated deep cuts in Pentagon spending and an array of costly
social programs.
   Reagan made his comments in a speech and a question and answer
session with the audience. He also made these points:
   _He did not know until recently that his former spokesman, Larry
Speakes, had made up quotes in 1983 and 1985 and passed them to
reporters as Reagan's own words. Speakes makes the disclosure in
his new book, ``Speaking Out.''
   Reagan said he reads the newspapers every day, but he did not
explain how he missed reading what Speakes had done.
   ``I can tell you right now that I have no affection for these
kiss-and-tell books that are being written and I find it entirely
fiction,'' Reagan said. Another longtime aide, Michael K. Deaver,
published an insider book about Reagan last year, and another by
former chief of staff Donald T. Regan is due out in May.
   In his speech, Reagan quipped that one of the nice things about
his job is that ``you get to quote yourself shamelessly, and if you
don't, Larry Speakes will.'' The audience laughed.
   _He expects Afghan rebels to continue fighting the Marxist
regime in Kabul despite an agreement being signed Thursday for the
withdrawal of 115,000 Soviet forces after an eight-year occupation.
   Reagan said there is nothing in the agreement that prevents the
United States from supplying the rebels ``as long as they need it
and as long as the Soviet Union continues to supply the Afghan
forces in their puppet government.''
   _The U.S. banking system ``has some troubles.'' But Reagan also
said, ``I don't think it is a problem that could suddenly bring
disaster down upon us.''
   Discussing politics, Reagan acknowledged the Republican
presidential race is down to one, Vice President George Bush, but
he did not give Bush his endorsement, saying there still is a
convention to be held.
   He spoke about Jackson when a member of the audience asked him
to assess civil rights in America in a year in which a black man is
running for president.
   ``I hope that race will not be a part of this campaign in any
way,'' Reagan said.
   ``But I'm sorry that in the campaign that's going on with one
candidate of the black race, that it seems that more attention is
being paid to the difference in color than is being paid to what he
is actually saying,'' the president said.
   ``And I have to believe that a great many of us would find
ourselves in great disagreement with the policies that he is
proposing and would perhaps be more vocal about them if it wasn't
concern that that'd be misinterpreted into some kind of a racial
attack,'' Reagan added.
   Defending his own record, Reagan said one of the most
frustrating things he has encountered is the charge that he is ``in
some way a racist and prejudiced with regard to racial matters.''
He said he has battled all his life for the removal of racial
barriers.
   Saying race has become a factor in the presidential race, Reagan
said, ``The candidates should all be based on what are their
policies and what is it that they would propose to do.''
   He said his opposition to Jackson's policies is the reason ``why
I've suggested everybody support a Republican.''
   Reagan refused to hazard any guess on the outcome of the
Democratic contest.
   ``I don't know whether the candidates now campaigning, whether
any one of them is going to wind up at the convention with the
nomination or whether there will be a brokered convention or
whether the Democratic Party will go afield seeking to draft
someone who has not been campaigning in the primaries,'' Reagan
said.
</TEXT>
