<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     04-13 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Heaps Praise On Jackson, and Vice Versa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, delighted with the decision
by Gov. Mario Cuomo to stay out of the endorsement business,
campaigned in upstate New York on Wednesday and was annointed by
the governor as ``a singularly important Democrat'' who could win
in November.
   Cuomo said Jackson was suffering from the ``dumb blonde
syndrome'' in which potential voters think that if a candidate
demonstrates charisma and passion there is little else there.
   ``Nothing could be further from the truth,'' said Cuomo, an
eloquent speaker who has complained in the past about being treated
that way himself. Of Jackson, he said: ``He is making this race a
manifestation of the American idea at its very best.''
   Jackson said he felt it was ``a wise use of power'' for Cuomo
and other party leaders to hold off backing any candidate until
after the primaries. Jackson said such a position encourages ``the
maximum people participation.''
   ``Governor Cuomo, just keep a freeze on all endorsements and
keep extending your support,'' he said.
   Cuomo has pledged not to endorse any of the three Democratic
candidates before next Tuesday's New York primary. That was fine
with Jackson, who may have thought Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis would get Cuomo's nod.
   Jackson and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. are locked in a battle with
Dukakis for the lion's share of the 255-delegate prize in New York.
A big victory could propel Dukakis to the nomination. Cuomo aides
said the governor expects to appear later with Gore and Dukakis.
   Cuomo has said he will get behind the front-runner after the
primaries and help that person collect enough uncommitted support
to win the nomination and thus avoid a deadlocked convention.
   Cuomo told Jackson that the fact ``you can get to be president,
or so close, that they put your face on the front page of national
magazines just to explain this phenomenon; that is extraordinary
progress.''
   ``I haven't heard a candidate address that subject as
consistently, as intelligently as Jesse Jackson,'' said Cuomo of
Jackson's message on combatting drug abuse.
   Asked whether Jackson should be guaranteed a spot on the ticket,
Cuomo said there should be no guarantees other than that Jackson,
Dukakis or Gore should be the presidential candidate.
   ``I think it would be a good thing to have a Jewish president, a
woman president, an Italian president, a black president; a good
thing to establish, to prove, that it's possible for everybody to
make it ... but I wouldn't make that the criteria,'' said Cuomo of
chosing a ticket.
   During his breakfast speech, Jackson turned to a favorite
campaign theme, that a key to battling drugs was more money for
education and social programs.
   ``Four years at state university costs $30,000, full
scholarship,'' said Jackson. ``Four years at Attica costs $160,000,
full scholarship. ... That's the message.''
   Jackson said he was encouraged to see the other presidential
candidates, both Republicans and Democrats, speaking out on drugs.
But he said they have come late to the cause.
   ``They are sergeants, but I am the bonafide general in this
war,'' he said.
</TEXT>
