<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Waldheim Bjt   04-13 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Waldheim, Bjt,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Panel Begins Televised Waldheim Inquiry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international panel of judges began a televised
inquiry Wednesday into whether Austrian President Kurt Waldheim
should be charged with Nazi war crimes or is a victim of rumors.
   About 40 witnesses are scheduled to testify in nine days before
the panel, which includes Shirley Hufstedler, a former justice of
the U.S. Court of Appeals and the education secretary under former
President Jimmy Carter.
   Thirteen German army World War II veterans who served alongside
the young Waldheim when he was a lieutenant in the Balkans are
among those scheduled to address the panel.
   Reporters are being allowed to watch some of the proceedings,
but reporting on them will be embargoed until a date to be
announced by co-producers Home Box Office and Britain's Thames
Television. The hearings will be edited to 3{ hours for screening
in Britain and the United States on June 5.
   In a studio-turned-courtroom at Thames' London headquarters, the
five judges will try to decide whether Waldheim is a victim of
rumor and exaggeration, or whether there is foundation to
allegations linking the former U.N. secretary-general to war crimes.
   Thames and HBO said six months of research have produced new
evidence and witnesses that weren't available to an international
historians' commission that investigated Waldheim's wartime
activities.
   That commission said in its February report that Waldheim was in
close proximity to Nazi atrocities but did nothing to stop them. It
left open the question of whether he was guilty of war crimes
himself, but it said he had concealed his wartime past.
   The producers of ``Waldheim _ A Comission of Inquiry,'' say the
$2.8 million project will be the most serious analysis yet of the
case against Waldheim.
   ``This is unique,'' said Telford Taylor, the U.S. chief
prosecutor at the 1946 Nuremburg trials and a program consultant.
   Some of Adolf Hitler's top commanders and perpetrators of
atrocities were sentenced at Nuremburg.
   Sensitive to charges of trial-by-television, the producers and
lawyers involved insisted at a news conference that the documentary
is an inquiry, not a mock trial.
   ``We will try to separate rumor, speculation and possible
fiction from fact,'' said retired British appeal judge, Sir
Frederick Lawton, the chairman of the judges' panel.
   ``We may not succeed, but we hope to go a long way to establish
what really happened.''
   Producer Jack Saltman said 24 researchers, including one who
``read through the entire West German telephone directory,'' had
tracked witnesses and collected 15,000 pages of material from 11
countries.
   Hufstedler and Lawton are joined by three other retired judges _
West German Walter Hubner, Canadian Gordon Cooper and Swede Gustav
Petren.
   Presenting the evidence is a Harvard lawyer and former director
of the U.S. Justice Department's Nazi-hunting Office of Special
Investigations, Allan A. Ryan. Challenging the evidence is Lord
Rawlinson, Britain's former attorney general.
   No one will represent the character of Waldheim, but Saltman
said he told the president about the proposed documentary in a
personal interview last summer.
   ``He said something to the effect that nobody but the Austrian
people could try him, and by electing him president they had given
their opinion,'' said Saltman.
   ``He also said that if I and what he called the Waldheim
industry searched for 100 years, we wouldn't find anything.''
   Producers said no attempt would be made to embellish the
proceedings with artificial drama.
   ``I don't think anyone's going to get rich on this, and there
are no movie stars,'' Bridget Potter, HBO's senior vice president
for original programming, said in a telephone interview from New
York. ``But certainly in this country, there's never been a real
examination on a broad level of the evidence against Kurt
Waldheim.''
   The allegations against Waldheim were raised in 1986, during his
presidential campaign. The president denied wrongdoing, and the
historians' panel that presented the February report was convened
at his request.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
