<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0694 04-13 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0694,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Calls for Speedy Execution of ``Drug Kingpins''
^Eds: Updates with Brock offering help, Bush saying he helped in
shipping newsprint to Nicaraguan newspaper, subbing 2 grafs for 8th
graf pvs, On the, and subbing 6 grafs for last 4 grafs pvs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said Wednesday that
``drug kingpins'' and people who commit drug-related murders should
be executed, and quickly.
   Bush, winding up a three-day New York campaign swing six days
before the state's primary, also talked with third- and
fourth-graders at a public school in East Harlem, trying a little
French on them during a discussion of homework.
   During a breakfast speech to the Association for a Better New
York, the Republican presidential candidate called for mandatory
death penalties for certain drug-related crimes.
   ``And, frankly, I'd like to find a way to make this penalty
swift,'' he said. ``Only a swift penalty will serve as a true
deterrent.''
   Asked by reporters how punishment could be speeded up without
infringing on a defendant's constitutional rights of due process,
Bush responded: ``Due process is fine, but we've got to find a way
to speed it up. I don't know the answer. I'm not a lawyer.''
   Bush also proposed a drug summit of Western nations and called
for an international anti-drug police force under the auspices of a
global body such as the United Nations.
   He suggested that the three Democratic contenders wouldn't as
aggressive in pursuing drug traffickers as he would. ``I challenge
the Democrats to stand up on this point. You say this is a war;
then treat it as such. Don't let these killers back on the
streets.''
   Bush himself has been criticized by Democratic candidate Jesse
Jackson for offering ``no leadership'' as head of the
administration's South Florida Task Force on Drugs
   And candidate Michael Dukakis unveiled a new television
advertisement Wednesday attacking the Reagan administration for its
previous support of Panamanian military strongman Manuel Antonio
Noriega.
   ``How can we tell our children to say no to drugs when we have
an administration that paid $200,000 a year to a drug-peddling
dictator from Panama?'' the ad says, quoting a Dukakis speech.
   Later Wednesday, Bush planted himself on a stool in the library
of Public School No. 146 in East Harlem and held forth on why he
hopes to be president.
   ``One of the things I like best, I like going into the White
House _ you know, the White House where the president lives and we
work.''
   What does he like about his present job? he was asked.
   ``I've been to a lot of countries. I used to live in China,
although that was before I was vice president. There are so many
exciting things.''
   ``But now, I'm running for president,'' he said.
   Bush got mixed responses from the group of about 25 third- and
fourth-graders to his question: ``How do you feel about homework?''
   ``Well,'' he told the class, ``comme ci, comme ca'' _ a French
phrase often translated in English as ``so-so.''
   Also on Wednesday:
   _Bush called Bill Brock, former campaign manager for Sen. Bob
Dole, to thank him for Brock's announcement that he wanted to be a
volunteer in the Bush campaign.
   Bush spokesman Peter Teeley said Brock ``has already been
helpful to us. He has put the Dole finance people in contact with
our finance people to help in fund-raising. The vice president is
confident there are things he can do and ways in which he can be
helpful.''
   _The vice president said he had played a role in helping to ship
22 tons of newsprint to the newspaper La Prensa in Managua. Bush's
effort was praised in an editorial in that newspaper.
   Teeley said that Bush worked with the State Department in
helping Americare, a private humanitarian organization, to ``cut
through red tape'' and make the shipment possible. ``He believes in
the importance of a free press, particularly in a country that has
had very little in the way of independent dissemination of the
news,'' Teeley said.
   _Bush made brief campaign stops in Buffalo and Rochester before
heading for a fund-raising dinner in Scarsdale at the conclusion of
his three-day swing through New York. He was accompanied in Buffalo
by Rep. Jack Kemp, a former rival for the Republican nomination.
</TEXT>
