<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FosterCare     04-13 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foster Care,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses Say Foster Care Law Not Being Enforced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foster children continue to be neglected and
mistreated despite a law meant to make sure they have safe and
permanent homes, preferably with their own families, Congress was
told Wednesday.
   The Adoption Assistance and Child Welfare Amendments passed in
1980 are not being enforced by the federal government or the states
and the results are devastating, said Marcia Lowry, director of the
Children's Rights Project of the American Civil Liberties Union.
   ``The harm to these kids is immeasurable,'' she told a joint
hearing of two House panels. ``Their ability to form relationships
with adults is destroyed. We are breeding a generation of
psychopaths.''
   Lowry was accompanied by a 12-year-old identified as Boyd A. who
spent years moving from one New York City foster home to another
while his mother, who had been temporarily hospitalized, tried to
get her five children back. It took a class action lawsuit to
reunite the family.
   ``They didn't let us come back because they said she wasn't well
enough. But that wasn't true,'' Boyd said.
   ``Sometimes we didn't like to visit our mother. You know why?
Sometimes they would have to tear us apart. We wouldn't leave. I
couldn't stand it,'' he said. ``They took almost five years away
from my life. That's almost one-half of my whole life that I spent
just waiting to come back to my real family.''
   More than 450,000 children spend some time in foster care each
year as a result of parental illness or disability, parent-child
conflicts, a child's severe emotional or behavioral problems or an
encounter with the law, said Rep. Tom Downey, D-N.Y., acting
chairman of the Ways and Means public assistance subcommittee.
   The foster care population declined by over a third between 1977
and 1984, but it has begun to rise again since then ``despite the
early success of the law,'' said Rep. George Miller, chairman of
the Select Committee on Children, Youth and Families. ``We will
attempt to unravel exactly what has gone wrong.''
   The 1980 amendments stress preserving and reuniting families as
well as finding permanent homes for children who cannot return to
their parents. They attempt to protect children in the system by
requiring case plans and case reviews within specific time frames.
   But Lowry said the ACLU, in research for lawsuits in several
states, has found widespread violations of the law and an almost
complete lack of federal enforcement.
   She said states are not monitoring and evaluating cases as
required, are not finding permanent homes for children, are not
providing family services that could prevent the need for foster
care.
   ``Access to adoption is a cruel hoax. It doesn't exist for most
of these kids,'' she said, largely because states are very slow to
move in that direction. By then ``the kids are so old and so
damaged'' by their experiences that they become very hard to place,
she said.
   Lowry also cited the troubling results of a Kansas City review
of 25 foster care cases, chosen randomly. She said 25 percent of
the children had been abused or inappropriately punished and 88
percent of the reports were not properly investigated.
   ``This amazing result violates the state's own procedures'' as
well as a consent decree and sections of two U.S. laws, she said.
   Boyd described several instances of physical abuse and other
problems, including his placement with a Spanish-speaking woman
with whom he could not communicate. Another foster care veteran,
Daryl Morris of Houston, said he was in six homes before finding a
family with whom he spent five years.
   ``I've had to deal with rejection all of my life,'' said Morris,
now 18 and a high school senior. ``It's hard living with different
people and being moved from one place to another. While we were
never physically abused, this was mental abuse ... The scars go
away from your body but not from your mind.''
</TEXT>
