<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bishops-Nuclear     04-13 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishops-Nuclear,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Report Retains Conditional Acceptance Of Nuclear
Deterrence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A report prepared for the nation's Roman
Catholic bishops urges them to stick by their conditional
acceptance of defensive nuclear weapons but questions President
Reagan's Star Wars program, the National Catholic Reporter says.
   A committee headed by Cardinal Joseph Bernardin of Chicago was
to have submitted the report on its study of morality and nuclear
deterrence during the annual meeting of the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops in Washington last November.
   However, Bernardin announced then that the report was being
postponed until spring so the bishops could assess the impact of
the arms control summit meeting at Washington in December.
   Editor Thomas Fox of the National Catholic Reporter, in an
article published in the weekly newspaper's April 15 edition, said
the ad hoc committee report was approved by the bishop's
administrative board at a meeting in Washington last month and will
be debated by the full body of bishops in June.
   The communications office at the Archdiocese of Chicago said no
one was available Wednesday for comment on the report.
   The newspaper said the 63-page committee report contains a
1,000-word pastoral message, a review of the 1983 ``Challenge of
Peace'' pastoral, a look at arms negotiations between the
superpowers in recent years and an analysis of arms race advances.
   ``We are persuaded to renew the judgment of `The Challenge of
Peace' that nuclear deterrence merits only strictly conditioned
acceptance,'' the newspaper quoted the report as saying. ``In a
dangerous world, a world of both wide-spread nuclear knowledge and
extensive nuclear arsenals, we find condemning nuclear deterence
too drastic a solution and embracing it too simple a response.''
   ``We believe that `strictly conditioned acceptance' is the
judgment most appropriate for urging countries, particularly our
own, to plan for and to pursue bilateral and multilateral arms
control and to move toward progressive disarmament.''
   The 1983 pastoral did not address the Reagan administration's
Strategic Defense Initiative, or Star Wars policy, since it was
announced shortly before the bishops released their letter.
   According to the Reporter, the new report questions the wisdom
of Star Wars, saying that while the goal of a defensive system may
sound attractive, it poses a ``collective danger'' and ``leaves us
unconvinced of the merits of proceeding toward deployment.''
   ``Once it is clear that intentions must be measured against
possible consequences, a morally adequate moral framework exists
for the policy debate on SDI,'' the report was quoted as saying.
   Some critics, members of the bishops conference among them, have
criticized even conditional acceptance of nuclear deterrence. For
example, Auxiliary Bishop P. Francis Murphy of Baltimore called
last year for withdrawal of that acceptance, saying it provided a
moral loophole for the nuclear arms race to continue.
   In an editoral, the Reporter criticized the committee report as
a technical document lacking encouragment ``for new energy in the
long and often lonely work of peacemaking.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
