<1ST_LINE>u w AM-IncineratorAsh     04-13 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Incinerator Ash,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Administrator Backs Effort To Clear Muddled Ash Picture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmental Protection Agency Administrator
Lee Thomas said Wednesday he backed efforts in Congress to better
regulate cities' incinerator ash, as local officials complained
that current waste standards are unclear.
   Thomas told a House Energy and Commerce subcommittee that he
supported the approach of a bill by Reps. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio,
that seeks to end confusion over the handling of ash from 140
municipal waste combustors processing about 15 million tons of
refuse each year.
   At issue is whether incinerator ash is to be considered
hazardous or non-hazardous solid waste. Thomas said EPA is looking
to Congress for help on whether ash from waste-to-energy
incinerators should be exempt from stringent hazardous waste
regulations that could mean high cost and lots of paperwork for
communities.
   Currently, the determination of whether a waste is considered
hazardous is based on toxicity tests.
   But confusion over the tests _ for example, how to handle the
varying levels of toxicity in bottom ash versus fly ash _ has
spawned lawsuits, and garbage-handling problems have mounted.
   ``Ordinarily, municipal officials, as I'm sure you well know,
resist and resent endless federal mandates,'' said Beulah
Coughenour, a city council member in Indianapolis who spoke on
behalf of the National League of Cities.
   ``This time we come before you from the opposite perspective. We
are here to ask for exactly that _ federal intervention in an area
that is uniquely a local government responsibility,'' Coughenour
said.
   Carrie S. Perry, mayor of Hartford, Conn., urged the panel to
pass ash legislation ``that provides more clear direction to public
jurisdictions currently facing waste disposal crises.''
   With room for exceptions, Lukens' bill would place incinerator
ash under non-hazardous waste regulations and give states the lead
in enforcing the bill's requirements.
   EPA, however, would be directed to write new regulations for
operating solid waste incinerators, and to develop a new test for
ash residue.
   Thomas said legislative action was needed, and ``the approach
(subcommittee) Chairman Luken has proposed seems to me to be on the
right track.''
</TEXT>
