<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Wheat-India     04-13 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wheat-India,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Okays Sale Of 1.2 Million Tons At Subsidized Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India has been given approval to buy 1.2
million metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices, the
Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
   Acting Undersecretary Richard W. Goldberg said India will be
allowed to buy the grain under the department's Export Enhancement
Program, or EEP. It is the first time India has been eligible to
buy subsidized wheat under the program, although vegetable oil has
been made available.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   Under EEP arrangements, exporters can sell specified U.S.
commodities to designated countries at reduced prices in order to
meet foreign competition and then collect free government surpluses
of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   Subsidies have ranged from less than $20 to more than $40 per
ton of wheat, or in the range of 54 cents to $1.09 per bushel.
   The Soviet Union also has been a big buyer of U.S. wheat under
EEP, with purchases totaling more than 11.8 million tons in the
last year, and China has bought more than 5 million tons under the
program.
</TEXT>
