<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     04-13 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Answering Gore, Says He Might Use Nuclear Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis, responding to campaign
criticism from Democratic presidential opponent Albert Gore Jr.,
said Wednesday that as president he might use nuclear forces but he
refused to elaborate.
   ``The policy I advocated has been the policy of the government
of the United States for many, many years. It's the policy of the
NATO alliance,'' Dukakis said at a Boston press conference.
   ``If Senator Gore wants to take issue with that policy, he
should do so. But he ought to get his facts straight,'' Dukakis
added.
   He was responding to criticism from Gore, who told an audience
in New York earlier in the day that it was ``unwise and
irresponsible'' for Dukakis to suggest that he would use nuclear
forces to repel a Soviet invasion of Europe.
   Dukakis and his aides insisted that Gore was distorting his
comments.
   And Dukakis dismissed Gore's criticism, insisting that his
position on nuclear weapons was the same as the policy of every
U.S. president in the nuclear era.
   The governor said he would consider the use of nuclear forces as
an option in the event of a Soviet invasion of Europe. But he
refused to spell out the exact circumstances under which he would
definitely use nuclear weapons.
   Dukakis was asked specifically how he would respond as president
if Soviet ground forces overwhelmed Western troops in Europe.
   ``We have always reserved the right to use nuclear force under
those circumstances. That's not saying we're going to do it, but we
have always reserved the right to do so. That has been the policy
of our government. It is the policy of the NATO alliance,'' the
governor said.
   Jack Corrigan, the deputy manager of the Dukakis campaign, was
more blunt in his reaction to Gore's comments.
   ``Senator Gore is shooting from the hip in an act of political
desperation,'' Corrigan said. ``We're just lucky that he's only in
charge of his mouth and not in charge of the button.''
   Gore, who is competing with Dukakis and Rev. Jesse Jackson in
next week's New York primary, said that traditionally candidates
and presidents avoid ``the trap of spelling out in advance'' when
the United States would use nuclear weapons.
   ``One of my opponents said in an interview yesterday that he
would launch a nuclear first strike against the Soviet Union if
they invaded Europe with conventional forces,'' Gore said. Dukakis
did not use the phrase ``first strike.''
   In a key passage of the Daily News interview, Dukakis said:
``I'm for a policy of no early first use. But our present strategy
in Europe assumes that if the Soviets were to invade and
conventional forces couldn't stop them that we'd reserve the right
to use nuclear force. I don't think that's going to happen, and in
fact I see the opposite happening. I see a real opportunity now to
bring down the level of conventional forces with the Soviets. I
think Gorbachev is serious about his need to significantly reduce
his commitment of conventional forces. So, I don't think it's going
to happen. But until that happens, we've got to be prepared to use
nuclear force. Obviously, with great restraint and only when there
seems to be no other alternative.''
</TEXT>
