<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DolphinKills     04-13 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dolphin Kills,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Critics Charge U.S. Foot-Dragging in Stemming Dolphin Kills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration came under attack
Wednesday for taking four years to implement a 1984 law intended to
reduce sharply the number of dolphins killed by tuna fishing in the
eastern Pacific.
   ``This is an embarrassment,'' Sen. John Breaux, D-La., said at a
Senate Commerce Committee hearing that also heard similar criticism
from conservation groups and the U.S. tuna industry.
   Drawing the fire was the National Marine Fisheries Service,
which is the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration agency
charged with carrying out a congressional order to deny foreign
nations access to the U.S. tuna market if their fishing boats don't
reduce their dolphin kills.
   ``The foreign tuna fleet in the eastern tropical Pacific is
killing over 100,000 dolphins a year, and our government agencies
have done little to implement the 1984 changes designed to address
the problem,'' Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said.
   The 1984 law was designed to put teeth into the Marine Mammal
Protection Act, enacted in 1972 to minimize the number of dolphins
killed by an international tuna industry that switched in the late
1950s from baited hooks to huge seines.
   For reasons unclear to biologists, yellowfin tuna congregate
beneath groups of surface-swimming dolphins, which serve as tuna
markers to fishing boats. Conservationists estimate that some 6
million of the mammals have drowned over the years after being
snared in tuna nets.
   Because of improved seining techniques, the number of kills by
U.S. tuna boats has dropped from 368,000 in 1972 to 13,992, the
hearing was told. Foreign kills reportedly fell from 423,678 in
1972 to an estimated maximum of 82,000 last year, compared with
108,767 in 1986 and 37,505 in 1985.
   William Fox, a member of the Marine Mammal Commission, said,
``We face a serious situation in the tropical Pacific.'' Fox said
preliminary findings from a dolphin census show some stocks are
smaller than thought and others are declining.
   It was not until recently that the fisheries service published
regulations to carry out the 1984 law. The plan would give foreign
tuna fleets until 1991 to match the performance of the U.S. fleet,
which is allowed to kill up to 20,500 dolphins a year.
   ``Why are we waiting until 1991?'' said Sen. Pete Wilson,
R-Calif. ``I think we should pursue why it will take until 1991 to
impose these import restrictions.''
   James Douglas, NOAA's acting assistant administrator for
fisheries, said, ``We're not particularly proud of the amount of
time it took to do these regulations.''
   He said regulators were walking a tightrope, wanting to foster a
reduction in foreign fleet dolphin kills but not wanting to cause
other nations to forgo the U.S. market, sell their tuna elsewhere
and not adopt techniques to save dolphins.
   David Burney, general counsel of the U.S. Tuna Foundation, an
industry group, said foreign tuna fleets should be required to
adopt U.S. methods. ``There is no excuse for them not having done
that,'' he said. ``It should have been done three years ago.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 2059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CoalSlurry     04-13 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coal Slurry,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Bill To Spur Pipeline Development</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Energy Committee approved
legislation Wednesday that supporters say would spur development of
slurry pipelines to transport coal from mines to markets.
   The bill, endorsed 10-6, is the latest attempt in a 10-year
effort by Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., and others to get a
coal-slurry proposal though Congress.
   The legislation would give coal pipeline developers a federal
right of eminent domain, the legal authority to force landowners to
sell them property for a pipeline's right-of-way.
   Supporters of the bill say that mixing coal with water or other
substances and shipping it through a pipeline would save
transportation costs and make the fuel more competitive with
foreign coal.
   The railroad industry has opposed such proposals in the past,
saying that if it loses coal business, it would have to charge
higher shipping rates for other commodities.
   As an inducement to the railroads, the committee voted 10-8 for
an amendment that would repeal the law that prohibits railroads
from owning coal leases on federal land.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
