<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CityBear     04-13 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-City Bear,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bear Living In Twin Cities Suburb Gets Second Reprieve</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE MALICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A timid, 450-pound black bear named
Thor has awakened from his winter slumber in the back yard of a
suburban home, unaware that he's been banished by municipal
officials to a home outside city limits.
   ``He's very gentle,'' owner Charles Crosby said. ``One time when
he was out, he saw a little poodle that was walking down the
street. Well, he just turned right around and high-tailed it back
to the house.''
   The city council originally wanted to move Thor out last fall,
but Crosby said he wasn't willing to wake him from his hibernation
for fear of raising the snoozing bruin's ire.
   ``That's something I really wouldn't want to do,'' Crosby said.
   The council delayed the move while the 6-foot animal hibernated
in his concrete den in the back yard. This spring, the council's
April 15 deadline was extended once again, giving Crosby and his
wife 30 more days to finish a new home, a log cabin outside this
Twin Cities suburb.
   Crosby said he and his wife had planned to move before the
council decided that Thor had to leave, but adds that he would have
fought the decision if they wanted to stay because they went
through all the proper channels when they got the bear.
   Crosby purchased Thor from a game farm three years ago when he
was 5 weeks old, getting up as much as four times a night to feed
him with a baby bottle. Before bringing the bear home, Crosby said,
he checked state and city laws and obtained a special license from
the Department of Natural Resources.
   But that was before the Bloomington city council passed an
ordinance that went into effect a year ago forbidding wild animals
from being kept in the city. Someone complained about Thor, and
that was that.
   ``We used to take him for walks around the neighborhood, but now
he gets about two houses away and won't go any further. He wants to
come back home,'' Crosby said.
   Still, the Crosbys are optimistic that Thor will take to his new
home. Deborah Crosby said the cabin is situated on 12 acres, and
Thor will have a large cage that has trees in it and a pond to swim
in, she said.
   Ardie Oberstar, who lives next to the Crosbys, said she'll miss
Thor. ``We love the bear. We never worried about him. He's very
gentle.''
   Crosby said he and Thor like to wrestle, but if Thor gets too
carried away, he knows how to stop him.
   ``He's real ticklish on his stomach. When I start tickling him,
he rolls over and shakes,'' Crosby said. ``His ears go back and it
looks like he's laughing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
