<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalBriefs     04-13 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrington Says Jackson Can't Win Presidency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Alabama New South Coalition supports
Jesse Jackson for the Democratic presidential nomination but the
former head of the black political group says he doesn't think
Jackson will win the White House.
   ``Some time in the future, it's possible a black can win,''
Birmingham Mayor Richard Arrington said Tuesday.
   ``But I do not think Jackson can win, partly because he carries
a lot of baggage among whites as a civil rights leader. This is not
to say anything negative about Jackson. This is a negative comment
on where America is.''
   In 1987, the New South Coalition, then headed by Arrington,
endorsed Jackson for the Democratic nomination.
   But Arrington, the first black mayor of Alabama's largest city,
said Jackson's recent successes are now backfiring.
   ``Now that he has become such a force, we're seeing a stop Jesse
movement,'' he said. ``I think initially it came out of the party
itself, which tossed the ball to the media, and now you'll see more
negative stories about Jackson.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Poll Says Dukakis Leading Jackson In Ohio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis has a
wide lead in Ohio over his two active rivals for the Democratic
presidential nomination, according to a Gallup Poll.
   The poll found Dukakis was preferred by 50 percent of Ohio
voters who plan to vote in the Democratic primary on May 3.
Trailing were Jesse Jackson with 23 percent and Sen. Albert Gore of
Tennesseee with 10 percent. Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois, who has
suspended his campaigning, drew 3 percent.
   The poll was based on interviews April 8-10 with 490 Ohio
Democrats. The poll's margin of error is plus or minus 5 percentage
points.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Chicago Mayor Urges Simon To Drop Out Of Presidential Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer, who supports Jesse Jackson
for president, says Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, who has put his
campaign on hold, should abandon the race for the White House.
   Sawyer said Tuesday he thinks Simon's withdrawal could help
Jackson, who trails Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis in the race
for national convention delegates.
   ``People will remember that he did not support Jesse,'' said
Sawyer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Flynn Says Democrats Need A Black On Ticket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Raymond L. Flynn says his suggestion that
Democrats put a black on their ticket for the November election has
prompted a flood of telephone calls from party leaders who disagree
with him.
   In an interview with The Boston Globe Tuesday, Flynn repeated
his earlier suggestion to columnist Mary McGrory that the Democrats
should select Jesse Jackson or another black to run for vice
president if Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis is the
presidential nominee.
   Flynn said the party should do that ``even if that means we lose
the election ... I'd rather see the Democrats lose than win without
a black on the ticket.''
   ``They have put their time and hard work into the party and have
gotten very little in return,'' he said. ``Having a black on the
ticket would help reunite this country more so than any piece of
legislation.''
   Flynn declined to identify party leaders who called to disagree
with him, but said he understands ``why others believe we should
win at all costs. But I'm talking from my gut instincts.''
   Democratic National Chairman Paul Kirk, in a statement from
spokeswoman Julie Anbender, said, ``Whatever combination of
candidates has the best chance of winning will be chosen. The color
of their skin is not what matters.''
</TEXT>
