<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 2128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DiplomaticImmunity 1stLd-Writethru a0696 04-13 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diplomatic Immunity, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0696,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Would Provide Greater Protection Against Crimes By Foreign
Diplomats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf bgng: ``The passage ...'' to clarify that
Martin is sheriff of Saginaw County.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers, police officers and New York City
officials on Wednesday endorsed a bill aimed at giving American
citizens greater protection against crimes committed by foreign
diplomats and dependents who are immune from arrest or prosecution.
   ``The passage of this bill will send a clear message to those
lawbreakers who know our hands have been tied by the present laws,
that they will no longer be able to wave a paper called diplomatic
immunity and walk away scot-free,'' said Dennis Ray Martin, deputy
sheriff of Saginaw County in Michigan and president of the
68,000-member American Federation of Police.
   The State Department said recently that from August 1982 through
last February, there were 147 criminal incidents in the Washington
area involving foreign diplomats, their staffs or dependents. The
violations mostly involved shoplifting but also included murder,
rape and assault.
   During the same period, 44 diplomatic crimes were reported in
the New York metropolitan area.
   Under an international agreement which was approved by the
Senate in 1965 and implemented in 1978, ambassadors and other
diplomats and their family members enjoy complete immunity from
criminal prosecution or civil lawsuits, but various exceptions are
made for lesser personnel.
   The bill, sponsored chiefly by Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y.,
would provide federal assistance to the 37 states that have funds
for compensating crime victims if they extend eligibility to
victims of diplomatic crimes.
   The measure would put Congress on record as favoring State
Department action to obtain waivers of diplomatic immunity or the
forced departure of diplomats who are charged with serious crimes.
   The State Department would be required to publish an annual list
of the names and countries of diplomats who have violated U.S.
laws, and to cooperate more closely with U.S. immigration
authorities in barring re-entry of those who have returned home.
   The department would be barred from hindering a state or local
criminal investigation or prosecution of a ``diplomatic crime''
where immunity is not involved. The bill also calls for the
president to study ways to prevent diplomatic pouches from being
used to smuggle arms or illicit narcotics into the United States.
   The State Department said recently that it generally supports
the draft legislation but objects to several provisions as
unnecessary or potentially harmful to U.S. relations with other
countries.
   At a hearing by the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on
international operations, the bill won qualified endorsement from
Steven Stein, chairman of the New York City Bar Association's
committee on international law, and Gillian Sorensen, the New York
City commissioner responsible for liaison with the 35,000 foreign
diplomats, staff members and dependents in the New York area.
   Stein said the victims' compensation provision may be the most
important part of the bill. He suggested creation of a federal
compensation fund to reimburse victims of diplomatic crimes in
states where assistance is lacking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
