<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceSymposium     04-13 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Symposium,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commercial Space Launch Competition Beginning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BURKHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commercial space launching will
develop into an important industry in the 1990s, and competition
may include the Soviet Union, a U.S. Department of Transportation
official said Wednesday.
   ``I think we will see innovation (in the commercial space
industry),'' Courtney Stadd, director of DOT's commercial
transportation office, told about 400 space industry workers at the
Fourth National Space Symposium here. ``There is some advantage to
taking private spaceports seriously.''
   DOT, as a result of the Commercial Space Launch Act of 1984, has
a mandate to define and regulate commercial space efforts.
   Stadd said DOT's role is to encourage a ``competitive and
diverse'' launch industry, and to ``regulate efficiently to ensure
safe and reponsible launch activities.''
   The scope of the space industry is expanding with the start of
competition in the commercial launch field, and the Soviet Union
may become one of the bidders, Stadd said. He added that he does
not see the Soviets as an active competitor in the near future.
   Commercial space launch was born in the era in which the U.S.
government concentrated its spending on the space shuttle program.
   When the Challenger explosion and U.S. rocket failures created a
large backlog of commercial payloads, Japan, China and France began
competing for U.S. launching business.
   The concept of commercial launch competition has brought up new
issues, Stadd said. The major problem being worked out is how to
allocate launching facilities among government agencies and private
corporations.
</TEXT>
