<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CaseworkersIndicted 1stLd-Writethru a0774 04-13 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Caseworkers Indicted, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0774,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Former Social Workers Charged in Deaths of Two Abused Children</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf ``The job'' to CORRECT to Federation sted
Association.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rare criminal misconduct charges have been filed
against two former social workers in the deaths of two abused
children whose cases they monitored.
   The charges against Hattie Roland, 37, and Diane Henton, 35,
should ``send a message to social workers that the state's
attorney's office will be reviewing their work to protect all the
children of this county,'' said Richard Daley, the Cook County
prosecutor.
   The two women, who had been fired by the Illinois Department of
Children and Family Services last year, were indicted by a county
grand jury Tuesday.
   Ms. Roland is accused of falsely claiming she visited a home and
Ms. Henton is accused of failing to report apparent abuse, said
Lisa Howard, a spokeswoman for Daley.
   The women are to enter pleas at a hearing Thursday. Daley said
Tuesday they were the first indictments of their kind to be brought
against social workers in the state.
   Howard Davidson, director of the American Bar Association Child
Advocacy Center in Washington, said Wednesday criminal charges have
been filed in rare instances but civil suits are much more common
because criminal convictions are difficult to obtain.
   DCFS Director Gordon Johnson said Wednesday that heavy
child-abuse caseloads, especially in Chicago, may make it
impossible for caseworkers to make the recommended once-a-month
visits.
   ``The question is lying about it,'' Johnson said. ``Those
individuals who don't tell the truth about providing services
should be fired.''
   ``The job just cannot be done,'' said Barry Friedman, president
of Local 2081 of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees. ``You're out there, and if you make the wrong
decision, you're going to be blamed as a baby-killer.''
   Ms. Roland was indicted on 63 counts of misconduct, including
allegedly falsifying reports, Ms. Howard said.
   She is accused of reporting nine visits to the home of Debra
Hardy between February 1983 and June 1984 that she never made.
   Ms. Hardy was convicted of murder in December for the 1984
strangling of her 4-month-old son and sentenced to 20 years in
prison.
   Ms. Henton was charged with eight counts of misconduct,
including failing to report the abuse of Jonathan Campbell. The
child was killed Jan. 25, 1986 _ his first birthday _ six days
after Ms. Henton closed the case after a home visit.
   An autopsy report said the child's ears were nearly torn off and
he had 25 or more bruises on his body, many at least 10 days old.
   Anthony Habener, a friend of the child's mother, was convicted
of murder last September and sentenced to 65 years in prison.
   The two women face up to five years on each count of misconduct
if convicted.
   Both defendants, who had supervised other DCFS caseworkers, were
fired after an internal investigation accused them of misconduct in
the babies' deaths, Johnson said. Six other supervisors from the
department's Chicago office also were fired, transferred or
suspended at that time.
   Civil service officials overturned Ms. Roland's dismissal on
appeal and ordered a 120-day suspension, said Dave Schneidman, a
DCFS spokesman. That suspension has expired, but Ms. Roland has not
returned to work and the department would seek to block any attempt
by her to do so, he said.
   Ms. Henton has accepted her dismissal, Schneidman said.
   The average caseload for state workers who investigate reports
of abuse is about 45, DCFS spokeswoman Jo Warfield said Wednesday.
It is expected to rise to 48 by next year despite an increase in
the work force, she said. Forty cases would be manageable and 30
would be ``ideal,'' she added.
   In Chicago, the caseload is as high as 60 or 80, Johnson said.
   ``We can point fingers, but the problem is that we just don't
have enough money,'' he said.
   The number of child abuse and neglect reports has been exploding
in recent years because of economic frustration, better reporting
procedures and more public awareness, Warfield said. Child-abuse
reports rose to 91,723 in fiscal 1987 from 6,700 in fiscal 1976,
she said.
</TEXT>
