<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EasternAirlines     04-13 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Airlines,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flight Attendants Sue Eastern Over Training of Non-Union Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Texas Air-Investigation Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines was accused in a lawsuit
Wednesday of violating a labor contract by using company planes to
train non-union flight attendants to serve passengers in the event
of a possible strike.
   The suit by the union that represents Eastern flight attendants
is the latest in a series of challenges to the labor-relations
policies of Texas Air Corp., which bought financially troubled
Eastern in 1986.
   The Transport Workers Union of America, Local 553, charged that
Eastern planes are being used by Orion Lift Services Inc., an
independent cargo airline, to train non-union flight attendants.
   Last month, Eastern lost a similar suit involving the training
of non-union pilots on its aircraft by Orion.
   The Transport Workers Union charged that the training of flight
attendants violates its contract with Eastern.
   Telephone calls to Eastern headquarters in Miami went unanswered
Wednesday evening.
   Last month, U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker ordered
Eastern to stop allowing Orion to use Eastern's planes to train
non-union pilots.
   Orion, which is based in Raleigh, N.C., has a contract with
Eastern to train flight attendants and pilots to fly the passenger
carrier's aircraft in the event of a threatened strike this spring
by 13,000 members of the International Association of Machinists
and Aerospace Workers.
   The flight attendants' suit was assigned to Parker, who
determined that the pilot training ``constitutes a unilateral
repudiation of the collective bargaining agreement'' Eastern had
with the Air Line Pilots Association.
   Eastern also suffered another legal setback last month when
another federal judge in Washington held the company in contempt of
court for taking steps to sell its northeast shuttle operation to
another subsidiary of Texas Air.
   U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt threatened to fine Eastern
$10,000 a day unless it stopped all efforts to complete the
transaction, which he said violated the terms of an injunction he
had issued last year in another labor dispute.
   The company agreed to comply with Pratt's order to purge itself
of the contempt citation and avoid the fines.
</TEXT>
