<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 2201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bolivia-Meese     04-13 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia-Meese,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Says Battle Against Drugs Can Be Won</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edwin Meese III, the U.S. attorney
general, said Wednesday a combination of reduced drug consumption
and sustained action against traffickers can win the battle against
narcotics.
   He commented at a news conference in La Paz, his last stop on a
Latin American tour that also included the Dominican Republic,
Colomoia, Ecuador and Peru.
   During a three-day visit to Bolivia ending Wednesday, Meese and
John Lawn, head of the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration,
visited the Chapare cocaine-producing region in the tropical
lowlands.
   The attorney general personally set fire to two tons of cocaine
paste captured by Bolivian drug police trained by the U.S.
military, DEA and Border Patrol.
   In La Paz, Meese conferred with the National Council for the
Fight Against Drugs, Vice President Julio Garrett and President
Victor Paz Estenssoro.
   ``We are embarked on a long-term struggle against drugs, and in
that context we are making recognizable progress, but whether we
are ultimately successful will depend on sustaining our effort and
reducing the consumption of drugs,'' Meese said.
   ``We are impressed by the commitment of the Bolivian government,
the quality of the anti-drug police and the government's efforts to
reduce coca leaf cultivation, interdict chemicals and arrest
traffickers.''
   He described Bolivia's anti-drug campaign as the most successful
in South America. The DEA says Bolivia produces one-third of the
cocaine that reaches illegal U.S. and European markets.
   Bolivia, an impoverished country of 6.4 million, has made an
agreement with farmers in the Chapare to reduce coca leaf
cultivation. Anibal Aguilar, undersecretary for alternative crop
development, says the farmers have destroyed 4,000 acres of coca
plants in six months.
   In return, they have received cash payments and aid to switch to
other crops such as coffee and citrus fruits.
   Police have confiscated 4.6 tons of cocaine paste since January,
with a wholesale value in the United States of $46 million, the DEA
says.
   Paz Estenssoro's government says it needs at least $300 million
a year for an effective anti-cocaine program. Washington provides
$33 million.
</TEXT>
