<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Gorbachev     04-13 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says `Window of Hope' Opened in International Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Trade, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev said Wednesday a ``window of
hope'' has been opened by the agreement on Soviet military
withdrawal from Afghanistan and other improvements in international
relations.
   The Soviet leader said the superpowers could reach agreement
rapidly on a 50-percent cut in strategic weapons, presumably
meaning before his fourth summit with President Reagan begins May
29 in Moscow.
   ``We are convinced that this goal is attainable in the immediate
future if both sides are guided by the fundamental approach agreed
upon at the meetings of the U.S. and Soviet leaders rather than by
momentary considerations and political opportunism,'' he said.
   Gorbachev played host at the Kremlin on Wednesday night to
visiting American business leaders attending the 10th annual
meeting of the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Trade and Economic Council. His
remarks were reported by the official Tass news agency.
   Gorbachev told his American guests, including Commerce Secretary
C. William Verity, that his ambitious program of economic and
social reform gives the two countries an opportunity to develop a
``new system'' of trade ties between the superpowers.
   The United States and Soviet Union ``can become mutually
supplementary components of the world economy in the 21st
century,'' he said, offering a review of his leadership's plans for
accelerating Soviet economic progress.
   He contended, however, that some Americans still want to use
economic relations as a lever to interfere in Soviet domestic
affairs.
   ``There are and will be serious differences between our
countries,'' Gorbachev said. ``But the times demand that these
differences not be a source of enmity and begin being used, insofar
as this is possible, as a stimulus to mutually advantageous
competition.''
   On international relations, ``We believe that the situation has
changed for the better, that a window of hope has opened a
little,'' he declared. ``The possibilities of finding solutions to
complicated issues engendered in the years of the Cold War have
become more apparent.''
   He said the agreement on Afghanistan to be signed Thursday in
Geneva may have international implications on a par with the
superpower treaty signed in December to ban medium-range nuclear
missiles.
   The Geneva agreement commits the Kremlin to withdrawing its
estimated 115,000 troops from Afghanistan. Soviet soldiers entered
Afghanistan in December 1979, presided over the replacement of one
pro-Moscow leader by another and stayed to help fight Moslem
guerrillas.
   ``By participating _ as mediators and official guarantors _ in
settling the Afghanistan problem, the U.S.S.R. and the U.S. create
a precedent of constructive interaction, which is needed so badly
to improve international relations in general,'' Gorbachev said.
   He said he hoped the Afghan settlement will ``lend an impulse''
to bring about settlements for other regional conflicts.
   Gorbachev said his program for domestic reform, known as
``perestroika,'' or restructuring, spawned disagreement in Soviet
society because some people are unwilling to change or give up
comfortable and convenient practices.
   ``Naturally, an acute confrontation, I would even say, a clash
of views, has begun,'' he said.
   The Soviet leader seemed at pains to assure his American guests,
many of whom do business with the Soviet Union or may enter joint
ventures with Soviet companies, that the confrontation has limits
and that his reforms will not include introducing capitalist
practices.
   ``There is struggle, but it takes place on a socialist
platform,'' Gorbachev said. ``I would like to warn against
delusions on this account on the part of those who watch this
struggle from the sidelines.''
  
</TEXT>
