<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FinanceMinisters 3rdLd-Writethru a0803 04-13 0957</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Finance Ministers, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0803,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Finance Ministers Pledge Efforts to Stabilize Dollar</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 18th graf pvs, bgng: ``Baker has ...''
to UPDATE with comment from Balladur on commodity index.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top finance officials of the world's seven
major industrial powers, putting on a show of unity to reassure
financial markets, agreed Wednesday to continue efforts to
stabilize the value of the dollar.
   The group, consisting of finance ministers and central bank
leaders from the United States, Japan, West Germany, Britain,
France, Canada and Italy, issued a statement announcing the
extension of a Dec. 22 agreement that has so far successfully
halted the greenback's three-year decline.
   The two-page joint communique followed a full day of private
meetings hosted by Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III and
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   The statement also announced the adoption of an innovative
suggestion made by Baker last September to use gold and other
commodities as a way of measuring inflation pressures.
   In addition, the finance ministers were critical of the newly
industrialized nations of South Korea, Taiwan, Singapore and Hong
Kong for not doing enough to reduce global trade imbalances.
   The meeting was the first face-to-face encounter the top finance
leaders have had since the global crash of stock markets last
October, a selloff triggered partly by squabbling among the top
economic powers.
   Mindful of investors' continued uneasiness at any signs of
disunity, the finance leaders went out of their way in their joint
statement to emphasize their strong desire to cooperate with each
other in keeping the global economy from toppling into a recession.
   The statement reaffirmed a Dec. 22 agreement that had been
issued after long-distance discussions in which the seven countries
pledged to work together to keep the dollar from falling further
against major currencies.
   The statement said the nations ``expressed their determination
to continue to coordinate economic policies to strengthen
underlying fundamentals.''
   ``The general feeling is that the economies of the various
countries are performing well,'' Canadian Finance Minister Michael
Wilson said at the conclusion of the session.
   The upbeat tone, in the view of most analysts, is justified.
Growth is higher this year than had been expected and the threat of
a global recession caused by the market crash has receded.
   While the United States is still running a large trade deficit,
the imbalance has been slowly improving in recent months.
   The seven nations adopted an American proposal to urge Taiwan,
South Korea, Singapore and Hong Kong to ``accept greater
responsibility'' in correcting large trade imbalances by making
further efforts to reduce trade barriers and to allow their
currencies to appreciate more.
   All four countries had large trade surpluses with the United
States last year, accounting for almost one-fourth of this nation's
record $171 billion trade deficit.
   The statement also said the seven nations had agreed to develop
a commodity price index as an additional economic barometer the
countries will use to help them to coordinate policy goals.
   The statement set no deadline for when the index would first be
used. There were also not details provided of what commodities
would be included.
   At the group's last meeting in September, Baker had caught other
finance ministers by surprise when he first suggested the use of
gold and other commodities as a signal of the presence or absence
of inflationary pressures.
   Baker has stressed that the proposal is not a first step back
toward a gold standard, the system by which currencies were
stabilized for a quarter-century following World War II.
   French Finance Minister Edouard Balladur, briefing reporters
after the meeting, said that the commodities to be included in the
index were still to be decided. While no timetable was set for
completion of the study, Balladur said he expected Baker's proposal
would be reviewed again in mid-June at the economic summit in
Toronto.
   The joint statement was generally in line with what economists
and financial investors had been expecting.
   ``I think they realize that if anything would be
counterproductive at the current time it would be renewed
squabbling,'' said Cynthia Latta, an economist with Data Resources
Inc. of Lexington, Mass.
   The dollar has risen in recent days on currency markets in
anticipation of the unity statement. Analysts cautioned, however,
that those gains could be quickly lost if a report to be issued
Thursday shows that the U.S. trade deficit for February was
unexpectedly large.
   The administration and its allies launched in effort in
September 1985 to push the dollar lower as a way of reducing
America's trade deficits and heading off protectionist moves in
Congress.
   The administration publicly renounced further efforts to weaken
the dollar in February 1987 in an agreement with its allies known
as the Louvre accord. In that agreement, the major economies
pledged to work to support the dollar's value at then-current
levels.
   Despite that pact, the dollar continued falling for much of
1987, pushed down by financial markets which feared that steadily
worsening monthly trade figures would force the administration to
work for a weaker dollar, despite public assurances to the contrary.
   The falling dollar raised fears in the United States about
renewed inflation and prompted the Federal Reserve last September
to hike interest rates.
   After the Oct. 19 stock market plunge raised fears of a possible
global recession, the economic powers issued the Dec. 22 pledge
reaffirming their commitment to stabilize the dollar. They backed
up that pledge with massive intervention in currency markets, the
process by which countries buy a weak currency such as the dollar
to prop up its value.
   The meetings of the seven top industrial countries were taking
place during sessions of the 151-nation Internatinal Monetary Fund
and World Bank.
</TEXT>
