<HEAD>Heavy Rain, Winds Hit North Carolina Coast</HEAD>
<HEAD>sday afternoon.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Winds gusted to 60 mph and tides ran as much as 8 feet above
normal, causing minor flooding and beach erosion and blocking some
coastal roads. On Hatteras Island, officials reported an average
loss of 6 to 8 feet of dunes to erosion.
   Elizabeth City, N.C. recorded 1.24 inches of rain in the six
hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT.
   The storm also produced winds of up to 49 mph at Wallops Island
and Norfolk, Va. and tides 2 to 3 feet above normal at Ocean City,
Md. and parts of southern New Jersey.
   Clouds and showers kept temperatures in the 70s in the southern
California desert after several days of 90-degree heat. Rain hit
the normally dry towns of Blythe, Thermal and Needles, Calif.
   Rain also spread from western parts of Washington and Oregon to
central California.
   Clear skies and temperatures between 75 and 80 degrees extended
from the lower Mississippi Valley across the central and southern
Plains and Rockies.
   The morning low for the nation was 17 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 37 degrees at Warroad,
Minn. to 89 at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Colorado Springs, Colo. tied its record high for the date of 76.
   Showers and thunderstorms were forecast from the West Coast to
the Rockies Thursday. A mixture of rain and snow was predicted for
northeast Minnesota and northern Michigan. Rain was expected to
extend from southern Michigan to the northern and central
Appalachians.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 80s across much of Texas
and the lower Mississippi valley and in parts of central Florida
and southwestern deserts; and in the 50s in New England, the
southern Great Lakes, the northern Plains and the Pacific
Northwest. Highs were forecast to reach only the 30s and 40s from
the northern Great Lakes to eastern North Dakota.
   Highs in the 60s or 70s were forecast for much of the rest of
the nation.
