<HEAD>Iraq Says It Beat Back Iranian Thrust in North</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Iran missile strike; picks
up 7th graf pvs: Tehran radio ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said Wednesday its troops repulsed
an Iranian offensive in Kurdistan province, and missile batteries
fired three long-range rockets into Tehran. Iran said it fired two
missiles into Baghdad.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency said Iraqi troops launched a
series of counterattacks Tuesday night, seeking to recapture
territory they lost in the northeastern Iraqi province.
   It said 3,500 Iraqis have been killed or wounded since the
offensive was launched Monday across the mountainous border, south
of the town of Penjwin.
   The Iraqi News Agency said two long-range missiles were fired
into Tehran around noon. A third was fired about two hours later.
   The Iranian agency said four civilians were killed and several
wounded in the first barrage.
   It said two missiles were fired into Baghdad several hours
later. Iraq did not immediately confirm the reported strikes.
   Iraq says it has fired 123 missiles into the Iranian capital
since the latest round of the so-called ``war of the cities''
flared Feb. 29. Iran has retaliated with 57 into Baghdad.
   Tehran radio said Iran also fired two short-range missiles at
the town of Al-Amarah in southern Iraq in retaliation for the
latest Iraqi attacks.
   It said Iranian jet fighters bombed Iraqi troop concentrations
in the northern province of Sulaymaniyah.
   Reporting on the land offensive, the Iraqi agency said the
Iranians ``could not seize a single inch of Iraqi territory.''
   ``The situation settled in favor of the Iraqi forces at 6:35
p.m. (10:35 a.m. EDT Tuesday) after 60 hours of unabated
fighting,'' it said, adding that the Iraqi troops killed or wounded
``thousands'' of Iranians, ``wiping out four entire brigades.''
   The Iranian agency claimed Iraqi warplanes dropped chemical
bombs as the defenders lost ground in their push into the strategic
region east of Iraq's important Kirkuk oilfields.
   It said Iranian troops were equiped with gas masks and
protective clothing, ``but many were injured.'' It did not
elaborate.
   It said the Iranians captured 25 square miles of Iraqi
territory, including ``strategic heights'' and several villages.
   The agency said Iranian jets twice bombed a headquarters of the
Iraqi army's 1st Corps at Kani Mizan, west of Penjwin, on Tuesday
``inflicting heavy damage.''
   Penjwin is 25 miles north of an Iranian bridgehead around Lake
Darbandikhan, seized in an offensive last month.
   The Iraqi agency said helicopter gunships flew 136 combat
missions on Tuesday, indicating a sizeable engagement.
   There was no independent confirmation of either side's claims.
Iran and Iraq rarely allow correspondents into the battle zones of
the 7{-year-old war.
   Baghdad has admitted losing territory around Lake Darbandikhan,
where the Iranians say they are threatening a hydroelectric dam
that supplies much of the power for the region and Baghdad.
   The new thrust appeared designed to intensify the pressure on
Iraqi troops in the region, who are already bogged down fighting
Iranian-backed Kurdish guerrillas.
   In the Persian Gulf, two more convoys of U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti
tankers sailed without incident Tuesday.
   The USS Jack Williams escorted the 81,283-ton oil products
carrier Surf City and the U.S. Navy tanker Gus W. Darnell from
Kuwait. Headed for Kuwait were the 46,723-ton liquefied gas carrier
Gas King and the frigate Samuel B. Roberts.
   The United States last July agreed to reflag 11 oil tankers to
protect them against attack by Iran, which accuses Kuwait of aiding
Iraq.
</TEXT>
