<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 2236EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IMF-WorldBank     04-13 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IMF-World Bank,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third World Governments Ask Debt Relief</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Finance Ministers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of 24 Third World countries
asked banks and governments of developed nations Wednesday to
relieve them of some of their debt burden, due to reach $1.245
trillion by the end of this year.
   ``There is no way out of the debt problem without a reversal of
the negative transfer of resources and a reduction in the debt
overhang,'' they said in a summary of their recommendations.
   The ``negative transfer'' refers to the estimate that payments
by Third World countries to the industrial countries last year were
$29 billion more than funds they received. This was largely due to
interest payments on the debt.
   The ``Group of 24'' speaks for about 130 countries of the 151
members of the World Bank and International Monetary Fund, which
are holding semi-annual meetings in Washington this week.
   ``The overriding issue is that the volume of (aid) to developing
countries is inadequate to meet the needs of economic growth,
poverty alleviation, structural adjustment and the resolution of
debt difficulties,'' President Barber Conable of the World Bank
said in a report being presented this week.
   He added that if more money is not forthcoming, the debtors
would hold back some of their payments.
   There was little expectation of any debt relief on a large scale.
   Dutch Finance Minister H. Onno Ruding, chairman of the interim
committee that makes major IMF lending decisions, spoke earlier in
the day against ``grandiose schemes'' for debt relief.
   He spoke in support of the present policy of dealing separately
with each debtor nation, though he added it has been working for
some but not for others.
   Negotiators for creditors say any reduction in debt should take
place only in agreement with the creditors. They have accepted some
losses by stretching out _ what they call ``rescheduling'' _
payments of interest and by reconciling themselves that few heavy
debtors are paying anything on the prinipal they owe.
   Brazilian Finance Minister Mailson Ferreira da Nobrega, chairman
of the Group of 24, agreed that solutions should be
``market-oriented.'' He repudiated the practice of some debtors of
suspending interest payments without the consent of creditors.
Brazil did that for most of 1987.
   ``Withholding of interest is not good for the whole system,'' he
told reporters after the meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
