<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nigeria-Riots     04-13 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nigeria-Riots,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Deaths Reported in Riots Against Gasoline Price Increases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government imposed a curfew
on a northern city Wednesday after riots in protest of gasoline
price increases. Newspapers said police shot three rioters to death.
   Nigeria's state radio reported the dusk-to-dawn curfew in Jos
and said some protesters were injured. It said the curfew was
imposed ``after a violent demonstration which paralyzed commercial
activity in the city today.''
   Three Lagos newspapers said their correspondents reported 15
people wounded, including an 11-year-old boy shot in the head and a
13-year-old who was wounded in the shoulder while selling soft
drinks on the street.
   Demonstrations are said to have begun Monday at the University
of Jos. The radio said the school was closed after the protests
became violent Wednesday.
   It said the situation was under control but several buildings,
including police stations and government offices, were damaged and
vehicles set ablaze. According to the radio, police fired tear gas
to disperse stone-throwing crowds.
   Gasoline and diesel fuel prices were raised by 3 percent
Saturday. The International Monetary Fund and World Bank
recommended higher prices for oil products to help reduce a
government budget deficit of $1.5 billion.
   Nigeria is a leading oil producer and, in the boom days of the
mid-1970s, its citizens came to regard cheap petroleum products as
a right. Even with the increases, gasoline sells for the equivalent
of about 40 cents a gallon compared with $4 or more in neighboring
countries.
   Bus fares were doubled in Lagos after the weekend price
increases and they rose by 50 percent in some other cities.
   The newspapers said violence in Jos began Wednesday when
protesting students were joined by taxi drivers and children who
rushed into shops and pulled people into the street.
   Col. Lawrence Onoja, governor of Plateau state, advised
residents to stay indoors. On Tuesday, he had told students to
return to classes and promised to relay their complaints to the
government in Lagos.
</TEXT>
