<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Holocaust     04-13 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Holocaust,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Herzog: Israel Is Guarantee There Won't Be Another Holocaust</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel on Wednesday remembered 6 million Jews
killed in the Nazi Holocaust, and President Chaim Herzog said the
Jewish state was the only guarantee Jews would never again be
victims of mass persecution.
   ``Never again will Jews become helpless victims, never again
will they be defenseless, homeless people without shelter at a time
of distress, never again will their fate be subject to others,''
Herzog said in a ceremony marking Holocaust Day.
   Israel later this month celebrates its 40th anniversary, but the
festivities are overshadowed by the four-month Arab uprising in
which 146 people have been killed _ 144 Palestinians and two
Israelis.
   ``The creation of the state of Israel saved the Jewish people
from complete destruction,'' Herzog told several hundred people at
the televised ceremony at the Yad Vashem Holocaust Memorial on
Mount Herzl. ``The Holocaust was so desperate it could have been
the death blow to the Jewish people.''
   ``Never again will there be another Holocaust, and the state of
Israel is a guarantee for that,'' Herzog added.
   Herzog also stressed that while Israelis may be divided on how
to solve the Arab-Israeli conflict, ``we are united in all issues
relating to the security of the nation, and there will be no
compromises.''
   Holocaust Day, officially called Martyrs and Heroes Remembrance
Day, marks the anniversary of the Warsaw Ghetto uprising of 1943,
in which Jews armed with homemade weapons fought house-to-house
battles with Nazi troops backed by tanks.
   The ghetto fighters held the Nazis back for nearly a month.
About 56,000 Jews were killed in the battle.
   On Wednesday and Thursday, about 100 memorial services were
scheduled throughout Israel.
   From 8 p.m. Wednesday to sundown Thursday, restaurants, movie
theaters and other places of entertainment were ordered closed.
Police officials said they would strictly enforce compliance, with
violators being fined a minimum of $100.
   On Thursday morning, a siren is to sound throughout the country
and Israelis are to halt for two minutes to remember the victims of
the Holocaust.
   ``Those who were there and those who were not, those whose
family was killed and those whose family was not _ we are all the
second generation of Holocaust survivors,'' poet Rivka Miriam told
Israel radio.
   ``I grew up in a house without grandparents, without uncles and
aunts,'' she said. ``I felt that since I live and exist ... I live
for them, too.''
   Earlier this week, about 2,000 Israelis, including two Cabinet
members and six members of Parliament, flew to Poland for
observances of the 45th anniversary of the Warsaw Ghetto revolt.
   It was the largest Israeli group ever to visit Poland, which
severed diplomatic relations with the Jewish state after the 1967
Middle East war. In 1986 the two countries established low-level
diplomatic ties.
</TEXT>
