<DOCNO> AP880413-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 2323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StolenTests     04-13 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stolen Tests,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search On For Stolen Test And Suspect, But Principal Thinks He Was
Set Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS G. KATSARELAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State education officials said Wednesday
they may nullify about 1,100 high school students' graduation tests
in Paterson after someone raced into a classroom and stole an
examination booklet.
   Eastside High School Principal Joe Clark, who has earned the
praise from President Reagan for his iron-fist, no-nonsense method
of ruling the urban school, claims someone was paid to steal the
test in order to embarrass him.
   ``It was the essence of chicanery and stealth,'' Clark said.
``It was done to denigrate and excoriate me.''
   Clark said he didn't know who was behind the Tuesday morning
incident, but called them ``adversarial forces.'' He claimed the
thief was not a student.
   Paterson Detective Sgt. Samuel Torres said he believes, based on
student accounts, the thief was a young man who attends the high
school. He said officers weren't able to track him down Wednesday,
but hoped to find him by Thursday.
   Approximately 1,150 Eastside students were scheduled to take the
test.
   Tuesday was the first day the High School Proficiency Test was
administered to about 130,000 students across the state. Students
must pass the three-part, three-day examination in order to
graduate. It is first taken in the 9th grade, but students in the
10th and 11th grades who failed the test in the past are also
taking the test this week.
   Assistant Education Commissioner Cummings Piatt says an
instructor was prepared to pass out the tests to five students in
one Eastside classroom when someone holding a hall pass walked into
the room.
   As the teacher inspected the pass, said Piatt, the individual
reached across a desk, grabbed one of the test booklets and ran.
   The teacher screamed for help, but hall monitors and others were
unable to catch up to the thief, Piatt added.
   He said that if there is evidence the booklet was circulated
among students, Education Commissioner Saul Cooperman and other
officials may determine that every student at the high school must
retake the test.
   Although the test is administered over three days, the booklets
include all three sections, said Assistant Commissioner Joel Bloom.
   Torres said he didn't believe that other students had seen the
test, but that he couldn't be sure until a suspect is apprehended
and questioned. He also refused to speculate about a motive.
   Clark discounted the theory that the suspect is a student, and
said a student wouldn't have been able to pull off the theft.
   ``The rigidity of discipline would have precluded that,'' he
said.
   Clark has been recognized by Reagan and U.S. Education Secretary
William Bennett for restoring order at the school, once known for
its violence and open drug dealing.
   Clark said the individuals behind the theft could include school
board members, city residents or state officials who are jealous of
his success.
   ``Being No. 1 makes you vulnerable,'' Clark added.
</TEXT>
