<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0725,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Goes to China, Philippine Troops on Alert at Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Aquino leaving for China.
Pickup 4th graf pvs ```Nothing can...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military was on full nationwide
alert as President Corazon Aquino left Thursday on a four-day visit
to China and Hong Kong, her first trip abroad since 1986.
   Coup jitters have been aggravated by the recent escape of rebel
military officers, including former Lt. Col. Gregorio ``Gringo''
Honasan, who tried to overthrow the government in August.
   ``The prudence of this visit, at this time, after a recent
incident, has been questioned,'' Mrs. Aquino said before leaving,
in a reference to opposition calls to cancel the visit because of
Honasan's escape.
   ``On the contrary, its cancellation would be the greatest
folly,'' she added. ``For our visit to China will show our great
neighbor that we have at least achieved the internal political
stability and peace to play a responsible and important role that
is expected of us in Asian affairs.''
   Mrs. Aquino said the visit would also provide an opportunity to
meet China's new leadership and renew ``our mutual principal of
non-interference in each other's internal affairs.'' China stopped
supporting communist rebels in the Philippines after Beijing and
Manila established full diplomatic relations in the mid-1970s.
   Mrs. Aquino's last trip abroad was to Japan in November 1986.
   On Wednesday, Mrs. Aquino assured her Cabinet that maximum
security measures had been taken to keep the country safe during
her absence, according to Presidential Press Secretary Teodoro
Benigno. Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos said the 160,000-member
armed forces would crush any attempted coup.
   ``Nothing can happen that can topple the government in one fell
swoop,'' said Brig. Gen. Rodolfo Biazon, Manila area military
commander, on Wednesday.
   However, he said both military renegades and communist rebels
fighting the government for almost 20 years could still be
dangerous. ``Of course, these crazy guys running around out there
can commit some crazy things, like bombing some isolated facility
or even assassinating somebody.''
   Cardinal Jaime L. Sin, the country's most prominent clergyman,
appealed for peace Wednesday. He said he was praying ``to keep all
the enemies of peace and democracy away from our beautiful land''
during Mrs. Aquino's absence.
   After Wednesday's Cabinet meeting, Ramos announced the
nationwide troop alert and said it would remain in effect until the
president returns Sunday.
   He also said security had been doubled at a military prison near
Manila to prevent further escapes by 157 military officers and
enlisted men held in connection with the Aug. 28 coup attempt. The
most serious of several bids to overthrow Mrs. Aquino since she
came to power in February 1986, it left 53 people dead and more
than 300 wounded.
   Honasan, the alleged mastermind of that coup, escaped with 14 of
his prison guards April 2 from a ship where he had been held since
his December arrest.
   Three other soldiers held for previous coup attempts have also
escaped in the past two weeks.
   The military also said Wednesday that communist New People's
Army guerrillas fired on one of its helicopters shortly after it
landed near Dumaguete, about 400 miles south of Manila on Negros
island.
   Two colonels and two sergeants were wounded in Tuesday's attack,
the military said.
</TEXT>
