<HEAD>Survey Of Tax Returns Shows Orchestra Music Directors' Salaries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS three grafs after 4th graf to UPDATE with dispute
over salary figure for Rostropovich; picks up 5th graf pvs ``Music
directors.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of the National Symphony and the
New York Philharmonic were the top-paid music directors of leading
orchestras, each pulling in upwards of $600,000, according to a
survey of 1986 tax records published Wednesday.
   Mstislav Rostropovich earned $687,000 at the National Symphony
in Washington during 1986, and Zubin Mehta earned more than
$638,000 as music director of the New York orchestra the same year,
according to Internal Revenue Service records.
   The Baltimore Evening Sun obtained the 1986 IRS records. The
survey offers a glimpse into the inner workings of these
organizations, which usually steer clear of revealing financial
details.
   At other orchestras with glossy artistic reputations, music
directors apparently earn more modest salaries. The Boston Symphony
paid its music director, Seiji Ozawa, $381,000 in 1986, the
Cleveland Orchestra's Christoph von Dohnanyi earned nearly
$332,000, and the Chicago Symphony paid Sir Georg Solti $355,000 a
year earlier, the newspaper reported.
   Patty O'Kelly, a spokeswoman for the National Symphony
Orchestra, disputed the figure for Rostropovich and said auditors
were reviewing tax records in response to the Evening Sun article.
   ``We ... believe that Mr. Rostropovich's salary was misstated by
more than $200,000 due to an inadvertent error by our former
auditors...,'' Ms. O'Kelly said. ``We are having the form reworked
by our current auditors, ... and will be filing an amended return
in accordance with their findings.''
   She said Rosptropovich's exact salary would not be known until
the audit is finished.
   Music directors conduct their home orchestras only part of the
year. Solti and Rostropovich, for example, lead their orchestras in
a concert season that lasts only eight to 10 weeks per year, plus
whatever time is spent in rehearsal. Ozawa conducts Boston about 16
weeks during the regular season.
   When they are not appearing with their home orchestras,
conductors make guest appearances at other orchestras and at summer
festivals, which can significantly increase earnings.
   Private expense accounts and the royalties from recordings and
broadcasts are also not listed on tax returns. Some conductors,
such as Solti and Ozawa, record extensively.
   As tax-exempt organizations, symphony orchestras must file IRS
tax returns. Those documents require each orchestra to list its
five highest paid employees as well as the five highest-paid people
hired as consultants or other professionals.
   Despite this, at least one orchestra surveyed elected to omit
the music director's salary from its tax return. Philadelphia left
out any reference to music director Riccardo Muti from its 1985 tax
return, the latest available. The orchestra declined to comment to
the newspaper.
   In some cases, the payments are made to corporations set up for
tax reasons.
   Boston's Ozawa is paid through a corporation called Veroza Inc.,
which is an amalgam of his wife's name, Vera Ozawa. Rostropovich's
fees are paid to Pooks Concert Inc., named after the Russian-born
conductor's late pet, a miniature dachshund. The Minnesota
Orchestra expressed former director Neville Marriner's salary as a
range of $250,000 to $350,000. A notation informs the IRS that the
exact figure is available on request.
   Symphony salaries have come under increasing scrutiny as many of
the nation's orchestras suffer difficult financial times and turn
to taxpayers for assistance.
   The Baltimore symphony has steadfastly declined to reveal
financial details of David Zinman's new six-year contract as music
director, even though more than one-third of the orchestra's $9
million operating budget is underwritten by Maryland taxpayers. The
orchestra's 1986 tax return lists Zinman's salary as $193,500 for
the 1985-86 season, his first as music director.
   Most orchestras had similar responses to requests for comment,
the newspaper said.
   ``We've made it a longstanding policy not to discuss any aspect
of salaries,'' said Francis Little, spokesman for the New York
Philharmonic.
   The newspaper quoted unidentified sources as saying that recent
reports that Lorin Maazel will get $1 million per year in a
contract set to take effect later this year at the Pittsburgh
Symphony were exaggerated.
   Nevertheless, music industry insiders believe that Maazel will
be the highest paid music director in America next fall, the
Evening Sun said. Maazel's salary at Pittsburgh in 1986, when he
was only a part-time music adviser, was $125,000.
</TEXT>
