<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Letter     04-13 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Letter,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Teen-ager Writes To Arab Newspaper, Calls For Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationalist Arab newspaper for the first time
published a letter from an Israeli, a 13-year-old who called on
Arabs to end violence and start peace talks.
   The writer, Lior Kay of Tel Aviv, also said in the letter
published Wednesday that the Palestinian people should have their
own state.
   ``Through your newspaper, I'm asking the representatives of the
Palestinian people and the Palestinian children to stop violence
and start negotiations,'' Lior wrote in pencil.
   ``I would like Palestinian children to read my letter and I hope
for an answer, especially from people my age,'' he said.
   The two-page letter was published in full in Hebrew in the
pro-Jordanian An Nahar newspaper, based in Arab east Jerusalem. The
newspaper translated the text into Arabic.
   An Nahar's editor-in-chief, Issam Anani, said he published the
letter because it was the first he received from an Israeli and
because he wanted to see how Palestinian children would respond.
   At least 144 Palestinians and two Israelis have died in the
4-month-long Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war.
   ``I'm an Israeli child, 13 years old, and I live in Tel Aviv,''
the letter begins. ``I like the Palestinian people, and I
understand the reason for your anger, which is your rejection of
the occupation.''
   Lior told An Nahar readers that violence and factional fighting
among Palestinians prevented them from achieving statehood. ``I
also want to point out that extremists among your people were a
reason for right-wing extremists among our people,'' Lior added.
   ``Your rejection of the occupation does not have to harm Israeli
children and pregnant women, and the solution won't come unless
there are negotiations between the two peoples,'' he said.
   ``You have a historical right and we have a historical right. We
should come to a solution which gives the Jewish people the right
to their own state, especially after what they have gone through,''
the letter concluded.
   There was no telephone listing for Lior's Tel Aviv address.
</TEXT>
