<1ST_LINE>u a AM-StarkSailor 1stLd-Writethru a0699 04-13 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stark Sailor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0699,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Psychiatrist Finds USS Stark Sailor Incompetent to Stand Trial For
Murder
^Eds: SUBS 5th graf ``The defendant'' with one graf to CORRECT that
victim's husband served on different ship.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19-year-old sailor accused of
killing a shipmate's wife and child is incompetent to stand trial
and meets the criteria for involuntary hospitalization, a
court-appointed psychiatrist said.
   Walter T. Taylor has been suicidal since his arrest for the
killings, Dr. Ernest G. Miller said in a letter filed Tuesday with
Circuit Judge R. Hudson Olliff.
   Olliff will decide if Taylor is competent to stand trial. If
Olliff finds Taylor incompetent, the defendant will undergo
counseling at a psychiatric center until he is competent.
   Taylor is charged with two counts of first-degree murder in the
killings last August of Paula Smits and her 3-year-old daughter,
Amanda. They died on Aug. 8 or 9, a few days after the USS Stark, a
guided missile frigate, returned to Mayport Naval Air Station.
   The defendant was a lookout aboard the Stark during the Iraqi
missile attack that killed 37 of their shipmates last May 17 in the
Persian Gulf. The victim's husband was aboard the USS Saratoga, an
aircraft carrier.
   Assistant public defenders Charles Cofer and Ann Finnell asked
Olliff last week to order a psychiatric examination of their
client, who is being held without bond in the Duval County Jail,
because he was staring blankly and refusing to answer their
questions.
   Assistant State Attorney Cheryl Peek, who is prosecuting Taylor,
said she will challenge the doctor's opinions during a competency
hearing scheduled for Friday.
   Miller said Taylor is suffering from post-traumatic stress
syndrome, which has been found in Vietnam veterans and victims of
violent crimes. The disorder was officially recognized by the
American Psychiatric Association in 1980.
   Miller also said Taylor's father is serving a prison sentence
for murder.
</TEXT>
