<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mofford-Mecham 2ndLd-Writethru a0808 04-13 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mofford-Mecham, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0808,0671</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mofford Working on Staff, Won't Comment On Whether She'll Run in
1990</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 4th graf to UPDATE with Mecham walking
out before live TV interview. Picks up 5th graf pvs ``Mrs.
Mofford.''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PN3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Rose Mofford, freed from the threat
of a recall aimed at her predecessor, began filling empty slots in
state government Wednesday, but said she had not decided whether to
seek a full term in 1990.
   Meanwhile, Republican ex-Gov. Evan Mecham criticized Tuesday's
state Supreme Court decision canceling the recall election but
declined immediate comment on his own plans.
   In a radio interview Wednesday, Mecham said an appeal to the
U.S. Supereme Court of the state court ruling is ``a possibility
that's open to us,'' but he acknowledged the high court might not
agree to hear the case. There's also been no decision on whether to
appeal a Senate impeachment decision to the federal courts, he said.
   ``We've been handed a bucket of lemons and we're going to make a
barrel of lemonade,'' he told supporters Tuesday. ``There isn't
anything in the law, in the constitution, that says that the
Supreme Court can cancel this election.''
   Mecham had been scheduled for a live interview Tuesday night on
a KTSP-TV news program, but he walked off the set seconds before
airtime saying, ``There was not a meeting of the minds'' on the
format. Mecham said he wanted to read a statement, but KTSP news
director David Howell insisted on only questions and answers.
   Mrs. Mofford, a Democrat, on Wednesday appointed a new secretary
of state to replace her in that position and said she plans to name
her permanent staff by Friday.
   She became governor April 4, when Mecham was convicted on
impeachment charges. She had been acting governor during the trial.
Mecham had hoped to regain the governor's post in the recall
election that had been set for May 17. In her comments to reporters
Wednesday, Mrs. Mofford, 65, declined to say if she would run for a
four-year term in 1990, saying it was ``a long way off.''
   She also said she hoped to begin sending nominations of agency
heads and commission members to the Senate for confirmation.
   State elections Director Jim Shumway was appointed secretary of
state after Karen Osborne, who had been serving as acting
secretary, turned the permanent post down, Mrs. Mofford said.
   Speaking with reporters after an appearance at a day care center
for state employees, she said she would oppose any effort by
would-be recall candidates to recoup expenses from the state and
had no plans for a quick State of the State address to the
Legislature because ``there's enough legislation there that needs
work'' already.
   The GOP-controlled Legislature's annual regular session began in
January and normally wraps up several months later. However,
Mecham's impeachment trial by the Senate took up so much time that
a delayed adjournment is expected, with a major sticking point a
1988-89 budget shortfall projected at $300 million to $350 million.
   Mrs. Mofford said she would concentrate on boosting Arizona's
economy. ``I plan to go out in the hinterlands,'' she said.
   In Tuesday's 4-1 decision on a suit filed by two taxpayers, the
state Supreme Court said that because Mecham already was removed
from office by impeachment conviction, the regular order of
succession must take precedence over the state constitution's
recall provisions.
   The justices did not give detailed reasons for their ruling,
saying they would issue a formal opinion later. Justice James Duke
Cameron provided the dissenting vote.
   Mecham still faces a May 19 trial on criminal charges accusing
him of concealing a $350,000 loan to his 1986 campaign.
   The impeachment trial ended with his conviction on charges that
he tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat and
that he misused a protocol fund by loaning $80,000 to his auto
dealership.
</TEXT>
