<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a07$Ls-3LiaGa 04-13
0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0780,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US To Keep Funneling Weapons Through Pakistan, Lawmakers Told</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs with letter from senators criticizing accord.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has plans to continue using
Pakistan as a covert resupply point for Afghan rebels so long as
the Soviet Union funnels weapons to the current regime in Kabul,
lawmakers briefed by Secretary of State George P. Shultz said
Wednesday.
   The arrangement, as understood by both the Soviets and the
United States, is at odds with a deal under which the Soviet Union
is pulling its troops out of Afghanistan and Pakistan is pledging
not to intervene in its neighbor's affairs.
   ``This is planned, calculated ambiguity,'' said Rep. Charles
Wilson, D-Texas, a member of the Intelligence Committee and one of
the leading House supporters of the anti-communist rebels, known as
the Mujahedeen. ``We have said publicly to the Russians and to the
world that we are going to continue to supply the Mujahedeen.''
   Asked whether that aid would be accomplished overtly or
covertly, Wilson said, ``Everything has been done covertly'' and
noted that Pakistan continues to deny officially that they have
helped in U.S. rebel supply efforts.
   ``We fully expect the Soviet Union to accuse Pakistan of
violating this agreement, and we fully expect Pakistan to deny
it,'' he said.
   ``And we fully expect the Soviet Union to accuse us of
continuing to supply arms to the Mujahedeen, and we fully expect to
accuse the Soviet Union of continuing to supply a minority puppet
government in Kabul. And we fully expect our side to win,'' Wilson
said.
   Shultz, who separately briefed House members and senators on
Wednesday, was traveling to Geneva Thursday for a signing ceremony
for the agreement, which he will sign for the United States as a
guarantor of the accord.
   Wilson and most other lawmakers said they were satisfied with
Shultz's assurances that the rebels will continue to receive U.S.
aid, but a few staunch conservatives voiced objections to the
agreement.
   ``We're depending on assurances, the good faith of the Soviet
Union to abide by vague agreements,'' said Rep. Phil Crane, R-Ill.,
who noted that the rebels themselves, whom the United States
recognizes as the legitimate voice of Afghanistan, have rejected
the agreement and vowed to continue fighting.
   ``I can't help but entertain a great deal of skepticism,'' Crane
said.
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Calif., said, ``I assume that there would
have to be some kind of violation of the accords'' to continue aid
to the rebels, because aid can only be supplied through Pakistan.
   ``My concern is that at some point they might be forced to live
up to the letter of the accords,'' Burton added. He said he feared
that the Soviet Union at some point would be able to turn any U.S.
covert supply effort in violation of the agreement into a
propaganda weapon against the United States.
   ``The Mujahedeen have the Soviet Union with their tail between
their legs, heading for the border,'' he said. ``The pressure
should be constant until the Soviets are completely out'' of the
country.
   Fourteen Republican senators, in a letter to President Reagan
made public Wednesday, said they were ``shocked that the United
States intends to sign as a guarantor to the Geneva accords,
despite the vehement opposition of the Afghan Resistance Alliance.''
   The senators said the U.S. action ``sends a tragic message to
the people of Afghanistan.'' The letter was released by Rep. Gordon
Humphrey, R-N.H., a staunch backer in Congress of the anti-Soviet
guerrillas.
</TEXT>
