<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 2359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gore 3rdLd-Writethru a0759 04-13 0916</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0759,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Hits Dukakis on Foreign Policy Inexperience</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To updates with new Gore comment on newspaper interview,
INSERT two grafs after 18th graf, ``Asked if...''; picks up 19th
pvs, ``Gore stood...''
^By WILLIAM M. WELCH</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WOODBURY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Albert Gore Jr. said Wednesday
that rival Michael Dukakis showed foreign policy inexperience with
an ``unwise and irresponsible'' statement that he would reserve the
right to respond with nuclear force if the Soviets invaded Western
Europe.
   Gore said Dukakis had erred in ``saying that he would launch a
nuclear strike against the Soviet Union under ... specific
circumstances,'' but transcripts indicated the governor did not
make such a statement.
   Nonetheless, Gore accused the Massachusetts governor of
violating a long-held ``tenet of American foreign policy'' that
presidents and aspirants for that office do not spell out to the
Soviets or any other country how the United States would make use
of nuclear arsenals in response to agression.
   With New York's Democratic presidential primary one week away
and looming as crucial for his candidacy, the Tennessee senator
seized on comments attributed to Dukakis in an interview published
Wednesday in the New York Daily News.
   ``Governor Dukakis made a significant mistake in saying that he
would launch a nuclear strike against the Soviet Union under the
following specific circumstances,'' Gore said. ``That's unwise and
irresponsible, and it underscores ... that experience in foreign
policy is relevant.''
   Gore made his assault on Dukakis at a breakfast with business
and civic leaders on Long Island, and later with reporters.
   Dukakis' remarks were contained in a story in the newspaper
which quoted him as saying of the scenario of a Soviet attack on
Europe: ``Our present strategy in Europe assumes that if the
Soviets were to invade and conventional forces couldn't stop them,
we reserve the right to use nuclear force. I don't think that's
going to happen and in fact I see the opposite happening.''
   Gore also had criticism for rival Jesse Jackson, saying he had
displayed his lack of foreign policy experience with a remark
before the U.S.-Soviet agreement on intermediate nuclear weapons in
Europe was reached that he would unilaterally halt deployment. Gore
said the agreement would not have taken place had the United States
taken the position Jackson advocated.
   Gore also criticized Dukakis as ``a little murky'' on the
question of establishing an independent state for Palestinians, a
subject of campaign discussion in recent days as the battle for New
York's 255 delegates has focused on Middle East issues and the
concerns of the state's influential Jewish population.
   The Gore campaign, however, considered Dukakis' statement on a
nuclear response to be a major event in the New York campaign. San
Francisco fund-raiser and Gore adviser Duane B. Garrett said
Dukakis has shown he is ``error prone'' and compared the nuclear
statement to major gaffes of earlier campaigns: President Ford's
suggestion that Poland was not under Soviet influence and
Republican George Romney's remark that he had been brainwashed on
the issue of Vietnam.
   ``I see this as a major blunder of that caliber,'' said Garrett.
   Speaking to the breakfast group, Gore said neither of his
Democratic rivals had any foreign policy experience and, defending
his own statement, added: ``That's not a personal attack. It's just
fact.''
   He described the Dukakis interview as a ``fresh illustration.''
   ``One of my opponents said in an interview yesterday that he
would launch a nuclear first strike against the Soviet Union if
they invaded'' Europe with conventional forces, Gore said in an
apparent misrepresentation of Dukakis' comments.
   ``It is a mistake. It is irresponsible to publicly state we'll
launch our missiles and trigger nuclear war under these
circumstances or those circumstances,'' Gore said. ``That's been
held in reserve and covered with uncertainty we want to exist in
the minds of our adversaries in this world _ for good reason.''
   Later, campaigning in Niagara Falls, N.Y., Gore stood by his
criticism of Dukakis and his characterization of Dukakis' remarks.
   ``I think it is most unwise for a president of the United States
or a major candidate for the presidency to be drawn into a
hypothetical discussion of when we would launch our nuclear forces
and trigger the destruction of human civilization,'' he said.
   Asked if he would rule out the use of nuclear weapons, Gore
said, ``I will not be drawn into a hypothetical discussion. ...
Governor Dukakis made a serious mistake in allowing himself to be
drawn into that discussion and then in saying that he would launch
a first strike against the Soviet Union if they launched a
conventional war on Europe.''
   During an appearance Wednesday night in Westchester County, Gore
read from a transcript of the newspaper interview and said Dukakis
had been asked whether he could conceive of the first use of
``strategic'' weapons
   ``NATO has purposely refused to respond to that hypothetical,''
he said. ``The president of the United States has traditionally
refused to respond to that hypothetical.''
   Gore stood in front of the Love Canal hazardous waste site and
denounced the Reagan administration for what he said was a failure
to enforce environmental protection laws and a failure to see that
such sites are properly cleaned up.
   ``This administration's record on environmental protection is
disgraceful and Love Canal stands as a symbol of their
unwillingness to act,'' he said.
   As a House member, Gore chaired the first congressional hearings
into the dumping of hazardous wastes at the Love Canal site.
</TEXT>
