<1ST_LINE>u i AM-MotherTeresa 1stLd-Writethru a0743 04-13 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mother Teresa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0743,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Teresa Weeps For London's Homeless</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads thruout to UPDATE with Mother Teresa's meeting with
Thatcher. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Teresa said Wednesday that
London's homeless living in cardboard boxes move her just as deeply
as India's poor, and that Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher pledged
to help.
   ``I find poverty in a rich country more difficult to remove than
poverty in a poor country,'' she said. ``Food aid can be gotten for
a famine, but food for these people?''
   The 77-year-old Roman Catholic nun, famous for her 1979 Nobel
Peace Prize and slight stature, made an unpublicized tour of
central London Tuesday with sisters of her Missionaries of Charity.
   The Albanian-Indian nun's charity mission, founded in 1950,
operates in 80 countries.
   She described her reaction to visiting London's homeless
Wednesday at a five-day Global Forum of Spiritual and Parliamentary
Leaders on Human Survival at Oxford. The nun came to Britain to
join the group, which is discussing how to tackle world problems
like nuclear arms, pollution and poverty.
   She told reporters in London just before meeting Mrs. Thatcher
that she would ask the prime minister ``to give us a house for our
people,'' a hostel for the homeless.
   Her organization already operates two small hostels in London
but wants to establish a larger one.
   As she left the official residence nearly 40 minutes later,
Mother Teresa said Mrs. Thatcher pledged her help and that the
prime minister's response was ``wonderful. She wants to help us to
help our people.''
   The prime minister's office said the two women did not discuss
details of a hostel but that Mrs. Thatcher told Mother Teresa about
the work being done by British voluntary service organizations.
   Mother Teresa said that during her London visit, ``I went with
the sisters to bring a little bit of hot soup and food to homeless
people.''
   ``They were inside that cardboard box made like a little coffin.
I didn't know what to say. My eyes were full of tears.
   ``There was this man, lying there, protecting himself from the
cold, with no home and no hope. He looked up and said: `It's a
long, long time since I felt the warmth of a human hand.'''
   Also at the Oxford forum, Mother Teresa disagreed sharply with
advocates of contraception, urging ``natural family planning
methods'' instead.
   ``I never give a child for adoption to a family that uses
contraceptives that kill the power of love,'' she said. ``How can a
mother love another's child if she has killed the child of her
love?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
