<DOCNO> AP880413-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 2321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Dukakis-HealthCare     04-13 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Health Care,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Hails Passage of Massachusetts' Universal Health Care Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis hailed an innovative
universal health care bill Wednesday as the product of broad
popular support despite its extremely narrow margin of approval in
the state Legislature.
   ``I'm very proud of the fact that Massachusetts will be the
first state in the nation, ever, to have legislation which will
guarantee basic health insurance to all of our citizens _ something
which is long overdue for Massachusetts and long overdue for the
country,'' Dukakis said at a Statehouse news conference.
   The governor, who has trumpeted the legislation in his
presidential campaign, said he had not decided when to sign the
bill. But it was widely expected that he would do so before next
Tuesday's presidential primary in New York.
   ``This is the culmination of months of work _ years, really _ by
a great many people in this state and across this country,'' he
said. ``We couldn't possibly have done it without the help ... of a
broad and very strong coalition'' of labor, business and health
care professionals.
   In fact, however, the bill barely passed the Legislature, which
is dominated by a 4-to-1 Democratic majority. The House accepted a
last-minute compromise version by a vote of 77-75, and the Senate
did the same early Wednesday by an 18-15 margin.
   The votes, which ended nearly nine months of intense legislative
debate and negotiations with a host of special interests, resulted
in a plan to guarantee health insurance to all Massachusetts
residents by 1992 at a possible cost of $1 billion.
   As late as Tuesday, labor unions were upset by a provision that
potentially could reduce public employee health care benefits by
removing the issue from collective bargaining.
   Legislative leaders, fearing they would be unable to get a
two-thirds majority needed to correct the bill, decided to put the
collective bargaining amendment in an unrelated bill, which Dukakis
promised to sign.
   Dukakis argued that the concern over ``rollbacks'' in public
employee health plans was the primary reason for the narrowness of
the vote. Citing public opinion surveys and a ballot question,
Dukakis said universal health care was an idea whose time has come.
   ``I think we're sending a very important signal out. That is
that 40 yeras after Harry Truman first proposed it, we're finally
on the road to basic health security,'' Dukakis said.
   The bill sets Jan. 1, 1992, as the deadline for businesses to
begin offering health insurance to their employees or begin paying
an unemployment surcharge to the state so it can provide coverage
to the estimated 600,000 uninsured residents of the state.
   Despite adding an exemption for businesses of five or fewer
employees, tax breaks, state-sponsored pooled insurance and the
possibility of outright state subsidies, Republican opponents
repeatedly warned that the bill would raise business costs,
bankrupt some businesses and discourage expansion of others.
   The two-part bill also renews the state's hospital financing law
and contains about $1 billion in hospital fee increases over the
next four years. About $95 million in additional new revenues was
added for 42 hard-pressed hospitals.
   Dukakis has budgeted $78 million in fiscal 1989 as the state's
share in the first full year of the four-year universal health care
phase-in. But cost estimates over four years vary widely _ from
$550 million to $1.2 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Turks     04-13 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Turks,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkish Aliens Rally Outside Parliament To Protest Deportations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 1,000 Turkish aliens and their
supporters rallied outside Parliament Tuesday but gained no
concessions from the government in their fight against deportations.
   About 100 Turks had marched for nine days from Montreal to
Ottawa in a proptest against Canada's deportation policies. Some
said they planned to march back to the Montreal airport and ask
people along the route for help in their campaign.
   Immigration Minister Barbara McDougall told leaders of the
group, and later informed Parliament in a special statement, that
she would not give a reprieve to the Turks who have been ordered to
leave the country.
   About 2,000 Turks sold their belongings and flew to Canada two
years ago after travel agents in Turkey told them they would have
no trouble starting a new life in Canada as refugees.
   Most settled in Montreal and found jobs.
   But Canadian authorities subsequently declared that the Turks
were not legally refugees and said they should have applied to
immigrate through normal channels. About 400 returned to Turkey
voluntarily. The march was launched after the government began
issuing deportation orders to the others.
   Opposition parties asked the Immigration Ministry to offer
reprieves to the Turks for humanitarian reasons, noting the
government granted special admission to 40,000 refugees last year.
   ``They were just fooled by some crooks in their own country,''
said Liberal Party Sen. Jacques Hebert, who joined the march.
``They are here almost two years now. And then we say, well,
bye-bye. There's something cruel and inhuman in that.''
   But the immigration minister said waiving the rules for the
Turks would set a precedent for handling the backlog of 48,000
refugee claimants who entered Canada in the past few years under
immigration policies that she said were lax.
   The government has introduced two bills, now in the Senate, to
toughen the laws.
   ``We recognize they (the Turks) were victims of unscrupulous
travel agents,'' the minister said.
   She added she would approve immigrant visa applications for any
of the Turks who, once back in their country, applied through
normal procedures to come to Canada and live.
   But the Turks said they could not afford the transportation
costs.
   The people at the rally marched to Parliament Hill behind a
large white banner saying, ``Today the Turks, Tomorrow the Rest.''
   One man held up a small message reading, ``I love Canada. Please
let me stay here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
