<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShipExplosion     04-13 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ship Explosion,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shipboard Explosion Kills Four In Gulf Of Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boiler room explosion Tuesday aboard a
ship in the Gulf of Mexico killed four crewmen and injured four
others, who were airlifted to a hospital, officials said.
   The explosion occurred aboard the 865-foot motor vessel Argo
Iduna about 5 p.m. CDT about 75 miles southeast of Galveston, the
Coast Guard said.
   ``The bodies are still aboard the Argo Iduna,'' said Coast Guard
Petty Officer 2nd Class Ron Mench in New Orleans. ``At last report,
they were trying to get the bodies out of the wreckage of the
boiler room.''
   Mench said the ship was of British registry and its home port
was Hong Kong. He identified the ship's U.S. agent as Deep Sea of
Galveston. The company is not listed in Galveston telephone
directories.
   Officials had not determined the cause of the explosion and
identities of the dead, he said, nor did he know the ship's cargo
and destination.
   ``As far as we know, the vessel is still seaworthy, it is
floating,'' Mench said. ``Of course, it has no power. They expect
it to be to towed by civilian tugs.''
   The four injured crewmen were airlifted in two Coast Guard
helicopters to John Sealy Hospital in Galveston, where they were
being treated Tuesday night, hospital officials said.
   They were identified as Remesh Chend, 30, in fair condition with
burns; Anthony Rodrigues, 28, in good condition with superficial
burns; J.R. Yadav, 29, in good condition with superficial burns and
Ratesh Kumar, 29, in good condition with a rib injury, said
hospital spokeswoman Leeann Teymour.
</TEXT>
