<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Levy Adv15   04-13 0802</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Levy, Adv 15,0826</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, April 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Eugene Levy Profiles the `Despicable' Bobby Bittman</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Funnyman Bobby Bittman doesn't get much of a
reaction when he tells his nightclub audience that a crew is there
filming his life story, but Bittman cannot be denied.
   ``I think that deserves a little applause,'' the shameless
Bittman says, and he gets it.
   Slimy, grasping, grating and unfunny, Bobby Bittman is easily
the least lovable television character outside of a World War II
documentary.
   ``He's getting more despicable by the day,'' said SCTV alumnus
Eugene Levy, director, writer and star of ``Autobiographies: the
Enigma of Bobby Bittman.'' The Cinemax Comedy Experiment premieres
Saturday, and repeats April 19, 22, 24 and 28.
   ``I love the character, because it was the only character I did
on SCTV that was just revolting and obnoxious,'' Levy said. ``He
was fun to do.''
   Levy's SCTV work also included Mel Slurp, the nerdy host of
``Mel's Rock Pile,'' anchorweasel Earl Camembert, and Stan Shmenge,
the skinny half of the Shmenge Brothers polka act.
   In the Cinemax show, Bittman is even more offensive and
untalented than he appeared on SCTV's ``Sammy Maudlin Show,''
braying ``HOWARYA?'' and trading fawning tributes with the host
(Joe Flaherty) and his oleaginous sidekick William B. (John Candy).
   The Sammy Maudlin Show was a product of Second City's attempt to
start a theater in a shopping mall in Pasadena, said Levy, who was
part of a group picked from the Toronto and Chicago casts to open
the venture.
   In California, they discovered a parodist's promised land on
television _ Sammy Davis Jr. and ``Sammy and Company.''
   ``Oh, it was just hypnotic,'' Levy said.
   ``Sammy would bring someone on and say, `Isn't this man
marvelous, isn't he just marvelous? Could I say something about
this man right here? I know you don't want me to talk about it,
man, but I feel it's a story that has to be told ...'''
   Then he would gush about the charitable works of the guest, who
in turn praised the host, and so on. On the SCTV version, Sammy,
William B. and Bobby were often reduced to tears by the
magnificence of each other's hearts and talents.
   And no, there was no truth to speculation that Levy brought
Bittman to the Big Apple to catch some reflected glamour from the
``Rat Pack'' tour, which brought Davis and Frank Sinatra through
town a week earlier.
   ``I would have seen that concert had it come to Toronto, you
know. I would have paid $75 and gone and seen those boys,'' Levy
said.
   Instead, he got a review from fellow Canadian Paul Shaffer,
director of David Letterman's ``Late Night'' band, who is either
doing or has become a never-ending parody of Vegas.
   Shaffer found the ``Rat Pack'' show disappointing, Levy reported
sadly.
   ``I was kind of hoping it would be a great concert for them, in
some strange, perverted way, because it's like a bygone era,'' Levy
said.
   ``It's true, a lot of the basis for some of the characters we
did on SCTV, like the Sammy Maudlin show, their center of gravity
was '60s Vegas _ you know, the Shecky Greens, the Alan Kings and
that whole thing.''
   In his Cinemax autobiography, Bobby shows a lot of Jerry Lewis,
especially in his split with partner Buddy ``Dummy'' Phelps. And
the trademark ``HOWARYA!'' is a swipe at Marty Allen's ``Hello
dere!''
   This is no affectionate tribute; Levy's Bittman is more of an ax
murder in some swingin lounge scene, man.
   ``There are a lot of people that might say, `Why don't you end
this man's life and do us all a favor?' But no, I'm not through
with him,'' Levy said.
   While waiting for that sentimental ``Bittman and Company'' tour
in 2010, Levy is spending more time writing, and he's just signed a
deal with Disney to develop some television programs.
   He hopes, too, that SCTV can come back together.
   ``It was just a huge creative high doing the show, a lot of
great memories, and it doesn't matter what we've done since the
show, I don't think there has been any one project that has been as
creatively fulfilling,'' Levy said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   TOUGH GUYS DO TALK SHOWS _ ``Liddy,'' a one-hour
``talk-confrontation'' show featuring G. Gordon Liddy as host, is
set to make its debut in syndication this fall, says the
distributor, All American Television. The show has already been
sold to stations in San Francisco, Dallas, Tampa, Miami,
Pittsburgh, San Diego and Fresno, says All American. Liddy will
match wits with well-known guests, then duke it out _ verbally _
with a studio audience.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, April 15</NOTE>
