<NOTE>$adv 14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday April 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>Tax Adventures in Babysitting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Use the same baby sitter often? Hire a
college-student neighbor to cut your lawn during the summer?
   Have a regular housekeeper, governess, au pair, handyman,
gardener, butler or chauffeur?
   Congratulations. You are most likely an employer of domestic
help, eligible to pay Social Security tax, federal and state
unemployment tax, and maybe even withholding tax on the worker's
income.
   You may not think of yourself as a member of the ``Upstairs
Downstairs'' set with the kind of resources at your disposal to
preside over a household staff.
   But the rules say that if you pay anybody as little as $50 or
more in any calendar quarter for household services, you may have
yourself an employee for whom at least Social Security taxes must
be paid.
   People who have been through this sort of thing attest that it
is an experience full of paperwork hassles and the potential for
bureacractic nightmares, dealing with a wide variety of government
agencies.
   It doesn't take a cynic to acknowledge that a great many
household helpers around the country are paid ``off the books'' in
cash. This kind of work is a big and vigorous part of what is known
as the underground economy. It is not only cheaper to operate that
way, but also a whole lot simpler.
   However, household employers who either wittingly or unwittingly
fail to follow the letter of the law do so at their peril.
   Suppose you hire a regular baby sitter with the understanding
that the two of you will ``skip the heavy paperwork'' and that
payments will be made in cash. Things don't work out to your
satisfaction, and a few months later you dimiss the baby sitter.
   If only just to spite you, the baby sitter could decide to
report you to the authorities.
   Once they determined that you hadn't complied with the rules,
they would very likely start dunning you for payment of both your
and the baby sitter's share of Social Security taxes owed.
Together, that's 15.02 percent of all wages up to $45,000 a year.
   Add to the bill interest from the date the payments were due,
plus penalties of up to 25 percent of the amount owed _ and another
25 percent for failure to file the required returns.
   ``Furthermore, you could also be subject to penalties for
negligence,'' observes the accounting firm of Spicer & Oppenheim.
   Beyond Social Security, federal unemployment taxes must be
withheld for anyone whose pay exceeds $1,000 a year, while state
rules vary.
   Earnings for domestic work performed in a private residence are
not subject to withholding for income tax purposes, unless both the
employee and you want to handle it that way.
   One school of thought holds that you might as well go ahead and
do the income-tax withholding if you are already reporting and
paying the required Social Security and unemployment taxes.
   There is at least one legal way to get the household services
you want done without taking on the burden of becoming an employer.
   If a baby sitter, for example, comes from an agency that is in
the ``sitting service'' business and that sets the hourly rates and
conditions of employment, in most cases the service, rather than
you, is considered the employer.
   Beware, though, of trying to make such a case if the service
merely operates as an employment agency providing referrals.
   This is a fine distinction in an area of the tax rules that is
full of fine distinctions.
   In the daily busyness of life, it is easy to let such matters
slide. It also can be very costly.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs April 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv14   04-13 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 14 ,0600</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday April 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>Does a Housing `IRA' Make Sense?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can defer taxes while saving money for your
retirement sometime in the future, but you cannot defer taxes while
saving for the down payment on a home for the present.
   To some housing people, this constitutes a monumental
incongruity, and they would like to see a housing equivalent of
Individual Retirement Accounts, which allow many people to
accumulate funds without immediate taxes.
   Among other things, they contend that living well during the
pre-retirement decades is equally as important as living well in
the fewer years to follow.
   They concede that low-income retirement years can be difficult
without a supply of funds. But they counter by saying that low
incomes and big expenses of young couples can make them as
distressed as any retiree.
   Among others, the National Association of Home Builders is now
pushing a housing agenda for the 1990s that would allow interest on
savings to be tax-deferred if earmarked for the purchase of a house.
   You'll be hearing a lot about that agenda because hearings are
now being held around the country to assist Congress in gathering
data on the subject, and that data is liking to serve as a
blueprint for later action.
   While it can be argued that home builders will support almost
any legislation that makes their lives more comfortable, they do
have some telling evidence in support of a ``housing IRA.''
   First, there is the high price of housing. High is a relative
term, of course, but how can you argue that a fivefold increase in
housing prices over the last 20 years or so hasn't exceeded that of
most increases in incomes?
   Price, no doubt, has a lot to do with the falling homeownership
rate, especially for younger people. Since 1980, ownership for
those aged 25 years to 29 years dropped to 35.9 percent from 43.2
percent; for households aged 30 years to 34 years, the rate dropped
to 53.2 percent from 61.1 percent.
   The down payment is the big obstacle; once a house is owned it
may cost no more to finance and operate than a rented apartment. By
deferring taxes, it is argued, young couples can at least get a
foot in the door.
   Anyone who came through the Great Depression of the 1930s might
be inclined to have little sympathy for this predicament, since a
house of any kind was out of the question for most of them. But why
use that period as a criterion?
   A more cogent argument is that a home is both shelter AND
retirement fund. It can be lived in during working years, and in
retirement the house can become an annuity to support the owners as
their incomes fall.
   Reverse mortgages, the financial instrument for utilizing home
equity, have existed for at least a decade, although with little
popularity. Those who have them withdraw equity on a regular basis
to finance day-to-day expenses.
   The flaw in the house-as-retirement thesis is that pre-retirees
might tap the equity to finance expenses during their high-income
years _ with interest tax deductible, incidentally _ leaving little
for retirement years.
   The housing lobby is strong, however, and is dedicated to making
housing a national commitment through legislation. It isn't likely
to retreat from the challenge, since safeguards against abuse could
be built into an ``IRA'' law.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs April 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0808EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-BlackColleges Adv18   04-13 1079</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Colleges, Adv 18,1113</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>After 10 Years, States Still Falter on Campus Desegregation</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decade after agreeing to desegregate their
university systems, Georgia and five other Southern and border
states still fall short of the goals.
   The six states have been chastised by the U.S. Education
Department for lagging in improving largely black colleges and in
better integrating the races at all public colleges.
   The president of one mostly black school says money _ funds for
capital improvements _ is the key. Billy Black, president of Albany
State College, noted that the Georgia Legislature usually approves
only half the budget requested by the University System of Georgia.
   ``There's no question but that these schools up until recently
were neglected,'' Black said in an interview at the campus here in
southwestern Georgia's pecan-growing country.
   ``If you have a couple-of-hundred-year history of being
underfunded ... you'll probably need some catch-up money to be
competitive,'' he said.
   But fatter budgets are not the only route to racial balance.
Georgia is also exploring another avenue: outright merger of such
``black'' colleges as Albany State with nearby white institutions.
   H. Dean Propst, chancellor of the state University System, is
expected to make final recommendations on mergers in May.
   The Education Department report in February sharpened the focus
on progress and problems at traditionally black colleges, which
last year enrolled 217,367 students and which account for 40
percent of blacks earning degrees in the United States.
   The report cited Georgia, Missouri, Delaware, Florida, Oklahoma
and Virginia for such shortcomings as poor facilities on black
campuses and failure to meet goals for recruiting blacks for
white-dominated colleges, and whites for mostly black colleges.
   The goals were set in 1978 in agreements between the states and
the federal government, which had accused the states of violating
the 1964 Civil Rights Act.
   At the time, Washington officials said the states, though no
longer segregating colleges by law, had not eliminated vestiges of
segregation from their ``dual'' systems of higher education.
   In the February report, Education Secretary William Bennett
asked the six governors for formal assurances they will carry out
building, repair and other projects to fulfill the plans.
   Samuel Myers, head of a Washington-based group that lobbies on
behalf of 117 traditionally black colleges, says facilities are
being upgraded and more programs offered at black schools,
attracting more students of all races.
   But Myers, president of the National Association for Equal
Opportunity in Higher Education, says further improvements are
needed to ensure equal educational opportunities.
   ``The consensus is that none of these states has done all that
they should do or all that they said they would do,'' he said.
   In the case of Georgia, Bennett ordered officials to:
   _Complete a business administration building at largely black
Savannah State College.
   _Renovate a complex at Fort Valley State, another mostly black
institution.
   _Better promote transfers from predominantly white Darton
College, a two-year institution, to four-year Albany State.
   _Start an agricultural extension program administered jointly by
the University of Georgia and Fort Valley State.
   In an interview, Chancellor Propst said the building projects
are in the works and other deficiencies should be easy to correct.
   Kay Miller, the chancellor's spokeswoman, says the capital
improvements mean the state spends significantly more per student
at black colleges than at other schools _ an annual $11,315 at
Albany State, for example, compared with $5,449 at traditionally
white Valdosta State College.
   The Bennett report covered 10 states. Four _ West Virginia,
Arkansas, North Carolina and South Carolina _ were found in full
compliance with their desegregation plans.
   Three other Deep South states _ Louisiana, Mississippi and
Alabama _ never submitted desegregation plans. The Justice
Department eventually took them to court. The Mississippi case was
recently dismissed; the others remain in litigation.
   The Education Department said the 10 states covered in the
report have spent more than $240 million enhancing black colleges.
In addition, Congress appropriated $73.2 million for support this
year.
   But after Bennett made his formal assessment of progress,
critics of the Reagan administration contended he should have been
tougher on the states, concentrating more on integration of
students and less on physical improvements at black campuses.
   After years of desegregation efforts, Albany State remains
overwhelmingly black. Of 1,994 students enrolled for the winter
quarter, 366 were white, five were Hispanic, two were Asian and
three were American Indians.
   But the college, which 10 years ago had less than 4 percent
white enrollment, has met the plan's general goal of a
20-percent-white student body and is now focusing on new buildings
and expanded programs.
   It will soon have a new campus entrance, more paved parking
lots, a $6 million library, and a new nursing and allied health
center. In the longer term, a performing arts center, a new
administration building and a new physical education complex are
planned.
   ``We had unpaved streets, unpaved parking lots, and the lighting
was terrible,'' recalled Walter Burgess, the business school dean,
who joined the faculty 14 years ago. ``I've seen tremendous
changes.''
   Albany State has six ``2-plus-2'' academic programs aimed at
boosting white transfers from the two-year Darton College and
offers $200,000 in annual scholarships to encourage whites to
attend.
   One white student, physical education major Carlton Fletcher,
said he is impressed with the Albany State teachers. As for the
facilities, ``some of the buildings are really old, but the newer
buildings are as fine as I've seen.''
   Few expect a speedy integration of Georgia's state colleges.
   Ingrained attitudes from the days of official segregation
prevent it, said Albany State sophomore Roger Collier.
   ``A black person is not going to go to a white school because
they would feel uncomfortable,'' said Collier, a black marketing
major. ``I see whites walking around the campus and ... they don't
socialize. You pass them and they don't ever say hello.''
   The Rev. Clarence James, a black educator, said historically
black colleges, if integrated, lose some benefits of environment
and development they can offer black students, and eventually lose
their black character as well.
   ``The racial reality is that there are no 50-50 institutions,''
said James, assistant admissions director at Morehouse College, a
private black institution in Atlanta. ``Once a school becomes 20 or
30 percent white, the shift is going to go on ... eventually to a
90-10 (white-black) split.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
