<DOCNO> AP880413-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0811EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv15   04-13 0802</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, Adv 15,0826</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, April 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Odyssey Of Lutheran Leader Personifies Ecumenical Change</HEAD>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When he was a boy on the way to school in
Litchfield, Minn., his route went by a Roman Catholic Church. It
then seemed such an alien place that in passing it, he would cross
to the other side of the street.
   Now, as head of his Protestant denomination in a new ecumenical
climate, he confers with the pope in Rome and moves about the
Vatican as a trusted friend.
   The change, in the short span of youth to maturity of Lutheran
Bishop Herbert W. Chilstrom, depicts the swift transformation of
Christianity into a broader, shared household.
   ``I have the strong sense that I entered a home with many rooms,
and that I was privileged to go into four of them,'' he says of his
recent visits to four centers of the faith.
   As the head of the newly merged Evangelical Lutheran Church in
America, inaugurated in 1988, Chilstrom made his get-acquainted
journey to inject a personal dimension to links with other churches.
   It signified ``that we are part of a great family of
Christians,'' he says.
   On his January trip, he visited the Eastern Orthodox Patriarch
Demetrios I in Istanbul, Russian Orthodox Patriarch Pimen in
Moscow, Anglican Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie in London
and Pope John Paul II in Rome.
   As a Lutheran, whose denomination bears the name of the 16th
century reformer, Martin Luther, who sparked the Protestant break
from Rome, Chilstrom's reception at the Vatican most pointedly
dramatized the new ties.
   His aides at the Chicago headquarters of the new
5.3-million-member denomination gave this account:
   Seated with the pope beside a desk in the papal library,
Chilstrom told the story of how as a boy on the way to school he
took to the far side of the street to avoid coming close to nuns
outside a Roman Catholic Church.
   ``I consider it a gift of the Spirit that I have now come
here,'' he told his Vatican host.
   The pope, smiling at how old aversions had gone, voiced
optimisim about ecumenical efforts, citing important progress in
U.S. Catholic-Protestant dialogues, and said steps must be found to
make unity visible.
   Chilstrom said he had helped officiate at the marriage of his
Lutheran niece to a Catholic and hoped that someday the couple
would be able to take Holy Communion together.
   Lack of agreement on sharing in that Lord's Supper, the central
act of Christian worship, remains one of the most poignant barriers
between Rome and Protestantism.
   The pope said of inter-communion he was ``keeping that hope
before us,'' seemingly implying that the churches may not have to
resolve all their theological problems before positive steps could
be taken.
   The Lutheran bishop was greeted with a hug by Cardinal Johannes
Willebrands, head of the Vatican secretariat for promoting
Christian unity, recalling their meetings in the U.S.
   Chilstrom also met other Vatican cardinals, including Joseph
Ratzinger, head of the Vatican's section on doctrine.
   He pointed to new potentialities in a study by German Catholics
and Lutherans about lifting the mutual 16th century condemnation's
of each other's churches, a step necessary for communion between
them.
   Eastern Orthodox Patricarch Demetrios I of the ancient see of
Constantinople (modern Istanbul) told Chilstrom ``we meet in the
same faith and have the same goal of celebrating the holy sacrament
together.''
   In a two-hour conversation with Orthodox leaders, Chilstrom said
Lutherans ``are an activist church _ very practical minded,'' but
had a ``growing desire ... for spiritual deepening.
   ``You have the gift that we need to know more about.''
   In Moscow, greeted by the ailing Russian Patriarch Pimen and
meeting with other Russian Orthodox leaders, Chilstrom said that
``when we reach out we learn not only about your faith but we
enrich ours as well.''
   In London at Lambeth Palace, Archbishop Runcie, head of the
world-wide Anglican Communion, voiced joy at the interim sharing of
Holy Communion between U.S. Episcopalians and Lutherans.
   In Rome, countering Chilstrom's story about his boyhood
avoidance of a Catholic church, Willebrands told of his own boyhood
in Holland when neighborhood Protestant and Catholic boys each year
set a day for a fight.
   They would line up across from each other and, on signal, began
slugging away. But Willebrands said he and a next-door Protestant
lad were friends, and they always made sure they were not opposite
each other.
   In more ways than one, Chilstrom says, the trip convinced him
that the old battlers are a lot alike. He says, ``The family of
God's people, with its rich diversity, shares much in common that
needs to be affirmed.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, April 15</NOTE>
