<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 15,0638</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, April 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study by a University of Akron sociologist
finds that religion contributes to a happy life, a comfortable
marriage and a positive outlook on personal health.
   Based on a survey of 560 Akron residents, sociologist Margaret
Poloma said simply feeling close to God is more important to
overall happiness than church attendance, denominational
affiliation or specific religious creed.
   She says the indications are that the frequency of prayer does
not directly relate to a sense of well-being, but the type of
prayer does.
   ``Those who use a conversational type of prayer are more likely
to feel good about their lives than those who limit themselves to
reciting memorized prayers,'' she says.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the United Church of Christ
says U.S. humanitarian aid should go to the Contra rebels in
Nicaragua only if ``aid of equal value is provided to the
Nicaraguan people.''
   The Rev. Avery D. Post said such aid as food, clothing and
medicine should be ``handled and delivered by international
organizations mutually acceptable to the Contras and the Nicaraguan
government.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in 75 years, German Lutherans
in the Soviet Union are to receive new hymnals for use in more than
450 congregations of German Lutherans.
   Lutheran Superintendent Harald Kalnins of Riga, Latvia, says the
Moscow Patriarchate of the Russian Orthodox Church is publishing
the new hymnals, with the first 10,000 copies to be ready this
summer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Anti-Defmation League of B'nai B'rith urges
Congress to adopt a proposed bill that would impose federal
criminal penalties for damaging religious property or obstructing
exercise of religious belief.
   In a letter to the Senate Judiciary Commmittee, the league said
that at ``a time when bias crimes are on the upswing,'' the
legislation ``would create an important new weapon in the fight
against anti-Semitism and other forms of religious bigotry.''
</TEXT>
