   However, the denomination's funding of that agency was reduced
from $448,000 to $400,000 for the current year, a 10.7 percent cut.
   The Southern Baptist Public Affairs committee had recommended
the denomination pull out of the inter-Baptist agency, criticizing
it for not supporting public school prayer and anti-abortion
amendments.
