<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Locusts-Africa Adv18   04-13 1136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Locusts-Africa, Adv 18,1174</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>North Africa Makes War on Locust Invasion</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARGOU, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A speckled, swirling mass crossed the
horizon at midday and circled like a huge, amorphous buzzard, then
vanished over the northern hills.
   ``We've got a swarm!'' a locust tracker shouted at a driver, and
ordered him to speed into town with the alarm.
   After 30 years of grace the locusts are back, cutting a swath
from the desert to the rich agricultural lands of North Africa and,
possibly, beyond.
   They have settled on the doorstep of Tunis, the seaside capital.
On its outskirts, an infested cemetery shivers with a strange new
life.
   Thousands of dead locusts have washed up on beaches outside
Rome, carried across the Mediterranean by the same winds that
pushed the Bargou on its northward course. Winds determine the
course of a locust swarm.
   Moving in waves from Mauritania, desert locusts have infested
Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia and Libya. They now are overrunning the
Atlantic islands of Cape Verde, off Mauritania.
   ``The magnitude of this plague is probably greater than the one
which struck the region in the 1950s,'' Edouard Saouma, head of the
U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization, said at his office in Rome.
The 1950s plague ravaged farmlands for years.
   His agency predicted a general invasion of the Sahel countries
on the southern edge of the desert in June if the North African
swarms are not reduced before the winds shift. Authorities said a
swarm covering 160 square miles was sighted in Tunisia early in
March.
   The one over Bargou, 100 miles southwest of Tunis in north
central Siliana province, had settled by nightfall in the hills and
groves of Borj el Amri, 15 miles from the capital.
   ``It was as big as a cloud. When I saw it I got scared,'' said
Youssef Mojhanmi, owner of an infested almond grove. ``People were
making noise, burning tires to stop the locusts from settling. But
they kept coming down.''
   Mojhanmi was happy, however, because his grove was saved. Local
officials had enough warning and began ground spraying soon after
the landing.
   By dawn, locusts were dropping in mounds under Mojhanmi's almond
trees or clinging stiff-legged to the branches. Tree trunks lining
the property seemed to writhe, covered with finger-sized insects
trying to escape.
   High winds limited aerial spraying at daybreak but falling
temperatures had immoblized the insects, which need a body heat of
77 degrees to take flight.
   Affected countries are mobilizing all available resources and
calling for aid. Locusts eat the equivalent of their own weight
every day and could devastate the food supply of North Africa's
agriculture-based economies.
   The FAO has said $150 million is needed to fight the plague.
   No official damage estimates have been available since the
locusts first were sighted in Morocco in October, and there is no
indication of widespread crop loss so far. Tactics have been either
to contain the swarms in non-agricultural areas or strike them when
they settle.
   ``We're trying to do the maximum killing at the Algerian
frontier,'' said Malek Ben Salah, director of Tunisia's
agricultural production ministry.
   Efforts to kill the flying hordes have led to violations of bans
on toxic pesticides. Tunisian authorities acknowledge minor cases
of poisoning, attributing them to improper use of masks during
spraying or eating chemically treated locusts.
   Some experts have reopened discussion on the toxin dieldrin,
suggesting its long-lasting poison could break the plague cycle,
but Lukas Brader, director of the FAO locust operations emergency
center, said it would not be used.
   Brader said aid donors and affected governments made the
decision at a meeting April 6-7 sponsored by the U.N. agency.
   Since the locusts arrived March 8, Tunisia has mounted a
veritable war with a national command post, regional situation
rooms, watch committee and a council that is led by the prime
minister and includes the defense minister.
   The U.S. Agency for International Development sent a team of
experts last week to provide technical and logistical support.
   A tour with the U.S. team revealed a patchwork of infestation.
   Carpets of dead and dying locusts _ pink, brown and yellow _
covered fields, groves and pine forests. The area stretched from
western oases around Gafsa near the Algerian border, where the
locusts entered Tunisia, to Cap Bon in the northeast, the nation's
breadbasket.
   ``The situation is changing very rapidly,'' said Jeremy Roffey,
the FAO locust expert. ``The swarms have moved north and many have
blown into the Mediterranean.''
   Since flight paths are determined by the wind, swarms now are
entering Tunisia through a northern corridor, moving straight to
rich farmland.
   By April 3, Tunisia had treated only 127,300 hectares compared
to more than 1 million treated in Morocco. One hectare equals 2.47
acres.
   Mehrez Chebil, entomologist with the agricultural production
ministry, said: ``The problem is much more serious with us because
our agricultural zones are directly threatened'' and Tunisia is
``fighting two plagues at the same time.''
   Because of a drought afflicting the country, only 18 percent of
the land planted in cereal grains is expected to produce a normal
harvest this year, officials say.
   When a swarm lands, teams attack it at night with ground
spraying and continue with aerial treatment in the morning when
feasible. National telvision tells people what to do when the
locusts come, and cars mounted with loudspeakers warn them when
treatment starts.
   ``This is the very beginning of a plague,'' Christopher Hemming,
a British locust expert on the U.S. team, said after seeing mounds
of dead locusts in an olive grove outside Kairouan, about 100 miles
south of Tunis.
   Local officials estimated the number of dead locusts under the
800 trees at 460 million.
   More than 250 species of locusts exist. Among the most
formidable is the Schistocerca gregaria, or desert locust.
   It is about three inches long, with a wingspan of twice that,
nearly weightless and like a piranha on the land.
   Beginning as earth-bound ``hoppers'' in larva form, they
accumulate and nestle, then move into their swarming _ and ravenous
_ phase, poised for takeoff with the right combination of hot wind
and humidity.
   A swarm, churning inward, downward and upward, can remain a
cohesive entity for weeks.
   ``Seeing a swarm from the inside, you get the impression of
towers of locusts,'' said Hemming. ``Someone once described it as a
column of advancing, tilting cigars.''
   Expert estimates of swarm density range from 125 million to 250
million locusts per square mile.
   Most accounts trace the origin of this plague to the summer of
1987 in regions of northern Ethiopia, southern Sudan and northern
Chad that could not be treated because they were theaters of war.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 18</NOTE>
