<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Locusts-Tracking Adv18   04-13 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Locusts-Tracking, Adv 18,0349</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>It Looks Like a Hummingbird, but Ravages the Land</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Locusts-Africa, b0318</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KAIROUAN, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A single fluttering desert locust has
the innocence of a hummingbird, but millions in a swarm are as
devastating to farmland as a prairie fire.
   A reporter accompanied experts from the U.S. Agency for
International Development on a two-day tour of infested areas in
Tunisia, which like the rest of North Africa faces the worst locust
plague in 30 years.
   Its netlike wings and pink, brown or bright yellow shell over
the locust's 3-inch-long body are an intriguing sight up close,
although short on beauty.
   Visiting land infested by locusts is an experience like no
other: walking on the writhing carpet of dead or dying insects,
seeing them cling to leaves and branches with spiny black legs in
what, to a farmer, is an embrace of death.
   Tree trunks, alive with them, appear to move. Locusts knock
against an intruder in the desperate attempt to escape.
   Crawl over an obstruction and a hand comes down in a patch of
insects. Settle to take a photograph and the ground crunches.
   Look down and they are crawling up your leg. Others settle on a
companion's shoulder, another's hat.
   With the U.S. team, led by Robert Thibeault of the U.S. Office
of Foreign Disaster Assistance, we pursued a swarm from central
Siliana province to its landing ground southwest of Tunis, in Borj
el Amri.
   After relaying a sighting over Bargou to a passing motorist, we
moved on to Kairouan, whose local watch ommittee said the swarm had
landed outside Tunis.
   Up at 4:30 the next morning, we hurried north again, arriving
for the finishing touches of an attack with insecticides on an
infested almond grove.
   Millions of locusts were dead, a rustling crunch underfoot, but
those that escaped the chemical fog scurried over a cemetery across
the road.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
