<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-HomeEquity Adv20   04-13 1119</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Equity, Adv 20,1153</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, April 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Chicago's Proposed Housing Value Insurance Draws Fire As Racist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joyce Zick saw it happen in her old neighborhood.
As Hispanics and blacks moved in, middle-class whites fled,
frightened by real estate agents fanning fears of declining
property values.
   ``When the panic peddlers came through, my parents made a
conscious decision to stay and live with the families who moved
in,'' Mrs. Zick recalled. ``They stayed and the property values
declined. Then the neighborhood changed again and the property
values declined again.''
   Today, Mrs. Zick is working with a homeowners coalition lobbying
the City Council to pass a plan designed to prevent drops in
property values and halt middle-class flight from racially changing
neighborhoods.
   But the plan, known as ``home equity,'' has drawn fire from
black leaders who contend it's intended to maintain segregated
black and white neighborhoods.
   ``It's saying that as a direct result of blacks moving in, the
economic stability and vitality of a neighborhood is undermined,''
said Alderwoman Marlene Carter, who is black.
   ``I'm insulted by it,'' she said. ``I think it's motivated by
racism under the guise of economics.''
   Supporters of the plan contend home-equity would benefit
minority middle-class homeowners as much as whites.
   Under the proposal, participating homeowners would pay a special
property tax _ $10 to $25 a year _ and the money would be used to
create an insurance fund. The fund would guarantee the resale price
of a person's home at its appraised value.
   If the home sold for less than its appraised value, the plan
would allow the homeowner to collect the difference from the home
equity fund. To be protected by the fund, a homeowner would have to
maintain the house in good condition and not sell for at least five
years.
   Supporters of the plan say home equity would take away the fear
some white homeowners have that their property's value will decline
if the racial makeup changes in their neighborhood.
   Once that fear is removed, home-equity supporters argue, whites
will be more likely to stay in a neighborhood when blacks or other
minorities move in, thus promoting natural integration and keeping
the white middle-class in the city.
   ``It doesn't matter what race you are _ this will protect the
value of everyone's home,'' said Alderman William Banks, who is
white and who co-sponsored the proposal. ``Everybody's money is the
same color _ green.''
   The City Council is weighing a proposal to establish home-equity
pilot programs in two predominantly white neighborhoods. If the
City Council doesn't act by May 1, Illinois House Speaker Michael
Madigan says he will push for a statewide program.
   ``The program is a psychological tool _ it makes people feel
confident they won't lose their property value,'' said Philip
Nyden, who studied the issue with fellow Loyola University
sociologist Kathleen McCourt.
   ``We saw this program as a way to intervene in this process and
build stable, middle-income neighborhoods that are integrated,''
Ms. McCourt said.
   Nyden added that ``the biggest winners of the home-equity
program would be the black middle-income homeowners who have a
tough time finding homes and have the most to lose if their
neighborhoods deteriorate.''
   Oak Park, an integrated suburb on the western edge of Chicago,
was the first community in the nation to enact a home-equity
program, Ms. McCourt said.
   Although Oak Park has never had to pay a claim from its
home-equity fund, she said, it instituted the plan in the late
1970s to prevent white flight when adjacent Chicago neighborhoods
became predominantly black.
   The 1960s and 1970s saw real estate agents engaging in a kind of
``block-by-block resegregation,'' she said.
   ``Their policy was to show blacks homes on a block-by-block
basis after several blacks had already moved in,'' she added.
``There was a lot of panic peddling at that time _ white people
being told they better sell their home quickly or they wouldn't get
a good price for it.''
   Mrs. Zick, for instance, says her parents were pressured to sell
when Hispanics began moving into the West Side neighborhood where
she was raised.
   She says her mother, now 78, resisted the tide of middle-class
white flight and stayed until last summer, but finally sold the
family home and moved to the suburbs because crime grew so bad.
   ``She lived under siege,'' Mrs. Zick said. ``There were gunshots
in the night, and she'd look out and see a dead body on the
street.''
   From 1960 to 1980, Chicago lost 263,278 middle- and upper-income
families, according to a report by the Save Our Cities-Save Our
Neighborhoods coalition, a homeowners' group pushing the issue.
   Last April, voters in predominantly white northwest and
southwest Chicago overwhelmingly approved advisory referendums
calling for testing home equity in their neighborhoods.
   Jane Sobczyk, a homeowner on the city's northwest side, says the
program is widely supported in her middle-class neighborhood of
ethnic Polish, Filipinos, Italians, Mexicans and Puerto Ricans.
   ``This is really talking about middle-class communities wanting
to keep their middle-class socio-economic base,'' she said. ``It's
a socio-economic issue _ it's not a color issue.''
   But Ms. Carter contends that by requiring homeowners not to sell
their houses for five years in order to qualify for home equity,
the program is ``designed to hold the line on integration.''
   ``It's in some people's interests to polarize the community and
pit different neighborhood groups against each other,'' said Erik
Wogstad, the Save Our Cities coalition's project director for home
equity.
   Ms. Carter and other black aldermen are painting the issue in
white vs. black terms to win political support from their
constituents, he asserted.
   The Chicago Board of Realtors, which has 3,000 members, also
opposes the program.
   It contends federal equal housing laws have eliminated the need
to protect homeowners from so-called ``panic peddling'' real estate
agents and views the program as ``a slap in the face'' to
minorities, said Tom Hughes, the board's executive vice president.
   Helen Coston, a middle-class black homeowner, doesn't object to
the program for racial reasons, but says she doesn't think it would
stabilize a racially changing neighborhood.
   When she and her husband moved to the Chatham neighborhood on
the South Side 30 years ago, there were only a few blacks in the
area. Gradually, all the whites left _ but not because of declining
property values, which she says have doubled and tripled.
   ``I would think probably back then the whites just didn't want
to live around blacks,'' she said. ``I think if a person wants to
move, I think they would move whether or not the plan was in
place.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, April 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
