<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv24-2nd Ld-Writethru,b0771,0957</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv24</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3 and 4, beginning ``I did...,'' with three grafs
to include dates Keach was in prison, background on Margaux
Hemingway's problems with alcohol and CORRECT Margot to Margaux.
Picks up 5th graf previous beginning ``Keach stars...'' SUBS 17th
graf previous beginning ``Playing Hemingway's...'' to CORRECT
Josephine to Geraldine.</NOTE>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stacy Keach, who portrays Ernest Hemingway in
a new TV miniseries, is working offstage with the famous writer's
granddaughter to combat the abuse of drugs and alcohol.
   Just as Hemingway was known for his boozing, Keach knows a thing
or two about drugs.
   While he was still doing the ``Mike Hammer'' series he was
arrested in April 1984 in England for smuggling 1.3 ounces of
cocaine. He spent six months in prison in late 1985 and early 1986
_ ``the lowest point of my life'' _ and says he has been free of
drugs ever since.
   ``I did an anti-drug film and I'm still very active in the
fight,'' he says. ``I just went to Corpus Christi, Texas, with
Margaux Hemingway to help raise money for a drug and alcohol
program.''
   Miss Hemingway, a 32-year-old model, was treated for alcoholism
at the Betty Ford Center in Rancho Mirage, Calif., in December.
   Keach stars in ``Hemingway,'' a six-hour syndicated miniseries
that will begin playing on stations across the country this weekend.
   He recalls that a few years ago he and a friend were touring
Hemingway's house in Key West and looking at pictures of the Nobel
Prize-winning writer as a young man. ``My friend asked me,
`Something ring a bell?' I said no and he said, `Go look in a
mirror.' So when we got back to that house to film it was like deja
vu.''
   Keach says that three years ago when he was doing `Mike Hammer'
he almost got a Hemingway project off the ground with CBS.
   ``Then I found out Danny Wilson was doing this show and that he
had me in mind for Hemingway. It's the old cliche of being in the
right place at the right time. In a strange way I believe I was
destined to play this part.''
   Hemingway's 16 novels and 49 short stories are still in print
with worldwide sales of more than 1 million copies annually.
Although some of his novels show signs of age, his distinctively
crisp, terse, action-packed style make his short stories and
journalistic pieces seem as relevant and as contemporary as ever.
   ``He was a man who looked for one true sentence,'' Keach says.
``He never used adjectives. He tried to write the way Cezanne
painted. But he was a man who turned on his friends. I think it was
the booze. He helped T.S. Eliot get started. He helped F. Scott
Fitzgerald get back on his feet. But he turned on them.
   ``He was passionate about his work and his family. He was
sensitive, although I hate to use that word because it can be
misconstrued. And when he got loaded he was a difficult person. He
was a terror. I think he felt he had earned the right to live the
way he did. He got up early, wrote, then had breakfast and drank a
bottle of wine.''
   Keach gained 35 pounds for the role, which he is still taking
off. He also grew a beard.
   The story follows Hemingway from 1925, when he became a voice
for the ``Lost Generation,'' through his turbulent romances and
marriages to four women, to the roles he created as hunter, lover,
fighter, adventurer, dreamer, sportsman and soldier-correspondent.
   ``We started filming 10,000 feet up in the Alps, overlooking
Switzerland and Italy at St. Moritz,'' Keach says. ``I had to ski
on the old-fashioned skis with no edges. They're really tough. The
director yelled cut and I just kept going down the mountain.''
   The filming took Keach and the crew to nearly all the places
associated with Hemingway: Venice; Paris; Pamplona, Spain; Africa;
Key West, Fla., and Michigan. They were unable to get into Cuba,
however, and filmed the Havana scenes in Puerto Rico.
   ``At Pamplona, they were supposed to film me before the bulls
ran through the streets,'' he says. ``Then a double was supposed to
run with the bulls. We had a German director, a Spanish crew and
actors of every known nationality. Once the bulls started nobody
had control of anything. I had to run with the bulls and I've never
run faster in my life.''
   Playing Hemingway's four wives are Geraldine Chaplin as Hadley
Richardson, Marisa Berenson as Pauline Pfeiffer, Lisa Banes as
Martha Gelhorn and Pamela Reed as Mary Welsh.
   Keach says he based his portrayal partly on the late director
John Huston, since he was ``the only Hemingwayish character I'd
ever known personally.''
   Besides ``Hemingway,'' Keach recently did a radio dramatization
of ``The Crucible'' for BBC and next will take ``Sleuth'' on a
national stage tour with Maxwell Caulfield as his co-star.
   Although Keach no longer does ``Mike Hammer'' as a series, plans
are under way to make three two-hour movies in the manner of
``Perry Mason.''
   Keach and his brother, Jim, also hope to do a sequel to ``The
Long Riders,'' a film written by Jim Keach that brought together
many of Hollywood's acting brothers, including the Carradines, the
Quaids and the Guests. Keach played Frank James and his brother
portrayed Jesse James.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
