<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Israel-BenGurion Adv17-1stLd-Writethru b0776 04-13 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Israel-Ben Gurion, Adv 17-1st Ld-Writethru, b0776,0504</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sun April 17 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Israel _ Grandson's Memories of Founding Father</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf `Ben-Gurion, who' to CORRECT date of death to
1973. One of a four-story package</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His grandson describes David Ben-Gurion,
who was the force behind the founding of Israel and became its
first prime minister, as an inveterate bookworm who often seemed
oblivious to life's realities.
   Yariv Ben-Eliezer, who teaches film and television at Tel Aviv
University, said his grandfather took him to a publishing house
every birthday after he was eight.
   ``He would say, `Choose whatever book you want and as many as
you want.' I ended up with a big box loaded with books, and then he
would sit down and write on each book `From Grandpa' and the
date,'' Ben-Eliezer recalled, showing his interviewer an
inscription from 1951.
   ``I guess this was his way of teaching me to love books. He
never preached or said you ought to read, like we do to our kids,''
said the 48-year-old professor, the eldest of Ben-Gurion's seven
grandchildren and the only one who knew him well.
   Books and politics so consumed Israel's founding father, his
grandson said, that he often seemed unaware of the value of money
and naive about the material needs of his family.
   ``He never carried money with him and he didn't know the value
of money so much because he never cared,'' said Ben-Eliezer, whose
mother was Ben-Gurion's daughter Geula. ``Grandmother care of the
household.''
   Ben-Eliezer mentioned his own wedding, where his grandfather
beckoned him to a corner and whispered conspiratorily: ``So, what
kind of book would you like me to give you for a wedding present?''
   The young man, who was in the army and had very little money,
said he was ``astonished because I didn't need a book. I needed a
stove and a refrigerator.'' He got his grandmother to intervene and
the appliances were forthcoming.
   Ben-Gurion never lost his sense of proportion, Ben-Eliezer said,
making his point with childhood memories of celebrations Nov. 29,
1947, the day the United Nations approved nationhood for Israel.
   ``Everybody went into the streets dancing and singing and he was
alone in his room,'' Ben-Eliezer said. ``My uncle came to him and
said, `Why don't you join the celebrating?' and Ben-Gurion said,
`Because I know what the cost will be.'''
   Ben-Gurion, who died in 1973 at age 87, also had an image of
sternness and most visitors were afraid to waste his time by
telling jokes or exchanging pleasantries.
   ``That's one of the reasons people would say that he wasn't so
friendly, and that he didn't like to associate with people,'' his
grandson said, adding that the opposite was true: ``He would love
to be with young people who didn't have inhibitions and would treat
him like another youngster.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
