<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Alarm-Paramedics Adv17   04-13 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Alarm-Paramedics, Adv 17,0639</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Paramedics: The Front Door of Emergency Medical Care</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Ambulance Alarm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sick junkie was dying from a bad batch of
heroin. But when paramedic Bill Jones rescued him by injecting an
antidote, he got no thanks for his trouble.
   ``I was saving his life, but he was mad at me for ruining his
high,'' Jones said with a laugh.
   ``But if you can prevent one death from happening that day,
we've accomplished something. When I save a human life, I get a
high you would never believe,'' said Jones, 40, who has also
delivered 27 babies in his 10 years as a Washington, D.C.,
paramedic.
   Paramedics and emergency medical technicians are the front door
of medical care. They are the eyes, ears and arms of doctors. Their
ambulances are emergency rooms on wheels.
   They never know if the next alarm will be a heart attack, car
wreck, shooting, stabbing or cobra bite. Sometimes, it's less
urgent: hemorrhoids, cut fingers, stubbed toes, bleeding moles,
splinters or people who use them as taxis to the hospital.
   ``This is the front line. It's Dodge City. We try to beat the
devil on every call,'' said Calvin Haupt, an emergency medical
technician here.
   ``They see the worst life has to offer as a routine part of
their job,'' said John Cavenagh, director of Washington's Emergency
Ambulance Bureau.
   Not all of it is as heroic as the life portrayed on the old
television show ``Emergency.''
   ``That program glorified everything. No one ever died. I'd never
lose a life either if I could edit the film,'' said Bo Pounds, who
runs the Metro Ambulance Service in Marietta, Ga.
   ``It's a high-risk, high-stress occupation. There's high
burnout, lots of divorce, lots of alcholism, lots of suicide. But
it's exciting work _ the red lights and sirens syndrome,'' said
John Chew, an emergency medical services specialist with the U.S.
Department of Transportation.
   ``EMS is more dangerous than police work, more hazardous than
firemen's work and more stressful than both put together,'' said
Frank Fishburne, president of Local 3721 of the American Federation
of Government Employees in Washington.
   On March 19, two New York paramedics trying to aid a Manhattan
man who'd slashed his left wrist were attacked by three men who
``felt the EMS treatment was not to their satisfaction,'' said
police spokesman John Clifford.
   One paramedic suffered a sprained wrist. The other was cut and
bruised. The three men were charged with second-degree assault.
   Paramedics require about 1,000 hours of training to be
certified. Their pay ranges from $21,000 to $40,000. They
frequently work 24-hour days, and, not surprisingly, they seek the
same esteem given police and firefighters.
   In New York City, paramedics were angered when Mayor Edward Koch
called them ambulance drivers who didn't deserve the same pay as
police and firefighters.
   ``They want to be recognized as legitimate professionals. They
want to be recognized for the risks they take and the lives they
save,'' said Dr. Alexander Kuehl, vice president of the Health and
Hospitals Corporation, the New York agency that runs the ambulance
program.
   ``EMS is a young person's occupation. People are very
enthusiastic at 20. At 40, it's hard to lift a person down 17
flights of stairs,'' Kuehl said. ``They're exposed to physically
taxing work and danger.''
   So why do it?
   ``We do it because we like it,'' said Fred Hurtado, 41, a
paramedic for 15 years in Los Angeles and a former Navy medic.
``You get a special feeling when you know you made a difference and
kept someone from getting their ticket punched.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
