<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1522EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Alarm-CapitalCrisis Adv17   04-13 0758</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Alarm-Capital Crisis, Adv 17,0784</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>D.C. Tries to Remedy Ambulance Ailments</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Ambulance Alarm</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The city's traumatized 911 ambulance service has been a
spectacular citywide disaster for longer than anyone cares to
remember.''
   _ Washington Post editorial.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BOB DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blood streamed from Mozone Kelly's mouth and
nose. His frantic family called 911 for an ambulance. They called
again. And again.
   After 38 tortuous minutes, they gave up waiting for an ambulance
that twice drove to wrong locations in a series of blunders Jan.
17. Two brothers wrapped the unconscious Kelly in blankets and
drove him to a hospital. He died an hour after the first call.
   ``It seemed like minutes were hours. I wouldn't feel so bad if
the ambulance had showed up,'' said Anne Glover, Kelly's mother.
   ``I could accept it if my brother was dead on arrival,'' added
Macleta Oliver, ``but I can't accept them saying they were just
lost. I'm outraged at this incompetence.''
   ``Mr. Kelly got caught up in a system that's got too many faults
in it,'' said William Jones, 40, a paramedic and officer of Local
3721 of the American Federation of Government Employees.
   Washington's Emergency Ambulance Bureau is among the nation's
busiest. Last year, it made 142,000 runs in a city of 626,000.
   Critics say it is also among the nation's worst. Some ambulances
take 30 minutes or more to arrive because of disorganization and
lost crews.
   A frustrated Jones called it ``crisis management at its worst.''
Dr. Howard Champion, head of Washington Hospital Center's trauma
unit, said its faults were ``an institutionalized litany of
incompetence.'' Dr. Joy Drass, a colleague, called it ``a national
disgrace.''
   Some items:
   Dispatching _ Callers to 911 at peak times sometimes get a taped
message advising them to wait for the operator. ``It's kind of hard
when a recording is telling you to hold the line when your husband
is holding his chest and turning blue,'' Jones said.
   Last March, a dispatcher was fired for telling a man whose
stepmother was dying of heart failure, ``Hey, hey, grow up.''
Paramedics did not arrive until 27 minutes after the first of three
calls.
   Training _ In June, an entire class of 14 emergency medical
technicians failed a national certification test. Until this year,
medical technicians were given two hours of map training on city
streets. It's now 40 hours.
   Management _ Fifteen directors have headed the service since
1974, including one for two hours on a Friday afternoon. ``We are
forever changing heads and never getting to the problem,'' said
Frank Fishburne, president of the paramedics' union.
   In February, Mayor Marion Barry stripped control of the
ambulance bureau from the fire department and placed it under the
city administrator. The shakeup came after the mayor's committee
overseeing city emergency services voted 5-4 it had no confidence
in Fire Chief Theodore Coleman's management.
   The system should be junked, according to critics such as Robert
Forbuss, president of the American Ambulance Association, an
industry group for private ambulance services.
   ``You just need to start over. It's flawed beyond fixing until
they have a major overhaul,'' said Forbuss. ``I don't care if
Superman is running it. It's clear they have no idea what they're
doing.''
   John Cavenagh, former EMS director in Philadelphia, was hired in
October to run Washington's system and has a 2{-year plan to turn
it around.
   ``The elements of an excellent system are all here. It remains
only to assemble those elements into a cohesive system,'' he said.
   Cavenagh maintains that help is on the way, though not as much
as he'd like.
   The bureau's budget this year was increased from $9.4 million to
$12.8 million, but that was $2.2 million less than requested. The
city has 33 paramedics. Cavenaugh will hire 32 more, although he
wanted 65 new posts.
   He called Mozone Kelly's death ``an isolated incident _ a very
unfortunate, but isolated, incident.''
   In that episode, the family called three times from 9 to 9:10
a.m. after Kelly had a seizure.
   The dispatcher gave an inexact address, and firefighters advised
the departing ambulance crew to try a location two miles from
Kelly's home. They twice drove to wrong locations.
   What should have been an eight-minute trip took 38 minutes.
Kelly, 38, the father of two, was already on his way to the
hospital in his brothers car.
   One of the crew was later suspended for 10 days; the other for
five.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
