<DOCNO> AP880413-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1525EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Alarm-ResponseTimes Adv17   04-13 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Alarm-Response Times, Adv 17 ,0818</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Response Times, Resources Plague Urban Ambulances</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Ambulance Alarm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 70-year-old woman died of heart failure while
waiting two hours for an ambulance summoned in three frantic phone
calls from relatives and friends.
   The delay last August was blamed on a dispatching mixup and a
shortage of units in a system that handles 100 emergency calls
every hour.
   ``New York City's response time kills people. It's a killer, a
genuine, true-bred killer,'' said Robert Forbuss of Las Vegas,
Nev., who runs a private ambulance company and is president of the
American Ambulance Association, an organization of private
emergency services.
   But New York is not alone in needing to improve on a job where
minutes are critical.
   A spot survey by The Associated Press of response times showed a
range from an average 3.5 minutes in Milwaukee and 4 minutes in
Seattle to 10.4 minutes in Detroit and 13.56 minutes in New York
last year.
   Critics say the averages are misleading. Some are measured from
the time the call is made to when the ambulance arrives. Others
count it from when the unit rolls, discounting the time a
dispatcher takes to screen a call.
   An ambulance should be on the scene in 8 minutes, experts say.
   ``If a 10-minute response time is the best you can do, why
bother to show up?'' said James Page, publisher of the Journal of
Emergency Medical Services.
   Time is essential because a stopped heart can be restarted by
electric jolt within 4 to 6 minutes. When a person stops breathing,
lack of oxygen damages the brain in 4 to 6 minutes. A trauma
patient can bleed to death if help is late.
   Here are capsule looks at three troubled ambulance systems:
   _ New York's response times have improved. The city upgraded its
dispatching system and separated life-threatening calls from
non-emergency ones, saying the critical calls are answered in less
than 6 minutes 40 percent of the time. The time starts when the
unit leaves, not when the call comes in.
   ``It's improved. But there are too many individual cases where
people wait an inordinately long time,'' said Saul Stern, spokesman
for City Council President Andrew Stein, a critic of the service.
   In July, an ambulance took 60 minutes to answer U.S. Attorney
Rudolph Giuliani's plea for help for a friend suffering chest pains.
   ``Unless I were reassured that this problem has been cured, I
would seriously consider getting a taxi or my car and going right
to the hospital,'' Giuliani said.
   In February, two paramedics were disciplined for waiting for
their sandwiches in a deli despite a call about a heart attack two
blocks away. The man died.
   ``That's just two stupid idiots,'' said Bo Pounds, who runs the
Metro Ambulance Service in Marietta, Ga. ``If two guys worked for
me and they were eating sandwiches, I wouldn't discipline them _
I'd fire them. You don't need breaks when people are out here
dying.''
   _ Detroit has also improved. The average dipped from 10.4
minutes to 8.6 minutes this year. Six extra ambulances were
deployed at peak times and one 24-hour ambulance was added.
   ``Response times were horrendous. They were inhumane. Compared
to what we were, we've improved 90 to 100 percent,'' said Jeff
White of Michigan Ambulance, one of six private companies that
handle overflow calls when city crews are busy.
   Detroit's $9 million-a-year ambulance service has just one
full-time advanced life support unit for 1.1 million people. A
second unit is available 12 hours a day, and the city has 19 units
offering a lower level of care.
   ``For $9 million of taxpayers' money, you get absolutely
nothing, except maybe a happy union,'' said Jack Stout, a Miami
consultant who has designed ambulance services in six cities.
   _ In Broward County, Fla., officials plan to take over a system
run by three private companies who serve 60 percent of the county
around Fort Lauderdale. The reason: slow response.
   The companies breach a 10-minute response limit 30 percent of
the time, according to Broward's emergency services division. The
$8 million takeover will replace the companies in three stages,
ousting the slowest company first.
   Broward emergencies are handled by a two-level system. County
paramedics treat patients at the scene while private ambulances
ferry them to hospitals.
   In one recent case, the daughter of an anesthesiologist from
Broward General Hospital had a heart attack at home. Her father
worked to revive her until paramedics arrived.
   The ambulance took 34 minutes to get there. By then, the woman
was dead.
   ``They got lost,'' said Pierce Adams, spokesman for the county
paramedics.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1521EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-MasterpieceCourthouse Adv17   04-13 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Masterpiece Courthouse, Adv 17,0832</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<HEAD>For Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Landmark Courthouse Turns 100</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note April 17 anniversary in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Behind the stern granite face of the Allegheny
County Courthouse and Jail, Kate Soffel whispered her
turn-of-the-century scheme of passion and escape with the
imprisoned Biddle boys.
   More than eight decades later, and four years after the movie
``Mrs. Soffel,'' her courthouse on Sunday marks 100 years since
completion, the last major work by Henry Hobson Richardson, who
helped shape American architecture.
   ``You know a Richardson building when you see it, either that or
a copy of one,'' said George White, current architect of the U.S.
Capitol.
   Richardson was said to be aiming for ``a dignified pile of
rocks.'' The result was the fortress-like, block-long courthouse
and jail, joined by a great stone walkway over Ross Street that is
still known by grim-faced prisoners and passers-by as ``The Bridge
of Sighs.''
   Other famous Richardson works include Trinity Church in Boston,
Marshall Field Wholesale Store in Chicago, City Hall in Albany,
N.Y., and Town Hall in North Easton, Mass.
   Many late 19th century buildings imitate Richardson's revival of
the medievel European Roman style that came to be known as
Richardsonian Romanesque.
   Architect Frank Lloyd Wright was said to be enchanted by the
courthouse, calling it ``worth all the other buildings in
Pittsburgh put together.''
   It might have been. Pittsburghers of the 1880s were horrified by
Richardson's extravagant plans and the $2.3 million pricetag.
   Expensive 8-foot-long granite slabs used to build the arches
were displayed on street corners by critics, according to James W.
Knox, a county planning director who has worked in the courthouse
for 42 years.
   ``They said the halls were too big, the courtroom ceilings were
too high,'' Knox said.
   But Pittsburgh led the nation in iron work and steelmaking, and
officials wanted a grand courthouse to serve the growing city.
   And yet, after being selected from about 100 American
architects, Richardson died a year before the building was
completed. ``Let me but have time to finish Pittsburgh and I should
be content without another day,'' he supposedly lamented in his
last days.
   In January 1901, Mrs. Soffel, the wife of the jail's warden,
engineered the escape of handsome Jack and Ed Biddle, who were
awaiting the hangman for murder.
   With them, she fled about 30 miles north before police shot the
men down. Mrs. Soffel was wounded and recovered to serve two years
in prison.
   Diane Keaton and Mel Gibson acted out the torrid tale in the
movie. Producers returned to the original setting, closed down Ross
Street, hauled in mud to cover asphalt and concrete, and sprinkled
manmade snow on stone in the summer sun.
   Today, what had been Mrs. Soffel's bedroom is jail Administrator
Ed Urban's office. Only the homey fireplace hints that the room
once served as living quarters.
   ``This place has an amazing history,'' said Urban, who has
collected old photos, records and letters detailing a century of
life and death in the jail.
   One record notes that a few years after Mrs. Soffel went astray,
William J. Byers was being hanged for murder on a wooden scaffold
in the courtyard when the noose slipped and he fell 10 feet to the
ground. Cold water brought him back to decidedly unheavenly
surroundings.
   ``Where am I? I can't be dead. I seem to be living,'' the record
quotes Byers as saying. A few minutes later, he was hanged
efficiently.
   Today, guards still carry heavy brass rings with keys that have
locked the jail's 620 cells since Richardson's time.
   Across the street, the courthouse's 325-foot tower houses a
183-bell carillon, and the smaller towers, as Richardson had
planned, store official records.
   ``He's the first really creative American architect who created
an architectural idiom that then became not only national in style,
but international,'' said William H. Pierson, an architectural
historian and author in Williamstown, Mass.
   ``His great genius as an architect was that he was able to solve
very practical problems and at the same time give those buildings a
very powerful, evocative, romantic expression,'' said Richard
Cleary, an architectural historian at Carnegie Mellon University.
   The interior of the courthouse and jail has changed much since
Richardson's day. The original 27-foot courtroom ceilings, for
example, have been dropped to 12 feet.
   More than 1,000 people work in the courthouse. The corridors
often are crowded and the cranky elevator breaks down periodically,
but county clerk Donald Glunt says no one minds much.
   ``I've never heard anybody say, `Oh, this building is so old or
the ceilings are too high,''' he said.
   ``You really feel that this is the people's courthouse, and
there is nothing like it anywhere else,'' Knox said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
