<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially ailing First RepublicBank Corp.
expects to post a $1.5 billion loss in the first quarter, and says
its chairman has resigned as part of a management shakeup arranged
by federal regulators.
   The projected loss disclosed Tuesday was attributed to a 50
percent increase in the company's loan-loss provision, to $231
million, and writedowns from foreclosed properties, all totaling
$1.5 billion.
   First RepublicBank also said Gerald W. Fronterhouse resigned as
bank chief executive and chairman as part of a management shakeup
arranged by federal regulators overseeing recapitalization of the
company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. says Vice Chairman Harold A.
Poling earned nearly $11 million during 1987 in salary, bonuses and
exercised stock options.
   The company disclosed Tuesday that Poling earned $808,697 in
salary, $2 million in bonuses and $8,060,272 in exercising stock
options.
   Ford Chairman Donald E. Petersen, who exercised no options
during 1987, earned $2.8 million in bonuses and $929,934 in salary,
according to the proxy, which was mailed to Ford's 265,000
shareholders.
   In all, the statement said the company paid $247.9 million in
bonuses to 5,166 executives. That works out to an average of nearly
$48,000 apiece.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Allegis Corp. has a contract that
pays $575,000 per year with a bonus worth more than $6 million to
replace valuable stock options he held previously at Tiger
International Inc., documents show.
   Under the Allegis stock appreciation plan, after Aug. 8.,
Stephen M. Wolf has the right to be paid the difference between the
market price of 590,000 Tiger International shares and $3.32,
according to documents filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
   Tiger International closed Tuesday at $14.75 on the New York
Stock Exchange, so the deal is currently worth $6.7 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loss-plagued Lorimar Telepictures
Corp., a major producer of television programming, has called off
merger talks with Warner Communications Corp.
   Lorimar's one-sentence announcement Tuesday offered no
explanation for cancellation of discussions that began early in
March with a buyout offer from the New York-based entertainment
conglomerate. Lorimar spokeswoman Sue Binford said the company
wouldn't elaborate.
   Warner spokesman Geoffrey Holmes declined to say why the talks
fell through or what Warner had been willing to offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northeastern states with high levels of public
spending have the most vital economies while ``low wage, low tax''
states in the South, Plains and Mountain regions have the worst, a
private research organization says.
   The Corporation for Enterprise Development released an economic
report card Tuesday that listed six states as leaders in the
economic competition between the states. They are Connecticut,
Maryland, Massachusetts, New Jersey, Vermont and Minnesota.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EVERETT, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing officials are defending their jets
against complaints from at least three airlines that said the
widebody series of 747s and 767s had serious quality-control
problems.
   Phil Condit, executive vice president for Boeing Commerical
Airplanes, said Tuesday the recent publicity about the complaints
was due partly to the company's open way of dealing with its
problems, which has made many workers aware of items that need
improving.
</TEXT>
