<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state of Iowa has widened its assault on the
powerful banking industry by challenging whether Goliath-sized
Citibank can bypass all state consumer laws when issuing credit
cards.
   Bankers and some lawyers maintained Tuesday that Iowa doesn't
have a legal leg to stand on, and that the Supreme Court already
addressed the question a decade ago in dealing with interest-rate
caps.
   But consumer groups and some analysts warn the credit-card
pricing structure could be thrown into turmoil should Iowa win its
case.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Makers of plastic foam food containers will
stop using ozone-destroying chemicals in their products after this
year, the first industry to give up the compounds completely, their
trade association says.
   Major environmental groups and the Environmental Protection
Agency hailed the decision Tuesday by members of the Foodservice &
Packing Institute as an important symbolic step in persuading
others to find substitutes for the chlorofluorocarbon, or CFC,
compounds.
</TEXT>
