representatives of the Farmers Group Inc., which is based in Los
Angeles. On Monday, Farmers Group had indicated that it is willing
to open talks with Batus under certain conditions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board says it is
taking the first step toward charging savings institutions in shaky
condition more for deposit insurance than it charges to healthy
institutions.
   Thrift associations are charged a regular annual assessment of
8.3 cents for every $100 in deposits, the same rate commercial
banks pay.
   As part of a program to rebuild the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp., which backs deposits up to $100,000, S&Ls have
been paying an additional special assessment of 12.5 cents per $100
since 1985.
   But the bank board proposal made Tuesday would waive part of the
special assessment for the healthy thrifts.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market hit a post-crash high Tuesday in its sixth
straight advance, as the Dow Jones industrial average rose 14.09 to
2,110.08.
   Bond prices edged higher and short-term interest rates fell.
   The dollar rose in foreign exchange trading, while gold prices
were mixed.
   Oil prices surged for the second straight day, closing above the
$18-a-barrel barrier for the first time in four months. In other
futures markets, frozen pork bellies plunged the limit allowed for
daily trading while livestock futures and copper futures fell
sharply.
