<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     04-13 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dow Industrials Top 2,100 For First Time Since Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led with government's March retail sales report
scheduled for mid-morning EDT release.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A stronger dollar, weakening interest rates and a wave of
computerized program trading has pushed the stock market to its
highest levels since the October market crash.
   A late rally sparked by program trading sent the Dow Jones
industrial average up 14.09 to 2,110.08, its first close over 2,100
since the Oct. 19 crash. The rise brought the widely-followed
index's gain over the past six sessions to about 130 points.
   Stocks rallied even though oil prices broke the $18-a-barrel
barrier for the first time in four months, a possible harbinger of
higher inflation. Oil was pushed higher by rumors of a Panama
pipeline shutoff and OPEC's moves to reduce supplies.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for May delivery
of West Texas Intermediate crude, which jumped $1.01 a barrel
Monday, rose another 20 cents to close at $18.09.
   Analysts noted the Dow average had flirted with the
psychological 2,100 barrier in several recent sessions, but on
Tuesday investors did not back away once the key market barometer
held above that level in mid-afternoon.
   Stock prices were mixed earlier in the session, and the market
appeared to lack direction.
   Analysts noted that volume remained extremely light, initially
indicating a lack of investor enthusiasm but then serving to
accentuate the move upward once buyers did step in.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
