<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NewspageStocks     04-13 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newspage Stocks,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Rally to Highest Point Since Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computerized program trading, a strategy blamed
by some analysts for worsening the 1987 stock market collapse, has
helped push the market to its highest level since the October crash.
   A late buying surge boosted the Dow Jones industrial average up
14.09 points to 2,110.08 on Tuesday, its first close above 2,100
since the market crashed on Oct. 19. The gain was the sixth
consecutive rise for a total increase of nearly 130 points in the
widely-followed market index.
   After lackluster early trading, a late-session flurry of program
trading triggered a surge of stock buying that rallied the market.
Such computerized trading programs seek to profit from price
disparities between stock index futures and the stocks represented
by the indexes.
   Trading volume remained light, which accentuated the move upward
once buyers did step in.
   Stocks also were helped by the dollar's strength in foreign
exchange and by declining interest rates in the bond market,
analysts said.
   Analysts said many investors are limiting their activity while
awaiting fresh economic data, such as the government's report on
the U.S. trade deficit for February, which is due out Thursday.
</TEXT>
