<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CreditCards     04-13 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Credit Cards,0690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iowa's Credit Card Suit Puts David Up Against Goliath</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If successful, Iowa's underdog challenge to
Citibank's practice of bypassing that state's consumer credit laws
could wreak havoc on the credit card industry's pricing structure,
say some consumer groups and analysts.
   ``Iowa is challenging banks where they've thus far been
unchallenged,'' said Elgie Holstein, director of the Washington,
D.C.-based consumer group Bankcard Holders of America. ``It's
revisiting the whole issue.''
   But bankers and some lawyers maintained Tuesday that Iowa
doesn't have a legal leg to stand on, and that the Supreme Court
already addressed the question a decade ago in dealing with
interest-rate caps.
   The state filed a federal lawsuit against Citibank on Monday in
an attempt to force it to obey Iowa consumer credit laws when
issuing credit cards to Iowa consumers.
   Citibank maintains that the more lenient laws of South Dakota,
where its credit card operation is based, apply to its cards
wherever they are issued.
   In December 1978, in the case of Marquette National Bank vs.
First Omaha Services Corp., the Supreme Court ruled that nationally
chartered banks could export their home-state interest rates to
credit card customers in other states. The court also barred states
from regulating fees materially related to interest rates charges.
   Congress passed a law granting similar immunity to
state-chartered banks in the early 1980s.
   But whether banks also can set all card fees, such as late
charges, in excess of levels permitted by state laws is at issue in
Iowa's suit.
   ``This is where we get into interpretation,'' said Anita
Boomstein, a banking expert and partner in the Boston law firm
Gaston & Snow.
   She said the banking industry probably would prevail in Iowa's
federal lawsuits, filed Monday against Citibank and three months
ago against First National Bank of Wilmington in Delaware.
   ``There has been no definite case law defining what's `material'
of the rates,'' she said.
   ``I think banks are in a good position, that all of the
financial outlook (including the fees) is in determination of
interest rates.''
   The American Bankers Association expresses the same position,
contending the individual states interfere with banking competition
by regulating credit card rates and fees.
   William McGuire, a spokeman for Citibank, the nation's biggest
credit card issuer and the flagship of the largest U.S. bank
holding company, has refused to comment on the case except to say
that the bank was following federal laws.
   Even Holstein concedes Iowa's suits are ``based upon a narrow
interpretation of the Marquette decision,'' but he commended the
state for taking such an unprecedented stand while others have
ignored the issue.
   ``It was a lawsuit just waiting to happen,'' he said.
   Citicorp and First National Bank of Wilmington aren't the only
two banks whose credit card fees and charges have surpassed the
levels permitted by some state laws.
   Connecticut imposed a 15 percent limit on interest rates charged
by local and out-of-state credit card companies during 1987, taking
the strongest action to regulate consumer credit practices. Eleven
other states also passed laws regulating consumer-oriented aspects
of the credit card industry last year.
   But enforcing those laws has been a different story. To get
around them, banks need only base their credit card operations in
states that have less stringent regulations and usury laws, like
Delaware and South Dakota, said Holstein.
   Iowa is seeking to stop Citibank and First National Bank of
Wilmington from applying the laws of South Dakota and Delaware,
respectively, regarding to late payment fees and insufficient check
charges. Iowa says other companies may be sued as well.
   ``If they (Iowa) were to win, Citibank may just decide not to
issue cards in Iowa,'' which only has 36,000 Citibank MaserCard and
Visa cards anyway, said Stephen Berman, a banking analyst with
County Securities USA.
   But he conceded that should other, larger states take similar
action, banks and their pricing structure could face some big
problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AT&T-Olson     04-13 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AT&T-Olson,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investors Take News Of AT&T Chairman's Illness In Stride</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors reacted calmly to news that AT&T
Chairman James E. Olson has undergone surgery for colon cancer and
will be absent from day-to-day management for an indefinite period.
   Analysts said Olson's forceful style of management has set the
company moving in the right direction, although some were concerned
that an extended absence could be harmful.
   AT&T confirmed newspaper reports Tuesday that Olson, 62,
underwent surgery March 25 to remove a malignant tumor from his
colon and was recuperating at his New Jersey home while receiving
outpatient chemotherapy.
   AT&T's stock rose 25 cents a share to $28.12{ in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading.
   Fulton Holmes, an analyst at Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc.,
said he was more pessimistic than other observers about AT&T's
prospects without Olson at the helm.
   ``He has essentially single-handedly turned this company
around,'' Holmes said. ``I have major reservations about this
company if he ends up having to either lessen his input or turn it
over totally to his successor.''
   AT&T said it could not predict when Olson would return to active
duty or whether he would attend the company's annual meeting in
Denver next Wednesday.
   Robert E. Allen, 52, the president and chief operating officer,
is running the company in his absence.
   Olson has made AT&T more aggressive, more cost-conscious and
more certain of its direction since taking office in September
1986, analysts said.
   Olson landed his first job in the Bell System at age 17,
cleaning silt out of manholes in North Dakota, and is considered a
take-charge executive with an emphasis on getting results.
   ``I think Olson's personality has begun to permeate throughout
AT&T's organization,'' said Jack Grubman, an analyst for
PaineWebber Inc.
   Olson's undisclosed illness was reminiscent of that of William
McGowan, the chairman of MCI Communications Corp., who suffered a
heart attack in December 1986, received a heart transplant and
returned to office in September 1987.
   Both companies drew criticism for failing to announce their
chiefs' illnesses until news leaked out to the press.
   The New York Times and Wall Street Journal reported Olson was
ill in their Tuesday editions.
   AT&T spokesman Bill Mullane, who confirmed Olson's illness when
asked about the reports, said lawyers assured him the matter did
not need to be disclosed because it was not considered ``material''
under the law.
   Mullane said Olson has kept up some correspondence from his home
and would be available in case of a crisis.
   ``If there was a critical issue that had to be discussed with
him today, it would be discussed with him just as if he were in
Fiji on vacation,'' Mullane said.
   Securities and Exchange Commission spokesman Chiles Larson said
the illness of a chief executive is not specified as a matter that
automatically requires disclosure. He declined to comment Tuesday
on whether the SEC was investigating the appropriateness of AT&T's
actions.
   The absence of Olson is less significant to AT&T than McGowan's
absence was to MCI, the distant second-place contender in the
long-distance communications market, said Daniel Rosenbaum,
executive editor of Wiretap, a Morristown, N.J.-based newsletter.
   ``AT&T is a much more mature company. It has executives in place
who can pick up the slack,'' Rosenbaum said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
