<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NASD-InsiderTrading     04-13 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NASD-Insider Trading,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Over-The-Counter Stock Group Asks For Safeguards On Insider
Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Association of Securities Dealers
task force is urging the federal government to impose rules for
brokerage firms that would help thwart illegal insider trading.
   In a report on Tuesday, the NASD Regulatory Review Task Force
said many brokerage firms already had so-called Chinese wall
procedures designed to keep sensitive information from leaking from
a firm's mergers and acquisition staff to its trading staff.
   But the report said neither the Securities and Exchange
Commission nor self-regulatory organizations such as the NASD,
which operates the over-the-counter stock market, have established
standards for Chinese wall procedures.
   Regulators must do a better job of making sure the information
barriers are effective, said the task force, which began work a
year ago and was headed by A.A. Sommer Jr., a securities lawyer and
former SEC commissioner.
   It also recommended:
   _requiring firms to more expeditiously announce news that could
affect the price of their stocks, thus cutting down on the
opportunity for illicit trading.
   _improving NASD computer programs designed to detect unusual
stock trading.
   _abolishing limits on NASD fines for insider trading.
   _making disciplinary records of brokers more readily available
to the public.
   _passing legislation making it easier to restrict re-entry into
the securities business of brokers found guilty of serious
misconduct.
</TEXT>
