<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Allegis-Chairman     04-13 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Allegis-Chairman,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bonus Package For Allegis Chairman Worth Millions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Allegis Corp. Chairman Stephen M. Wolf has a
contract paying $575,000 a year and a bonus worth more than $6.5
million to replace stock options he formerly held at Tiger
International Inc., documents show.
   According to documents filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, the bonus is part of the Allegis stock plan offered to
Wolf when he was hired in December from Tiger, where he had served
as chairman and chief executive officer.
   Allegis, the parent company of United Airlines, plans to change
its name next month back to UAL Inc., after recently shedding its
hotel and rental car businesses.
   Under the stock plan, Wolf has the right after Aug. 8 to be paid
the difference between the market price of the 590,000 Tiger shares
he had options on and a base price of $3.32 a share.
   Tiger stock closed Tuesday at $14.75 a share on the New York
Stock Exchange, making the deal worth $6.7 million currently.
   Allegis, the SEC filing says, ``recognizes that its compensation
of (Wolf) must take into account at least a portion of the value''
of his former Tiger stock options.
   Besides the salary and bonus, Wolf is entitled to another annual
bonus, an option to purchase 250,000 shares of Allegis stock and
retirement benefits that give him credit for 22 years of service,
the SEC filing says.
   When asked Tuesday about the contract and any possible labor
friction because of its price tag, Allegis spokesman Joe Hopkins
declined to comment other than to confirm that the deal had been
made.
   Allegis is currently in contract negotiations with its flight
attendants, who already have rejected the company's request for
concessions in exchange for a 4 percent wage increase over 42
months.
   Pat Friend, chairwoman of the United branch of the Association
of Flight Attendants, was in negotiations Tuesday and didn't return
phone calls requesting comment.
   But F.C. Dubinsky, chairman of the United pilots union, said the
size of Wolf's contract wasn't a surprise.
   ``We've always found it curious that management can always
justify reducing costs everywhere but their own wallets,'' he told
the Wall Street Journal.
</TEXT>
