<HEAD>Businessman Gets Apology Over $4 Late Fee</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WYOMING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose business was seized for a day
by tax collectors after he refused to pay a $4 late fee will get a
refund and an apology from city officials.
   Refunds and similar apologies will also be issued to 13 other
Wyoming businesses penalized for failing to meet a personal
property tax deadline that fell on a holiday weekend in February.
   Roger Wilson paid his taxes but refused to pay the late fee, and
his business was shut down by authorities March 17. The next day,
Wilson paid the fee and reopened his business.
   Wilson said he was pleased to hear about the refund, but even
happier that the city council is considering a measure that would
establish new policies restricting the treasurer's authority to
seize property.
   ``It's scary when a person like that has the authority to
mobilize a police force to take her point of view to the limit,''
Wilson said.
   City Treasurer Anne Porritt declined to comment on the matter.
