<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1002EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Soviet-JointVenture 1stLd-Writethru f0029 04-13 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Joint Venture, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0029,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Occidental, Soviets to Build Plastics Factories</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th graf pvs `There are ...' to UPDATE
with announcement of joint venture consortium. Pick up 8th pvs,
`The two...'; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armand Hammer, chairman of Occidental Petroleum
Corp., today signed an agreement with the Soviet government on a
joint project to build a pair of plastics factories worth as much
as $200 million in the Ukraine.
   Hammer said the two plants, which are expected to begin
operating in 1991, would help improve the supply of consumer goods
to the Soviet public.
   ``If socialism is to succeed in Russia, you must improve the
standard of living of your people,'' Hammer told Alexander
Ustkachkinzev, first deputy minister of the Soviet Chemical
Industry, after signing the agreement.
   Hammer, who has had business dealings with the Soviet Union
since the 1920s, told a news conference he is convinced the Soviet
Union ``is committed to making joint ventures succeed.''
   U.S. Commerce Secretary C. William Verity and a group of 400
American business leaders are in Moscow this week for meetings with
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other officials on expanding
trade relations.
   The Soviets are actively seeking joint business projects with
capitalist countries in an attempt to revive their stagnant economy
with more and better quality products.
   There are few joint Soviet-U.S. business ventures. But on
Monday, Honeywell Inc. announced a joint venture to supply
automated production controls for Soviet fertilizer factories, and
on Tuesday Roma Food Enterprises of Piscataway, N.J., began selling
pizza in Moscow from a mobile van.
   In addition, seven major U.S. companies today announced they had
formed the American Trade Consortium, an umbrella under which
U.S.-Soviet joint ventures will be negotiated to produce consumer
goods ranging from cookies to cars.
   No new joint ventures have been signed yet, but negotiations are
under way on several, said consortium president James H. Giffin of
The Mercator Corporation.
   The other six companies involved are Chevron Overseas, RJR
Nabisco, Ford Motor Company, Eastman Kodak, Archer Daniels Midland
and Johnson and Johnson.
   The two plastics plants, to be built near Kalush not far from
the Czechoslovak border, will produce polyvinyl chloride, or PVC,
said Hammer.
   One will produce film for food packaging, wall coverings, pond
and reservoir linings, while the other will produce resins for
vinyl flooring, upholstery fabrics and molded vinyl items, the
company said in a statement.
   Hammer said Occidental is the largest producer of PVC in the
United States.
   The estimated cost of the plants is between $160 million and
$200 million, Hammer said. Three-quarters of the plants' capacities
will be sold in the Soviet Union and its allied countries, but
Occidental will receive 25 percent to sell on the international
market, where it can earn convertible currency.
   One of the major stumbling blocks to more joint ventures is that
the Soviet ruble is not convertible into other currencies, so it is
difficult for Western companies to earn profits that can be taken
out of the Soviet Union.
   Companies must make agreements to produce goods that can be sold
outside the Soviet Union for hard currency or agree to take other
kinds of Soviet goods that they can sell abroad.
   Hammer announced in November that Occidental Petroleum, Italian
and Japanese companies would participate in another joint venture
to build a petrochemical complex near the Caspian Sea.
   Occidental President Ray Irani told the news conference
negotiations on the two plastics factories began in late 1986 but
originally focused on another site. Once the focus shifted to the
Kalush site, negotiations were completed in six months, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1008EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Earns-IBM 1stLd-Writethru   04-13 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-IBM, 1st Ld-Writethru,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Computer Giant's First Quarter Earnings Up 16.3 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS analyst comment, stock price grafs 1-6; picks up 4th
graf pvs, ``IBM's earnings...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. today
reported strong first-quarter earnings on sharply higher revenue,
which analysts called an important signal that the world's largest
computer company is snapping back after a disappointing slump.
   IBM said earnings for the three months ended March 31 totaled
$913 million, or $1.53 a share, up from $785 million, or $1.30 a
share, a year earlier. Revenue totaled $11.75 billion, a 10 percent
increase over 1987 first-quarter revenue of $10.68 billion.
   ``I think it's very very good,'' said Peter Labe, a computer
analyst at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York. ``It's a better
revenue gain than anybody was expecting.''
   Analysts said the improvements were particularly encouraging
because they followed a string of lower-than-expected results for
the company and came during a quarter that historically is the
weakest in the computer industry.
   The gains in earnings and sales also came despite a higher tax
rate and fears of a business-spending cutback in the aftermath of
the stock market crash six months ago.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, IBM jumped $1.37{ to $115 a
share in heavy trading, a reflection of investor confidence.
   ``IBM's business continues to improve,'' Chairman John F. Akers
said in a statement from the company's world headquarters in
Armonk, N.Y. ``We are pleased that customers are responding
positively to our strengthened product line.''
   IBM's financial health is regarded as an important barometer of
the computer industry and the competitive position of U.S.
companies in world markets. The company's products are widely
considered the industry's trend-setters.
   The company is a leading producer of information handling
systems, equipment and services with products ranging from large
computer networks to personal computers, typewriters, copiers and
other office machinery.
   Earlier this year IBM announced the enhancement or introduction
of several product lines ranging from system printers to its
Personal System 2 personal computers.
   It also announced a restructuring that Akers said would make the
company respond more quickly to customers and ``compete more
vigorously in all of our lines of business.''
</TEXT>
