<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     04-13 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0312</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed today as traders
cashed in some of the gains from the rally of the past six sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up 1.49 to
2,111.57 in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 5 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 397 up, 576 down and
524 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 29.52 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   International Business Machines gave a boost to the Dow Jones
industrial average, rising 1] to 115.
   Analysts generally gave good reviews to the company's
first-quarter results, which showed earnings at $1.53 a share, up
from $1.30 in the comparable period of 1987.
   Otherwise, however, brokers said the mood was cautious and
subdued.
   Wall Street is looking for favorable news from the meeting today
of the so-called Group of Seven industrialized countries in
Washington, and from Thursday's report by the Commerce Department
on the nation's trade balance for February.
   But many traders apparently are worried that whatever positive
stimulus comes from those sources may have been already reflected
in stock prices with the market's advance of late.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.09 to 153.28. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .21 at 306.80.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 14.09 to
2,110.08, bringing its advance over the past six sessions to more
than 129 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 879 up, 621 down and 471 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 140.40 million shares, against 146.37 million shares in the
previous session.
