<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Staley-Tate     04-13 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Staley-Tate,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Staley Board Meets to Discuss Takeover Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of Staley Continental
Inc. have put off a decision on a $1.33 billion takeover offer from
the British sugar refiner Tate & Lyle PLC.
   The Staley board met Tuesday, but decided not to take any action
on Tate & Lyle's cash tender offer, spokesman G. David Satterfield
said.
   Satterfield said Staley, the second largest U.S. refiner of
corn, would announce its position on the offer before April 21. He
refused further comment, except to say that the company was urging
stockholders to postpone any decisions on their shares until after
the board makes its recommendation.
   The Tate & Lyle offer, which works out to $32 per share, will
expire at midnight May 5.
   Staley was unchanged at $36.75 in early New York Stock Exchange
trading today.
   Tate & Lyle chairman Neil Shaw met with state legislators in
Springfield Tuesday. Shaw said he and colleagues had met with local
officials so the public would see that ``we're not financial
operators, we are manufacturers.''
   At a news conference, Shaw called his company's offer ``a very
good price,'' but refused to speculate about any possible change in
negotiations with Staley.
   The acquisition of Staley would give Tate & Lyle its first
interest in the U.S. corn-sweetener market. The company said it
would become the only supplier of all three types of sugar _ corn,
beet and cane _ in the United States.
   Tate & Lyle currently owns nearly 5 percent of Staley's stock.
   Staley Continental is a holding company formed in early 1985 for
the A.E. Staley Mfg. Co. of Decatur, Ill., a leading corn
processor, and CFS Continental Inc. of Chicago, a food-service
supplier.
   Staley's main corn product is high fructose corn syrup, known as
HFCS. The company has about a fourth of the $1 billion-a-year U.S.
market for HFCS sales, Tate & Lyle said.
   Also Tuesday, the Staley board promoted Robert M. Powers to
president and chief operating officer, holding the No. 2 position
behind Donald E. Nordlund, Staley chairman and chief executive
officer.
</TEXT>
