<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Japan     04-13 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Japan,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Threatens GATT Complaint On Japanese Car Taxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community
Commission Wednesday threatened to take its opposition to Japanese
taxes on car imports to the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
if Japan does not answer EEC complaints within two weeks.
   EEC External Affairs Commissioner Willy De Clercq will raise the
issue at a meeting with Japan's Commerce Minister Hajime Tamura in
Vancouver, British Columbia, this weekend, an EEC spokeswoman said.
   U.S., Canadian, EEC and Japanese officials will meet for trade
talks in the Canadian city.
   Japan levies special taxes on cars with engines bigger than 2
liters and a width of more than 1.7 meters. As most European cars
imported by Japan exceed these measures, the EEC finds the taxes
discriminatory.
   The EEC spokeswoman said the EEC believes the tax ``unduly
penalizes EEC imports in various ways'' and might take the matter
to GATT if it does not get a satisfactory answer by the end of the
month.
   GATT is a 94-nation organization that oversees international
trade.
   On another issue, De Clercq will seek a Japanese pledge in
Vancouver that it will not discriminate against EEC firms under the
U.S.-Japan accord of last week to open Japanese public works
projects to U.S. bidders.
   De Clercq will also meet with U.S. Trade Representative Clayton
Yeutter on bilateral issues such as a dispute over an EEC ban on
hormones in meat and soybean trade as well as prospects for
adoption of the U.S. omnibus trade bill.
</TEXT>
