<HEAD>Ply-Gem Industries Drops Bid for Wolverine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ply-Gem Industries Inc. has agreed to
terminate a merger agreement with Wolverine Technologies Inc. after
a French industrial group offered more for the manufacturer of
vinyl siding and windows.
   A subsidiary of Compagnie de Saint-Gobain of France, SG
Acquisition Corp., began a tender offer Monday of $23 a share, or
about $75.9 million, for Wolverine Technologies.
   Ply-Gem, based in New York, had previously offered $18.50 a
share under an offer that expired at midnight Tuesday. It agreed to
terminate its merger agreement in return for $4.7 million.
   Thomas Jeffers, Wolverine vice president and treasurer, said the
company's board was studying the Saint-Gobain offer and would make
a recommendation to shareholders by April 21.
   The Saint-Gobain offer extends through May 6 and is conditional
on at least 2.1 million of 3.3 million outstanding Wolverine
Technologies shares being tendered.
