<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Steady To Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened steady to
lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Traders were taking profits after recent jumps, especially in
soybean and wheat, said Walter Spilka, a grain analyst at Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   ``I think generally it's a wait-and-see type of thing,'' Spilka
said. ``Trade is mostly bullish. At the same time, the markets have
rallied in recent days. What you're seeing this morning is
profit-taking. The markets have moved pretty fast to the upside.''
   The markets appeared to be drifting lower because of the lack of
bullish fundamentals, he said.
   Wheat opened higher, then tapered off. Corn was off slightly
while soybeans were also down.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to 1 cent higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $3.20\ per bushel; corn was {
cent to 1} cents lower with May at $2.05 per bushel; oats were
unchanged to { cent higher with May at $1.66} per bushel; soybeans
were 1\ cents to 3{ cents lower with May at $6.78 per bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
