<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-RetailSales 1stLd-Writethru f0035 04-13 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Retail Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0035,0367</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: CORRECTS 7th graf, Much of, to show department store sales
decreased in February, sted increased; Also moved on general
newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales, spurred by gains at department
stores and auto showrooms, rose a strong 0.8 percent in March, the
fifth consecutive increase, the government said today.
   The Commerce Department said retail sales rose a seasonally
adjusted $1.1 billion to $130.7 billion.
   Sales were strong in all categories except furniture stores and
restaurants, and were well above expectations. Most economists
before today predicted an increase of 0.2 percent to 0.3 percent.
   The March increase came atop a 0.6 percent gain in February,
revised upward from the 0.4 percent estimate released a month ago.
   The latest rise was the strongest since a 1.1 percent increase
in December. Ever since the October stock market crash, economists
have watched retail sales closely for signs that the consumer
sector of the economy would weaken.
   But more recently, some analysts have raised fears that too much
consumer demand could re-fire inflation and lead to higher interest
rates.
   Much of the strength in March came from sales at department and
other general merchandise stores. Boosted by an earlier-than-usual
Easter, their sales rose 1.6 percent following a 2.6 percent
decrease in February.
   Auto sales rose 0.9 percent, following a 2.0 percent increase a
month earlier. Excluding autos, sales were up 0.8 percent, the same
as the overall rise.
   Sales of all durable goods, items expected to last three or more
years, were up 0.5 percent, while non-durable goods were up 1.0
percent.
   The department offered these details of March sales:
   _ Hardware and garden supply stores, up 0.5 percent after
soaring 3.0 percent in February.
   _ Furniture and appliance stores, down 2.0 percent after a
strong 2.9 percent increase a month earlier.
   _ Food and grocery stores, up 1.1 percent after an earlier 0.6
percent rise.
   _ Gasoline, up 1.4 percent following a 1.2 percent decline.
   _ Specialty clothing stores, up 0.3 percent; restaurants and
bars, down 0.6 percent, and drug stores, up 1.6 percent.
</TEXT>
