<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   04-13 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares End Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices ended slightly higher Wednesday, with
most of the activity coming in the morning as Swiss chocolate maker
Jacobs Suchard S.A. launched a ``dawn raid'' that netted it 14.9
percent of British confectioner Rowntree PLC shares.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 5.1
points, or 0.3 percent, at 1,810.4 at the close.
   Rowntree's share price soared as Suchard stepped in, pulling up
stocks in the food and store sectors.
   Oil shares also continued to firm before the April 25 meeting of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   The index moved up as much as 11.3 points shortly after the
opening, but hit a low of 3.1 points up in late afternoon on the
back of early losses on Wall Street.
   Volume was moderate at 514.2 million shares, up from 364.7
million on Tuesday.
   There was little institutional buying interest, dealers said, as
many players remained on the sidelines awaiting developments from a
gathering of monetary officials of the Group of Seven major
industrialized countries in Washington on Wednesday. Caution also
prevailed before Thursday's release of U.S. February trade figures.
   The activity in Rowntree was the major news of the day, as
Suchard picked up 32.0 million shares, or 14.9 percent, at 630
pence each. The Swiss company said it plans to increase its holding
to not more than 25 percent, and doesn't intend bidding for all of
Rowntree.
   Rowntree shares leaped 146 pence to close at 623 pence, after
trading as high as 633 pence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
