<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     04-13 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Slightly, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AM version is planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose slightly in quiet European
trading Wednesday as the market awaited news from a monetary
meeting of the Group of Seven major industrial nations and
Thursday's release of U.S. trade figures.
   Gold prices fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the market was mostly quiet before
an expected statement from the G-7 meeting of finance ministers and
central bankers in Washington. Some bullish sentiments reflected
expectations of a dollar-supporting statement from the group, they
said.
   Other U.S. currency gains came late in the day as market players
took positions before Thursday's release of figures on the U.S.
trade balance in February.
   There was speculation that the U.S. trade deficit has shrunk
from January's $12.4 billion gap, perhaps as low as $10 billion.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar dipped 0.05 yen to a closing 126.45 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 126.30 yen.
   Other dollar rates late Wednesday, compared with late Tuesday:
1.6895 West German marks, up from 1.6853; 1.3983 Swiss francs, up
from 1.3967; 5.7295 French francs, up from 5.7165; 1.8950 Dutch
guilders, up from 1.8890; 1,252.50 Italian lire, up from 1,249.75;
and 1.2367 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2370.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8445, cheaper for buyers
than late Tuesday's $1.8515.
   Gold bullion was sold at a bid price of $449.25 a troy ounce
late Wednesday, down from late Tuesday's $451. At midmorning
Wednesday, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $448.50.
   Traders said trading was lackluster in Europe because most
participants have squared their positions ahead of the release of
U.S. trade figures.
   In Zurich, gold's bid price was $449.50 an ounce, down from $451
late Tuesday. Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.39 to close at a
bid $450.82.
   Silver was quoted in London Wednesday at a bid price of $6.41 a
troy ounce, down from Tuesday's $6.45.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
