<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated today as traders
cashed in some of the gains from the rally of the past six sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 129 points
in the past six trading days, fell back 9.28 to 2,100.80 by 2 p.m.
today on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 9 to 5 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 506 up, 901
down and 503 unchanged.
   The market's decline came despite buying in International
Business Machines, which rose 1| to 115\.
   Analysts generally gave high marks to the company's
first-quarter results, which showed earnings at $1.53 a share, up
from $1.30 in the comparable period of 1987.
   Otherwise, however, brokers said the mood was cautious and
subdued.
   Wall Street is looking for favorable news from the meeting today
of the so-called Group of Seven industrialized countries in
Washington, and from Thursday's report by the Commerce Department
on the nation's trade balance for February.
   But many traders apparently are worried that whatever positive
stimulus comes from those sources may have been already reflected
in stock prices with the market's advance of late.
   Pfizer gained 3 to 59~, apparently benefiting from takeover
rumors and speculation.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.56 to 152.63. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 1.21 at 305.38.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 139.87 million shares with two
hours to go.
