<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TakeoverBill     04-13 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Takeover Bill,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania Lawmakers Introduce Anti-Takeover Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two western Pennsylvania congressmen Wednesday
introduced legislation in Washington aimed at preventing investment
firms and foreign bank holding companies from pursuing certain
corporate takeovers.
   Rep. Doug Walgren, a Democrat, and Rep. Tom Ridge, a Republican,
said their proposal stemmed from the $1.7 billion takeover battle
for Koppers Co., a Pittsburgh-based cement and building materials
concern.
   British industrialist Brian C. Beazer joined with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. and National Westminster Bank PLC in launching a
bid for the company.
   The congressmen said their bill would prohibit a financial
services company that owns an federally insured bank from taking
more than a 5 percent equity interest in a company not involved in
financial services.
   Shearson owns Boston Safe Deposit and Trust Co., which ranks as
the nation's 20th largest bank. It also owns nearly 50 percent in
BNS, the company Beazer formed to make the bid for Koppers.
   The Ridge-Walgren bill also would prohibit a foreign bank
holding company that owns a federally insured bank from using its
financial resources to acquire interest in a company not engaged in
financial services.
   ``If investment banks are permitted to become full partners in
takeover efforts through an equity interest _ that is, to go beyond
the traditional role of lending money _ corporate America will be
controlled by banks at unprecedented levels,'' Walgren said.
   The bill is expected to be referred to the House Banking
Committee, Walgren's office said. Ridge serves on that committee.
   Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., has introduced similar legislation in
the Senate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1442EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TexasAir-Investigation 4thLd-Writethru   04-13 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Air-Investigation, 4th Ld-Writethru,0506</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 6, Texas Air Corp., to add Texas Air loss last
year.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Transportation Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government today announced a
special investigation of Texas Air Corp. to determine whether the
nation's largest airline company and its management are ``fit,
willing and able'' to carry commercial air traffic.
   The investigation by the Transportation Department came as the
Federal Aviation Administration announced a civil penalty of
$823,000 against Eastern Airlines, a Texas Air subsidiary, because
of ``recurring trends'' of violations of safety regulations.
   Transportation Secretary James Burnley told a news conference
the investigation of Texas Air Corp. will be completed within 30
days and is being conducted to determine whether the company is
complying with federal regulations and whether its management is
competent to operate commercial aircraft.
   Burnley said that one reason for the investigation is the FAA's
fine against Eastern, which came just over a year after Eastern
agreed to pay a $9.5 million fine in connection with other safety
violations.
   In addition, he said, the department's concerns were raised
after an examination of Texas Air's financial filings with the
Securities and Exchange Commission which showed the airline company
to be ``under substantial, increasing financial pressure.''
   Texas Air Corp. had record losses since the beginning of 1987,
Burnley said. It had a net loss of $466 million last year.
   B. Wayne Vance, the departmemt's general counsel, said 15 to 20
government economists and auditors will focus on Texas Air Corp.'s
financial records, management practices and the circumstances
surrounding Texas Air's purchase of Eastern and more recent
attempts to shift Eastern assets away from the Miami-based airline.
   In its order directing the 30-day investigation of Texas Air,
the department said recent filings by Texas Air with the SEC
suggest ``a need to examine ... (Eastern's and Continental's)
financial fitness.''
   ``The recent activities of the Texas Air and its carriers
-particularly Continental and Eastern - raise questions concerning
whether the carriers can and are disposed to comply with the safety
and economic rules applicable to air carriers,'' the order said.
   Texas Air, which is based in Houston, is the parent company for
Eastern and Continental Airlines. Together, these two carriers
account for nearly 20 percent of the commercial airline market.
   In a separate action, FAA Administrator Allan McArtor said the
FAA will begin an in-depth, 30-day inspection of Eastern that
``will literally touch every one of Eastern's 267 planes'' to
determine whether they are being operated within federal safety
requirements.
   McArtor said at the same time the agency has proposed a civil
penalty of $823,000 against Eastern for alleged violations already
discovered in the Miami-based airline.
   The new round of inspections by FAA teams was prompted by ``what
appears to be recurring trends of non-compliance'' of safety
regulations. ``I am concerned about the degree to which Eastern
management systems are providing adequate supervision and control
over Eastern's (aircraft) fleet,'' McArtor said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
