<DOCNO> AP880413-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1450EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-France-Tourism     04-13 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-France-Tourism,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>France Fetes New York Couple As 500 Millionth Tourist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France rolled out the red carpet Wednesday for a
New York couple chosen to symbolize the 500 millionth foreign
tourist to visit the country during the past 20 years.
   Mr. and Mrs. John Benchivenga of Brooklyn, who arrived here
Tuesday by Concorde, were selected from lists of travelers who made
reservations for April 12 on Air France, the French national
airline. They were on a regularly scheduled evening flight but were
upgraded to Concorde after their names were selected.
   The Benchivengas, who have three children, had a whirlwind,
luxury tour of the capital Wednesday beginning with lunch at the
Jules Vernes restaurant at the Eiffel Tower with French singer
Charles Aznavour and French tourism minister Jean-Jacques Descamps.
   Earlier they went on a guided tour of the year-old Orsay Museum
of 19th century art and in the afternoon visited some of Paris'
most elegant designer boutiques.
   ``It's like a second honeymoon, a dream, the kind of thing that
only happens once in every second or third life,'' Benchivenga, a
43-year-old IBM executive, told reporters.
   The celebrations are part of a government campaign to
``sensitize the French to the importance of giving foreign tourists
a warm welcome,'' Descamps said.
   He said Americans were chosen to symbolize the 500 and 501
millionth tourists because American tourism, after a disastrous
year in 1986 due to terrorism and the falling dollar, was again on
the rise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
