<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Diamandis-Hachette     04-13 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Diamandis-Hachette,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine Company Agrees to $712 Million Buyout by French Concern</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs story expected by 5 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diamandis Communications Inc., a leading
consumer magazine publisher, said Wednesday it has agreed to be
acquired by the French communications concern Hachette SA in a deal
valued at $712 million.
   The announcement came four days after Hachette reached an
agreement to buy Grolier Inc., a Danbury, Conn.-based book
publisher, for $450 million.
   The Diamandis deal includes 12 consumer magazines, including
Woman's Day, Car and Driver, Popular Photography, Road & Track and
Boating.
   Diamandis Communications was created only last fall when it
acquired the magazine division of CBS Inc. for $650 million.
   The buyout team included the management of the CBS magazine
division led by the division's president, Peter G. Diamandis, with
financing from the merchant banking subsidiaries of Prudential
Insurance Company of America.
   At the time of the purchase, it was reported that Hachette had
talked with CBS about buying its magazine group, which included 19
magazines at the time.
   Since buying the magazine from CBS, Diamandis has sold seven of
them.
   Prudential and Diamandis said in Wednesday's announcement that
the sale to Hachette combined with previous asset sales and excess
cash flow would bring the total proceeds generated by the
originally acquired properties to more than $1 billion.
   Hachette, which is based in Paris, has interests in television,
radio, magazines and book publishing.
   It is making the magazine acquisition through its Hachette
Publications Inc., a subsidiary of Hachette's magazine group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
