<DOCNO> AP880413-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-CBS     04-13 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-CBS,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Posts Big Profit Gain on Records Group Sale, Interest Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. said Wednesday its first-quarter
earnings rocketed higher, but the rise resulted from a huge
one-time profit on the sale of its records group and from interest
earned by investing cash from other asset sales.
   The company said the operating profit of its broadcast group
fell 19 percent compared with strong results a year ago.
   CBS reported an after-tax profit of $911.3 million, or $35.34 a
share, for the January-March period, compared with earnings of
$48.7 million, or $1.93 a share, a year earlier. Revenue fell 4.6
percent to $696.3 million from $729.7 million.
   The latest results included a one-time gain of $866.6 million
mainly due to the sale of the CBS Records Group to Sony Corp., the
Japanese electronics concern, for $2 billion.
   Income from continuing operations surged to $44.7 million from
$7.8 million a year earlier. But CBS said that was because it
netted $51.7 million on interest income in the latest quarter,
while it had interest expenses of $9.3 million in the same period
in 1987. Its interest income was augmented by a pre-tax gain of $14
million on the sale of Treasury securities.
   CBS has accumulated its cash by selling assets that are not
directly related to its core broadcasting business over the past 18
months. It sold its book and music publishing units in late 1986
and its magazine division in 1987.
   The CBS Broadcast Group made an operating profit of $15.6
million, down from $21.9 million, mainly because of lower results
for the CBS television network, which has seen its prime time
ratings slump to third place behind NBC and ABC for the first time.
   The TV network's results a year ago benefitted from the
inclusion of broadcasts of college basketball's and professional
football's championship games. Another network carried the Super
Bowl football game this year and the CBS telecasts of the NCAA
basketball finals occurred in the second quarter.
   CBS said that net sales for the broadcast group, which were off
5 percent at $696.2 million, would have improved if the impact of
the sporting events were excluded.
   ``Despite a difficult sales environment, Broadcast Group
earnings met our budgeted expectations,'' said Laurence A. Tisch,
president and chief executive officer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
