<DOCNO> AP880413-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1551EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-FannieMae     04-13 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Fannie Mae,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fannie Mae Reports Earnings Jump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal National Mortgage Association,
which buys mortgages and packages them into securities for
investors, said Wednesday its earnings rose 71 percent in the first
three months of the year.
   Aside from an unusual gain in the fourth quarter of last year,
attributed to accounting changes, earnings for the January to March
period were the highest quarterly earnings in the association's
history, said David O. Maxwell, Fannie Mae chairman.
   For the first quarter, earnings totaled $100.9 million, or $1.27
a share, up from $58.9 million, 75 cents a share, for the same
period in 1987.
   Fourth-quarter 1987 earnings, with the accounting adjustment,
were $195 million, or $2.40 a share. Without the adjustment,
earnings were $60.4 million, or 75 cents per share.
   Maxwell attributed the strong first quarter to Fannie Mae's
effort to reduce its sensitivity to interest rates. The company's
net interest income was $170.8 million in the first quarter,
compared with $102.9 million a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
