<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Exxon-West     04-13 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Exxon-West,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exxon, Texaco Trading Service Stations on West Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Co. U.S.A. is swapping 92 gas stations in
Southern California and three other states for 92 Texaco Inc.
service stations in the San Francisco area, company officials said.
   As part of the agreement announced Wednesday, Texaco has agreed
to offer Texaco-brand motor fuel franchise agreements to all Exxon
dealers who are leasing service station property from Exxon in
connection with their sale of Exxon-brand motor fuel.
   The Exxon stations involved in the trade are in San Diego, San
Bernardino and Riverside counties in California; Clark County,
Nev.; Clackamas, Multnoman, Washington and Yamhill counties in
Oregon; and Clark County in Washington.
   The market withdrawal by Exxon from those counties will involve
about 90 Exxon stations and 11 distributors and takes effect Oct.
31, Exxon U.S.A. spokesman Les Rogers said.
   Exxon U.S.A., the Houston domestic subsidiary of Exxon Corp.,
said it has been concerned with the increasing difficulty of
providing motor fuel supplies to certain West Coast markets.
   It has also had an interest in obtaining secure local markets
for motor fuel produced at the company's Benicia Refinery in the
San Francisco Bay area, Rogers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
