<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-13 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Slides, Dragged Down by Soybeans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures closed down as much as 9 cents
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade and the grain markets
followed suit as traders took profits amid an absence of bullish
news.
   Soybeans started the day lower and plunged near the bell,
extending for a second day a sell-off that follows last week's
rally linked to government reports indicating potentially tight
supplies.
   ``What you're seeing is a normal fall,'' said Walter Spilka, a
grains analyst at Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
``There's no bullish news at the moment. When you don't have it,
you have profit-taking, which we are having now.''
   Wheat and corn slid, despite a planned meeting this week between
Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng and officials from India about a
potential deal for wheat.
   Spilka said traders believe nothing will come out of the
discussions.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 2{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.18 a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
to 3{ cents lower with May at $2.04} a bushel; oats were 1\ cents
to 3} cents lower with May at $1.62} a bushel; soybeans were 4\
cents to 9 cents lower with May at $6.75 a bushel.
</TEXT>
