<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1619EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SoftDrinkMerger     04-13 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soft Drink Merger,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prudential Joins Soft Drink Merger</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto DN7</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Dr Pepper, with no period, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By READ MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group led by Prudential-Bache Interfunding Inc.
will become a major stockholder in the new firm merging the
Seven-Up and Dr Pepper holding companies, officials said Wednesday
as they announced terms of the $1.3 billion transaction.
   Prudential-Bache Interfunding _ the merchant banking arm of
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. _ and other investors will own 49
percent of Dr Pepper-Seven-Up Cos. Inc., which will be the third
largest soft drink company in the nation behind Coca-Cola Co. and
Pepsico.
   After the deal is completed, existing shareholders and senior
management will own 51 percent of the merged operation, the
companies said in a statement. Dr Pepper Holding Co. and Seven-Up
Holding Co. announced last month they had agreed to merge.
   The companies' current stockholders will be paid a total of $500
million in cash and $100 million in debt and preferred stock, the
statement said.
   Exactly how much will go to each company's stockholders has not
been determined, spokesman Tom Bayer said.
   Prudential-Bache's role in the new company was not foreseen by
management of Seven-Up and Dr Pepper when the pair announced their
initial merger agreement, Bayer said.
   Prudential-Bache approached the companies in March and proposed
to buy into the merged operation, he said.
   Financing for the transaction incudes about $75 million of
additional bank borrowings by Dr Pepper and approximately $125
million by Seven-Up, arranged with Bankers Trust Co.
   The transaction is expected to be consummated within 60 days,
company officials said. No new management changes are expected,
said John R. Albers, chief executive officer of both Dr Pepper and
Seven-Up.
   Thomas O. Hicks and Robert B. Haas, who will be co-chairmen of
Dr Pepper-Seven-Up Cos. Inc., led separate investment groups in the
purchase of Dr Pepper Co. and the Seven-Up Co. in 1986.
   The companies together have more than 800 employees, 500 of whom
are in the Dallas headquarters. The remainder are field sales
personnel or management and staff of the Technical Center in St.
Louis, Mo., where the companies make their concentrates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880413-0306 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1544EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FirstRepublicBank Bjt   04-13 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-First RepublicBank, Bjt,0746</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Chief Brings Record Of Success</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Casey, who piloted American Airlines to
profitability as its president during the turbulent deregulation of
the 1970s, could find the ride even bumpier as the new chief of
ailing First RepublicBank Corp., analysts said Wednesday.
   Texas' largest bank-holding company announced Tuesday that it
expects to lose $1.5 billion for the first quarter, even after a $1
billion emergency cash infusion last month.
   In addition, its top executives have left in a steady stream,
the latest on Tuesday when chairman and chief executive officer
Gerald W. Fronterhouse resigned.
   Casey, 68, named president and chief executive officer by the
bank's board of directors the same day, has been described by
financial analysts and former employees as both a motivator and a
hatchet man.
   He was credited with stripping Fort Worth-based AMR Corp.,
American's parent company, of layers of bureacracy and mercilessly
streamlining its operations. His was one of the few major airlines
showing a profit when he stepped down as its president in 1984.
   ``Casey smiles a broad Irish smile, shakes hands with a firm
grip and tells the best jokes at any dinner party,'' said an
executive once fired by Casey. ``But he carries a big stick and
doesn't mind using it.''
   But Casey is also known as a ``people man,'' an executive who
works well with others and motivates his employees.
   ``Al Casey is clearly an outstanding executive who has had very
broad experience,'' said Robert F. Erburu, chairman of the Times
Mirror Co. and a former Casey associate. ``He is well-versed in
problem-solving and possesses skills as an outstanding motivator of
people with special strengths in financial matters.''
   First RepublicBank Corp. presents the veteran corporate
repairman with a daunting set of challenges:
   _A projected $1.5 billion first-quarter loss, triple that of
corporate projections.
   _Panicked depositors, whose run on First RepublicBank was
stemmed March 17 by a six-month, $1 billion emergency loan from the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   _Resignations of top executives _ including the chairman of its
lead bank in Dallas _ and the company's largest shareholder, Dallas
Cowboys owner H.R. ``Bum'' Bright.
   As a condition of the emergency aid from the FDIC, top
executives agreed to resign if asked following a financial
examination of the company. Fronterhouse's resignation, timed to
coincide with the stunning revelation of First RepublicBank's
quarterly figures, threw a spotlight on the new chief executive.
   Casey took over AMR in 1974 at a time when it was top-heavy with
management layers brought on by 30 years of government regulation.
   In a series of dramatic moves, Casey sold off holdings
unconnected to running the airline, including large, unprofitable
holdings in hotels.
   ``When I came to American, I just took the whole thing and found
layers and layers of stuff, vice chairman of subsidiaries, hotel
companies and five management consulting firms,'' Casey recalled in
an interview with the Dallas Morning News not long before he
retired from American Airlines. ``(I) fired them all, cleaned them
out.''
   During Casey's 10-year reign, he cut American's cost per
operating unit by 25 percent. The company relocated from New York
to Fort Worth and liquidated its money-losing hotel business.
   ``Casey's whole career has been one of financial markets,'' said
Donald J. Carty, senior vice president at American, who worked with
Casey. ``He knows and is well-respected by every major banker in
the country and by every financial guru on Wall Street.''
   Casey said he would spend the next few weeks reviewing the
existing management team before making further changes at the
company.
   Casey also announced the board's appointment of a new executive
committee with Casey as chairman and Mark Shepherd Jr., chairman of
Texas Instruments Inc., the vice chairman.
   The $1.5 billion loss projected would be the second-largest ever
for a U.S. bank after Citicorp's $2.5 billion loss in second
quarter 1987.
   The bank holding company, the nation's 14th largest in terms of
assets, attributed the loss to a 50 percent increase in its
loan-loss provision, to $231 million, and writedowns from
foreclosed properties, all totaling $1.5 billion.
   The bank reported a loss of $656 million in 1987.
   FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman last month estimated that the
First RepublicBank bailout will cost a total $1.7 billion, although
industry experts say it is likely to cost substantially more.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
