<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SocieteGenerale     04-13 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Societe Generale,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Societe Generale Shareholders To Vote On Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Societe Generale de
Belgique SA are scheduled to vote Thursday on the fate of Belgium's
largest holding company, which is at the center of a bitter
takeover battle.
   The special meeting, expected to attract some 1,000 shareholders
and their representatives, is to start at 9:30 a.m. local time in a
specially built tent at the company's headquarters.
   Hundreds of journalists will monitor the session via
closed-circuit television.
   Societe Generale's outstanding shares will be counted at the
meeting, and a slate of directors will be elected to the company's
board.
   The meeting was requested by Carlo De Bendetti, the flashy
Italian financier who announced nearly three months ago that he
sought control of the 166-year-old company, which has interests in
a third of the Belgian economy.
   De Benedetti, who heads Olivetti SpA, claims he and his
associates own about 49 percent of Societe Generale's 28.2 million
outstanding shares.
   But an alliance led by Cie. Financiere de Suez of France and
Groupe AG, Belgium's biggest insurer, claims to hold a 50.7 percent
stake in the company.
   Shares will be counted for the first time at Thursday's meeting,
and shareholders will establish how many of those shares are valid.
The ownership issue has been clouded by the fact that the Belgian
government does not require shareholders to identify themselves or
their allies.
   On the eve of the meeting, the rival bidders tried once again to
negotiate a settlement but were unsuccessful.
   Cie. Financiere and Groupe AG are expected to claim they can
purchase another 2 million shares that are part of a contested bloc
of 12 million new shares issued to dilute De Benedetti's stake in
the company.
   De Benedetti is seeking seats on the board for himself and two
allies, including Andre Leysen, chairman of Belgium's Gevaert NV.
   His rivals are willing to let him join management but are
opposed to his taking control of the company.
   De Benedetti wants to turn Societe Generale into a pan-European
holding before 1992, when the European Economic Community will
remove a thicket of regulatory curbs that frustrate free movement
of goods and services within the community.
   Societe Generale has its tentacles in some 1,300 companies
involved in banking, financial services, engineering and mining and
chemicals, among other industries.
   During the heated takeover battle, Societe Generale stock shot
up at one point to 10,000 francs a share, or $286. But on
Wednesday, it was trading at 4,830 francs a share, or $138.
</TEXT>
