<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-ICIndustries     04-13 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-IC Industries,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IC Industries Profits Up 40 Percent In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong performance by its newly expanded
Pepsi-Cola bottling operations helped IC Industries Inc. post a
nearly 41 percent increase in profits in the first quarter, the
diversified company said Wednesday.
   IC reported record first-quarter net income of $40.7 million, or
38 cents a share, compared to $28.9 million, or 26 cents a share,
in the same period of 1987.
   The profits came on record sales of just over $1 billion
compared to $900.5 million in 1987, the Chicago-based company said
in a statement.
   Pet Inc., IC's specialty foods subsidiary, accounted for more
than a third of the company's revenues for the quarter.
   But Pepsi-Cola General Bottlers Inc., a subsidiary that was
expanded late last year through a joint venture with Pepsico Inc.,
showed the greatest improvement. Sales for the division increased
51.4 percent to $186.4 million and operating income was up nearly
140 percent, at $22.4 million, due to improved operating margins,
IC said.
   IC also owns muffler-and-brake specialist Midas International
Corp., aircraft parts maker Pneumo Abex Corp., food-service
equipment manufacturer Hussman Corp. and the Illinois Central
Railroad, which it is in the process of spinning off as a separate
company.
   The results included a gain of $23.7 million, or 22 cents a
share, from an accounting adjustment made to conform with a change
in income tax laws. That was largely offset by a $19.6 million loss
at Illinois Central, which is reported as a discontinued operation.
Although the railroad had an operating profit, there was a special
pre-tax charge of $35 million to cover a downsizing and
cost-reduction programs.
</TEXT>
