<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1553EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Banks     04-13 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Banks,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Morgan Reports Jump In Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   J.P. Morgan & Co. reported Wednesday that its first-quarter
profit jumped 24 percent from a year ago, and the chairman of the
nation's fifth largest banking company expressed cautious optimism
about the rest of 1988.
   ``After the difficulties of 1987, the new year has begun on a
more optimstic note,'' Chairman Lewis T. Preston said at the
company's annual shareholders' meeting.
   For the three months ended March 31, Morgan said it netted
$281.4 million, or $1.52 a share, compared with earnings of $226.4
million, or $1.22 a share, the same time a year ago.
   The increase reflected several factors, including higher net
interest income and corporate finance-related fees, which more than
offset an increase in non-interest operating expenses and in its
loan-loss provision.
   Non-interest operating income during the quarter totaled $435.2
milion, up from $336.8 million. But non-interest expenses also rose
sharply, to $444.1 million from $371.1 million.
   Interest income increased to $1.42 billion from $1.30 billion,
while interest expenses also rose, to $438.2 million from $383.0
million.
   Morgan said that during the quarter it raised its provision to
cover troubled loans, including those from Third World countries
like Brazil, to $50 million from $35 million.
   Last spring, Morgan and other major banks made hefty additions
to their loan-loss reserves after Brazil imposed a temporary
moratorium on interest payments on its international debt. The
banks had hoped to safeguard themselves against possible future
losses.
   Preston told shareholders that while the Brazilian government
has since resumed partial payment of interest on its debt, he was
also optimistic about current negotiations on restructuring that
country's debt.
   ``We remain convinced that the developing countries' debt
problems cannot be solved by any single action or institition,'' he
said. ``The situation of each country and each creditor is
different.
   ``The starting point for any solution is structural economic
reform in the developing countries.''
   Achieving ``significant progress'' in that direction has been
Mexico, Preston said.
   Earlier this year, Morgan's principal subsidiary, Morgan
Guaranty Trust Co., sponsored a debt-swap program aimed at helping
reduce that country's $105 billion foreign debt. The plan called
for Mexico to issue new 20-year bonds, back by U.S. Treasury
securities, in exchange for old bank debt.
   ``The Mexican loan exchange was not intended as a panacea for
the LDC (less developed country) debt problem, but we believe it
was useful effort that will lead to other approaches,'' Preston
said.
   Besides the Third World debt crisis, he said, Morgan and the
banking industry faced a myriad of other problems during 1987,
including the Oct. 19 stock market crash that followed a sharp rise
in interest rates.
   ``The heartening fact is that the world financial system, and
Morgan, have weathered these shocks rather well,'' Preston told
shareholders. ``The crash itself has been much less harmful effect
on the economy than had been commonly feared.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
