<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Owens-Illinois-Brockway     04-13 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Owens-Illinois-Brockway,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Owens-Illinois, Brockway Complete Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Owens-Illinois said Wednesday it had
completed its merger with Brockway Inc., creating the nation's
largest glass container company.
   Toledo-based Owens-Illinois said integration of the companies'
operations had been under way for several weeks. Completion of the
merger ended a process that began last September and has so far
survived a challenge by the Federal Trade Commission.
   On Feb. 29, a subsidiary of Owens-Illinois completed the
acquisition of more than 98 percent of Brockway's shares
outstanding for about $740 million. That followed a decision by the
government against appealing a court decision in favor of the
merger.
   Each common share of Brockway still outstanding will be
converted to $60 in cash, Owens-Illinois said.
   Robert Lanigan, chairman of Owens-Illinois, has said the merger
will make the combined operations and the glass container industry
``significantly more competitive with can, plastic and other
materials in the worldwide packaging business.''
   The FTC had attempted in court to block the merger, saying it
might violate antitrust laws by substantially reducing competition
and creating the conditions for price discrimination.
   However, U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green denied the FTC's
request for a preliminary injunction on the basis that the agency
had failed to prove the deal would harm competition. A federal
appeals court sided with Judge Green, saying the FTC had failed to
make its case.
   The FTC has scheduled administrative hearings on potential
anticompetitive effects of the merger. And spokeswoman Susan
Ticknor said Owens-Illinois could be ordered to divest itself of
Brockway holdings if the agency determines that the merger violates
antitrust laws.
   Brockway, of Jacksonville, Fla., had sales of nearly $1.1
billion last year; Owens-Illinois had sales of more than $3 billion.
</TEXT>
