<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0188</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined slightly today as
traders cashed in some of the gains from the rally of the past six
sessions.
   The market's decline came despite buying in International
Business Machines, which rose 2| to 116\.
   Analysts generally gave high marks to the company's
first-quarter results, which showed earnings at $1.53 a share, up
from $1.30 in the comparable period of 1987.
   Otherwise, however, brokers said the mood was cautious and
subdued.
   Wall Street is looking for favorable news from the meeting today
of the so-called Group of Seven industrialized countries in
Washington, and from Thursday's report by the Commerce Department
on the nation's trade balance for February.
   But many traders apparently are worried that whatever positive
stimulus comes from those sources may have been already reflected
in stock prices with the market's advance of late.
   ``We have to wonder if there will be `selling on the news' even
if the economic figures come in as expected,'' said Newton Zinder
at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
