<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 2043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PSNHFinances     04-13 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PSNH Finances,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Estimated Seabrook Start-up Date Set Back 18 Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public Service Company of New Hampshire
won't flatly predict when or if its Seabrook nuclear power plant
ever will operate, but the estimate it makes for financial planning
purposes has slipped again _ to Jan. 1, 1990.
   That is 18 months later than Public Service's prior written
planning assumption, though company officials told state regulators
last year that the date had slipped at least to April 1989.
   In its annual report for 1987 filed this week with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, Public Service also raises the
possibility that federal regulators would set rates if the company
emerges successfully from bankruptcy protection _ and reiterates
that rates likely would have to increase.
   Barred by state law from charging ratepayers for any of its 36
percent share of the $5.3 billion reactor before the plant operates
commercially, and unable to borrow any more money, Public Service
on Jan. 28 became the first big investor-owned utility in more than
50 years to seek bankruptcy protection.
   Company spokesman Nicholas Ashooh emphasized on Wednesday that
the new Seabrook startup assumption is not a prediction of when the
beleaguered reactor will produce electricity.
   After earlier projected startup dates repeatedly passed with
Seabrook remaining idle _ Public Service originally hoped to have
it operating commercially in 1979 _ the utility in recent years has
said it cannot predict when or if the 1,150-megawatt plant will
ever surmount evacuation-planning obstacles to a license.
   But in compiling its reports for the SEC, ``We just have to have
an estimate to make some financial planning assumptions,'' Ashooh
said.
   The company's most recent previous Seabrook startup assumption
had been July 1, though utility officials had told state regulators
during hearings on an emergency rate request last year that date
probably would be missed.
   Public Service was denied the Seabrook-related rate increase
when the state Supreme Court upheld the law that bars utilities
from charging ratepayers for power plants before they produce
electricity. Two days later the utility, New Hampshire's largest
power company, sought bankruptcy refuge.
   Public Service this month appealed the state court ruling to the
U.S. Supreme Court, hoping to increase the value of the company in
reorganzation by being allowed to charge ratepayers for Seabrook
before it operates.
   ``It is believed that some level of rate increases will be
essential to develop and implement a successful plan,'' the company
told the SEC.
   Two New England utilities have announced they are interested in
taking over Public Service's non-Seabrook assets. New England
Electric System of Massachusetts has said it envisions having New
Hampshire regulators retain ratemaking authority, while Northeast
Utilities of Connecticut has not divulged details of its takeover
plan.
   ``The (reorganization) plan could involve a sale of the company
or certain of its assets, or a split-up of the company and its
assets into two or more companies, resulting, in the latter case,
in a potential change in rate regulation to the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission,'' Public Service told the SEC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
