<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   04-13 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0533</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market took a backward step Wednesday
as traders cashed in some of the gains from the rally of the past
six sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 129 points
over the last six trading days, slipped 2.98 to 2,107.10.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 4 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 666 up, 829 down and 493 unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 185.12 million shares, against 140.40
million in the previous session. The NYSE's composite index edged
up .01 to 153.20.
   The market's decline came despite buying in International
Business Machines, which rose 2{ to 116[.
   Analysts generally gave high marks to the company's
first-quarter results, which showed earnings at $1.53 a share, up
from $1.30 in the comparable period of 1987.
   Otherwise, however, brokers said the mood was cautious and
subdued.
   Wall Street was looking for favorable news from the meeting
today of the so-called Group of Seven industrialized countries in
Washington, and from Thursday's report by the Commerce Department
on the nation's trade balance for February.
   But many traders apparently are worried that whatever positive
stimulus comes from those sources may have been already reflected
in stock prices with the market's advance of late.
   ``We have to wonder if there will be `selling on the news' even
if the economic figures come in as expected,'' said Newton Zinder
at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   IBM's showing helped produce a modest echo effect in some of the
other prominent computer and technology issues. Digital Equipment
added } to 108], and Hewlett-Packard was up ~ at 64{.
   Pfizer gained 3\ to 60[, apparently benefiting from takeover
rumors and speculation.
   Federal National Mortgage rose 1] to 35\. The company reported
first-quarter earnings of $1.28 a share, up from 76 cents in the
like period last year. Fannie Mae warrants jumped } to 8| to rank
among the day's best percentage gainers.
   Hospital Corp. of America, which said its first-quarter profits
came in above analysts' expectations, climbed 2\ to 36.
   Auto stocks were mixed as the industry posted a 10.8 percent
decline in early-April domestic car sales. Chrysler rose [ to 24},
but Ford Motor dropped [ to 47[ and General Motors was down ] at
75].
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 129 points
over the last six trading days, slipped back 2.98 to 2,107.10.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $0.07 billion, or 0.003
percent, in value.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 210.23 million shares.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose .33 to 316.49, and S&P's
500-stock composite index was up .18 at 271.55.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
gained .03 to 383.41. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 305.79, down .80.
</TEXT>
