<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OilPrices     04-13 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Prices,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Hold Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices were little changed Wednesday, but
analysts were heartened that the market had no trouble holding at
higher levels after an impressive two-day rally.
   Contract prices for unleaded gasoline posted a modest gain,
while crude and heating oils were fractionally higher.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for May delivery
of West Texas Intermediate crude, which jumped $1.21 a barrel in
the last two sessions, rose 2 cents to settle at $18.12 a barrel.
   Oil prices had not traded above the $18-a-barrel level since
last December.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline rose .35 cent a gallon to close at
52.42 cents, and heating oil rose .11 cent a gallon to close at
49.02 cents.
   ``The market was exceptional simply because it had been expected
to fall'' after the sharp, two-day run-up, said Bob Baker, a senior
energy analyst at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Reports of higher U.S. inventories and some profit taking took
crude below $18 a barrel in early trading, but prices soon moved
higher and held in a narrow range.
   ``The market couldn't be depressed,'' said Richard Kane, a
trader at Merrill Lynch Energy Futures. ``There's good underlying
support.''
   Echoing that sentiment, Baker said the market ``showed
surprising resilience.''
   Analysts anticipate little change in oil prices between now and
April 23, when a number of non-OPEC exporters are scheduled to meet
to discuss coordinated strategies for reducing output and forcing
prices up.
   News that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries had
invited eight nations to participate in the meeting was a key
factor in sparking the rally earlier in the week.
   The impending meeting will ``keep the market in a
sideways-to-upward momentum until we have some solid evidence on
supply,'' Kane said.
   Analysts expect the market to be pelted with rumors until the
meeting actually takes place. ``It will be a psychological battle''
until then, Baker said.
   Reports that 100 U.S. Marines clashed with unidentified
intruders at a military fuel tank farm in a Panamanian jungle had
no effect on trading.
   In the previous session, however, the market advanced when the
fatal shooting of a Marine who was guarding a petroleum storage
area on a U.S. military base in Panama sparked rumors that a
crucial trans-Panama oil pipeline would shut down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
