<DOCNO> AP880413-0322 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 2103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PaperTalks     04-13 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paper Talks,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Paper Offers Contract Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Paper Co. presented
contract proposals Wednesday to the United Paperworkers
International Union in an effort to settle bitter labor disputes at
four facilities.
   International Paper spokesman William Greener said the union was
evaluating the proposals, but both sides agreed not to discuss any
details until the plans are presented to local memberships.
   Wayne E. Glenn, international president of the union, said in a
statement issued from its Nashville, Tenn., headquarters, that the
next step would be to take the proposals to the membership. No time
frame was announced.
   When negotiations got underway March 28, International Paper
said it hoped to defuse hostility between management and labor and
to set up a framework for pursuing the company's labor problems on
a local level.
   About 3,500 workers in four locations are affected by the
contract disputes. In Mobile, Ala., 1,200 workers have been locked
out of their jobs, while an additional 2,300 workers have struck
plants in Jay, Maine, Lock Haven, Pa., and DePere, Wis.
   The International Brotherhood of Firemen and Oilers represents
some workers at the Maine facility, where the contract proposals
also would apply. Contracts also are open in Pine Bluff and Camden,
Ark., and Natchez, Miss.
   International Paper and its unions have been at odds for more
than a year over contracts that have come up for renewal. At the
heart of the disagreement is the issue of whether local contracts
should restore premium pay for Sundays and holidays.
   Premium pay had been eliminated with labor's approval from past
contracts, but an improved financial picture for the industry in
the last year prompted the unions to campaign to revive the benefit.
   International Paper has continued to operate its mills with
replacement workers. The company has claimed throughout the dispute
that strike-breakers were permanent employees and offered
assistance to strikers who wanted to re-enter the job market,
including positions at other company mills.
   International Paper, based in Purchase, N.Y., earned $407
million in 1987, but the company said its profitablity was below
the industry average.
</TEXT>
