<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1758EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Diamandis-Hachette     04-13 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diamandis-Hachette,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hachette To Acquire Magazine Company in Second Big U.S.
Acquisition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The French communications giant Hachette SA made
its second major venture into the U.S. publishing market this week
with an announcement Wednesday it will buy a major magazine
publisher for $712 million.
   Hachette said it had agreed to buy Diamandis Communications
Inc., a privately held concern that publishes a dozen magazines,
including Woman's Day, Car & Driver, Popular Photography, Road &
Track and Stereo Review.
   The announcement came four days after Hachette reached an
agreement to buy Grolier Inc., the Danbury, Conn.-based book
publisher, for $450 million.
   Hachette, which is based in Paris, has interests in television,
radio, magazines and book publishing.
   In conjunction with Publications Filipacchi, Hachette publishes
74 magazines in 10 languages that sell 650 million copies annually.
   It said the acquisition of Diamandis would give the
Hachette-Filipacchi organization revenue of $1.9 billion this year,
rivaling Time Inc. for the title of the biggest magazine publisher
in thw world. Time reported $1.6 billion in magazine revenue in
1987 but has made no projection for 1988.
   Diamandis was formed in October when it acquired the magazine
division of CBS Inc. for $650 million in cash.
   The buyers in that deal included the management of the CBS
magazine division led by the division's president, Peter G.
Diamandis, and two merchant banking subsidiaries of Prudential
Insurance Company of America that financed the buyout and took a 70
percent stake in the new firm.
   Since the acquisition from CBS, Diamandis sold seven of its 19
original magazines, raising in excess of $232 million.
   The money from those sales combined with that from Hachette and
excess cash flow boosts total proceeds from the originally acquired
properties to more than $1 billion, Diamandis and Prudential said.
   ``Given the magnitude of the overall gain and the timeframe
involved, this has to be considered one of the most sucessful
leveraged buyouts ever undertaken,'' said Kenneth E. MacWilliams,
president and chief executive of Prudential Capital Corp., one of
the two Pudential subsidiaries.
   Analysts said the consensus when CBS sold the magazine division
was that it had gotten a good price. They said a combination of the
dollar's decline against the French franc, cost-cutting steps
undertaken since the buyout and Hachette's evident desire to expand
apparently made it worth more to Hachette.
   Hachette had talked to CBS about buying its magazine division
for $600 million before it was sold to Diamandis.
   Daniel Filipacchi, vice chairman of Hachette, acknowledged
Wednesday that Hachette had ``held some discussions with CBS'' in
July although nothing came of them.
   ``We continued to watch the company and felt that it was
becoming more and more attractive. That together with the quality
of its people decided us on the acquisition,'' he said in the
statement announcing the agreement.
   The purchase price includes $345 million for the equity in
Diamandis Communications and the retirement of $367 million in debt
that the Prudential subsidiaries arranged, Prudential spokesman
Scott Peterson said.
   Peter Diamandis said in a telephone interview that his company
was not actively seeking a buyer when it was approached by Hachette
about the possibility of selling. He said their talks took about a
month.
   Diamandis, who has signed a three-year contract to continue at
the company, said the deal gives his organization greater financial
resources to expand its publications overseas, tailor some Hachette
foreign publications to the U.S. market and start new magazines.
   Filipacchi said his company bought Diamandis Communications ``to
expand it, not sell it off in pieces.'' He said it would be ``the
nucleus for expansion'' of Hachette's activities in the United
States.
   The Hachette-Filipacchi organization entered the U.S. magazine
market in 1985 by launching an American version of the French
fashion magazine Elle in a 50-50 joint venture with Murdoch
Magazines, which is controlled by media figure Rupert Murdoch.
   It also publishes Premiere, a movie magazine in a joint venture
with Murdoch Magazines.
   The purchase of Diamandis Communications is being undertaken
through Hachette Publishing Inc., a subsidiary of Hachette's
magazine division.
   The Grolier acquisition is being made by the Hachette book
publishing division.
   Filipacchi said the deals were negotiated separately, and said
it was a coincidence that the deals ``have come so soon after one
another.''
</TEXT>
