<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Staley-Continental     04-13 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Staley-Continental,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Staley Board Delays Action On Takeover Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Staley Continental Inc. said
Tuesday that its board of directors has delayed action on a $1.33
billion cash tender offer from Tate & Lyle PLC, a major British
sugar refiner.
   Staley spokesman G. David Satterfield said the company would
announce its position on the $32-a-share offer before April 21, and
urged stockholders to postpone not to take any action until after
the board's recommendation.
   Staley, the second-largest U.S. refiner of corn sweeteners, said
its management will continue to review the Tate & Lyle offer with
legal and financial advisors.
   ``I'd like to think that the acquisition of Staley by Tate &
Lyle would be friendly,'' Tate & Lyle Chairman Neil Shaw said, at a
news conference Tuesday.
   Shaw called the offer, set to expire at midnight May 5, ``a very
good price,'' and refused to speculate about any possible change in
negotiations with Staley. Tate & Lyle owns nearly 5 percent of
Staley's stock.
   Also Tuesday, the Staley board elected Robert M. Powers as its
president and chief operating officer. Powers previously served as
an executive vice president and has been a director of Staley
Continental since 1975.
</TEXT>
