<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1808EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-13 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum, Gold Futures Sink</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices fell sharply Wednesday as the dollar
gained strength ahead of Thursday's report on the U.S. trade
deficit, which many traders expected to show a lessening of the
import-export gap.
   The dollar's advance against most foreign currencies also
contributed to weakness in the other precious metals, analysts said.
   On other exchanges, soybean and grain prices fell; crude oil
futures edged higher; livestock and meat were down and stock-index
futures retreated.
   Fairly heavy selling of platinum futures by foreign investors
sparked the decline in the precious-metals complex, analysts said.
The active June gold contract cracked the psychologically important
level of $450 a troy ounce on New York's Commodity Exchange, but
buying interest then surfaced to halt the slide and held losses to
$4 to $5.
   Platinum plunged $16.30 across the board on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for delivery in July
settled at $522.80 a troy ounce.
   Expectations of a sharp reduction in the February trade deficit
from January's $12.4 billion added to the negative tone in precious
metals, said Stephen Platt, an analyst in Chicago for Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   ``What traders are looking at is the dollar's strength and the
subsequent limiting of any strong investment demand by the U.S. in
precious metals if that does occur,'' Platt said.
   Working in favor of higher gold prices, however, was a drop in
supplies at Commodity Exchange warehouses, said Jerry Rothman, an
analyst at Elders Futures Inc.
   Rothman said the Comex reported warehouse stocks at 1.548 troy
ounces, down from about 2.6 million troy ounces less than two
months ago.
   The relatively tight supplies of deliverable gold stocks
indicates that ``in the longer term, the price of gold should tend
to move upwards,'' Rothman said.
   Gold settled $3.90 to $5.50 lower with June at $449.60 a troy
ounce; silver was 7.5 cents to 8.7 cents lower with May at $6.345 a
troy ounce.
   Soybean futures lost as much 9 cents a bushel on the Chicago
Board of Trade. The grain markets followed suit as traders took
profits amid an absence of bullish news.
   Soybeans started the day lower and plunged near the bell,
extending for a second day a selloff that follows last week's rally
caused by government reports indicating potentially tight supplies.
   The wheat market received some bullish news after the close when
the Agriculture Department announced it had targeted India for 1.2
million metric tons of subsidized U.S. wheat.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 2} cents lower with May at $3.18\ a
bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 3{ cents lower with May at $2.04} a
bushel; oats were 2 cents to 3} cents lower with May at $1.62} a
bushel; soybeans were 3} cents to 9 cents lower with May at $6.75{
a bushel.
   Crude oil moved higher on the New York Mercantile Exchanage for
the third consecutive session on rumors that the Organizaiton of
Petroleum Exporting Countries would declare their April 25 meeting
an emergency session, said Nauman Barakat of Smith Barney, Harris
Upham & Co. in New York.
   Such a declaration would enable the oil ministers to take action
to limit production, a prospect that appears increasingly likely,
Barakat said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 3 cents to 15 cents
higher with May at $18.12 a barrel; heating oil was .02 cent lower
to .11 cent higher with May at 49.02 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .31 cent to .54 cent higher with May at 52.42 cents a
gallon.
   Live cattle futures settled sharply lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange with the sentiments matched to a lesser degree
in the feeder cattle and pork pits.
   Live cattle settled 1.17 cents lower to .50 cent higher with
April at 73.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .47 cent lower to
.05 cent higher with April at 79.65 cents per pound; hogs were .37
cent to 1.28 cents lower with April at 45 cents per pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.37 cents lower to .10 cent higher with May at
51.65 cents per pound.
   Stock-index futures retreated slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for June delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled .45 point lower at 272.10. The underlying
spot index advanced .21 point to close at 271.58.
</TEXT>
