<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Raytheon     04-13 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Raytheon,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Raytheon First-Quarter Earnings Rise 11 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raytheon Co., one of the nation's top
government defense contractors, reported Wednesday that its fiscal
first-quarter earnings rose more than 11 percent over a year ago.
   For the three months ended April 3, Raytheon said net income
totaled $113.3 million, or $1.68 a share, on sales of $1.95
billion. That compared with earnings of $101.8 million, or $1.37 a
share, on sales $1.75 billion last year.
   Raytheon credited some of the increase to a boost in profits
from several divisions, including aircraft and electronics.
   The company attributed a 22.6 percent increase in earnings per
share to a drop in the number of shares outstanding due to a stock
repurchase program. Raytheon had 67.3 million shares outstanding
during the first quarter, compared with 74.2 shares outstanding
during the year-ago period.
   Raytheon's Wichita, Kan.-based Beech Aircraft Corp. division was
boosted by last year's introduction of the 19-seat Beech 1900
turboprop plane, which is being used by several domestic and
foreign airlines, said spokesman Larry McCracken.
   The electronics division, currently producing air-traffic
control radars for the U.S. and Canada, led the company in both
sales and profits, while the energy services division, which
produces nuclear and non-nuclear power plants, was the only segment
to report a drop in sales.
   Raytheon was ranked as the sixth largest defense contractor by
the Department of Defense for fiscal 1987, which ended Sept. 30.
The Lexington-based company was ranked seventh the previous fiscal
year, McCracken said.
   The backlog of goverment-funded orders, including the five-year
contract for the Patriot surface-to-air missile, rose from $5.20
billion in the first quarter of 1987 to $6.31 billion for the first
quarter this year.
   Total orders are presently $8.6 billion, compared to $7.52
billion for the first quarter of 1987.
   Raytheon non-defense divisions also produce text books, road
construction machinery and home appliances.
</TEXT>
