<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OSHA-CollyerWire     04-13 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OSHA-Collyer Wire,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OSHA Fines Rhode Island Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department fined a Rhode Island
company $612,000 Wednesday for what officials described as a scheme
to underreport job accidents and deny injured employees full
workmen's compensation benefits entitled them.
   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration cited Collyer
Insulated Wire Co. of Lincoln, R.I., for 102 instances of
``willfully'' under-reporting or misrecording workdays that
employees lost to injuries and the medical treatments they required.
   OSHA officials cited one instance in which a worker had to have
the tip of his thumb amputated, and another in which a worker had
to have his index finger amputated.
   While both workers were off for several days,
government-required records showed them not missing any work,
according to the officials.
   Collyer, a subsidiary of the Santa Monica, Calif.-based Wickes
Cos., employs about 340 workers at the Lincoln plant.
   Officials at the plant referred questions to the parent company.
Its spokeswoman, Susan Williams, said Wickes officials would have
no comment on the OSHA charges until after they have studied the
agency's complaint.
   Under the law, the company has 15 days to either pay the fine or
contest it before a three-judge review panel.
   OSHA investigators said there were dozens of cases at the
Lincoln plant in which workers who were off because of injuries
were told to ``punch in'' for their shifts and then return home.
   ``The company called this `light duty,' but in fact these
represented lost workdays which the company did not report,'' said
Terry Mikelson, a spokesman for the agency. ``In some cases injured
employees may have collected less in pay and benefits than they
would have under workers' compensation.''
   Deputy Assistant Labor Secretary Frank White said the so-called
light-duty program effectively masked serious injuries and the
number of lost workays.
   It is lost workdays that OSHA, state agencies and insurance
companies measure in determining whether to inspect a plant and in
calculating the premiums it has to pay for workers' compensation
insurance.
   ``It was clear to us that Collyer's approach was deliberately
misleading to OSHA and posssibly to others,'' said George Salem,
the Labor Department's solicitor. ``One incentive for companies to
under-report is to keep their workmen's compensation insurance
rates low.''
</TEXT>
