<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Westinghouse     04-13 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Westinghouse,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts 1st-Qtr Profit Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. on Wednesday said
improvements in its financial services, commercial and industries
divisions helped lift its first-quarter profit by 13.8 percent from
a year ago.
   The company said it earned $168.5 million, or $1.16 per share,
in the first three months of the year compared with $148.1 million,
or $1.03 per share, a year earlier.
   Revenue for the quarter rose 11.1 percent to $2.75 billion from
a restated $2.48 billion in the 1987 first quarter.
   The company said accounting changes exaggerated the improvements
slightly.
   Spokesman Paul B. Jones said the improvement in profits ``would
have been slightly less'' than 13.8 percent without the accounting
changes.
   Operating profits improved significantly in the financial
services, commercial and industries divisions and also improved in
electronics and broadcasting. But operating profits fell
significantly in energy and utility systems compared to a strong
1987 first quarter.
   ``I was particularly pleased by our sales and operating profit
margin improvement in the first quarter,'' said Chairman John C.
Marous. ``Sales were strong even when adjusted for recent
acquisitions. Incoming order rates were well ahead of lest year,
and our businesses are demonstrating continuing strength as we move
into 1988.''
</TEXT>
