<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EconomyRdp     04-13 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy Rdp,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Finance Ministers Agree To Stabilize Dollar; Retail Sales Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Top finance officials of seven nations announced Wednesday they
would keep working to stabilize the value of the dollar, extending
an agreement reached last December.
   In domestic economic news, the Commerce Department said retail
sales rose 0.8 percent in March and automakers said sales of
domestic cars and light trucks fell 10.8 percent in early April
compared to a year earlier.
   Stock prices retreated slightly as the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 2.98 points to 2,107.10. It was the first Dow decline
after gains of more than 129 points in six sessions.
   The finance officials, meeting in Washington, announced they
would use gold and other commodities as a way of measuring
inflation pressures, a concept long advocated by Treasury Secretary
James A. Baker III.
   However, their announcement fell far short of suggesting a
return to a gold standard for currency values.
   The group consists of finance ministers and central bank leaders
from the United States, Japan, West Germany, Britain, France,
Canada and Italy.
   The finance ministers were critical of the newly industrialized
nations of South Korea, Taiwan, Singapore and Hong Kong for not
doing enough to reduce global trade imbalances.
   The meeting was the first face-to-face encounter the top finance
leaders have had since the global crash of stock markets last
October, a selloff thaty may have been triggered partly by
squabbling among the top economic powers.
   The drop in auto sales came after three months of unexpectedly
strong results.
   ``It's the weakest period in a long time. (But) I think it's
just a hiccup,'' said David Healy, industry analyst with Drexel
Burnham Lambert in New York.
   Retail sales were helped by Easter buying at department and food
stores.
   The Commerce Department said retail sales for the month
increased by a seasonally adjusted $1.1 billion to $130.7 billion.
   It was the fifth consecutive monthly increase and the largest
since December, when sales shot up 1.1 percent. Revised figures
showed sales rose 0.6 percent in February and 0.1 percent in
January.
   Ever since the October stock market crash, economists have
watched retail sales closely for signs that the consumer sector of
the economy would weaken. But more recently, some analysts have
raised fears that too much consumer demand could rekindle inflation.
   The dollar rose against most of the major foreign currencies
Wednesday although most traders stayed on the sidelines, waiting
for Thursday's release of U.S. trade deficit figures.
   Gold prices fell. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
late bid of $446.60 for a troy ounce of gold, down from $450.20
late Tuesday.
   A better-than-expected figure could boost the dollar Thursday.
The market was expecting the February deficit to fall within the
range of $11.2 billion to $11.8 billion.
   The dollar ended the day down to 126.44 Japanese yen in New York
compared to 126.685 yen late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
