<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Mead     04-13 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Mead,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profit Nearly Doubles in 1st Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mead Corp. said Wednesday its first-quarter
profit nearly doubled due to improving prices and supply conditions
in the paper industry.
   Mead earned $65.8 million, or $1.01 per share, for the quarter
ended April 3 compared with $34.2 million, or 55 cents a share, a
year earlier.
   The latest results included a 17 cent-per-share gain from sale
of Mead's recycled paperboard business.
   First-quarter sales rose to slightly more than $1 billion from
$957 million in 1987.
   Burnell R. Roberts, chairman and chief executive, said
production has reached record levels, but backlogs continue to
increase in some product lines and prices continue to improve.
   Demand for Mead's coated paperboard also remains strong, the
announcement said. The company is moving more heavily into that
value-added packaging line by selling some of its traditional
corrugated cardboard box plants and building a $500 million
expansion to its existing coated paperboard mill in Phenix City,
Ala.
   Favorable foreign exchange rates have helped Mead's
international sales, and sales of Mead Data Central, its electronic
publishing subsidiary, also were up substantially over 1987's first
quarter, the company said.
</TEXT>
