<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PECO     04-13 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PECO,0333</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>PECO Stockholders Hammer Dissidents' Bid to Stop Limerick
^By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philadelphia Electric Co. stockholders on
Wednesday overwhelmingly rejected a dissident move to cancel the
utility's costly Limerick II nuclear power plant as protesters
demonstrated outside on stilts.
   Limerick I, located on the Schuylkill River 20 miles northwest
of Philadelphia, has been operating for nearly two years and its
controversial twin tower is 85 percent complete.
   Stockholders defeated the Limerick resolution, with 88 percent
voting against it and 12 percent in favor.
   About 500 stockholders of more than 295,000 who own shares
attended the annual meeting where about 30 people, many walking on
stilts and with animal masks on their heads, demonstrated outside.
Protesters carried signs that read, ``Stop Limerick,'' ``Nuke Power
We All Lose'' and ``Just Say No to Nukes.''
   Protesters also criticized PECO's Peach Bottom nuclear plant on
the Susquehanna River near York, Pa., which the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission temporarily closed a year ago after control-room workers
were found sleeping on the job.
   Both plants have been costly to PECO, with the Peach Bottom
shutdown costing the company $5 million a month and Limerick II
having $1 billion in cost overruns.
   Corbin A. McNeill, Jr., PECO's executive vice president-nuclear,
told stockholders the utility hopes to reopen Peach Bottom before
the end of this year and load nuclear fuel into the Limerick II
reactor by August 1989.
   J. Andy Smith III, director of the American Baptist Church's
National Ministries Investment Program, for the ninth consecutive
year introduced a resolution aimed at cancelling Limerick.
   ``We are following the guidance of the policy of the General
Board of American Baptist Churches that utilities place a hold on
nuclear plants until they can be safely constructed and operated
and the waste permanently disposed,'' he said.
   Citing Peach Bottom's management problems, Smith said he ``had
serious doubts about the ability of PECO to operate any nuclear
plant.''
</TEXT>
