<HEAD>New York Times Co.'s First-Quarter Earnings Up 11 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBs 2nd graf pvs The company... with two new grafs to UPDATE
with McClatchy earnings, edits to conform. Picks up 3rd graf, The
company... ADDS 4 grafs detail on McClatchy.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Times Co. reported an 11 percent gain
in first-quarter earnings Wednesday, attributing the improvement
largely to strong performances in its broadcasting and
forest-product divisions that offset weakness in newspaper and
magazine advertising.
   Separately, McClatchy Newspapers, publisher of the Sacramento
Bee and 11 other newspapers, reported its first quarter profit rose
33 percent over the same period last year.
   New York Times said its earnings for the three months ended
March 31 totaled $45.5 million, or 56 cents a share, compared with
$41.1 million, or 50 cents a share, in the 1987 first quarter.
Revenue totaled $430.4 million, vs. $409 million, a 5 percent gain.
   The company owns the New York Times, 35 regional newspapers, a
one-third interest in the International Herald Tribune and a group
of magazines.
   It also owns a cable television station and radio station in New
York, TV stations in five other cities and interests in several
pulp and paper operations.
   The company said earnings in the newspaper group declined
slightly despite higher revenue, which it attributed largely to
increased costs. The magazine group's earnings also decreased
because of what the company called repositioning costs associated
with Family Circle and development costs of Child, Decorating
Remodeling, Southern Travel and Snow Country.
   The broadcasting-cable TV group's earnings strengthened in the
quarter because of higher cable subscription prices, while the
forest products unit's earnings grew sharply becuase of higher
paper prices, the company said.
   Sacramento, Calif.-based McClatchy Newspapers reported a first
quarter profit of $4.44 million, or 16 cents per share, up from
$3.34 million, or 13 cents per share, in the same period last year.
   Total revenue for the quarter rose to $82.7 million from $75.3
million in the same period last year.
   The company attributed the gains to advertising and circulation
increases at the Sacramento Bee and Modesto Bee, but said the gains
were partially offset by increased newsprint and payroll costs.
   The McClatchy group also publishes nine other newspapers in
California, Washington and Alaska.
</TEXT>
