<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TexasAir-Lorenzo     04-13 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas Air-Lorenzo,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aggressive Lorenzo Built Texas Air Into Major Carrier</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Texas Air-Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank A. Lorenzo, chairman of Texas Air Corp.,
often has said one of his major goals was to solve problems
connected with consolidating several airlines and winning back
disaffected customers.
   His task took on new dimensions after the Transportation
Department's announcement Wednesday that it was investigating Texas
Air's finances and management to determine whether the troubled
airline was fit to carry commercial traffic.
   Lorenzo was traveling Wednesday, and was not available to be
interviewed by reporters, said Texas Air spokesman Bruce Hicks.
   Lorenzo, 47, spent more than a decade building Texas Air Corp.
into one of world's largest and most aggressive airline companies,
acquiring such carriers as Continental Airlines, Eastern Airlines,
New York Air, Frontier Airlines, People Express and smaller
commuter airlines.
   Texas Air's airlines now serve nearly one-fifth of the U.S.
commercial airline market.
   But along the way came major problems with coordinating computer
systems, flight schedules, work forces, often bitter
union-management relations and customer defection to other carriers.
   Texas Air has said problems in consolidating several airlines
were unavoidable, and that by acquiring other carriers in many
cases it was helping them stay in business.
   After a bitter takeover battle in 1981, Lorenzo merged
Continental with his smaller, regional carrier called Texas
International Airlines. But by mid-1983, the new carrier was losing
money heavily. Lorenzo took Continental to bankruptcy court, later
emerging with a non-union airline.
   But the losses continued, with Texas Air sustaining a company
record loss of $466 million last year.
   In an interview aired last week on ABC's 20@20, Lorenzo said he
hoped to create the airline of the future.
   ``Our mission today is to put together and continue the process
of smoothing out what has been put together, and to bring to the
consumer what the consumer demands and create the airline for the
1990s,'' Lorenzo said.
   ``I can tell you that in my 16 years in this business, safety
has never taken second place,'' he said.
   Lorenzo studied economics at Columbia College, and received a
master's degree in finance from Harvard Business School in 1963. He
joined Trans World Airlines as a financial analyst in 1963 but left
two years later to become manager of Eastern's financial analysis
department. In 1966, he and Robert J. Carney, a Harvard classmate,
formed a financial advisory firm.
   Three years later, the two men founded Jet Capital Corp., which
bought a controlling interest in Texas International in August
1972, with Lorenzo becoming the carrier's youngest president ever
at age 32.
   In 1981, Texas International bought Continental for $100
million, with the resulting carrier keeping the Continental name.
Continental is now part of Texas Air, whose principal shareholder
is Jet Capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
