<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Caterpillar     04-13 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Caterpillar,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caterpillar Reports $146 Million Third Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caterpillar Inc. posted an $118 million
profit in the first quarter of 1988 compared with a loss during the
same period a year earlier, the company reported Wednesday.
   Caterpillar, the world's largest manufacturer of earth-moving
equipment, lost $84 million in first quarter 1987.
   Sales rose 42 percent to $2.35 billion in the first quarter from
$1.65 billion in the same period last year.
   The January-March results gave Caterpillar four consecutive
profitable quarters. The surging company is rebounding from a 1981
market collapse which led to three years of record losses totaling
$950 million.
   Len Kuchan, Caterpillar treasurer, attributed the company's
performance to higher-than-expected sales due to high demand for
its expanded product line. He said profits were curbed somewhat by
the new 1988 tax laws and shortages of certain popular models.
   Caterpillar sales in the United States rose 38 percent to $1.18
billion during the quarter, while foreign sales jumped 47 percent
to $1.17 billion.
   Sales fell in South America because of declining demand in
Brazil and Argentina, but sharply higher sales in Japan and the Far
East, as well as gains in Canada and Europe.
   The company suffered in the early 1980s due to a general
overcapacity in the industry and fierce competition at home and
abroad, where it was hampered by the strong U.S. dollar.
   Caterpillar has plowed its way back to financial health through
a cost-cutting program that included plant closings and widespread
layoffs.
</TEXT>
