<HEAD>Helmsleys Indicted in Tax Evasion Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf with 3 grafs to UPDATE with comment from
lawyer; picks up 4th graf pvs `The ailing ....' INSERTS one graf
after 12th graf pvs ``The Daily'' to add NY Post investigation;
picks up 13th graf pvs, ``The Daily.''
^By SAMUEL MAULL</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire real estate developer Harry Helmsley
and his wife Leona, the self-described hotel queen, have been
indicted on federal and state income tax evasion charges, a law
enforcement source said Wednesday.
   ``They were indicted several days ago,'' according to the
source, who added that federal and state prosecutors ``are just
waiting for a convenient time to hold a joint press conference.''
   The Helmsleys' lawyer, Stephen Kaufman, denied the couple ever
evaded taxes and said any such charge was ``unfounded, unfair and
unjust.''
   ``The Helmsleys have paid more taxes to the government over the
years than practically any other individual in this city or
country,'' Kaufman said in a two-page statement. ``In the last five
years alone they have paid more than $250 million in taxes.''
   The offices of the state attorney general and U.S. attorney
refused comment.
   The ailing Helmsley, 80, and his wife are accused of disguising
millions of dollars in renovation costs on their Connecticut
mansion as business expenses, according to the source, who spoke on
the condition of anonymity.
   The renovation bills on the sprawling Greenwich estate were
allegedly written off as tax deductions, the source said.
   The source said the expected charges were income tax evasion and
falsifying business records.
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani and state Attorney General Robert
Abrams mounted a joint investigation into the Helmsleys' taxes 18
months ago.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 68, who is prominent in ads for the family's
string of hotels, recently turned down a deal from prosecutors, who
said they would not seek the indictment of her husband if she
pleaded guilty to fraud, the source said.
   A problem for prosecutors will be the immunity Mrs. Helmsley
received last year in return for her testimony in cases against
merchants of expensive luxury items, including jewelry. Stores were
accused of shipping empty boxes to addresses out of state so
customers could take goods with them but avoid paying state and
city sales taxes.
   Immunity received in state cases does not apply in federal
cases, even if the federal charges stem from the same acts that
prompted the state charges, according to Paul Shechtman, chief
counsel to Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau.
   But federal prosecutors may not use leads and develop cases from
testimony given under immunity before a state grand jury, Shechtman
said.
   The Daily News, quoting unidentified sources close to the
defense, said Frank Turco, Mrs. Helmsley's former top aide, and
Joseph Licari, the couple's former financial manager, also were
expected to be indicted.
   The indictments followed a 15-month investigation into the
Helmsleys' finances by the New York Post.
   The Daily News said the four targets of the probe were directed
to surrender for arraignment at 8:15 a.m. Thursday. Their attorneys
in the past have denied any illegal activity by their clients.
   William Broadsky, Turco's lawyer, said his client ``is confident
that when all the facts are disclosed in court, he will be fully
exonerated.''
   The News said as many as 30 past and current employees of the
Helmsley organization were given immunity from prosecution in
return for testimony before state and federal grand juries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
